name: A Shimmer in the Darkness
description: B Side or a Rarity?  You make the call.  Definitely one or the other. Start with a low undercling for the right hand and a biter pinch on the arete for the left.  Establish and likely jump to the lip and mantle out through the hole.

name: Act of Valor
description: Sit start with ledge for hands.  Do a funky mantle and climb the short face.

name: Arete Right of Warm Up
description: Fun

name: Baby Burmese
description: Climb out the cave and topout on Like Shaking Hands with God.  Start left hand on a crimp and right hand on a good sloper pinch.  Super fun movement and friendly holds.  Very steep and pretty pumpy.  This is a shorter version of Burmese Python and cuts off a few moves.

name: Baby Crane
description: Sit start left hand low in crack, right around the arete. Gain left arete and do a couple cool moves to a chill topout. Definitely fun!

name: Banana Split
description: Start with left hand on good sidepull and left hand pushing on the arete to get off the ground. The crux is pulling on the far right hold to get in position for a big move to gain the top.

name: Bananarama
description: This is the arete just left of Banana Split.  Start low with your left hand on the arete (If your hand touches the boulder next to it, it's not on), and your right on a low 3 finger gaston.  Pull a subtle and hard first move, then continue up the arete.

name: Burmese Python
description: Starts on 2 crimps way down in the roof under Shaking Hands with God and climbs into that line.  Wild upside down climbing with some really neat holds.  Pumpy.

name: Classic Warm Up
description: Big juggy moves with small smeary feet. One sketch section up top but I'll leave that for you to figure out!

name: The Clinger
description: Sit start on obvious shelf and move into good undercling on the bottom of the bulge. Move your feet across the ledge and topout using slopey holds.

name: Common Decency
description: Eliminate/contrivance Alert.   We did this and it’s fun so sharing it here. Sit with jug.  Large ledge left is off, and any holds right of the arete are off, along with for feet to right of the arete/crack. Makes perfect sense right? So there ya go, do with it what you will.  There is a really cool pinch hold on this.

name: Corner Crack
description: Start low on jug and move out to crack in arete.  Fun problem.

name: Dabatron Arete
description: Start sitting, right hand with an undercling and left on the arete.  Climb the arete to a tricky, and tricky to avoid dabbing mantle.  A little heads up actually.

name: Ding Dong
description: Start seated with a left hand on an undercling in the arete and right hand on the vertical slot. Make a long move to a pocket. Set up on the face and launch to the lip on poor feet.

name: Easy on Backside of Burma
description: Easy.

name: Easy Street
description: Stand start on easy arete to the left of Entrance Slab.

name: Enigma
description: A sweet and pretty line..Start standing in the pit off a couple pads, right hand on the arete, left on a thumbdercling pinch.  Climb the tall face encountering crimpy knobs up high.  The shorter may have to stack an extra pad to start.  A blubber or thin pad is nice to cover the rocky ridge to the right.

name: Entrance Slab
description: Stand start on crack system that works it way up the middle of the face.

name: Entrance to "The Pit" PROJECT.
description: Project?

name: Escargot
description: Lieback and jam your way up the finger crack in the dihedral. Located around the right corner of Enigma. Don't fall up top or you'll bounce down the laundry chute. Difficulty may depend on finger size.

name: Face left of "The Scoop"
description: Face route.

name: Hard Arete
description: Hard face.

name: Head Over Heels
description: Great climb. Start on large rail and move out to left arete. Make some fun heals hook and slaps to gain your way to the top.

name: The Jug Haul
description: Good jug haul warm up. Very unlike DL bouldering.

name: Le Ribbit
description: Start in juggy slots or matched on the left one.  Gain a good sidepull in a crack right, move through gaston and a sidepull then finish through slopers and finally a jug.  A good sustained line and a nice addition to the Burma circuit.  People should get on this thing.

name: Like Shaking Hands with God
description: Start low and left at a block jug feature around chest height! Left hand up to hold on arete and bust a move out right to a side pull/rail feature. Work out the feature to top out boulder. Beware of top out its not bad but the you have the potential to fall in the pit on the backside of the boulder far out of reach of pads and spotters!

name: Mad Cow
description: This is an intimidating, awesome line I forgot to add a while back.  From a stand on the ledge, climb the thin vertical face right of hard arête.  A good one to have many pads at your disposal.

name: Murder Slab
description: Crux is pulling up to the slab.

name: No Foot Left Behind
description: Start just to the left of Shaking hands with God.  Climb completely under the roof using the jam crack.  Interesting and unique movement will see you out of the crack (don't lose your foot in the process). Exit up and to the right.

name: The Nose
description: Sit start with an obvious horizontal hold to the right and a low side pull on the left arête. Climb straight up.

name: Pinball Arete
description: Climb the arete just right of Tick Tock in the middle of the pit to a spicy topout.  Start standing on the boulder and go straight up the arete.

name: Pit Crack
description: Stand start in crack system and move.... up.

name: Pocket Problem
description: Climb the face with the pocket, just left of Classic Warmup.

name: Purple Gold
description: Start from a stand with your left hand on the arete and right on an undercling that will pinch you if not grabbed just right.  Pull on and climb up through the center of the wall through edges, a sidepull and big moves.  An easy mantle gets you on top.  A real gem I think, and surely one of the best of the grade in park.  Wait for a dry day, this thing can be wet sometimes.

name: Quaker Oats
description: Stand start on really small holds and use the obvious good foot. Move up to tiny crimp on the right and reach for the top.

name: Scammy Fly-By-Night Superpac
description: Start seated on the good, sharp hold. Make a move to a decent hold before reaching a good horn at the top and topping out.

name: The Scoop
description: Slab, tricky start.

name: Second Degree
description: Murder Slab variation. Using the right arete at the bottom, climb your way up and into Murder Slab.

name: The Seven Year Itch
description: Sit start on low rail, move up and left to topout.  We started right hand underclinging and left on rail but it goes without the undercling too.

name: Shorty
description: Short problem.

name: Sloper Problem
description: Slopey

name: Tick Tock
description: Left hand side pull start, Right hand low flatish hold.  Tricky and balancey climbing up the slightly overhanging face with some weird, and kinda sharp holds.  Great moves, technical and sustained.

name: traverse
description: Begin on any set of big jugs around the arete 15' left of Classic Warm Up.  Traverse around the corner avoiding putting your feet on the big ramp below the overhang.  Move into soap dish on face and match there.  A long stretch into Classic Warm Up and an easy traverse from there to the Arete Right of Warm Up.  Top out on face to the right of the arete.

name: Twinkle Toes
description: Start right of Pinball Arete in the horizontal seam, with your right hand in a pod hold and left on a slimper next to it.  Climb leftwards through a technical and powerful sequence and finish up Pinball Arete.

name: Unkown Crimpy Traverse
description: Traverse Right to Left, start with left on a crimp and right on a sloper. Mostly sharp crimps until you get to a three finger pocket and then top out. I don't know if this is an established line.

name: V-Dyno
description: Stand start with good jug and dead-point(dyno) to the lip.

name: Waffle House
description: Use underclings to move into better holds at the top.

name: The Whole Shack Shimmy
description: Start seated on the smaller hands. Follow jugs to the top. Beware, some of the rock quality seems suspect.

name: Bushmills Bulge
description: Climb up corner with interesting start.

name: Earth Mechanics
description: Start low in face on large sidepull and climb your way up and out left on thin holds.

name: Emily's Naptime
description: Climb up using the arete to the left and the crack to the right.

name: The Grenadine Corner
description: The chunky outside corner and chimney. A beginner's scamper or down-climb.

name: Horseshoes & Hand Grenades
description: Climb 14 feet on thin face holds avoiding the ledge to the right. The ledges to avoid have red arrows pointing to them in the picture. Spotting someone climbing below the upper blocks is no problem, but if you fall above that you'll have some problems landing as there are small jagged boulders on a small hill directly behind you - likely to be an ankle snap. One of my favorite boulder routes.\  On the north end of the North Shore. The first problem on the northernmost stretch of rock.

name: Jameson Arete
description: Climb up arete using anything you can, very tricky for the grade.

name: Little Lia
description: Low ball traverse from left to right.  SDS as far left as possible and traverse right using good edges over the lip and small low feet.  Top out over far right end.  Named after my youngest daughter shortly after her birth.  Not sure if its V1 or not but didn't want to show favoritism for this problem over the one named after my other daughter... Parents will understand!

name: Naptime Chimney
description: The obvious chimney between Emily's Naptime and V1 Face. A good choice for scoping Emily's Naptime.

name: Oil Can
description: Start on Jameson Arete, and move left onto the ledges on the face.

name: Sheriff's Approval
description: An eliminate that avoids using the crack to the left and the holds of Earth Mechanics (V5) to the right. A hard sit start leads to big moves and sharp crimps.

name: V1 Face
description: Start with large wavey ledge and pull up to top.

name: Big Dud Arete
description: Down the hill and off to the side of Big Bud lies another tall and scary highball. Although similar in aesthetic and height to the mega-classic, in comparison the climbing is sadly inferior.  Big Dud is a much easier climb and the landing is much worse. Follow the juggy shelves up the prominent arete and dont fall.   This line has probably been soloed by many in the past.   If being up high excites you but pulling hard doesn't, this is the route for you!

name: Confidence Booster
description: Follow the vertical seam, using big holds on either side. Head straight up, I would suggest avoiding the ledges to the left to keep the problem a little more interesting.

name: Eubank's Lady Bits
description: Start with small right hand and a left sidepull, pull up to a ledge, and mantle. From there it is jugs to the top.

name: I Don't Know, B
description: Start low on a huge rail, work your way up with a mantle, find a sidepull, and topout with another mantle. That's right, two mantles on one route. Crack and face to the left are definitely off.

name: Office Building
description: 14 Feet. Use everything. Avoid the mossy area on the extreme upper left part of the face. There are some large holds which I don't think are part of the climb.

name: Special K
description: Special K climbs the arete on sidepulls and small holds to the top. I don't remember seeing any jugs. Seems borderline V0-V1.

name: The Tullamore Dew Arete
description: Climb up the arete, lots of heel hooking and a couple of crimps. Topout is a bit heady, crux is definitely high up. Landing isn't the best, didn't test it though, so it could be anything.

name: Welcome Arete
description: Climb up arete in between Welcome Crack 2 and Welcome Face.  A real balance act.

name: Welcome Chimney
description: The Obvious Chimney in the Welcome Area.

name: Welcome Crack
description: Climb up crack just right of Welcome to the Lake.  Really fun, and tricky.

name: Welcome Crack 1
description: The obvious crack between Welcome Chimney and Welcome Crack 2.

name: Welcome Crack 2
description: Climb up crack to top.  Fun warm up.

name: Welcome Face
description: Climb up face with cool moon shaped hold just to the right of Welcome Arete.  Nice warm up.

name: Welcome to the Lake
description: Climb face avoiding the seam, arete and right crack.  Sort of an eliminate, but tricky and fun.

name: Wild Turkey
description: Climb overhanging arete on south side of boulder. Sit start on large holds on either side of arete. Move your way up large holds to top, slapping either side of the arete.

name: Big Bud Arete
description: Starting on right corner climb up to break and head straight up face using both aretes.  Super tall and scary, but the landing isn't bad.

name: Big Bud North Face
description: Take the left arête up to the break. Maneuver up the north face from there to the lip. The sloper on the arête at about 20 feet is a little bit scarier than on Big Bud Arête. Slipping off that would likely send you into the rock behind you.

name: Big Bud’s Baby Brother
description: Climb up and mantle on the first flat. Shift right, climb up, and mantle on the second flat.  Shift left, climb up, and mantle to the third flat.  Then top out.Great warm-up route

name: Bud's Chimney
description: A potential down climb after sending Big Bud or an unappealing chimney boulder problem to ascend.

name: Egyptian Divinity (Happy Scrambling)
description: Crank on twin pyramids with a high foot and lean in to obtain a godlike state of balance (at least that's how I did it).  Reach up for good holds and float up to the heavens.  Photo to come.  Also called "Happy Scrambling" in Ian Colter-Brown's "Devil's Lake Bouldering".

name: Friday Night Fever
description: behind tree climb right side of of small cliff band.  use both aretes and face holds to reach top.

name: Mini me
description: use small starting feet and both aretes to gain top with a throw. Named on a Wednesday night outing after Paul Wagener took Tommy D and Peter Cleveland to an Austin Powers movie.

name: Purple Bud
description: Good holds and an a cool top-out make this a must do warm-up for the area.    Anyone claim the FA?

name: Chrome Dome Arete
description: Start on large rail and make some fun moves up the arete. Watch out for the wall on the left, dab potential.

name: Chrome Dome Warm Up
description: Climb up featured lay-back just left of Giese Dome.

name: The Giese Dome
description: Start just left of corner, crank up to a good ledge and slopey topout.  Really fun V2, a must do.

name: Invisibility Cloak
description: Start from a stand, right hand up high on an okay shelf and left on an undercling. Pull on and launch up the intimidating and airy arête, probably moving slightly right on good holds and feet for the finish. The walls, detached blocks, trees or whatever aren't used, climb the arête!

name: The Power of The Chrome Dome
description: Climb up boulder just right of corner and Giese Dome.  Avoid the crack on right.

name: Red Hair Arete
description: Fun arete, kind of tricky with squeezy balancy moves.  Super satisfying topout.

name: Reef on This
description: Tricky.  Climb up on thin holds to the top.  Avoid the left arete.

name: Show Me Mercy
description: Same face as Show Me the Kind, but uses large sloper right hand just over the roof and over to the right.  Also can use the big foot over to the right.

name: Show Me The Kind
description: Figure out a way to balance your way up the slab in order to get to the left facing crimp in the crack.  Make a dynamic move to a big hold and then top out.

name: The Urumi
description: Start standing in the hole, on the ledge at the base of the striking arete. Right hand on a decent spot on the arete, left on a crimp sidepull.  A few compression moves, mostly standing on your feet, leads to a long move to a juggy hold in a seam.  Follow good holds in the seam left and top out the pointy spire.  A spectacular and fun climb in an intimidating position.

name: Blue Skies And Ski Hi
description: This boulder had many different problems all over the face.  Start anywhere and go straight up on great holds.

name: Dagger of the Lake
description: Start low facing toward the lake(Ian swears it's easier) and pull up and out boulder on bad slopers and powerfull foot trickery.

name: Closer to Coal
description: Sit start under short roof with left hand on good hold at the lip and right on under cling.

name: Diamond in the Rough
description: Start on good edges and bump out left to good hold.  Hike feet and stand up into under-cling.  Top out is interesting.

name: Humble Beginnings
description: Start straddling the corner of the right side of the boulder with both hands on jug at the lip. Pump on up the edge and top out on left side of the point. Fun core moves.

name: Everclear
description: Start on the jug at chest height in the middle of the wall as per Evergreen, but at mid height move to the left side of the face and top out.  Tall with an exciting last move.

name: Evergreen
description: Climb clean, steep face with big moves on small holds, finishing up and right.  Fun and commiting!

name: Fantastic Four
description: High ball boulder.  Not terribly tough, good warm up.

name: Project Zero
description: Start low on undercling and jug.  Move up overhang on large features.  Fun top-out.

name: Struggle Ass Outta Hole
description: The boulder starts low to the ground, foot on a ledge near the ground. (the left wall and right wall are off)  Get outta the hole

name: The Wind Rider
description: Start down low on good edges.  Power your way up steep arete to a crux finish.  Really fun movement, and thanks to Mike Lohre for cleaning this one up!

name: The Exfoliator
description: Start on left hand pinch/crimp left side of boulder, and right on upper crimp on the right side.  Paste feet and get to high jug.  Harder than it looks.

name: Fantasticorner
description: SDS with block on left, squeeze your way up corner to the lip.  Fun committing top-out.

name: Slab
description: Start with good crimps and climb up face to top.

name: Fresh Air
description: SDS with large side-pull and gun for good jug.  Top-out is the crux

name: Ghosts of the Forest
description: Sit start with left hand on good edge/pinch and right on sharp pinch under the roof.  Set feet and dead-point the rail at the lip.  Top-out

name: Cray Cray Project
description: Start on an OK side pull and do three very hard looking moves to a jug.

name: Galactic
description: Start sitting matched on the bottom of the arête.  Follow the arête right, using the huge foot to finish.

name: Good Morning Veruca
description: Stand start with right hand crimp and reach left out to slopey jug.  Hike your feet and move up intimidating arete.  Super exposed, but really fun!

name: Space Jam
description: From a high stand, surmount the bulgey head wall.  I started left hand jugglet and right on a pinch on the lip.  Only a few mover so maybe it's not so hard right? A pure and tricky problem.

name: Party Hole
description: Start on crimps just above the roof and go straight up through a very cool sandstone jug to an easy topout.

name: High Radiance
description: Start from a slanting edge and a crimp just below for the right.  Bust a big move right (crux). Continue along the lip and mantle.

name: Low Radiance
description: Start right hand on crimp-pinch at the lip and left on a crimp just below the lip. Right heel and scummy toe hook beneath the roof. Pull into the heel then throw for the left hand start holds of High Radiance. Match and carefully set up for start then climb out High Radiance.

name: Rubick's Groove
description: Fun cube-like boulder. SDS with left hand on crimp and right hand around corner on small block. Work up the arete and then throw for the top! Mantle

name: 80 and Rainy
description: Start on an obvious edge just above the roof and climb straight up the nose of the boulder.

name: Battle Cry
description: Start with good left hand low and right out on lip.  Kick feet high and climb feature out and right.  Lots of power and focus gets you up this one.

name: The Little Roof That Could
description: Start left hand on a good sloper and right in the slot.  Go left out the roof on good holds.

name: Spring Slab
description: Start with low left side-pull.  Paste foot on wall and mantle up into slab.  Smear feet and top-out.

name: Swoop There It Is
description: Start low on detached block.  Make long reach out to lip of overhang.  Keeping tension, move out right along lip to top-out.  Really fun moves.

name: Wee Man
description: Start on low slopers.  Gain arête left and continue up the arête.

name: A Scanner Darkly
description: Arete just right of Science Friction with the bad landing.  Good climbing and a little dicey.

name: Bird Beak
description: Start low with high right foot, climb up and left to gain the bird's beak.  Top-out is pretty cool.

name: The Commander
description: From a stand, climb the stiriking, intimidating and long arête.  The landing is double tiered and it works out that you can pull onto almost any move and work it out..

name: Metric Measures
description: Start with hands matched in crack, move out left to a good side-pull and gain the lip.  Top-out is crux on this one.

name: Science Friction
description: Start with decent side-pulls low and right, gain the textured edge and sack-up and send!  Originally probably soft 9 but a foot broke making it bigger and the last move got a bit easier.

name: Boo boo
description: Start with both feet out right. Left foot on small edge and right heel hooking. Pull up on good edge with right hand and push for the top. A very fun low ball problem.

name: Sunny & 60's
description: Start with good block on lower right, paste foot and throw for incut edge.  Cross through and gain good slopey bread loaf.  Turn the corner and get out to face.  Top out is a bit heady.

name: SunnyD (aka Sunny & 60's Direct)
description: Same start as Sunny & 60's, but from bread loaf hold move out right to small crimp on face.  Move feet and stay tight while you bump your hands to the top.

name: Yogi
description: Start on a okay left crimp and right hand on the arete. Pump your right hand up to a cool sloper and keep moving up. A lot of moves for such a low problem. You can also start with your right hand on a crimpy  undercling but climbs fun starting on arete.

name: Small Pad Complex
description: Sit start under the roof and climb your way out to a glorious layback to the top.

name: Rain or Shine
description: Climb up face of pillar to committing top-out.

name: Uncertainty Principle
description: From a sit in the crack, climb up and right across the tall face above the bouldery landing.  There is a long crux move in the middle that will surely feel harder or easier depending on your height.

name: Booty Rider
description: Was bored so climbed the right side of the Wave Rider Boulder. Sit start on right aerate and climb left into the overhang and then top out on a slopey crimp. Another climber tried this and unfortunately butt rocketed onto the boulder beneath Wave Rider (yes there were pads but apparently was still very painful).

name: Wave Rider Direct
description: Start as for Wave Rider, but instead of veering left to finish, stay true to the arete and face.  This is a great problem and it deserves some action.  It has an airy feeling but is safe if padded.  One of the best of the grade in the park?  Quite possibly.

name: The Wave Rider
description: To get started grab large block in middle of boulder, get a good left heel-toe cam, left hand pinch, and right hand on good rail.  Bump out left to good crimp and fight your way up using smart footwork to gain high side-pull.  Committing throw to the finish.  So rad!!

name: Blood Diamond
description: Start standing high, with a good left hand pinch, and an inverted undercling pinch for the right just on the edge of the roof.  Pull on, perhaps get a toe hook and shuffle up some holds.  Better holds are gained and an airy but not so hard finish awaits.

name: Danger Mouse
description: Start on the obvious two edges back in the cave. Place a solid toe jam and work the moves along the sloping edges and pinch out of the tight cave maintaining tension and body positions to prevent dabbing. Following the toe jam release crux, set up into the start holds of Gnarls Barkley and finish it off.

name: For the Little People
description: SDS with long rail on right side of boulder.  Work your way up left to great ledges.

name: Icicle Tusk
description: Start low with large meat-hook and climb up block on right side of boulder.

name: Rubik’s Groove
description: Start standing with a good juglet in a seam for the left hand, and a juggy sidepull for the right.  Climb the left side of the arete, moving slightly left to mantle.

name: Uncut Gems
description: Start from a stand, right hand in the arete and left probably on an inverted pinch below the lip.  Climb up the arete, mantle and finish with easing but airy climbing.  A fall off to the right could be really bad so pad and spot, and of course climb accordingly.

name: The Winter Blues
description: Start with hands in slanting crack.  Set foot on good ledge and dead-point to lip.  Very core intensive and very hard.

name: You Only Fall Once
description: Start hugging both sides of the pillar and go straight out the overhang.

name: Gay Gigolo
description: Start on underclings/sidepulls and make your way up good holds to a fun throw for the top.    You can also do this climb from a sitstart.

name: Imp Act
description: I'm pretty sure I've climbed this but I can't remember the grade. Any care to fill in the blanks?

name: Imp Act Sit
description: Climb Imp Act from a sit.

name: Shark's Fin Arete
description: I remember Dobbe and I doing this a long time ago. I believe the start was an undercling.

name: Slippery Seam
description: Start on the left facing slopey jug and make your way up the face using slope out left and the infamous "Green Seam".    Bring a brush so that the seam is a little less green.

name: Stinky Feesh
description: I think I recall it being good.

name: Wiceps
description: starts with the crack left of Imp Act, lean into it with feet out to the right near the start of Imp Act. follow the crack and look for the hole in the rock (handle) to grab. Topping out can be tricky if you aren't flexible.

name: Caleb's Cave
description: Start deep in cave formed by 2 boulders on good left hand and right on whale tooth conglomerate.  Slap out bulge and topout up arete.

name: Circus World
description: Start seated on two rounded edges.  Climb five moves into the start of Greatest Show.

name: Elegant Design
description: Start right hand edge and left hand juggy undercling. Climb up face to pocket and topout.

name: Greatest Show on Earth
description: Start on underclings and climb straight up the center of the largest boulder.  I think the problem was originally topped out by climbing straight up, however recent repeats have found that escaping left is both easier and somewhat less scary.  Do what gets you psyched.

name: Greatest Slab
description: Start with right hand on arete and left down low, establish feet and head up boulder using arete and face features.  Really fun!

name: Pocket Problem
description: Climb up boulder from low pocket with undercling and get to double pockets.  Top-out.

name: Shadow Walker
description: Start as for pocket problem and traverse through tricky moves into the start of the v1 face. This one would clean up well with traffic.

name: Shady Fucker
description: Start as for "Shadow Walker" but climb straight up the face.

name: Small Warm-up
description: Climb up right side of boulder to easy top-out.   Variation- from left side of boulder, climb seam up and right to the same finish. V1ish

name: V1 Face
description: Climb up face using good edges and a slopey topout.

name: Mutual Attraction
description: Small, yes.  Potentially a new age classic?  For sure.  Start on the prominent flat ledge on the left side, probably pull up and far right to a pinch and finish it up.  A pure and high quality little problem.  Also easily accessible and not so hard to find.

name: Oz
description: Good V2 with an interesting start and landing!

name: Perth
description: Warm up!

name: Talus From Gnarnia
description: The middle of the face that beckons to be climbed. Was going to be Tales From Gnarnia, but the approach and landing of this problem makes the name more valid. Anyways, climb the middle of the face starting just left of perth and use all sorts of sharp, painful crimps. I would ask that any future ascents be mindful that the lichen on this boulder make it VERY cool. Please try to not scrape too much off. The view from the top is SPECTACULAR and if the movement was little better, it would be 4 stars no doubt.

name: Big Wobbly
description: This is a unique problem with excellent movement just a short distance from the upper trail. Sit start with big hand holds low in crack and under suspended block. You could use the detached block to the left for feet or keep your feet low and right to avoid this (I chose this path) foot decisions will not effect difficulty. With some trickery obtain the small holds on the lip of roof. Make a hard move to establish on small face holds (crux) and then follow slab to the tip of the boulder.

name: Dr. Strange
description: A funky and unique one.  Start crouched with a left sloper on the arete and right low undercling at the base of the block.  A scrunchy bicycle may prove useful.  Gain the lip, work up the arete and mantle as for Big Wobbly.  The detached blocks aren’t used.

name: Magic Carpet
description: With so many heady test pieces, bold highballs, and sketchy landings around, a solid cruisy warm-up is a welcome addition to the monolith zone.This climb is relatively short but packs in acrobatic moves on big volumesque holds all the way to a fun and secure topout. Nothing fancy here, just big moves on good holds with a decent landing and a nice view of the lake. This would be a great candidate for a gym rat's first outdoor boulder.The location does leave a little to be desired, but its worth running a few laps on before moving on to harder things in the area. If you do manage to make it off the beaten path, you'll enjoy a ride up the Magic Carpet!

name: Devils Pit
description: This is the full extension of Unholy Hole. Descend all the way into the pit (bring a head lamp). Problem starts in the pit with an under cling (left hand) and the arete (right hand). Work up the slab and then transition into the Unholy Hole line. What's cool about this line? It's long, pumpy, uses two caves. What's not cool? Dabby, no protection out of the cave, and the slab is only V1. Please be careful if you try it, falling off the slab would be very bad.

name: Unholy Hole
description: This is a super fun line starting on the arête. Work up the crimps and a pinch then mantle out of the cave. Nice warm up for Mean Gurlz. If it was a bit longer I would give it 4 stars but if you're in the area you should definitely try it!

name: Thunder From Down Under
description: Start with hands matched in the crack, left foot on the good chip, right foot in a toe hook on the lip. Make a move out right then, bump to the jug. Roll over and top out.

name: Jaws 2
description: Sit down and start on lower crack.  Slap your way up feature to committing move at the lip, top-out.     Reminded me of Jaws at Sawmill Creek Dome MN, only easier.

name: Wrestling The Bear
description: Start with a low right hand on the arete and left on a shallow edge.  Go straight up the arete.

name: Mean Gurlz
description: Start from a sit on the right arete, with your right hand on a biter sidepull crimp, and your left on a slanted slopey edge.  Move to the rail system, then trend leftwards through the rails, encountering interesting moves.  Once the left arete is gained top it out.  The moves get easier at the finish, but blowing the mantle could be a very bad, be careful!

name: Mean Gurlz Direct (aka The Clique)
description: Start seated low on the right arete as for Mean Gurlz. The first several moves of that problem lead to a long lock off to the lip.  Top out directly over the slab.

name: The Substitute
description: Same start as Mean Gurlz then follows the right arete to an airy top out!

name: Minnesota V10
description: Start on a jug on the block below the roof.  Pull out the roof and encounter a tricky mantle crux.. New school V4.  Minnesota V10?

name: Ballad of a Thin Man
description: start using good edges to work your way up the right side of the large slab, utilizing ample feet and then the usual devil's lake high step to an excellent top out jug.

name: Espionage
description: From a sit with your arms wide, left hand on a low downpulling edge, right on a low and thin sidepull, pull on and go up the face.  Tough first move and fun delicate climbing on perfect rock.  A 5 move problem or so.

name: Half Moons of Doom
description: Sit Start under the boulder with two good edges on the face, feet out left. Make a left hand move up to the next good edge, then move out to the right hand side pull. Then get your feet set to make the bump up to the right hand jug. Make one more move to the to a left hand jug and top it out. Hardest part of this boulder is not dabbing on the boulder next to you, it gets a bit cramped.

name: Par 4
description: Start on a good right hand pinch and left any of the crimps. Pull up into a good heel hook and pump left hand up twice then heel the right and go for the top. Very fun movement for this short problem!

name: Squirrel Heckler
description: Sit start on left side, climb under the roof using arete and up into the prow.

name: Roofie
description: Start left hand in jug/slot, right hand on crimper. Big move to the lip and some fun moves get you to the top

name: Friday Night Heights
description: Highball boulder with a poor landing.  Good news is that the crux is low and pretty well protected.

name: Bonamici Arete (aka Tequila)
description: Start low on large ledge and get out to right arete.  Follow the arete to the top.  Super fun, and the grade varies depending on who you ask.

name: Born in Blood
description: This is a low start to Tipping Point.  Start with your right hand on a sidepull, and your left on the arete.  Pull on and climb into Tipping Point.  Core intensive and a lot of moves.

name: The Joy of Life
description: Climbs Born in Blood through Tip Top. 20+ moves of hard climbing.

name: Just the Tip
description: Starting on good holds where you would normally mantle The Tipping Point, pull on and climb the left arete feature.  A physical problem with perhaps some meat hooking involved

name: Placenta
description: Start as for Born in Blood, with your left hand the arête and right hand with a crimpy side pull.  Climb up the arête and face. A knee pad is helpful.

name: Tip Top
description: Climb The Tipping Point into Just the Tip.  Quite pumpy.

name: The Tipping Point
description: Amazing new roof!!  Start on a small right undercling and the large feature in the middle of the roof for your left.  Very cool tension moves out the roof.

name: Water Chestnut
description: Start in lower left side of cave, right hand on a sloper and left hand in a crack. Left hand to a pinch, hit the sloper and bump to the sloper sidepull. Go straight up.

name: Brototype 1.0
description: Big under-clings to start, big throw to a nice sloper, foot trickery and slap the lip to the top.

name: Talus Scramble
description: Off the trail to monolith there are some talus fields you can climb around in. There are some boulder problems, as well as technical 4th class scrambling. This is one of the harder scrambles.

name: Thigh Bar
description: Same start as Brototype but now ascend the crack directly with hand/footjams and mantle the lip.

name: Tyranny of Heaven
description: Start on small holds and work your way through more of the same.    This was "The Money Pit" project.

name: Wedge Antilles
description: Start with a low edge on the right arete and a good left hand on the left arete in between very sharp sections.  Climb the mini refrigerator-like feature.

name: Axiom Direct
description: Climb AAA, and instead of traversing of like everybody does, keep climbing to the apex of the pillar through a somewhat slopey bulge that would really suck to fall off.

name: Axiom of Arete Aesthetics
description: Start at the base of pillar, and climb directly up arete to ledge, top-out.

name: Crack of Minimal Motion
description: Climb up right side of face into thin crack, avoid the right arete.  Sandbagged for sure, this thing is hard.

name: Left side of East of Trail Boulders
description: Hmmm...did it in 2004. Warm up.

name: Monolith Traverse
description: Two hand start in the far right crack, finish on the far left jug near slope of dadaism.

name: Not a Gimmie!
description: Starts on the left arete then moves on to the face. Don't through to what looks like a good ledge...It's not a gimmie!

name: Off-trail Connection
description: Starts where Warm Up Face begins and travers right around the arete to the start of Slope of Dadaism.  Continue following the crack through the start of Slope of Dynoism, and finish where the line runs into Crack of Minimal of Motion.  Depending how you climb the crux could be in a couple places.  Doing the line in reverse-order could warrant a more difficult grade.

name: Pillar of Contemporary Movement
description: Starting on lower block, using arete and crimp up left, set feet high and dead-point to upper block.  Top out.

name: Slope of Dadaism
description: A super fun climb, my vote for best V3 in the park!  Climb up the left side of large face to slopers up high, top-out.

name: Slope of Dynoism
description: Formally known as the dyno project, this thing is a monstrous dyno in the middle of the face to the right of Slope of Dadaism. Start with hands matched on the jug at head height in the middle of the face. From there work your way up into two  slot crimps. The dyno is from these crimps and goes to a bad rail about a foot below the lip!

name: Spring Cleaning
description: Follow the arete all the way to the top. Start sitting (if you're in to that sort of thing) and stand up to a couple of very small sharp holds.  Make a difficult move up to a good hold in the seam.  At the seam use a good left hand jam, or some other trickery, and stand way up to the only good hold on the face, a two finger full pad crimp.  Delicately make a long move for the lip.  Top Out.

name: Warm Up Face
description: Good warm up, avoid the bird nest. Couple of different ways to do this.

name: A Hunger Artist
description: From the toe of the arete, climb the right face and arete.    #72 on Zschiesche's bouldering guide.

name: Fat Crack
description: 12 feet. A nice crack to exercise jamming skills, with plenty of face relief.  #74 on Zschiesche's bouldering guide.  Also know as "Thumbs of Steel" [107686548]

name: Gnome Ladder
description: Work up side pulls into a ladder of easy jugs.

name: Jack Spraight Delight
description: Ascend the west side of the corridor on nice finger-sized holds and sidepulls.    #75 on Zschiesche's bouldering guide.

name: Soul Satori
description: Soul satori is located in the Thin Man Corridor, on the right arete as one is looking towards the lake. Although it may be over looked due to its easy grade, this climb may be the most aesthetic in the park when climbed at sunset. this is a must do for any climber, good exposure, beautiful view, and extremely fun climbing! Simply climb up the slabby arete, using good crimps on both sides, aiming for a nice ledge for the top out. A definate DL classic!

name: Thin Crack
description: Climb perfect finger crack just left of Soul Satori.  (The wide crack to the left is "Wide Open Burger".)

name: Thin Man Corridor
description: Climb the center of the east face to the top. 14 feet.    #71 on Zschiesche's bouldering guide.

name: Arrow Head Arete
description: 12 feet. Climb using both sides of the arete. There are hidden holds on the left side, and you can use some of the holds on Venus Rising (route 59).

name: Arrow Right
description: Climb the face and thin crack just left of Broken Pottery Left.

name: Awkward Mushroom
description: Across the slight gully left of Shawn's Slab Arete. Climb up over center of the bulge. Avoid using the obvious, large, hollow-sounding flake (labelled "DEATH FLAKE" on the topo photo) on the left.

name: Bark Biter
description: 12 Feet. Climb the crack on the right side of the arete avoiding the generous corner on the far right. Really really really watch out for that tree. Above 1/2 of the way up, any fall you make will result in an unwanted slide with your back down the tree, and eventually face planting back into the rock.

name: Boulder right of Bark Biter
description: 17 Feet. This isn't in any published guide but it's a pretty fun problem. It's located right next to Bark Biter. Start on the small platform at the bottom and climb up the face starting with a hidden hold pointed to by the green arrow. Aside from the start, stay off the left arete. Using the hidden hold, probably a V0-V1. Without using the hidden hold will be a bit trickier, probably V2. Sorry for the vague ratings, I suck at rating climbs.

name: Broken Pottery Left
description: Same as Right version, but avoid the hidden hold.

name: Broken Pottery Right
description: Starting up right side of face, find hidden hold and move up and left to top.

name: Cannon Fodder
description: SDS on shelf with right hand on good side pull and left on a sloper on the face of the boulder. Mantle and climb up the face. The arete is off. No credit if you sit on a crash pad.    Admin adds: It should be noted that this is an SDS to Boulder right of Bark Biter.

name: Claustrophobia
description: From a sit, with your left hand on the lowest part of an obvious slopey shelf and your right on a good spot low on the arête, pull on and climb up and right out of the corridor.  A confined problem with fun moves.

name: Cow Pie
description: Start seated and use good face holds to a rounding top out.

name: Cow Tipping
description: Start seated near the left arete of the boulder. Use the wide crack for a few moves and top out.

name: Deep Doodoo Left
description: Start on chockstone in the back of the "cave". Climb the wide crack to the top.

name: Deep Doodoo Right
description: Start on ledge in right corner of "cave". Climb hand crack and hanging corner to top.

name: El Nino
description: Starts in the cave to the right of the V1 slab.  Starts left hand on the sloper shelf in the center of the wall and right on a wide pinch near the right arete in the back of the cave.  Traverse left to the arete.  Continue up the arete and top out.

name: Follow the Owl
description: This is a fun body tension problem. The minimal feet combined with a great hand rail makes this climb strong for the grade. Bring your muscles!

name: Haunted Warmup
description: Climb up the slightly overhanging wall on good holds.

name: The Haunting
description: From a sit with your left hand on a slopey sidepull and your right on an undercling, climb up the face through a pocket hold.

name: Holy Cow
description: Start sitting on a tree on the left side of the spotted cow wall, left hand on a good hold, right on a sidepull.  Traverse low into the start of spotted cow center and finish it up.  The last move is a kicker.

name: Just Another Sick Old New Rig Left
description: SDS on the obvious low jug. Move up-and-left through slopers to top.

name: Just Another Sick Old New Rig Right
description: SDS on the obvious low jug. Move up-and-right through pocket to top.

name: Not Gonna Eat Bark
description: Climb tall arete on block just right of Bark Biter.

name: Pillar Left of Venus Rising
description: Climb up pillar with good holds.  Good one to climb up for scrubbing the top of VR.

name: Precious
description: Start from a crouch, with your left hand on a low side pull on the left side of the arête, and your right on an obvious low side pull on the right.  Pull on and climb right wards to an easy mantle.  Spotters beware.  Detached blocks are not used for feet.

name: Scary Slab
description: Climb the cool slab arete next to the trail.

name: Shawn's Direct
description: Long reaches with thin feet. Do not use either arete. Start on balancey slap reach heigh for two jugs, move feet up the slick surface, reach high right for amazing pinch, work the feet high, and top out.

name: Shawn's Slab
description: Climb up right side of slab, really fun and a good warm-up.

name: Shawn's Slab Arete
description: The left arete of Shawn's Slab. A few fun moves to the top.

name: Spotted Cow Center
description: SDS on large hold at the bottom of the wall. Work your way up the thin face using a glassy crimp and some awkwardly placed feet. Throw for a good flake, breathe, then fight your way up a slopey topout.

name: Spotted Cow Far Left
description: Stand start with decent holds and traverse right to top. Fun, and a good warm up.

name: Spotted Cow Left
description: SDS and pull up on large hold and move left to thin crack.  Fun and tricky.

name: Spotted Cow Right
description: Same start as Left and Center variations, but move right.

name: Thunderbird Bulge
description: Start with good sidepulls, hike your feet and throw for good hold.  Exit right.

name: Use Your Delusions
description: Four move campus start goes at V4, V2 if you use the feet.

name: Venus Rising
description: Venus Rising is a nice problem on rounded rock. Pull up from a stand start on the undercling with strenuous moves to the top of the arete. The left arete is off but doesn't really seem to be tempting with the flow of the movement. A sit start adds a number to your 8a card, if that's your bag.

name: Big Easy
description: Start on the big, obvious ledge and go directly up the face on great edges.

name: Big Time
description: Climb up the very tall face just left of Sex and Chocolate.  Don't use Detached boulders or the ledge out left.  A fall from high up could be bad.  Good climbing.

name: Cherry Underneath
description: This problem adds a high quality sit start and a bit of difficulty to already the classic "Sex and Chocolate with a Cherry On Top." Start seated with hands on two underclings and then move up and left through thin crimps to join the stand start. Keep it together for the heady top out.  Some would say that this is the full line on the boulder.  For the faint of heart, this problem has also been done with a drop from the break (like "Sex and Chocolate").

name: Drunk and Disorderly
description: Climb up the left arete of the tall pillar.  There is a committing move that leads to an airy topout above a less than perfect landing.

name: The Gargoyle
description: From a stand climb the right side of the arête encountering an airy crux.  The top does ease off.

name: Lumberjack
description: 7 Feet. Butt start on double crimps to a left hand pinch and right hand on the arete. Proceed to move left on the problem to a pretty straight forward top out.

name: Manhattan
description: Start in the dual cracks and make your way up the vertical face.  Some have called the large right hand crack off but really, do whatever is fun.

name: Perfect Medium
description: Start using arete on right and small crimps on left.  Make your way to the obvious horizontal break at half-height using razor crimp, sloper, and abysmal feet.      Continue from the break up easier moves to the top of the boulder if you are feeling brave or just traverse off left or right to ledges.    Large foot hold at bottom might be considered "off" by some...just have fun

name: Perfect Medium Right
description: A right variation to perfect medium where you stay true to the arete.  Pretty powerful and some good moves.  If confused check out the video below.

name: Pink T-shirts and Berry Skoal
description: Short little boulder with a very smooth face, have a seat and give it a hug. Proceed to heel hook your way up to the slopers on top. Fun, strong climbing. Crux is probably the topout.

name: Prairie Dog Disco
description: Starts on flake pinched between rocks. Get high foot. Work your way into crack and pop your head over the top. Right side of crack is OFF

name: Sex & Chocolate
description: Start right hand on a the crimp on the face, left hand on the good hold on the arete.  Move onto the arete and make a long move to the slopey jug.  Exit left or right from here, or continue to the top for the direct finish if you're into that sort of thing.  This is the style of problem where there is a fine line between it feeling impossible and impossibly easy...    With the completion of the direct finish, this is listed as a separate problem more for historical purposes than anything else...

name: Sex and Chocolate with a Cherry on Top (aka S&C Direct)
description: Climb Sex and Chocolate, traverse right at break and head straight up the head-wall using the arete and face holds.

name: Alexandria
description: Start low, below the face and climb straight up using the right arete and left side-pulls on the face.

name: Blubber Face
description: Start sitting low and left on two ledges.  Move up to long crimp, match and head further right to side pulls.  Finish up crack/flake to easier terrain above.

name: Sit Burner
description: Same sit start as "Blubber Face", low and left. Move up to crimp then up to left sidepulls. Top out the same "Blubber Face".

name: Tier Two
description: Sit start with right hand on good vertical edge and left on sloping nothing.  Make a move into the crack on the left to continue up the face with some squeeze compression.    If you punt off the top you could miss the first tier pad.

name: Let's Go Fly a Kite
description: Start sitting, low and right on a left hand sidepull and a right hand meat-hook pinch.  Move up and left eventually using the arete to top out.  Fun warm up with comfy lip holds.

name: Let's Go Fly a Kite (Direct)
description: Same start as the traversing variation, but instead of heading left... top out straight up once you match the comfy lip hold.

name: Bearded Baby Jesus
description: Start on the left on a right hand flat crimp and left hand incut crimp above it.  Move right to a gaston, set up and throw for the lip.

name: Lil Bud
description: Start low and climb up compression arete right on same boulder as Bearded Baby Jesus.  Top-out is the crux.

name: Lost In The Wood
description: Start on obvious jugs and move up through cool compression moves to a classic DL topout.

name: No Man's Land
description: Begin low in the center of the face starting in a finger crack.  Follow the crack for a couple feet then find face holds as the rock face steepens.  Finish way up high with some committing moves to good holds.  Top out direct above where you started.

name: On That Lean
description: Start low and left on leaning column.  Move up the arete, slapping and squeezing.

name: On the DL
description: Sit-down start on the large horizontal crack. Move straight up using the face holds and pinches on the aretes.  Using only the face holds is a bit more stiff. Goes at about V4.

name: Short String
description: Fun little crack, would be great if it was longer.

name: Summer Time Chi
description: Climb tall slab with nice holds

name: Through the Wormhole
description: Start on opposing side-pulls, middle height of right column.  With feet low on the sloping rail, pop to the jug and top out through the notch.  A lower start is possible, but very scruchy and will be hard!

name: Sowing Life
description: Start with the large jug on the face. Climb the tall arete and detached block using awesome holds.

name: Higgs Boson
description: A short boulder with great moves. Stand start with right hand on an amazing pinch on the arete and left hand on the low block on the face. A big move to the lip leads to a tricky top out.

name: Barnyard
description: Start with your hands matched on the right side arete and follow it up using a right sloper to get onto the easy side. Really aesthetic arete climb that is on a ridge overlooking the lake. Definitely has been climbed before, but haven't been able to find it in anywhere on MP or a book. If you continue left instead of using the sloper it was definitely harder

name: Fallen Soldier
description: The line starts low left side of boulder. Climb up using the crack and some face holds..

name: Mysteriosa
description: Start on the right side of the slopey arête feature, right hand on a slope with and edge on it, left on an undercling. Climb left through the feature and finish it up.

name: On The Eve
description: Start on positive opposing sidepulls and go directly up the clean face on positive, comfy holds.  Nice warmup for the area.

name: Barking Spiders
description: SDS low and right.  Move left through protruding feature on face and throw to the lip.

name: Spirit Fingers
description: SDS on right arete of slightly overhanging face.  Move up using holds on the face and arete to gain the lip.  Top out is the crux and one could say it's a bit spicy for a V1.

name: Fake News
description: From a sit, left hand on a ledge and right on a low sidepull, climb the short arete.  The right most line on the little 3 boulder.

name: Lying Leadership
description: Center line on little 3 boulder.  Start matched on edge from a sit.  One way or another get the jug up and right and finish up the slab.

name: Russian Puppet
description: Start sitting matched on an obvious edge (same start as Lying Leadership). Bust big left to an incredible sloper then finish up the slab.  The left most line on the little 3 boulder.

name: Trash Panda
description: Start low and right with a LH undercling and RH on arete. Make a strong move to a thin sharp crimp on the slab and slap out left. Continue up and left to top out.

name: 52 to 1
description: Start matched on a good undercling and climb up fun holds on the slab.

name: Card Shark
description: Sit start on rail and make some difficult moves up overhang. Maybe bring a kneebar pad.

name: Never Tell Me the Odds
description: From a sit with a right facing jug, climb the dihedral feature. A nice little problem, probably of similar quality and a similar feature to There is No White Knight if you are familiar with that one though a bit more on the feet and a bit harder.

name: Wildwood
description: Gorgeous line starting on right side of face.  SDS with right hand on good ledge, left hand on decent sloper and feet out right.  Move out left to rail and use some fancy footwork to head up from there using decent holds and left arete.

name: Awning Crack
description: Climb large crack.

name: The Awning
description: Stem up to the block hanging over then find away around and top out

name: Mantel of Death
description: Start left of the cool roof feature on a big jug above your head, hand traverse out to the apex of the roof, and do an exposed and committing mantel.  Not too bad but feels exposed and scary... Really cool, definitely check out the top first.

name: Hybrid Wanderer
description: Good Route.  Start 4 feet left of small tree on crimps and delicately climb the thin face.  Find a good flat hold at the bottom of a triangular niche to gun for at the top.

name: Levitation (formerly The Office Project)
description: This boulder sticks out like a sore thumb in the talus field to the north of the lost and found area, it's simply huge!  On the downhill face of this boulder is a difficult thin climb.  All the holds are there, it was just over my head.  Landing is a flat elevated pedestal.  A little heady to spot, but should be fairly safe. A proud line there for the taking.

name: Not Your Grandmothers Boulder Problem
description: This is the scary left trending exit on the "Office Project" Boulder.     Sit start on good side pull make one move over the pedestal landing then trend left through an under-cling into definite no fall territory.   You will have good side pulls and one really high step to a committing move to a good sloper. Then jugs at the lip.    Keep breathing and stay calm this climb is not for the faint of heart.

name: Snack Room
description: Pretend that you in the gym and the floor is right under you.     Big moves on Big holds to a high top out.  Perfect to get blood flowing and to get use to topping out 20 ft off the deck.

name: Bossy
description: Start low in middle of boulder with obvious start holds.  Get a high right foot and do a hard mantle to gain a bad right hand side pull.  Make another hard move to gain the lip.

name: Chemotaxis
description: Chemotaxis climbs a beautiful looking overhanging rail. Start with your right hand on the jug and left on the low crimp. Follow the rail till you are able to throw for a jug and top out.

name: The Good Life Arete
description: Start low with slopey ledge and sharp point for right foot.  Climb up nicely featured arete with a big last move to the lip.

name: lost slab
description: start on low left point and climb up and right of fern. Fun slab

name: low lying fruit
description: Start on low jug climb up lip and holds under roof. When you get to last jug set high right foot and roll over it. Topping out is the hardest move.

name: SSS sit start slab
description: Start under right low roof and bump right hand to corner. Get left foot on face and roll your weight over it. A great problem with very low crux.

name: Old Man
description: Start on a jug and stand up on to a ledge from the ledge jump to another jug then continue on jugs to top.

name: The Bee's Knees
description: Start in Horizontal crack under rippled roof and work your way up good holds to the top out.

name: Bubble Gum Cigar
description: Start on the horizontal break at waist height and work your way up the tall, but easy slab. Be careful for loose rocks.

name: Cowboy Up
description: Start down and left in the corridor, bust a mantle, then trend right above the poor landing, encountering a scary delicate crux right at the top that would maybe really suck to botch...  awesome climb.   You can step off if you feel scared.

name: Dirty Pockets
description: A short crack with good dirty holds

name: Don't F With the Bees
description: Start sitting on jug flake down and right.  Climb up using compression encountering a tough move to a sloper near the end.   A good problem.  This was the Harpoon Project.

name: Limited Shelf Life
description: From a stand on compress your way up with awesome moves to an obvious jug about 14 feet up and drop, or continue up to the top.  We topped out, but it is a little sketchy with some big and maybe loose blocks.  Up to the jug is great climbing and still the same grade.   This is a very good climb.

name: Orchestra In Your Head
description: Start on the good holds at shoulder height and work your way up the tall arete, avoiding the thin crack out right (Never really comes into play). Cool holds on the arete itself and a few face holds out right lead you to a committing top section.

name: The Plank
description: Start on ledge and reach up for a side pull on the bottom of the overhang then get a high foot and reach for the large ledge mantel up onto the ledge then up to the top of the boulder.

name: Trust Face
description: start with high left side pull and low right hand mantle with a foot smear. Press up and get right foot on and move up. Trust your feet to hold and they might? More fun slabs!

name: Whales on Crack
description: Whales on Crack starts on jugs and moves into the large crack then tops out onto the detached block.

name: The Wizard
description: Difficult continuous compression problem on arete. Sit Start with left hand a descent side pull and right hand on arete.  Stand up on sloping feet and bump right hand to crimp.  A series of bumps and pinches to the top.

name: Six Foot Girlfriend
description: Sit start and match hands on the crimp. Work the left and right point crimps up the face and out the roof. Match on the second ledge for finish.

name: Cake Knife
description: From a crouch, with a good full pad sidepull for the right and left on a good slopey spot near the base of the arete, climb the technical and tricky arete. Gain better holds up high, mantle, and the easiest way off is to down climb left.  We both thought this was quite fun.

name: Dude, Where's My Keys?
description: A nice little compression boulder adjacent to the railroad tracks. Sit Start with feet on big ledge and hands squeezing the right and left areate.  Make a hard move or two and then find the easiest way up.

name: Funicular
description: Relatively vertical, splitter #5 crack in a right facing corner. Offwidth moves to an easier topout.

name: Grand Central
description: Sit start and go straight up the arete.

name: Steam Engine
description: Sit start on jugs as per Grand Central, move onto crimps on left face, dyno to lip.

name: Big Foot Arete
description: From a sit on the obvious big ledge, climb up the arete.

name: Birthday Arete
description: From a sit, climb up the NE arete.

name: Birthday Warm-up
description: Stand start with crimps on arete.  Pull on and climb arete to top.  Fun.   This has probably been done before.

name: Coreshot
description: Check out this route if your rope gets coreshot on that sharp quartzite and you don’t have any pads to boulder.Start at the bottom left of the boulder (in the water) and follow the seam up to the top.

name: Angular Sensations
description: Start sitting with a rightward facing jug, and possibly a heal hook.  Climb the overhanging arete feature through good angular holds and mantle it out.

name: Die Hard
description: Start on the left side of arete on jug and go up using cool sidepulls, topout rolling up over to the right.

name: Drawn On Eyebrows
description: Start in the the dihedral in the hole, matched on the lip (see photo).  Climb up via tense moves.

name: Empty Beer-can
description: Start on the big jug on the arete that shares the start of the Fukness, but climb directly up the arete and face holds.  Serves as a nice warm-up to do a few laps on.

name: The Fukness
description: Starting with a jug a chest level on the left arete, climb rightwards through the face on seams and crimps to a not so bad top out.  Get on this thing, it's a fun hard problem.

name: Horn of Africa
description: Start high, matched in the obvious slot or perhaps do a couple campus moves into it.  Move right, somehow gaining the big horn feature and finish it up.

name: Oak Savanna
description: Start matched on a sweet pinch.  Mantle directly up.

name: Out on a Limb
description: Start with a pinch on the lip for the left hand, and a lower edge for the right (see photo), gain the right arete and top out.  A right exit to Oak Savanna with a slightly different start.

name: Rarity Roof
description: A pretty wild one! Start with your left hand in a blocky gaston and right on a faint slipper next to it.  With some awkwardness set an extended, and aggressive toehook out right to establish on the problem.  Probably ride the toehook and shuffle out the right side of the roof to a somewhat easing finish.

name: Septic
description: From a sit, squeezing the slabby diamond-like feature, climb up and left with difficulty and trickery.

name: Vacation Grades
description: Vacation grades hell yeah.  Start wide in the pit.  Left hand on a flat halfpad crimp, right wide on the arete (see photo).  You probably will bump right up the arete then Dyno to the lip and mantle.  Yup, two moves oh hell yeah.

name: Whale’s Belly
description: Pull on with compression on sidepulls (I think, see photo..). And climb the belly feature.

name: Heatwave
description: Start crouched, right hand with an obvious full hand sidepull and left with a low sidepull. Squeeze up the arete top out. Pretty darn fun, the start is the crux.

name: Feature Presentation
description: A low start to Ice Queen. Start with left hand on a three finger tooth and right at the low part of the arete.  Climb into Ice Queen.

name: Ice Queen
description: I started from a stand with my left hand on a good hold on the arete, and right hand low, hamhocking a jug fin.  I thought this was a lot of fun.

name: Dolphin Fingers
description: Start with a left hand sidepull and right hand on three-finger dish above the lip.  Pull on with heel hooks and tension, move across the slopey lip eventually culminating in a toss for the lip jug.

name: Flipper
description: Mantle the overhanging block on the right side of the Ocean Floor Boulder.  Begin standing at the jugs in the break and surmount the quartzite bulge above you.

name: Lonely Oyster
description: Sit Start on the bottom corner of the boulder with good in-cut crimps.  Perch the feet high and avoid the dab as you move up the left hand arete and holds out right.  Top out directly above.

name: Ripples of Time
description: This is the low start to Dolphin Fingers and the whole line in my opinion.  Start with your right hand on the arete, and your left on a toothy and small 3 finger hold just above the lip.  Climb leftwards along the lip.  This is a physical compression problem and the moves are super fun.

name: Riptide
description: Climb the rippled slab that faces directly downhill.  Start with hands on opposing aretes, hike feet over the lip and balance your way up to the lip.  A fun and committing problem!

name: Bunker Arete
description: super good moves up the Arete and a fun top out. with some work most holes could be filled but with enough pads all things look better.

name: The Deserter
description: Start on 2 cool pinches at head height and move up and around the arete on great holds.

name: Muffin Top
description: Start on the right side of the obvious crack that runs through the width of the boulder and traverse left around the side of the boulder.

name: Spit Spot Spit
description: Start on a right hand undercling and left hand pinch and move up to a big move to the jug.  Very fun, natural movement.

name: Equestrian Project
description: Start matched on obvious slanted rail. Make a series of moves using the sharp crimp, arete, and side pull. Top out straight up. Watch out for the fragile rock to the left of this climb.

name: Jockey Rocket
description: Sit start with left hand jug and right hand crimp.

name: Little Jockey
description: Climb the face

name: No Place for a Horse
description: Start on low jug and climb to point. At first we did it with a right toe hook and that might have been a 4 but then we found a heel out left and that made it more like V2. Still super fun moves

name: Pony Rider
description: Start with small left side-pull and right sloper edge.  With some foot trickery and power, make your way up face.    Project eliminate: avoid any holds left of the crack.

name: The Pony
description: Start low on good edge and work your way up steep face.

name: Undercling Fling
description: Start low with undercling and small crimp.  Set heel and toss for good hold.  Top out.

name: Thoroughbred
description: Start on two slot-like holds on the face then pop to the jug ledge. Gain the lip and work your way to the top, and top out straight up.

name: Carrot On A Stick
description: Start right hand on the Arete, left hand on a small sidepull. Use either Arete and a variety of face holds to work your way up. Avoid the feature left of the crack.

name: Exotic Evangelical Equestrian
description: Start on left hand side pull and right hand pinch. Climb through a few good holds before encounter a cruxy sloper for your left hand just before the outro. Avoid using the obviously detached feature down low to the right.

name: Pegasus Was A Pony
description: Start matched on two crimps at about chest height and work you way up the face, topping out on the ledge. Downclimb the dirty dihedral to get down.

name: Ride The Pony
description: Start left hand on a good sidepull, right hand on the arete. Work your way up the easy, but somewhat broken arete through a variety of holds.

name: Shetland
description: A bit of an eliminate, start with feet on the belay ledge sized hold at the base of the wall, left hand on the side pulling crimp, and right hand on an undercling. Follow a variety of small crimps to a good ledge before a committing topout. Avoid the broken features on the right arete.

name: Bippity Bop
description: Start sitting with a rail and an edge.  Climb the slightly overhanging face, using the arete probably and top out.

name: Juice
description: Start low with left hand on arete and right under-clinging the boulder.  Set a bicycle with your feet and work way up face.

name: Plop on Top
description: Start sitting on the right side of the Bippity Bop boulder with a good ledge.  Do a few moves and mantle over with grace.

name: Solidarity
description: This is a good one if you are into steep, powerful stuff... and it’s not so far from the car.  A nice find by Baker. Start crouched with sidepulls.  A big opening move to a sloper with little edges on it likely leads to some moves left, a tricky foot cut or switch, and then a mantle that you might not want to fall off.

name: Unity
description: Start as for Plop on Top and traverse left through slopes and a shoulder move into the finish of Bippity Bop.  Pretty darn fun.

name: Unity Walk
description: Start low in pit and climb up fun and featured slab.  Easy warm up for the area.

name: Worth a Squeeze
description: Start with hand on right arete and left on horizontal pocket.  Slap the lip and top-out.

name: Balanced Rock
description: Pull onto block and gun for the summit.

name: Groth Arete
description: Climb up arete on small holds to jugs up high. EZ's guide says "to ledge at 17 feet and off" but the jugs start ~17 feet. It's perhaps 25 feet to the top. You can downclimb or traverse off at the jugs or top it out, I guess.  Apparently this has a name on top rope: Joy Ride.

name: The Anvil aka The Cardinal
description: Start sitting, squeezing low, wide sidepulls.  Maybe grab a jug up left first then trend up and right gaining an incredible slopey pinch in the middle of the face.  Shouldery and barn doory moves right to the arete then an easing finish.  The detached ledge/block feature right of the wall is not used.

name: Atlas Lion
description: Start sitting matched in an obvious vertical slot.  A powerful first pull followed by an incredible thin pinch, then a jug and an attention keeping finish.

name: Best Bulge aka Black Rhino
description: A true stunner! From the obvious jug climb straight up the tall overhanging wall.  Sustained and committing, though it does get easier at the top.

name: Little Dude
description: Start on low left jug. Bust out to good edge and reach juggy ledge. Top out

name: Orion
description: Start with left hand block under roof and right hand side-pull. Slap up arete and reach good crimp on face. Top out

name: Road Runner
description: A low trending version of The Cardinal.  Start as for the Cardinal, sitting with low wide sidepulls.  Move right, staying low and gaining the arete.  Finish it up.

name: Silently Judging
description: Starts with left hand on sidepull jug and right on vertical crimp.  Make a move left to a fat edge and windmill your way up to the roof.  After the roof keep your cool and bare down on the good crimps until your standing on the top.

name: Silently Judging Sit
description: The low start to Silently Judging.  Right hand starts on a softball sized hold and left on a vertical crimp.  Heal hook your way though some "comp style" climbing through the the start of the stand.

name: Beginners Luck
description: Strong handholds, with quick access to trails back to bottom. Great for first time out, but bring pads for your protection. Rentals with Wisconsin Climbing Association in Madison is great.

name: Bulbous Left
description: Start on good hold at the base of overhang.  Move out left to pinches and finish out the top.

name: Bulbous Left Center
description: A Classic hardman problem!  Start on good hold at base of overhang and make big moves to good pinches.  Technique and power get you up this one.  Top out right along the lip.

name: Final Cut
description: From a sit on the right arête of the Bulbous boulder, left hand on obvious juggy sidepull, and right on a low decent sidepull slot.  Pull through the center of the roof and join Bulbous to finish.

name: Finality
description: Climb the right arête of the Bulbous Boulder from a sit with a big left side pull and a slot on the right side of the arête.  More or less a direct finish to Final Cut.  A couple pinches on Bulbous below the lip probably won't be used.

name: Lost in Eden (Crimp Overhang)
description: Climb up pyramid shaped face on thin holds to a big dyno to jug.

name: Pony Ride
description: Sit start on large ledge and move up shallow dihedral with thin holds to top out.

name: Three Step
description: Start in the crack, then move up and left.

name: Two Step
description: Climb left side of face on thin holds, avoiding the left arete.

name: Wednesday Nighter
description: Climb obvious crack to top.

name: An Intro to Heel Hooking
description: Fun short problem. Bump up to left meat hook and surf up and right into a few heel hooks.

name: Easy Going Lou Reed
description: Climb up the very juggy and low angle face.

name: Lou Reed Arete
description: Climb up the arete just left of Lou Reed crack.  Really fun!

name: Lou Reed Crack
description: Climb up crack on the SE face of boulder.

name: Lou Reed Lunge
description: Climb LR Crack and at 8ft mark dyno to hold out right.

name: Lou Reed Pinches
description: Start around the left of Lou Reed arete on the slabby face and climb straight up with the fin hold.

name: Lou Reed Squeeze
description: From a stand with your right hand on the arete and left in the crack, go up the boulder. Sit start goes at V3.

name: A Feather in the Wind
description: An obvious and tricky line.. Start with the jug in the roof.  Perhaps set a knee bar with some awkwardness and climb out.

name: Finding the Right Balance
description: Start right hand on good jug under roof and left out on coarse sloper at lip.  Pull on and squeeze your way up boulder.  Powerfull and dynamic!

name: Francesca’s Pillar
description: Just right (east) of A Feather in the Wind.  Start with your left hand on the left arete and right on a sidepull in the face.  A fun little climb.

name: Don't Want Your F!@ $%g Trail Mix
description: Start on two pinches down low with tight foot,  throw for jug. use side pull and jugs out ride to top out

name: Saddle Sores
description: Another one with interesting beta.  SDS with hands on both sides of the roof and your back facing the wall.  Pull your legs up and over until you have mounted the horse.   Does anyone have a copy of the Rock and Ice issue that featured pictures of Eric sending this thing?  If so please scan them in.

name: Superstition
description: Establish on the clean wall with two holds at waist level, a sidepull crimp for the left and an undercling for the right.  A very cruxy start and bumps up the arete will gain a crimp and better holds above.  Traverse the break off left and down climb.  The juggy sidepull left of the arete near the start is not used.

name: Travesty
description: From a sit, with the right hand in a two finger undercling pocket tooth, and left just below, climb the arete.  The name stems from wanting to start where the feet are but it is a bit cramped.

name: Battle Wound
description: Start left on sloper and traverse right to gain corner.  A mix of power and technique get you to the top on this one.    A direct line out the roof would be really hard.     Has anyone been on this before?  It's obvious from the base of the talus field.

name: Block Corner
description: Start low with good under-clings, work the feet and dead-point to lip.  Heady top-out.

name: Butter Burger
description: Hard!  Climb steep face starting with opposing gastons.  Make hard move to triangle pinch and get to arête.  Top-out.

name: The False
description: From a stand, matched on a left facing block hold, pull on with difficulty and climb up through slopey pinch holds to a juggy hold.  From there move left to top out.

name: Get the Party Started
description: Start low on good holds and work your way up jugs.

name: Pre-Party
description: Start low in crack and get to jug. From there work your way up edges and slopers.

name: True Lies
description: Start as for the False, matched on the obvious blocky hold.  Climb up the face, gaining the right arete and topping out at the apex of the Boulder.  An intricate, proud, and striking line.

name: Ice Man
description: From a sit with your left hand in a crack, right on a sidepull, climb the striking arete.  Be wary of loose rock up high.

name: Crimp On
description: Starting with a right undercling and a gaston, power through the short, overhanging face to an easing finish.  In the DL Bouldering Guide as a V5 from a higher start.

name: Night Grinder
description: Stand start with left crimp and right on slopey ledge, hike feet and throw for lip.  Swing feet right and get good heel and toe hooks and bump your way up arete.  Fun climbing and very gymnastic!

name: Hazy Warmup
description: Short problem on the Southeast Arete. Sit start and move to huge right facing flake feature. Top out using numerous good feet.

name: I Got Five On It
description: Fun start. Hang off the huge start hold, left foot has a good hold under the boulder, right foot out to a small toe catch. Make a big throw to a sloper. Match that, move up to gain easier climbing. Pretty pumpy little number.

name: Northeast Arete
description: Climb on big holds to top of Northeast Arete if you are bored. Use detached block on the ground or not, won't make much of a difference.

name: Roll One Up
description: Sit start using the left hand start hold on "Smoker's Delight" for your right hand and a small crimp on the face for you left. Your right foot uses the same low right foot as the start of "Smoker's Delight". Make a throw to a good right crimp, move up to the small thumb catch, gain the upper crimp and top out.

name: Smokers Delight
description: Northwest Arete on the Purple Haze boulder. Sit start with decent right hand crimp in small seam. Left hand low on good hold. Move up to bigger and bigger holds.

name: Snuggle Bunny
description: On the West side of the boulder.  From a sit, left hand on blade hold and right on a seam crimp climb the short rippled face into good holds to the top.  There are some aggressive holds on this one.

name: Solar Slab
description: Start with good holds in horizontal crack, finger mantle up to small finger lock.  From there balance your way to the top.

name: Le Corbusier
description: Begin using a tricky right knee scum with left hand is low on a good sidepull and right hand is higher on a sloped sidepull both on the left arete. Compress into the starting position and cross left hand high on the arete to a sidepull with a thumb catch. Move along the lip right to the other side of the boulder. Stay tight for a technical top out up across the face.

name: Double Trouble
