description: Start matched on a slanting rail.  A few tricky moves up the arete gets you a good hold.  Move left, through seams and a long move to a better hold.  Gain the crack left, then keep going left utilizing a couple thin holds and a pinch.  Gain the arete and easily top out the spire.  Long and really fun I think.  Not so dangerous feeling, though with the double tiered landing it deserves some caution. The direct crack finish has also been done which definitely ups the danger level a bit, though is about the same difficulty.

name: Self Quarantine
description: From an obvious jug, climb the striking arete.  The direct version stays very true to the arete and is quite airy.  The other version stays slightly right, using the arete and more face holds, and is also airy.  If you traverse in from the Social Distancing start it likely adds a grade (FA Evan Stoddard?)

name: Social Distancing
description: Loooong, pretty fun and tricky.  On the Double Trouble boulder just on the other side.  Start in crack.  Traverse right through the crux.  Climb a fairly moderate slab to gain the second tier and finish up the arete (same one Double Trouble finishes on).

name: The Ghost
description: From a stand, climb the striking and tall arete.

name: The Naturalist
description: Start sitting with obvious sidepulls.  Climb the tricky and technical arete.

name: Thrasher
description: A sweet little compression rig!  See photo for the starting position we did!

name: Beanie Baby
description: A fun little boulder!  Start matched on a sloper dish on the left side of the arete.  Climb right along the arete, wrap the corner and finish it up.  It’s possible to exit the feature earlier but dabby and a bit easier. Ride it out for a complete life experience, ya know.

name: Decadence
description: Excellent line up the CCC Trail Project boulder! Begin under the roof with a left hand slot crimp and a right hand block. Establish and climb out of the roof onto the textured vertical face avoiding the detached block under the roof. Great movement up a proud boulder!

name: ObZen
description: Follow the horizontal crack out from under the roof then straight up useing both aretes and the face    On the same boulder as the CCC trail project

name: Farmer's Crack
description: Nice warmup crack just to the right of Farmer's Daughter. Easy layback moves with small feet on the left face.

name: Farmer's Daughter
description: Gain steep slab using a couple thin feet to start.  First couple moves are the crux.

name: Farmers Wife
description: Fun slab route and definitely not climbed enough.  Use the face only and if you eliminate the right side flake/jug it's a little bit tougher, but a lot more fun.  I love going on the boulder just left of it and doing the left side arete, then farmers daughter, the crack in between the two rocks, and then the wife for a perfect warmup.    The top out is a little gross.

name: Heads Up Arete
description: Sweet boulder 15ft off of CCC trail. Start at right side overhand with small crimp on corner and follow the rail/arete to the exciting top out. Sit start and face direct are significantly harder.

name: Easy Crimps
description: Follow positive crimps up the vertical face.

name: Mosstop Cocktail
description: Climb the right arete and top out straight over for V1/2. Follow lip over to left arete for V3 top out. Fun moves with a little moss on top

name: On Your Knees
description: Start on two dished out flat jugs. Move up right to obvious pinch. Double knee bars are a option here. Surf left hand up arete and move right to the lip.

name: Rail Gun
description: Start on Undercling sidepulls and finesse your way out the little roof and then move up and right to top out

name: Rail Gun Left
description: Start as for Rail Gun but head left at the lip instead of right.  Sharp!  Good movement though.

name: Beer Buzz
description: Start on thin section low and climb up face.

name: Big Flat Iron
description: Start from a sit, matched on the polished foot most use for their feet for the classic Flat Iron.  Crimp down and bust a tricky move left to a good side pull and continue up the Flat Iron. This will probably get some heat but four of us did this and we all thought it was pretty fun.  So there ya go.

name: The Captain's Traverse
description: Start at the base of the left corner and traverse right with reachy moves between good holds.

name: Crack
description: Climb up thin seam and move left up high to easier finish.

name: The Flatiron
description: The first rock an out of breath climber encounters upon reaching the East Rampart is the Flatiron, a perfect little boulder reminiscent of its much larger counterparts in Colorado.  Two parallel cracks spill down from the top, and the difficulty of the problem lies in attaining these cracks. Easier variations exist on both sides. One hard variation uses only the right crack.  Climb this problem on a busy summer weekend, and be prepared to feel like an animal in a zoo.    I hesitate to list this as a "chipped route" despite the rumors that Gill deliberately broke a loose flake out of the upper pocket in the right crack.  Gill was bad ass, and it seems unclear why he would chip an already large hold on the easier upper part of the problem.  Does anyone know if the rumor is true?

name: Flatiron-right side
description: Crack on right side of the Flatiron. Climb this as a consolation for flailing and failing on the Flatiron.

name: Highball
description: Same start as the Crack, but stay right on face and avoid the left arete.

name: Martini Madness
description: Start on left arete and face holds eventually getting up and right into upper face.

name: Straight Shot
description: Interesting beta.  Start in Crack, and at the 5ft level move right.  Avoiding the seam and good holds above it, move up on thin crimps and slopers.     I'm wondering if this has seen a repeat.  Jim(shoe guy) showed this to me a long time ago but I can't recall if he sent it.

name: Unzipped(aka The Zipper Direct)
description: Same start as the Zipper, but from the finger jug you stay direct on the wall.   Classic moves with a scary and hard finish!  Harder than the original.

name: The Zipper
description: This is an impressive effort by Eric Zschiesche. The blank looking face to left of Monster was an aid climb. Now, a balls out high ball boulder problem. It's not "git on it" but "GIT UP IT!!!!"

name: Anarchist Crack
description: Route 57 in Sven's book. Short but very enjoyable crack climb. Better off bouldering this route.

name: Beer Can Full of Roaches.
description: Another climb that is too short for a rope but easy enough to climb with out pads. It's a great area to warm up in before a day of climbing.

name: Decapitation
description: Route 58 in Svens book. Another one better off bouldered. (Climb wall just right of corner to upper ledge. Continue on small holds to the top.)

name: Gopher
description: Seeing as the Guillotine is a great area to get warmed up at, this is a great route to warm up your psyche.  The crux is right at the top trusting a tiny edge for a foot and reaching for the lip at the top. A must do while in the area.     Gopher climbs up the arete on a detached pillar split by the Guillotine chimney.

name: Guillotine West
description: An enjoyable tight chimney climb. Get on it.

name: Mezzanine Arete
description: Make big moves on big holds to climb the arete to the right of Mezzanine Credit. Topout (crux) on the ledge above.

name: Mezzanine Credit
description: A short problem for the tall climber. Crimps and a high-step lead to an attention getting topout. Use the face holds between the aretes to ascend the slightly slabby face.

name: The Nihilist
description: Sweet slab climbing up a beautiful quartz face.  Stand start in the thin seam left of Anarchist Crack, and go straight up.  Arete to the left, and Anarchist Crack to the right are off, but don't really come into play.

name: Fat Pants
description: Start matched on the low jug on the left side and compress up the arete.  Fun climbing

name: Headbanger
description: Start in the low horizontal seam and climb the left arete of the pretty white face.  Good climbing and rock, the landing is just annoying and crappy.

name: The Ivory Face
description: Climb the center of the beautiful, blank looking, white wall from a sit in the obvious horizontal.

name: Room to Grow
description: Sit start at left side pull and right hand on crack. Move up to break and top out right while avoiding the detached block. The trick is to avoid destroying the growing tree.   Location    On the left before Ivory Face and Fat Pants if heading up from Little Flatiron    Protection    1 or 2 pads

name: 2nd Wind
description: SDS low with higher right hand side-pull and lower left hand side-pull. Set feet and gun for good sloper.  Set you hands, and hike feet.  Get into the mantle for the finish.

name: Bachelor-ete
description: Start under small roof on good edge.  Toss out left and follow the arete to the top.  Fun warm-up.

name: Slab of Doom
description: Start low and right on big ledge.  Move out left to good edges and work feet to gain high in-cut crimp.  Top-out.

name: Bad Backwards
description: Start with a left hand edge around the arête, and right hand on the other arête where the angle changes.  Wrestle out the steep fridge feature and top out.  Close to the ground, though the feature and climbing are great.  If you enjoy steep, squeeze rigs check this one out.

name: Brinton’s Arete Left V3/V6 sit
description: For the sit, start on the left side of the arete, with a low downpulling crimp for the left hand and a gaston for the right.  Climb the left side of the arete.  A sustained and pretty darn good problem with a quite a good landing.  For the stand, just stand.  It’s a sweet problem.  From a previous description by Peter Erard in 2007 : "The crux would be the second move from a standing start. What's bad about it? The hands, barely any handholds. When there are handholds, they're non-existent. Semi-sharp edges leading into a slopy two-finger edge. From there, finish on top with a solid bomber hold."

name: Bubble Bee
description: Start low with two good slot holds.  Get a right heel-toe cam and with some tension climb out roof along crack.

name: Autumnal Fire
description: Start sitting with a left hand sidepull crimp and a right hammock on the arete. A few moves through cool and not as good as you would think holds will get you near the top, then finish it up.  A fun and safe little problem.

name: Dry Fired
description: Just left of Flux Boulder Classic on the same face.  Start sitting on boulder with a slick right pinch and a left sidepull.  A couple cruxy moves gain the arête left and an easing finish.

name: Flux Boulder Classic
description: The left Obvious Line on the Flux Boulder.  Start standing on the big right facing sidepull feature and climb up the technical face with cool holds to a slightly insecure topout.  In the shade most the day since a large pine tree is over the boulder.

name: Flux Warm-up
description: Sit down start with good edges and climb up corner of boulder.

name: Purple Shadow
description: A traverse on the Flux Boulder.  Sticky Arête into the far left line Dry Fired.

name: Sticky Arete
description: On the far right side of the downhill side of the sap boulder start sitting on the double arete and climb to the top.  The mantle is a little slopey.  Fun.

name: [Redacted]
description: Start on the far right side of the boulder on big holds (obvious start holds). Throw up your heal and move left, topping out on the left arete. Pumpy.

name: Fist Fight
description: You'll find this monster directly below Brinton's Buttress. Move down through the talus until you come upon a large overhanging boulder with a huge roof fist crack. The Good - it's a giant roof crack. The Bad - it's painful as hell. Tape is highly recommended.

name: Gills Booger
description: Stand start with large pinch feature.  Hike feet and dead-point to lip.  Top out along lip to the right.

name: Long Arm John
description: Start in the middle of the boulder, directly under the overhang. Left hand on 3 finger crimp, right hand on large rail to the far right. Bump to a weird pinch and move right. Big moves. Top out is obvious.

name: High Crimes and Misdemeanors
description: Start from a sit or crouch under the overhanging belly.  Right hand on a sloper edge above arete, left on a positive edge.  Squeeze out the bulge and send the boulder.  Quite good, spot the finish well.  A lower start is a project.

name: Diesel Additive
description: Start with the same sidepull for the right hand as for Influx and a slopey undercling just left and down in the roof for the left.  A burly first move leads to more climbing out the roof and up the arete.  A lower start to Influx.

name: Influx
description: Sit down start with right hand on large side-pull and left on corner near the arete.  Set your feet, keeping a tight, right heel-hook, and work your way up the arete.  Top-out is a bit heady because you climb over a pit.

name: Lip-enstein
description: Start with good edge on right side of lip.  Traverse left using perfect crimps and side-pulls while keeping a right heel-hook the whole way.  Turn the corner(crux), and hike up sloping arete to finish.

name: Back Scratcher
description: SDS with two slopey edges.  Using some tricky footwork, power your way up using crimps and slopers.  Getting your feet up high is the crux.    Pictures to come...

name: Mixed, But Not Stirred
description: Sit start with left hand on sharp jug and right on the arete.  Bump right up to get slopey jug, and either go straight up or move left a bit and top-out.  The stand start is maybe V0.

name: Funeral Service
description: Start low and left on good side-pulls.  Work your way up center of face using a combination of balance and power.  Finish move is exciting!

name: Orgasm Arete
description: Climb right arête on the Orgasm Boulder.

name: The Undertaker Arete
description: Start with jug and work your way up arête using good flakes and pinches.  Fun but scary dyno to the lip for the finish.

name: The Pedestal
description: Climb the the Hanging double arete Boulder.

name: The Piano
description: From a sit on the uphill side of the boulder with your left hand on a good edge on the lip and your right on the low jug, pull on and follow interesting slopey holds that you will have to grab just right all the way around the corner and top out.  Really fun and pumpy!  Do be careful though, if you explode off there is a very good chance you could go tumbling down the hill...

name: Purple Hatchet
description: With a sidepull for the left hand and a slick pinch crimp for the right, establish with difficulty.  A couple tense and hard moves will get you to the mantle.  A blubber pad would be nice for this one.

name: Purple Hatchet Project
description: From a sit climb the aesthetic arete.  There are holds and maybe there is a way.

name: Brave Heart
description: Climb directly up the left arete of the downhill side of the Rampart Roof Boulder.  This is a cool and exposed feeling climb with the hard moves at the top.

name: Cory's Problem
description: On the rampart roof boulder.  On the left of the downhill facing side and do a tricky sequence to a good hold and trend left on jugs above a boulder and mantel it out.

name: Purple Heart
description: Start in the Center of the downhill facing overhanging face and go right around the arete and topout on the slab.  The safety line on the boulder.

name: Rampart Roof
description: Start low in middle of boulder and work your way up and out roof to good holds at the lip.  Two variations exist.     Wow, this boulder is impressive!  It sits about 50ft down the talus from Many Pines Buttress and sticks out like a sore thumb.  It's huge and has a beautiful roof with lots of features.

name: Sketch Slab
description: Climb up from a sit the slab just right of the right arete (Summer Lovin') of the Rampart Roof boulder.  a little forced to not trend right in easier territory, but good moves, and exciting.

name: Purple Roof
description: Starting on the boulder beneath the roof, climb out the right side of the roof on good holds.  The mantle is the crux.  Probably harder if you're shorter.

name: Sea of Purple
description: Start on the block below the roof and climb out the left side on cool holds.  There is a definitive thrutchy crux getting to the lip.  Could be easier for the taller.

name: Green Sharpie
description: From the start of Purple Sharpie (sit, left hand on edge by left arete, right hand in the face on an incut side pull), move left, rock onto the slab, and finish up the slab via the face and arete.  Surprisingly fun, we thought.

name: Highliter
description: Start in the pit, matched on an obvious edge.  A big move to the lip and a few more moves will get you outta there.

name: Inkwell
description: Start on obvious rail, possibly with a gaston spot for the left hand.  Gain an undercling in the face and pull through to better holds above.  An elegant little problem.

name: Pocket Protector
description: A sweet little problem, start sitting on the left side of the clean arete, left hand out on the face with an undercling and right hand on the arete at the second bump feature (probably the best feeling spot).  Pull on, gain a better hold on the arete and finagle your way to the top.

name: Purple Sharpie
description: Start sitting with right hand in small incut edge on face, left hand crimp on arete. A few fun compression moves will get you to the top.

name: Fully Aroused
description: Start on good in-cut edge.  Crank you way up left to dime-edge crimp.  Get your feet set and hit the top.  Technical and fun.

name: Groggy
description: Thin and balancy start.  Make your way up and a little left to good side-pulls.  Top-out.  Good footwork gets you to the top of this one.

name: Still Awake
description: Sharing the right arete with the V1 Still Sleeping, this compression problem was uncovered after a tree blocking the left arete was mysteriously removed.  Differing in character from other climbs on the sleepytime boulder, this problem relies more on power than technical footwork. From a stand, find small feet, squeeze both aretes, and power your way up to the boulder's apex. The good holds, slight overhang, and clean landing make this thing great!

name: Still Sleeping
description: Stand start with good side-pull holds.  Set feet, and mantle up to reach good edges up high and right.  Top-out.

name: Golden Crescent
description: From a sit with your right hand on a low pinchy crimp and left on a side pull (the low good part of the scoop feature), climb the short face right of the scoop.  And yes, your left hand uses the scoop feature but stay on the face.

name: Inception
description: Start sitting underneath the overhanging blade feature, left hand on the arete, right in a low crispy edge.  A low right toe hook could be useful.  Climb the feature and finish it up. More climbing than you would think, 3/4 pads would be ideal, then it is fun and safe.

name: Space Pants
description: Sit start under small roof with right hand on good edge and left hand on dimple feature and climb up the prow.

name: Witness the Slickness
description: Start with low, wide sidepulls.  Gain slopers and follow them to finish with jugs.

name: Z's Arete
description: SDS around left corner from Z's face.  Use arete to establish on face then up to top.

name: Z's Face
description: start standing in pit. use underclings and same feet then dead point or lunge to top.

name: Shredder
description: From an undercling jug at the base of the route Vivisection, pull on and traverse right, staying low. Pass through several very small holds, yank through them, keep going and once you hit the next crack system (Bucket Brigade/The Funnel) grab the wedged block. Give it a few taps with your hand, and you've sent.

name: Capstone
description: Start on the left corner and climb up between the left arete and hand crack.  Nice big moves.

name: Easy Arete
description: Climb up big and fun corner just right of Footstone.

name: Footstone
description: SDS at the bottom of the blocky wall, and climb up through fun holds.

name: Headstone
description: Just around the corner from Thin Crack, start in middle of wall and climb up thin holds to top out.

name: Headstone Left
description: Start low on pinch and work your way up seam with crimps to good holds.  Heads up at the top!

name: Leaning Tower South Face
description: Highball/solo up the rear slabby face.  After doing either a lowish traverse from left to right (V1) or going straight up the right arete (V0), hike up the staircase ledges and top out.

name: Left Crack
description: From the left side climb up into jam crack.

name: Right Crack
description: Ascend right most crack on Tombstone wall.

name: Textured Face
description: Climb up the tall and well featured sandstone face past the Tombstone wall.  Good warm up.

name: Textured Face Right
description: Start to the right of the large vertical crack in the sandstone. (No using the crack or the perpendicular facing wall on the right). There are a couple good slopers and finger holes to make use of.    Fun warm up.

name: Thin Crack
description: Crank the face moves up into good jug, from there climb nice splitter crack to top.

name: Tombstone Classic
description: Same start as Tombstone Direct, then up-and-right (but still perhaps more direct than the direct?). The route stays just left of crack in the upper wall.    A classic in its own right, this is Gill's original line on the wall.

name: Tombstone Direct
description: Start on crescent holds in the middle of face.  Head up and left for a tricky finish.

name: Tombstone Left
description: Start sitting with a prominent sidepull left of the Tombstone classic.  Without the giant foot ledges, gain pockets up and left with some difficulty and finish up the tall hand crack.

name: A Glimpse Beyond the Veil
description: Start on a jug at the far right side of the wall underneath the roof. Traverse left through a series of good holds eventually reaching a jug pinch at the lip. Set feet and head up the arete.

name: Bruised and Confused aka Dong of Dob
description: Sit start on left arete. Climb straight up.

name: Cankle Arete
description: Start on obvious feature with undercling and side pull. Traverse left to the arete and climb it using the hard-to-spot crimps.

name: Cheers to Voyager
description: Start left hand side pull middle of face in cave.  Right hand jug on right arete.  Work out right side of roof.  A few moves, mantle, freedom.

name: Chiseled Edge
description: This thing is way too hard for me to ever have a chance of sending, but all the holds are there. It likely starts matched on a half pad crimp rail down low. A few powerful moves on perfect edges and horridly small feet leads to an easy finish. It is about 25 degrees overhanging. Edit: Ben Summay has done a V7ish version of this.  See photo for his starting position.  He thinks he maybe could add another move.

name: Critters
description: Start matched on low horn used as a heal as for pivot point.  Climb the Boulder.

name: Dazed and Contused
description: Right arete and face. Crux is high (last move). I sat started, but had to dig out a rotten pile of leaves to do so and I don’t think a sit adds anything.

name: Flesh Rodeo
description: Sit start on slopey shelf on the right side of the boulder, climb up the overhanging face and then mantle for the finish. In my opinion a very good obvious pure boulder problem.

name: Haploid
description: Stand start with right hand meat hook and left hand on notched area of the arete. A few powerful moves on edges leads to a jug system that trends left to the top out.

name: I See the Bucket
description: Climb tall face with a committing topout.  This face feels almost like sandstone with actual texture.  Originally a toprope and listed in the "West Post" crag in Swartling guide.  Without using the arete it's listed as 11a (the Variation) and with the arete 10a.  I originally did it without the arete not knowing it was already a TR, but since have been back and done it with the arete; it's probably a better problem with the arete, and only a touch easier.

name: Inquisition
description: The left face of the same boulder as "Perscrutation." Start in the pit with two slopey compressions on the arete. Continue to use both aretes and some muscle to move up the face.

name: Jafar
description: Left arete of cool over hanging boulder. Any way up. Right arete is considerably harder

name: Little Pine Tree
description: Sit start on a good left hand rail and right hand edge. Do a couple of big moves on small holds to gain the compression features of the arete and continue to an easy topout. Tom insisted this be called "Joel's Little Pine Tree."

name: Lost and Abused
description: Start low on right lay-back rail and work your way up face to comfy top-out.  A couple variations you can do on this boulder.

name: Neutral
description: Start on the arete and a slopey left hand crimp. Use the large block for feet. Trend left across face using good holds. Top out left.

name: Oogenesis
description: Start low with hands matched on left facing pinch rail. Powerful left hand move to gain the start hold of Young Eggs.

name: Over Easy
description: Climb the juggy blunt arete with a committing top.

name: Perscrutation
description: Start on sharp left hand undercling and small right hand crimp. Make a big move and then, using compression, continue up the face.

name: Pivot Point
description: Start from a crouch with a sloper pinch for the right hand, left on a good sidepull in the face, and a right heel hook.  Move right gaining rail systems, a jug and an easing finish.

name: Pivotal Project
description: Start as for Pivot Point and climb the obvious squeeze feature.

name: The Postmaster
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: Rocket Man
description: A low start to Cheers to Voyager.  Start with low sidepulls from a sit.  A hard opening move (probably with the left hand) leads to more tricky climbing and a dabby but manageable finish.

name: Spelunker
description: Start low on two underclings and a massive foot. Move diagonally up the face on tenuous feet and good crack system to a casual, but fun finish. A very unique climb. This would be 3 stars if not for the dabby start and un-protectable landing.

name: Spinal Tap
description: Start left side and work right using sloper in mouth of boulder.  Obtain slopey jug on center prow and wiggle your way up and right.

name: Surrounded by the Lonely
description: Start on the left facing jug. Climb through great underclings and sidepulls to an airy topout. Stays on you the whole time.

name: Swivel Sit
description: Sit start with left hand edge and right out in crack.  Stand into side-pull and slap the juggy arete.  Top-out.

name: V-Easty
description: Groove your way up easy slab

name: Warmup
description: Topping out is crux.  Would not trust center hollow flake.

name: Young Eggs
description: Start matched on a slightly positive flake. Pull a series of heel-hooky moves around the corner to an easy topout.

name: Zebra Slab
description: A very cool face. Climb straight up the middle using good edges and side pulls. Crux is halfway up.

name: Atari Dream
description: Low start on good jugs and work up and around the left (west) arete.

name: Atari Nightmare
description: Start right hand on notch of the right arete, left on blocky pinch. Climb straight up the double aretes compressing to the lip. A fall at the top would be dangerous.

name: Bald Eagle
description: If you are standing at the lookout this probably tops out right where you are. Start sitting with sidepulls.  Move through a sidepull and a slopey ledge and finish up the airy arete.  And you are back on the lookout.

name: Barn Swallow
description: Start under roof with left hand on block pinch and right on sloping side-pull under a notch.

name: Carcass
description: Start matched on good ledge, climbing up through a great pinch and edges.

name: Carrion
description: Start from a crouch with a pockety hold for the right hand and an edge for the left.  Climb through the center of the pillar feature, gaining an undercling, a huge foothold, and pop for the lip.  A left version goes at V3, a right about V2.

name: Charlize Heron
description: Start sitting with a slopey right hand and a faint gaston for the left.  Climb the slab, gaining a good edge for the right hand and a pocket for the left.  A long move to the next break and an easing finish follows.

name: Electric Sky
description: From a sit with good low holds climb through the lightning boltesque feature to an engaging mantle.  A spot and a few pads are nice.  Get on it!

name: Emperor Penguin
description: From an obvious left facing sidepull climb the face through sidepulls and utilizing the arete higher.  A longer pull to the lip, mantle and boom, you’re standing on the lookout.  No detached blocks are used.

name: Empty Nest
description: Obvious start on ledge and goes up to a good right hand gaston.  Tops out direct.

name: Escanaba in da Loonlight
description: Start sitting with a jug for the left hand and a bad, slopey undercling for the right.  Bust a big move for the right hand and finish it up.  Next to Loon Song.

name: Featherweight
description: Start low on good ledge climb up and right through roof and climb up jugs on the face. V1 variation - Climb the direct straight up though triangle feature directly above start and quest up the face.

name: Finches
description: Start sitting with right hand undercling/sidepull and left on a pinch. Climb up arete.

name: Fledgling
description: From a sit on the slabby side of the arete, balance and squeeze up, transferring left to the overhanging side at 2/3rds height and finish it.  A little dabby and not the best landing but a long and fun problem.

name: Freebie
description: Start on large right hand side-pull feature and small left hand. Work through the bulge.

name: Gristle
description: Climb the tall slab, avoiding detached blocks.

name: Ground Strike
description: Low start to Electric Sky. Start at the base of the small gulley on a jug. Climb a series of relatively easy, yet taxing moves into the start of Electric Sky and top out as for that boulder.

name: Hawk Watch
description: Start low on left slot and good right hold and lock off to hit the funky crimp.  Work your way up face and top out.

name: Learning to Fall
description: Climb up boulder to a cool and committing top-out

name: Learning to Fly
description: Climb fun easy boulder to a really cool top-out.

name: Linchpin
description: Start with a low right hand edge and a left hand jug at about head height. Interesting moves lead up the gently overhanging feature.

name: Loon Song
description: From a sit with a sidepull feature under the roof and a sidepull with the right hand, climb the Boulder.

name: Medium Smalls
description: Start in obvious pockets. Make two dynamic moves to the lip.

name: Murder
description: Start matched on large undercling and climb up double arete feature to the lip.

name: Overgrown
description: Start with a right hand side-pull and left hand on the arete. A few powerful compression moves lead up the face. Detached blocks are not used.

name: Pigeon Post
description: Start right hand on arete and left on a jug in the face. Climb straight up the overhang by compressing. A spotter would be good for the top.

name: Tweety Bird
description: Start left hand on ledge and right hand on arete. Slap up arete and topout.

name: The Verdant Wilds
description: Start matched in the horizontal crack underneath the roof. A few powerful moves lead to a tall slab.

name: Woodwose
description: Start matched in a jug around the corner and work up the aretes.

name: Baby Bringer
description: Start standing with right hand edge left hand gaston.

name: The Baker’s Fantasy
description: From the jug start of Fire Escape, move left, gain the arete and continue on.  Grade unconfirmed and not graded on the FA.

name: Big Bird
description: Start matched on a slopey edge.  Climb through sidepulls and punch a big move to a jug.  Top out.

name: The Big Year
description: Start the same as for Chicken Run but move right into a large side pull and climb up exiting the left side of the roof.

name: Chicken Run
description: Start matched low on a good ledge, climb up the left side of the arete on good edges.

name: Dodo
description: Start from a sit, squeezing the supreme slabby feature with your left hand on the arete.  A few slaps, fancy footwork and a long pull will land you on top.

name: Duck Tales
description: Pure and tricky..  Start matched from a stand in the obvious juggy undercling.  Climb the very clean arete.  A delicate and powerful problem.

name: The Filigree Feather
description: Start on the massive jug and climb straight up the committing arete. The right wall is off and traversing left to the face drops the grade to V1.

name: Fire Escape
description: Start on the shelf in the mini corridor. After a couple not so bad moves to nice edges, bust a big move to a crimp right then head right through the roof feature and top out as for Spiral Staircase, gaining the arete and mantling into the scoop.  Fun and funky.

name: First Flyte
description: up the huge flake using the obvious holds

name: Hoots the Owl
description: Sit start on low sidepull jug and right hand scoop. Traverse left behind the tree and continue up the arete.

name: Mockingjay
description: Start sitting with an obvious ledge system, probably hamhocking with the left hand.  After a tricky first sequence climb up and right out of the cave.  A lengthy Boulder problem for the lake.

name: Plumage
description: Start sitting with a jug.  Climb up and left through edges and slots and finish.

name: Spiral Staircase
description: From an obvious ledge system climb up and left out of the cave.  A left exit to Mockingjay (same start) and probably a little harder.

name: Spread Your Wings
description: Possibly the first thing you will look down on walking to the Vulture Lookout East.  Start sitting matched on the left arete.  Move right through a slot, gaining good sidepulls, probably quite extended.  Work thin feet and fire off a long move and top out.  No feet or hands are used right of the right crack, and no holds left of the starting arete.. Sounds contrived but makes sense when you climb on it.. just climb the beautiful shield of rock.

name: The Stork
description: Stand start on good edges, climb up with big moves on great holds.

name: Swimming Pools
description: Sit start on large undercling feature. Work up the face using interesting and comfy holds.

name: Yankee Buzzard
description: From a sit climb the slabby arete.

name: B Sides and Rareities
description: A tricky little thing! Start crouched, with a small left hand around arete and a lower right sidepull.  With precise foot work, establish, gain the lip and probably move a little left to mantle.

name: Simon’s Butter Sculpture
description: Start sitting, left hand undercling in the face, right on a crimp on the right side of arete.  With some difficulty, pull on, gain the prominent juggy side pull and climb the arete.

name: Easy Life
description: SDS on right side of face.  move to right arete and follow arete to apex of boulder and top out

name: Pulling Downs
description: SDS in middle of Triangular face. climb straight up to apex of boulder

name: Red Slab
description: Climb up red Slab on South side of boulder

name: White Vein
description: start as far left as possible by block.  traverse left arete (follow a white quartzite vein) to the right to the apex of boulder. top out over high point

name: Bearded Lady
description: Same start of The Petrified Man. Move directly up to a good crimp high above the roof. Hike your feet and hit a good jug. Move up arete to top out.

name: The Petrified Man
description: Stand start, left hand in the start of the broken crack, right hand under roof in undercling. Move out left along crack and left side of boulder.

name: Widow Maker
description: Start same as the rest of the problems on the boulder. Move straight up the middle of the boulder on small crimps.

name: Mammoth Tracks
description: Start on good edges and work your way up face to right hand flake.  Make a big move to the lip and top out.

name: 24 Carat
description: From the slot jug left of the arete (same start as Medallion) climb the tall slab.  The crux is pulling the mini roof but you do have to keep it together for the finish.  The top top is quite easy.

name: Long Winter
description: Start matched on ledge climb directly up face to better holds.

name: Medallion
description: This thing is a stunner.  Starting with an obvious slot jug, climb the big and beautiful arete.  The climbing eases the higher you get.  I did it with four pads, though the more the merrier.

name: Frigid
description: Start matched on large side pull and climb up edges.

name: Frostbite
description: Start sitting left hand sloping pinch right hand side pull and crack some moves up the prow.

name: Goosebumps
description: Start on the low left arete with left hand undercling and right hand sloping edge. Use a toe hook from the start to lurch to a good edge near the top. One cool/hard move.

name: Shivers
description: Start sitting on jug and climb the arete.

name: Snow Leopard
description: Start matched on large vertical side pull under the roof. Climb out roof using a pinch and an amazing sloper to get to better holds.

name: Extinction
description: Awesome dyno! Start with both hands on good holds in the horizontal. Get high feet and gun to good hold up top. Detached block under the roof was not used for feet.

name: The Thaw
description: Start with good right hand undercling and left hand edge. Climb up arete.

name: Bengal Tiger
description: Starts in the pit on a left hand sloper and a right hand sidepull. A few moves up the arete leads to a left hand jug. Top out to the left.

name: Primal Instinct
description: Start on opposing jugs and climb the arete.

name: Saber Tooth
description: Start with left hand on arete and right hand on low sidepull. Climb the arete.

name: Slap It
description: Two hand start left on boulder (on a hold with grooves). Dynamic move up right, up to a jug and top out.

name: The Nipple
description: Severely overhanging. Heel-hooks to spare. Layback to "the nipple," match; then throw for jug to the right towards the top. Top-out above dubious block below.

name: Fruity Pebbles
description: Sit start just left of Twoarete syndrome on the Rebel Pride boulder.  Make a difficult first move to two quartzite pebbles.  Continue to the top.  Not a bad warm-up.

name: Rebel Pride
description: You won't find better sandstone anywhere.  Bullet hard and extremely difficult, this is a fantastic project.  Sit start with obvious holds under right arete roof.  Use small holds and slopers to make it to the good holds on lip.  You can see all the moves on this problem, they are just really hard!  Get on it.

name: Twoarete Syndrome
description: The best Sandstone in Wisconsin!  Stand Start with right hand on pebble and left hand on bad sloper.  Use horrible feet and slap up the slopey aretes to gain a good hold at top.  Very unique for the area.

name: Aqua Dagger
description: Start on good holds on the block directly beneath the cube. Move up right on the arete using a series of obvious crimps, and throw for the lip. Crux is probably the tensiony move getting the left hand from a face undercling onto the horizontal crack in the arete.

name: Splash Mountain
description: Start on obvious jugs below the cube, dyno straight up to the crack, top out left.

name: Face Right of Purple Tower Project
description: Starts low on the center of the face climb up. Unknown what kind of holds exist on this one.

name: Damn Black Flys
description: Named after the black flies got so bad, we could handle it anymore.    Stand start on small crimps and work your way up the face, left arete is off, its gets tempting near the top. Gain the good finger crack and top out.

name: Don't Touch That
description: Stand start on the Arete using good holds on both sides of the arete. Make easy moves up to good jug on the right and top out.    Named for the loose hold John told me not to touch, which I decided was a good side-pull; making a fairly huge block land on John's pad.

name: Frogsmack
description: Nice isolated block. Sit start on the low shelf to the right and follow good holds all the way up. Not using the detached feet low adds to the grade

name: Cast Iron
description: Climb slightly overhanging face on slopers and thin holds.  FA was April 2016.  No repeats yet.    Going into the corner has been done subsequently and is V7ish, "Softer than Iron".

name: Cobra
description: This line is the right variation of Leopard Cobra; a solid climb reminiscent of Special K and the Welcome Crack on the north shore. The technical feet up high and the wall looming close behind make this thing pretty spicy. All the holds are there and the top out is satisfying, so git on it!

name: Happy Trails
description: Same difficulty all the way up corner climb.  Side pulls along crack line and plenty of foot hold options.

name: Leopard
description: A variation of Leopard Cobra, this line stays on the left arete to the top. With the left hand starting under the low roof and right on a half moon side pull, use tension to reach a rail and a crimp. Find high feet, move up to the jug and top out.  Not using the detached feet makes the first move more balancey and fun

name: Leopard Cobra
description: A great blocky feature on the backside of a tower right in the projects. Start squeezing the face and then find a combination of crimps and compression moves to reach a jug. This route climbs in classic DL style.. a technical and unforgiving sequence leads to easier but more consequential climbing to the top  Thanks to some new beta from Cody Wheeler, the beginning moves go much easier and keep this thing consistently V1 all the way.

name: River Boulder  1
description: Historically this boulder has many variations (problems) on it. They were never named or graded. Climbs ranged from V0-V6. This is one of the  more obvious lines we saw on this boulder.    There are 2 variations to start this problem out.    1. V3 Start on the far left end of the boulder in the pit. Heel hook and use left hand jug and right hand on sloper. Make a big move and work your way up.    2. V2 Start using large undercling rail on the right side of the overhang. Make a large move for the same hold as the start 1.

name: River Boulder  2
description: Historically this boulder has many variations (problems) on it. They were never named or graded. Climbs range from V0-V6. This is one of the  more obvious lines we saw on this boulder.    This problem is on the riverside of the boulder. Start in the middle of the boulder on good holds. Heel hook and make move to good undercling. Make a huge move out right to gain jug, make a few move big moves to finish it up on the arete

name: Skillet Dinner
description: Corner splittie with many feratures inside little mini buttress.

name: State Land Stout
description: Climbs the steepest section with good holds. Led on gear in the 90's.

name: Tick Tock
description: I'm sure someone has climbed it before me, but I thought I'd add it since it's not there. Face to the left of skillet dinner. You can use the arete, but can't go inside the crack. See picture for the route.

name: Tinfoil
description: Crux is right off the ground.  Small crimps and small side pulls with slim feet.  There is a 2 finger sized flake sticking out at about 12 feet for left hand.  The upper half is sustained 5.8 with slopers and side pulls.

name: South Pillar
description: Mostly big holds up the arete, then pull onto the bulbous summit cap.

name: Logical Bastard
description: Fun mantle problem 2 minutes from the parking lot.

name: All Along The Messenger Shore
description: Start on obvious jugs in the crack and go straight up to a small series of crimps.  Top out around the nose of the boulder.

name: You've Got Mail
description: Stand start with slopey right hand rail and lower left hand compression sloper. Climb straight up the tricky slab. Detached block is not used.

name: Crack Mouth
description: Start as for Meth Mouth but go straight up instead of traversing the sloper.  Topout directly above the sloper.

name: Meth Mouth
description: If The Gobbler is Illinois' biggest sloper, Meth Mouth HAS to be Wisconsin's. You start on the far left end of the feature on a blocky start hold. Traverse the incredible feature, enjoying perfect slopers, move up and left to a perfect ledge and make the crux move (reminiscent of the move to the sloper on Slope of Dadaism, though slightly easier) to the lip. Celebrate having climbed the coolest thing at DL.

name: Methier Mouth
description: Start low on the face, just left of Mouthin' Off and climb up and into Meth Mouth.  Adds a handful of moves into Meth Mouth.

name: Mouthin' off
description: Start just left of the arete and climb directly up the face on inviting holds.

name: The Needle
description: Climb up the arete just left of Resin Breath.

name: Pot Mouth
description: Start on opposing holds in the middle of the face and climb up on great, comfy holds to a fun topout.  Fantastic warmup.

name: Potty Mouth
description: Climb up the short boulder on top of Meth Mouth.  Contender for shortest in the park?  Has a cool heel hook at least...

name: Resin Breath
description: Start on the right face and go straight up.

name: Big Poppin'
description: Sit start with opposing holds, make your way straight up the nicely overhung rock using comfortable holds to a sloped top-out. Watch out for semi-loose flakes.

name: Caught Off Guard
description: Climb the obvious crack.

name: Out Of The Blue
description: Sit start the same as for Backside Surprise Right, but after two moves trend left onto the face.  Follow a crack system to a good hold and an incredible pinch with an easy topout.  Fantastic problem!

name: Pleasant Surprise
description: Original problem starts on two side pulls below the slab and goes directly up and over the cool slab.  Can also be started as for Out Of The Blue and traverse right to the slab.    Excellent problem with a really cool move over the slab!

name: Ruining The Surprise
description: Short climb which follows easy balancing moves up the dihedral. Start at one of the low jugs which appear to be detached,.

name: Sneak Attack
description: Starts on a low jug that looks detached but isn't really and goes straight up to the obvious jug and then follows the crack directly left on small holds.  Tops out in the crack.

name: Surprise Arete
description: Start matched on a sloping ledge and go straight up the arete on incuts.

name: Surprise Arête
description: Climb up the arête just to the right of the dihedral used in Ruining the Surprise.

name: Surprise Ledges
description: I started sitting, left on a sloping edge and right in a somewhat sharp jug.  You could do a move into the jug but it might be awkward.  Go straight up comfy holds to a tricky topout.

name: Surprise Party
description: Starts on a large, obvious jug and goes up and right on the face.  I ran out of light to get on this but it looks like the best line on the boulder.

name: Surprise Slab
description: Start on the break, and go up the short slab.

name: Surprise The Moss
description: Sit start just left of the crack and go straight up to the wide ledge to a somewhat tricky topout.

name: Surprise Warmup
description: Sit start on a low jug and go up the arete on comfy holds.

name: Bully
description: Using two underclings powerfully establish on the boulder (with your feet not on the detached boulder), do a hard move to a blocky sloper, trend right and up through blocky holds and big moves to a mantle on jugs.

name: Show Time
description: A more natural looking start to Bully. Start with right hand on the left of the two under clings on Bully and left out left on blocky side pull. Move out right and up Bully. Fun big moves all the way to the top.

name: Fustercluck
description: Start on an undercling for your right and a sidepull for your left and go straight up small but positive edges.  Deceptively tricky.

name: Krishna
description: Start left hand on lower sidepull crimp and right hand around the arete higher on a good sidepull. Make a move into a larger sidepull then hold tension to work through the lip and slopers on the face of the boulder. A short but sweet boulder that requires you maintain tension throughout.

name: Makin' Bacon
description: Start on the large sidepull left of Fustercluck and climb up and left into a tough mantle.  Slightly dabby but it's got some engaging moves.

name: Ghost Dance
description: SDS with small side-pull out left and ledge on corner.  Stand up and reach right to good side-pull.  Bump up arete and top-out.

name: Phantom Face
description: Climb easy face left of Ghost Dance.

name: Full Sail
description: Sit start with your right hand on a good, sharp crimp just left of the arete and your left hand on a lower edge. Climb into "Sail Away."

name: Green Fire
description: Start on a great left hand pinch and a small sidepull for your right.  Climb into two slick edges and topout the left side of the boulder.

name: Green Haze
description: Direct start to Green Fire.    SDS with left hand on blocky gaston on arete and right hand on good edge, and move up to side-pull.  Set feet and toss up to crimp on Green Fire.  Top-out.

name: Pine Time
description: Nice slab with a low start on a good left hand on  pinch, right hand small sidepull. High foot start. Go to arete with left, crank up to awesome crimp jug with right hike up feet and throw for the top. Obvious straight up line on a freshly cleaned boulder.

name: Sail Away
description: Hard start.  Stand start with high right hand on arete and left down on pinch.  Get your feet established and crank up and out overhang of boulder. The upper moves are fantastic!   There is a jump start that skips the first hard move.  V4/5

name: Chossome
description: Start matched on a large jug ledge with a heel hook, move out and left to the lip and topout directly up.

name: Let's play doctor
description: Start as per 2 Balls in a Sack, and move right across the face into the finish of There is No White Knight.  Really fun movement, combines the fun parts of both these problems.

name: There are Two
description: The sit start to "There's No White Knight."  Start seated with a juggy right hand pinch under the roof and your left hand on a thin edge.

name: There is no White Knight
description: There is no White Knight is a sit start from a positive crimp rail. After two really hard crimp moves, you move to the triangle ledge and up the fun topout. This is a very fun dihedral, despite being a short problem. The topout features engaging moves on comfy holds.

name: Two Balls In A Sack
description: Start with a left hand sidepull and right hand gaston.  Follow the arete up to a slightly insecure mantle.  Nice warmup for the area on comfy holds.

name: Amazing Face
description: Start on the face left of Amazing Pillar and climb the left side of the Amazing Pillar.  The crux is up high, make sure to have a few pads and spotters as a fall will probably put you right on a rock in the landing. I believe this is right of the Original Route but correct me if I'm wrong.

name: Amazing Pillar
description: On SE corner of pillar: start with left hand on large pinch, work your feet up and get small crimp on face, get your left hand up, hike feet and throw for good hold up and left.  A classic DL hard problem!  Easier for the tall in my opinion.

name: Amazing pillar original route
description: THE classic with the arete on the pillar. Climb up center of tall face with slab below(don't worry you'll easily clear it if you blow it)and follw crimps and rails to the top. Inspect the top out for accumulated debris first as the top out is super good if clean and scary if dirty.

name: Bumboy
description: From a sit in the middle of the face climb up and left on cool holds.  Good little warmup

name: Bumped Boy
description: Start down low in seam and work your way up into the top of Bumboy

name: Centerpede
description: From a sit climb up the center of the face.  Fun little thing.  Reminiscent of Horse Pens.

name: Dab on Paul's Nuts
description: Sit start of left side of overhanging arete on underclings.  Move up crimps to a big move right, topout.

name: Easy route
description: Face and corner to the right of the Amazing Pillar.  Climb up using slopy ledges and holds in corner.  Fun warm-up

name: GeriaTricks
description: Sit start on right side of overhanging arete with undercling and sidepull, move up bulge and topout.

name: Humpback
description: Start with good edge.  Climb the arête feature not using wall right or jamming in the crack to a slopey finish.

name: Left of Love Triangle
description: Sit start on the corner just left of Love Triangle with a right-hand undercling and left-hand sidepull. Try to find feet on the actual boulder for 5 minutes or so, then give up and just use the detached block. Use good holds on the block up and to the left to top out.

name: Love Triangle
description: Named after the the shape of the rock and the heart shaped hole in a tree up and to the right of the problem, sit start with arms spread out wide and feet on detached block/s. Stand up to a slick left hand and the crux is  figuring out how to get right hand up to a smallish jug on the right (there is good beta to make the crux easier but figuring that out is half the fun). Pull up to the big jug on the apex and top it out.     A pretty good little problem. Using the detached block/s seems appropriate on this problem. It might be possible to do it without them but it would be really hard and probably contrived (unless you figure out some really cool beta).

name: Magic Slab
description: Start on jug at chest height and make a couple tricky moves to get up on the face. Cool pinches and smears get you to the top.

name: The Magician
description: Climb up the pretty arete from the obvious jug start.

name: Midlife Crisis
description: Starting left of Love Triangle, pull on from a sit (for me), with a right hand undercling crimp and a left sidepull crimp in a seam and power to a crimp.   From there move right, staying low, into the double aretes of Love Triangle.  This is a forced line with good moves.  The large detached blocks are not used for feet.

name: Millipede
description: Fun warmup, tricky.  Climb the Right side of the face and arete.

name: Slice of Life
description: Although squat in stature when compared to the classic routes next to it, this interesting feature has quality rock and is worth climbing. Start sitting with hands low on the face and a heel out left in the dish. Hike your weight, throw for the ledge and try to stick the crux move to the horizontal. From here move up to some good holds, step up into the crack and top out to the right. The friction in the horizontal is superb, you may actually lose some skin trying this one!

name: Slice of Pie
description: An easier way up the Slice of Life boulder. Start on the left, straddling the low corner with hands matched on the rail. Move up to the horizontal and traverse to the good holds up and right. Use a left handed sloper and a dish for the left foot to avoid beaching on the slopey and slippery topout

name: Thumbs Up
description: From a sit climb the nice arete trending left near the end.  Balancey and there's a cool thumb hold.  A grade easier from the stand.

name: West Face
description: Climb the West face of the pillar.  Fun, and a good warm up.

name: White Rabbit
description: Start standing on ledge. Compress and balance your way up the blunt arete.

name: Asteroidea
description: An obvious, natural sit to Starfish.  Start seated on the left side of the face beneath "Lake Boulder Lunge" with your left hand on an undercling and right hand on a gritty edge.  Climb through the crack up and right into Starfish.  Stick the jump and top out as on that problem.

name: The Bottle
description: Start with hands on both sides of pillar. Move your feet up and work your way up the left arete, using good compression and small feet to keep yourself on. Go straight up for the slopey top out, make sure it is clean first.    Bonus points for sit start.

name: Corner right of Starfish
description: This is one of my favorites.  Climb corner just right of Starfish.  Start with left hand on icey side pull, paste feet and throw for good sloper.  Match hand and heel and yard up to the slopey lip.

name: Easy Flakes
description: Climb up face using multiple holds, fun.

name: face left of west face lake boulder
description: Instead of climbing the standard route up the west face climb the face to the left using a smeared palm and decent side pull with th eright hand. A tenuous move out left to a camo'd crimp leads to good pulls to the top and a straight mantle finish. One of my favorites at the reserve.

name: Flying Mancuso
description: Start with good ledge, slap right hand up and undercling with left, fight your way to the top.

name: Flypaper
description: Super subtle problem on the left side of the west face of the lake boulder. Eric sent this on a cool oct. day as high friction is key. Start below big jug on the corner problem and climb face without using corner. A few super balancy moves sets one up for a quick pop to the jug. A testpiece in control.

name: The Gasch Traverse
description: On the south face of the lake boulder, start with your left hand on an undercling on/close to the SW arete, and your right on the sloper rail right.  Pull on and move right through the slopes and top out on the SE arete.  Fun and powerful moves, and if you like slopers you will like this.

name: Its Bumpin
description: This is the direct line up the arete of the warm up wall. Start sitting with feet together low on the arete and with arms fully outstretched. From a sharp good undercling left and an incut side pull right, make a series of bumps up to a stand.  From here a fun campus move can be done to reset feet with style. Stay on the arete to top out

name: Lake boulder crack
description: The crack on the east face of the lake boulder is one of the last unclimbed obvious lines at the reserve.(Unless its been sent)EZ and I spent a lot of time trying to unlock the cryptic sequence of this problem. It doesn't seem difficult until you trey to send it. Very thought prvoking.

name: lake boulder lunge
description: On the left side of the east face of the lake boulder is the classic huck of the reserve. climb into two good sidepulls and shoot for a perfect soap dish and top out on the center of the face. EZ and I were repeatidly missing the hold while being heckeled by a buch of drunks and pot heads before it got sent.

name: Le Eagle
description: From a sit, left hand with a sloper and right with a sidepull, gain slopers and mantle into the scoop.  Pretty much a sit start to the problem Spread Eagle.

name: Left of Mancuso
description: Warm up.

name: Man of War
description: A trafficked problem that is well liked. Sit start with underclings.  Grab the small, sharp crimp and climb the blunt arete.

name: NW Corner of Lake Boulder
description: Stand start with good hold up left.  Basically campus through slopers to the finish.     Variation- sit start with underclings and small crimp, move up into slopers.- V7

name: Pedestal Mantle
description: A must try!  Mantle up on short pedestal near entrance to Reserve.  Harder than it looks- Glassy feet!

name: Pocket Problem
description: Start low and work you way up good side-pulls into large slopey pinch.  Hike foot into pocket and go for the lip, great top-out!

name: Power of the Scoop
description: Using cracks, hike your way up side-pulls and move out to slopey arete to jug.  From there work your way up slopers to top.  Tricky.

name: The Powerful Mancuso
description: Start matched in the constriction of horizontal crack 5' left of Flying Mancuso, make a large left hand move and then go right to the sloper.

name: Project wall
description: Hard wall with no holds, just glassy slopers.  As far as I know nothing has been done on the direct face.

name: Project wall pullup
description: Start with hands matched on a sloper in the middle of the project wall. Do a pull-up. Up gets you 10, down gets you 11.

name: Reservoir Dogs
description: Climb up good break in rock.

name: Roll Top
description: Begin with stacked fists. Chicken wing up into a heinous foot jam, flex your knee and reach up for a solid fist. Pull up to an insecure and exposed mantle and roll your way to safety for the top out.

name: Seams Tight
description: From good start holds, hike feet and get into thin seam.  Yard you way up on small holds to top.

name: Short Boulder
description: Boulder just behind the Lake boulder.  Start low with right hand on small side-pull, left on crimp, work your way left through fun rail.

name: Slab Right of Seams Tight
description: Warm up slab right of Seams Tight. Good holds on left arete.

name: Slope Opera
description: Start on the right arete of Pocket Problem boulder.  Reach the sloping lip and traverse to your left with the slopers on the lip.  Use Pocket Problem's top out.  There are many possible lines on this boulder however, this one is worth posting as the nature of this sloping lip makes for challenging and unique climbing in Wisconsin.

name: Spread Eagle
description: Establish on opposing slopers.  Using high feet and balance, work your way to the right crimpy gaston.  Find a good body position and go for the top. Top out.

name: Stairway
description: Climb up corner to nice steps heading left.

name: Stairway Slab
description: Climb direct from middle of face into Stairway half way up.  Poor feet low.

name: Starfish
description: On the east face of the Lake Boulder, start with left hand on small edge and move up to starfish like hold, hike your feet up and throw for the doughy lip up right.  Top out straight up.  Classic!

name: Struggle Bus
description: Start with feet outside the crack and step into a bad knee jam. Wrestle your way up to a good ledge and pull into a good rest. Press up into another knee and mantle out of the widening.

name: SW Corner of Lake Boulder
description: Start low and climb up slopeing arete.  Lake boulder classic.

name: Tall Boy
description: Climb up features in steep and tall face.  Super fun and a great warm up.

name: Tall Boy Sit
description: Sit start the mega classic Tall Boy with a crimp for the left and a low undercling for the right.  Some folks feel that starting matched on the left crimp makes it even better.

name: Thin Crack
description: Climbs up really thin and hard seam.

name: Ursa Major
description: This is a bear-y good lip traverse on the back side of the boulder below the Lake boulder.  Start with your left hand on a triangular notch, and right hand in an oblong pocket.  Slap and shuffle to the right along the lip until you gain better holds around the corner, and can top out where Short Boulder finishes.

name: Warm up 2
description: Climb break in rock.

name: Wave Mantle
description: Stand up slab and find jugs over lip.  Mantle finish.

name: Welcome Crack
description: Climb up tall and super fun crack.

name: Welcome route
description: Fun warm up.  Start with best hold and climb crack to top.

name: West Face of Lake Boulder
description: Climb up west face of Lake Boulder using gastons and reachy side-pulls.

name: The Zschiesche Problem
description: Start with left hand laybacking on corner.  Paste left foot high and gun for good holds.  Top-out is fun.

name: Zschiesche Project?
description: Climb up through featureless face to good break, top out.

name: Baphomet (Project)
description: An extremely obvious and difficult line that exits a ~45 degree overhang. Sit start on low jug rail. A series of left hand crimps and right hand sloper/compression features leads to a huge throw to a full pad edge. Topout using another set of decent slopers.

name: Cloven Hoof
description: Start on a large jug feature below the roof. Work through a series of slopers and non-holds to the lip.

name: Dorothy's Slab
description: A very nice slab climb up the tallest face of the prominent pillar in the Shark Tooth area. Starts on the bulge above the horizontal break, and follows a ledge system up and left across the face.  Named in honor of my grandmother Dorothy who recently passed away.

name: Deep Water
description: Start on two good pods in opposing cracks low in the dihedral.  Climb out crimps on the left wall to an exposed but easy top out.

name: Pool Shark
description: Start on the overhanging west face of the Shark Tooth Boulder, left hand down on a slanting, glassy rail (starting right hand for Shark Tooth) and right just above on a glassy crimp.  Get a toehook out right, establish on the wall and float your way to the top.  A strange problem that might just suck you in!

name: Scent of Blood
description: Start with right hand on jug underneath the roof and left hand on slopey edge. A few powerful moves lead up the arete.

name: Secrets Of The Lake Project
description: Start on a low edge/undercling and go up the face trending right.  Couple of obvious crimps on the face.

name: Shark Bait
description: Path of least resistance on the the boulder. Start on the right arete with a right hand tooth, left hand edge. work your way up to easy moves on the slab.

name: Shark Tooth
description: From an obvious sit, left hand on the arete and right on a slanting, glassy sidepull, climb the arete trending slightly right to finish.  A sustained and very good problem.

name: Dream Fatigue
description: Start on the large jug. Climb great holds up the compression feature to a tricky topout.

name: Ejaculation
description: Problem on right side of Ejaculator boulder.  Stand start and move up corner to a great throw to the finish.

name: Ejaculator Left
description: Same start as Ejaculator, but move left to a cool pinch, and top out straight up the arete.  In my opinion this is the most logical and least contrived version of the Ejaculator.

name: Ejaculator Right.
description: Same start as the Ejaculator, but move out right to good rail above sharp boulder landing.  Hard, and scary due to bad fall.

name: The Ejaculator
description: The Ejaculator problem is a classic.  SDS with good holds and work your way up the breaks in rock.  Steep powerful moves from under the boulder lead to slapping your way out to the corner.  A must do for the DL boulderer

name: Eject
description: Problem climbs middle breaks in boulder, just left of Ejaculation.

name: Nocturnal Emissions
description: From a sit, pull on using to side pulls make a big move to a sloper and a bigger move to a crimp then top out.

name: Z MOVE
description: Climb up short, steep, and extremely powerful crack in rock. Previously named due to the fact that Eric's wife kept calling him during his send efforts.Called Pussy Whipped in the guidebook

name: Z MOVE Left
description: Start right hand in crack and left on slopey flake.  Gun up to good edge and right up to crack.  Top-out.

name: Beagle
description: Start on good holds down low, paste feet, and climb up

name: Galapagos
description: Stand start with left hand jug-edge and right hand crimp edge. Work your way out to the jug on the face then top out.

name: Talus Troll
description: Start on two crimps over lip, climb straight up.

name: Talus Troll Sit Project
description: Sit start the Talus Troll. Start on large undercling for left hand and small undercling for right.

name: Midwest Connection
description: This is the large slab that is at the north-west end of the talus field. We climbed the cleaner looking slab face on the left, but there is the possibility to finish out right. The rock quality is very questionable though on the right side, and most likely should be avoided.

name: Mini Fridge
description: Climb the fridge

name: Sad Dad Bar
description: Start on flake, head up to the point

name: Salmon Slab
description: Climb up the short slab

name: Sturgeon Slab
description: Climb up the slab

name: The Glass Bench
description: Head up the low angle slab to the base of the hanging block. Use both aretes to gain a very committing smear foot. A few more bumps, bad feet, and a toehook leads to a victory jug and a cruiser finish.

name: Over the Garden Wall
description: Sit start on the white crimp and a lower slopey edge. Continue directly up the face using a series of faint crimps, while avoiding crack to the left.

name: Loonie Boulder
description: This is the long wall behind and above Mountie's Bounty. There are a few lines on this thing. Make your own up, mix and match, whatever you want. The top out needs cleaning. Grades could range from v0 - v3/4.

name: Mountie's Bounty
description: Start on obvious large jug down low. Head up onto the face and finish up on the point.

name: Chimney Sweep
description: This is an off the beaten path style problem for an off the beaten path area.  Somehow wedge yourself down an into the bottom of the crevice behind Vision Quest, facing south. The route starts below a horizontal on a great shelf about 7 feet up. Trend up and right towards the apex of the chimney on good feet the whole way. When the feet run out at the tip, do a pullup mantle to finish.  Definitely not a conventional style but fun if you get into it. Can be one star or three depending on what you like

name: Fever Dream
description: From an edge and a sidepull just next to it, climb the face not using the crack or sidepull features right.  Very subtle movement on this one and not a give away.  The crux comes at the lip and pulling the bulge.

name: Foggy Vision
description: From a sit in the cave with a blocky fin, compress out the roof to a tricky lip encounter and finish up the easing arete.

name: Spectacles
description: Just right of Vanishing Point on the same wall.  Start sitting matched on an incut edge or using a pinch for the right hand.  Bust a long move to a good, slopey jug.  Gain more jugs, pull a long lock off and finish with an easing mantle.  The crack and wall right aren’t used.

name: Vanishing Point
description: Sit start on the left facing jug and climb up interesting holds that are strangely worse than they appear.

name: Vision Quest
description: Start underneath the obvious tall arete with a giant foot.  A few steep moves lead you into squeeze moves on the face.  An airy, easing and slightly insecure finish awaits.  A real beauty.

name: Agape
description: Climb face left of the arete on the Titan boulder, capped by a triangular prow & press it out. Enjoy the ride if you miss the huck!

name: Boom Box
description: You hiked all the way out to Boomtown, so you may as well climb a little bit...This problem climbs out of the pit between Buzz Bomb and Jones' Roof.  Start matched on a good edge, and climb straight up through the crack, and top out.

name: Buzz Bomb
description: Buzz Bomb is the beautiful headstone feature with a flaring seam running right up the center. Left, direct and right faces are all super fun.

name: Jones' Roof
description: Sweet hidden overhang problem. Start on good underclings and make big moves straight over the roof. Things get brutal at the lip!

name: Shadow Wall
description: Located in the upper area above the buzz bomb and jones' roof is a nice little warm up wall. there are 4-5 decent problems here that have extremely fun topout cruxes. Stay cool and be patient and there's nothing to worry about.

name: The Titan (aka Birthday Prow)
description: This gem is waiting for an ascent. When first glancing at it it looks simple, that is until you try crankin' on it. Big features with even bigger moves. Git on it!

name: The Arcanist
description: SDS on the left side of the large ledge. Climb to the right arete, then punch up several powerful moves.

name: Divination
description: Stand start on large jug. Follow good holds to the left, eventually reaching a dihedral.

name: Kvothe
description: Stand start left hand large sidepull, right hand jug notch. Climb straight up.

name: Merlin
description: SDS on the left side of the large ledge. Climb up and left through an amazing pocket and ledges.

name: Seiðr
description: SDS on left hand sidepull jug, right hand on wide notched sidepull edge. Climb powerful and  consistent moves directly up the slopey arete.Note: This boulder is very rarely dry. It's most predictably dry after about a week without rain and with temps below freezing.

name: Sygaldry
description: SDS on left hand vertical sidepull, right hand downpulling edge. Climb interesting moves up the center of the slightly overhanging face.

name: Taborlin the Great
description: Stand start with right hand on high three finger edge, left hand on large undercling. Two tough moves lead up the overhanging arete. Detached blocks are not used.

name: Elephant Ear
description: The guidebook says 5.11a, but it's only 25 feet and has a good landing.

name: Face Time
description: Good one. Climbs ledges with some crimps added in.

name: Left of Elephant Ear
description: Side pulls up the face to an interesting top out.

name: Big Money Project
description: SDS near left side of cave.  Right hand on good edge and left hand-heel match out left.  Cross through to small crack and bump out right to a shitty two finger pocket and throw to the finish- hard!  Small and sharp holds through the crux.  Surprisingly this is not a dabby problem.  Super cool!

name: Double Pinch
description: This route is essentially a highball boulder problem, but takes protection at a couple spots. It is among the few routes to the left of the access gully to the Main Wall. The route climbs a narrow face just left of a crack and arete on the right, and finishes with an awkward top-out.

name: Heineken Crack
description: Layback the crack or squeeze the overhang block.

name: Heineken Pillar
description: Climb up thin pillar just left of Heineken crack.

name: Jack Backwards
description: In the 3rd edition guidebook. Listed as project.    April 2016   Pull off the ground and move though good holds to bomber ledge.  Chalk up and reach back in the dihedral for a less then good edge, set your feet and make a committing reach left.  High-step on the ledge, press into the dihedral then continue to good holds for the finish.

name: Mason's Line
description: Thin Line around the corner from the Steinke wall access.

name: Unknown  5
description: #5 in the 3rd Edition guidebook. Face and crack just left of route 6.

name: Unknown  6
description: #6 in the 3rd Edition guidebook. Wide crack.

name: Unknown  7
description: #7 in the 3rd Edition guidebook. Face and crack right of route 6.

name: Mini Left
description: Easy warm up, start with a undercling.

name: Mini Right
description: Easy warm up.

name: Center Face
description: Crux is pulling onto the face.

name: Fudge Shoppe
description: Fun

name: Left Arete
description: Good problem.

name: Right Side
description: Crux is gaining the slab.

name: West Side
description: Great warm up.

name: Bootlegger
description: This is a very very easy route and very short. Climb up the crack that leans inwards and you will be at the top before you know it. After the first lead the belayer decided he would follow in his boots and made it look to easy. Hence the name Bootlegger!

name: Iceberg
description: This climb is hard to find if you are looking from the bottom of Storm wrack wall only because the crack is not visible until you get close to the climb. Climb flake to top.

name: That's it
description: The name That's it says it all. By the time you finish the first move you are practically done with the climb. Climb crack until you can mantel on left ledge. Dont you the chimney on the left for your feet!
Climb center crack with good break at top.

name: Arrested Layback
description: Climb the sharp flake. Guidebook say 5.7 but it's very protectable with pads. Classic.

name: Cherry Pop
description: One move wonder. Crimp and "pop!" to good in-cut with your right hand.

name: Committee Climbing
description: Climb steep face to nice layback up high.  Super fun climb.  Given 5.10b in the new guide.

name: DL Love
description: Start low on right side of overhang.  Place feet out right and gun up for pinches and pockets to gain upper crack and left block.  Top-out is fun on jugs at roof.

name: Dodge the Choss
description: Start on a couple of crimps and move up to a deceivingly slopey topout.  Fun athletic moves on comfy holds.

name: Good Grief
description: The book lists this as 5.10a. We did it without using a small horn and ledge on the other side of a crack. That made it V4ish and fun.   Could be a hard left hand version up the face to some mega slopers.

name: No Holds Barred
description: #13 in the 3rd Edition guidebook. Narrow V-shaped inside corner. Interesting if only the crack is used.

name: Project
description: Start below overhanging diamond.  Squeeze and slap you way up to gain upper crack.  The start will be the crux.

name: Slap Happy
description: One good hold near the top.

name: Stankonia
description: Great route. The landing looks bad but isn't because the only place to pop will send you on a casual fall on top of a flat boulder.

name: A View to Kill
description: Start with two good under-clings and power your way to the lip.

name: Dark Side of the Cube
description: Start low on good side-pull/undercling.  Work your way up and out of pit on good edges.

name: Blade
description: Climbs up corner of blade like boulder.  Fun climb.  Not sure who FA'd this?  There was a little chalk on it when I found it.  Paul J.?

name: Headstone
description: Climb up tall boulder just up from the Blade. Easy to notice this guy.  Tall and fun.

name: Another Coin in the Wishing Whale
description: Start matched on an obvious edge/pinch on the right side of the face.  Bust big left to the prominent jug and top out.  Starting from the jug is a V0/1 Walk the Plank.  A lower start from edges goes at V5.

name: Boulder Across from Pete's Pebble
description: Start on good jug, go up to good crimp and pinch and gun for jug.

name: Fill the Void
description: Start low on middle of boulder, bump out to crimp and rock up to slopey jug.  Top-out.

name: Live With Porpoise
description: Start with a sloper sidepull for the left, and a downpulling crispy hold for the right on the face.  Squeeze up the arete!

name: Lochness Monster
description: With a good hold for the right and an edge for the left, set a heal and smack a sloper.  Continue onwards.

name: Storm Troopers
description: Starting on a right hand undercling and your left hand on the block work your way out the roof on cool slopers to a finicky throw for the lip.

name: Storm Troopers Right
description: Do the first couple moves of Storm Troopers to the slopers, get your feet off the block some how and follow the slopers right to a jug and top out.

name: Basking Pine
description: Good warm up friendly.

name: Quaking Aspen
description: Nice warm up,

name: Safety Maple
description: Crux is first move with left hand, short but fun climb up the corner edge of a large boulder

name: Cornerstone
description: Starts on the triangular ledge.

name: West Face
