description: Start with the jug as for Twist.  I started matched but it doesn't much matter.  Bust right to to a sloper then use edges and slopers to gain a jug then mantle onto the slab and finish it up.

name: Lake Perch
description: Start sitting with a left undercling ( a little more left than you think ) and a right sidepull.  Pop to a sloper and continue onwards through interesting moves and a mantle.

name: Twist
description: Start under roof with left hand of slopey jug and right using a half pad mono pocket.  Hike feet and gun to pinch.  Set feet and throw for lip.  Top-out.  Super fun moves!

name: Twisted
description: A low start to Twist.  Right on an edge in the roof, left on a chippy crimp (see photo).  A lower start might just happen and will likely make it even harder. It will likely be hard and good.  The crux move is a huge cross to an undercling and when you miss it you back flop hard.. 4/5 pads recommended.

name: Vine Street
description: Climb friction slab.  Similar to Super Slab just smaller, and trickier than it looks.

name: I Wanna Be Your Lover
description: Sit start with left hand crimp and right hand side pull.  Move up good edges and hit arete.  Top-out

name: Wanna Be Corner
description: Start low on jug and climb corner of boulder.

Very cool climb that's less than a minute from the car. Start on an obvious jug at chest height and continue up the tall face using an amazing "bread loaf" rail. Line of least resistance is going right at mid height to a juggy lip and topping out.

name: Buffalo Sauce
description: Sit start low on a obvious crimp rail at the bottom of the arete. Use an awesome pinch and some crimps to get up to a juggy side pull. From here there seem to be three options, all about the same grade, but with varying degrees of scariness:Mild: Move right up through underclings.Medium: Continue up the right side of the arete through several cool pinches.Hot: Transfer over to the left side of the prow using a block pinch and top out over the bulge. (I haven't committed to this one yet...)The stand start for each of these (from the left hand pinch and right hand juggy sidepull) is also fun and around the V2 range.Note: The talus at the bottom of this climb is pretty unstable due to the slope, be careful!

name: Tranquility Pillar
description: Start sitting with a jug.  Move right onto the striking face.  Climb the face, bumping up the arete with your left hand.  The wall left of the wide crack doesn’t come into play.   Beware, there are some moves up high, so be prepared.  If this were on a freestanding boulder in a meadow it would be world class, no doubt. Instead it is here, really close to the car, and still awesome! Comparable to the nearby Godzilla in terms of difficulty and quality, and more accessible, though probably a little more serious.

name: Criminal Activity
description: Start as for public enemy, and somehow climb up the vert face to the right.  Funky moves, public enemy # 3?  Pretty interesting climbing really.

name: Deviled Egg
description: Sit start, climb up arete.  Rock is a touch fractured and chossy down low.

name: John Dillinger
description: Start sitting with two large underclings, slot the left kneebar and climb up face using sloping sidepulls and nice two finger pocket, topout left rolling up onto the horn.

name: Public Enemy
description: A cool roof 100 feet off of the trail just above the last cabin before the trail starts on the south side of the West Bluff.

name: Public Enemy Direct AKA Public Enemy Number 1
description: Start as for Public Enemy and instead of heading left after the foot cut wrestle your way up the Dihedral.  Physical!

name: Double Elephant
description: Starting under the middle of prow, climb up and left gets you into big moves squeezing the bulge.  Huge huck to the thank-god jug for the top-out.  Committing, and bring the spotters.

name: Elephant Cheek
description: Start under middle of prow and climb up and right to gain good ledge.  From ledge, hike feet and go out to good bucket.  Top-out

name: Godzilla
description: Start sitting on the obvious jug.  Climb up and left to the arête, and continue through an airy finish. The other walls/detached blocks are off.

name: Mothra
description: A proud line.  Start sitting with the obvious jug, same as for Godzilla.  Instead of heading left to the arete, climb straight up the tall, aesthetic face through sidepulls, seam holds, and edges.  There is a committing move up high.

name: Hog Wild
description: From a sit, matched on a positive undercling, climb the arête.

name: The Pecan Tree
description: Start low and right in a good horizontal. Make a few powerful moves on bad feet into some bigger moves up the face. Top section is easy but heads-up. Gave it 4 stars for really the fun movement. Maybe it deserves less...

name: Expect Nothing
description: From a flat jug on the face, bust big right to a flat edge.  Rock up on a heal probably, bumping through crimps to the juggy lip and mantle.  No detached blocks are used.

name: Kajiu
description: Sit start same as Karloff.  Move thorough the horizontal rail to the left.  Exit to an airy finish to the left of the vertical crack that splits the boulder.

name: Karloff
description: Sit start on good edge to the right of large block sitting under the boulder.  Climb up right arete on funky pinches and ledges to the jug right below the top out.  reach back and crank the feet high and roll it out.

name: No Expectations
description: Start matched on an obvious, flat juggy hold.  Climb the steep overhanging arete. There is also a higher start that goes at V4 or so with a low sidepull for the left hand and a glassy pinch for the right on the arete.

name: Youggary
description: Start on large side pull.  Move thought a large ledge onto moderate crimps. Exit boulder on right side or the large crack that splits the boulder.

name: Corner
description: Start low and climb up corner of boulder.  Trickier than it looks.

name: Slab
description: Climb up face of boulder.  Depending on which side you climb could change the grade.  Right is easier than staying left.

name: Alpine Club
description: Start on the obvious jug and start to wonder why this wasn't as easy as you thought it was going to be.  A deceivingly difficult problem to say the least.

name: Corner Roof
description: On left side of boulder under roof, start with good underclings and throw to lip.  Mantle top-out is the crux on this one.  Cool feature and a good warm-up for Alpine Club.

name: Fight Club
description: Sit start down and right from alpine club and climb into it.  FA started matched on good holds to the right.

name: Hammer Club
description: Start on Alpine Club and bust a big move out left to a slopey edge and top out as for alpine club.  The easiest line on the wall and surprisingly the last to be done... maybe.

name: Hammer Club Sit
description: Sit down and right and climb into Hammer Club

name: Rapture Variation
description: Start standing (maybe stack pads if you're short) left hand on the right hand you do the hard Alpine Club move off of and move to a small gaston out right.  Go to the top after that.  The real start might be really hard and will totally go.

name: Spider Monkey
description: Another problem here? Yeah.. probably been climbed before.. maybe..  And a fun one.  Start sitting on the boulder propped up just left of Alpine Club with your left hand on a blocky pinch and your right higher on a juggish slopey ledge.  Pull on, with perhaps a heal or toe hook, and climb straight up.   If you start a move or two in it's a fun V4 dubbed "spider monkey high start".

name: Velvet Hammer
description: Begin matched on the start hold for Alpine Club.  Make a long cross-through move and head left along boulder, top out.

name: Beautiful Soup
description: Start on the left hand sidepull crimp and go up right to another small crimp.  Big huck for the rail and then traverse off right to the jug on right side of wall.

name: The Key Maker
description: Start at the bottom right corner of the Beautiful Soup boulder on an undercling and edge.  Work your way up and left until you get into the start holds of Beautiful Soup.  Do the moves on BS to reach the rail but instead of traversing off right continue straight up to the top of the boulder using a very small, slopey crimper.

name: Pi Maker
description: Slap up the arete left of Beautiful Soup and topout via the Key Maker.  The arete felt about v7 to the jug break.  Good climbing. Unnamed and unrated, so the grade is just a guess..

name: Soupmaker
description: Climb the crux of Beautiful Soup but instead of heading right at the ledge go straight up the finish of Keymaker.  A pure line with no traversing.

name: V2 Bulge AKA Bulgesaurus
description: Start low with two good side pulls, set feet and throw for the ledge. Finish right via fun and easing but attention grabbing slab climbing that wraps up the pillar.  The direct top-out is a little trickier and gets a PG-13 rating(watch the ledge).

name: The Gilf
description: Start sitting, matched on a slanted blocky ledge, as for the Milf.  Climb straight up the arete through an interesting sequence of moves, and a committing finish.

name: The Glutton
description: Sit start on blocky jug on left arete and move up via rightward trending rail into the final jugs on the right side of the boulder.Known as "The Milf" in the DL bouldering guidebooks.

name: Two Gilfs
description: Start on two women, climb to the jug and go left to top out on the gilf, which is to say straight up the center of the Boulder. A bit harder than two women and an added few fun moves.

name: Two Women
description: Start low and right on opposing holds, move up to gain slopey jug.  Set feet and toss out left to good edge.  Swing feet, and hold position to snatch high crimp.  Top-out.

name: Oofda Arête
description: Start sitting with a jug, under the min roof. Squeeze up the arête to a somewhat airy though easing finish. Surrounding blocks/ walls etc. are not used.

name: I've Got Wrinkles
description: Start off by cutting up your fingers on the lowest part of the corner. Then up corner; fantastic feet, then look out to the center for a sturdy crimp. Keep going up the edge, top out nice & easy.

name: Slabby McGee
description: Have you ever touched slab before? The smooth, almost glassy, or otherwise lichen covered slick? NO?! Then this is for you. Put the kids on it, even.

name: Anchorpoint
description: Start left hand on big sidepull jug and right hand on big flat jug.  Use a heel hook and some trickery to gain a crimp and top out on slopers.  Classic!!

name: Center Face
description: Start on two small crimps, hike feet on ledge and move up left to small crimp, pop for break and top out.  There could be a harder version, by skipping the large ledge low, but the feet would be horrible.

name: Easy Corner
description: Start low on jugs and climb up corner using big holds.

name: Foreplay
description: Start on 2 nice flat edges about chest level right of Intercourse arete and climb into that problem.  The block below and the crack above were not used on the possible FA.

name: Grasping at Nothing
description: Start at Left Anchor, Do the move to the sharpish flake jug and move right along slippery slopers into Anchorpoint.

name: Grasping at Something
description: Do Anchorpoint through the crux and then move left along slippery slopers and top out as for Left Anchor.

name: Hogleg Corner
description: Right of Anchorpoint and left of Hogleg is an open corner.  Climb up it using everything.

name: Hogleg Direct
description: Go up Hogleg without using the arete.  May be unrepeated this way.  P.J. can offer up some more info.

name: Hogleg Overhang
description: Head up the tall overhanging face and arete, top out straight up over slopey lip.  Classic highball.

name: Intercourse Arete
description: Cool moves up the short overhanging corner.  Sit start on the arete. Low detached block is off.

name: Left Anchor
description: Start low on ok jug and gun up to good right hand pinch, top-out.

name: Raisin Vehicle
description: Start on RV and traverse into The Raisin.  Another nice warmup in an area stacked with them.

name: The Raisin
description: Start in the middle of the Recreational Vehicle traverse and do a surprisingly big move up to the lip.  Traverse off left by the corner.  Oddly fun if you're in the area.

name: Recreational Vehicle
description: On the far right side of the area is a nice right to left traverse on slopers.  Cool moves and a late crux make this one worthy.

name: Right Anchor
description: Start on good block right of Anchorpoint and climb up side-pulls and crimps to reach the summit.

name: Trad Anchor
description: Crack in the corner to the left of Easy Corner. Sit start, jam up the crack, finish right at the top of Easy Corner.

name: Trust Fund Slab
description: Very cool low angled slab with really neat rock.

name: Veasy
description: Starting on good holds, hike feet and climb corner to good top-out.

name: TCC Boulder
description: Climb up jugs on west face of large block up hill past Anchorpoint.  Face used to have TCC spray-painted on it.

name: TCC Right Arete
description: Starting on the two-hander ledge with feet jammed in the horizontal crack underneath, slap sidepulls up to a sloper horn and top out on the exposed right face.  You could also climb into the main TCC route, but the right face has great holds for those comfortable with DL soloing/exposure.  Missing an unnecessarily-dynamic throw to the left-hand sloper could possibly send you down the chute.  I wasn't that sketched out by it.  There is a good spotter stance, but good luck finding a willing body to stand across the drop.

name: Ace of Spades
description: Start sitting in the middle of the pretty face.  Left hand on a sidepull, right on an edge below.  Gain the right arete and climb the sweet feature.  This thing is pretty darn awesome! The stand start is a fun V3/4ish problem.

name: Aramandi
description: Start sitting, with a crimp/pinch for the right hand and a crimpy sidepull for the left.  Climb the arete.  Quite tiring and a little trickier than it looks.

name: Exit Through the Gift Shop
description: Start as for Aramandi and after the first move traverse left for two moves. Pull up into the slab and head to the top without letting the loose branches and vines pull you down. Hard first couple of moves with a fun slab finish.  Variation: Start two moves in on the two left facing sidepulls. Make the shouldery move left and pull up into the slab. Goes at around V2.

name: Lockoff Problem
description: Start on good holds and shoot straight up the face, avoiding the left arete and the ledge system and corner out right.  Gain a slopey crimp, get a good high foot, and pull down until the lip is within reach.  This is listed as a 5.11b in Swartling's guidebook (3rd edition) but its height seems more fitting of a bouldering grade and listing.

name: 45 Center
description: Start low with holds in crack.  Work your way up through slopers and meathooks to the top-out.

name: 45 Left
description: On left side of boulder, start low in good slot and work your way up to top-out.

name: 45 Right
description: This one is a bit steeper than the other two, maybe 50 degrees.  Start on right side of boulder and climb corner to the top.

name: The Comet
description: Start low with right hand edge and left pinching the arete.  Set feet under roof and slap up to left hand slopey crimp.  Hand-heel match and bump up.

name: Misery Pillar Arete
description: SDS below overhanging arete left of Pillar crack. climb though good holds to committing top out.

name: Misery Pillar Crack
description: Start low in overhang and bust up to slopers.  Mantle into the crack and follow that up to top.  Heads up top-out!

name: Misery Pillar Face
description: Start low on slopey pinch and make your may up into a mantle on small edges.  From there move into slopey edges in middle of boulder and toss right to good hold near corner.  Top-out.

name: Misery Pillar Slab
description: Climb easy face/slab on south side of pillar.

name: Darkside
description: Starting in the back of the cave on the slightly overhanging wall with your left hand on a good hold on the arete and your right on an obvious slopey hold, pull on and trend rightward encountering fun and sometimes tricky moves. Once you reach the other arete you can drop off on juggy holds in a seam. This is always shady and has a very good landing.

name: Holy Grail
description: Direct line of Relic. Start sitting on the same jug as Relic, traverse a bit left into good holds then proceed straight up using a side pull edge and a sloper rail just before the lip.

name: Relic
description: Start on a jug above a slippery slab.  Trend left through the corridor, fun moves and cool holds along the way.  Top out near the left arete.  Reminiscent of the classic Autobot in RMNP and about as hard.  Falls likely won’t be too bad, I only give it PG13 because of the less than perfect landing.  A couple pads and a slider is pretty good.  As long as you don’t blow the opening move (the easiest on the climb) you should be alright.  This is definitely worth seeking out if you’re looking for fun climbs of the grade, it’s sustained and has quite a few moves.  If you’re looking for v4/5 with fantastic views, linking this with the pretty close 45 degree boulder would be a great day out.

name: Feel the Fern
description: The right arete of the Fern Friend face. Start sitting with a side pull for the left and crimp for right I think..  or what ever makes sense.

name: Fern Friend
description: Start matched on a prominent right facing rail.  Climb.

name: Fiddlehead
description: Sit with jug.  Climb slabby face.

name: Invasive Species
description: A cool, obvious and fun line.  From a sit with left hand on a prominent rail and right with an undercling, climb the blunt arete to an easing finish.

name: Sneaker Arete
description: From a sit, climb the arete above the jumbly boulders.  I started with sidepulls.

name: Soaring Block Project
description: Likely establish on the hanging block with a right hand edge and a good pinch for the left.  Climb the block.

name: The Compressor
description: Compress up the overhanging refrigerator block.  See Photo for start.  A little dabby but great moves and some cool slopers.

name: The Professor
description: Eliminate line on the the compressor block. Climb the compressor but avoid using the right arete. Right starting hand is an undercling on the face. Top out to the left.

name: Africa Crack
description: Africa Crack and its neighbor "Ptooey" are two good options if the popular routes at Old Sandstone are occupied. Africa Crack climbs up the appealing looking thin hands crack to the Africa shaped feature and up the overhanging hand crack. Start in the thin hands crack, work your way up onto a slab, place gear, and unlock a tricky hand jam sequence to surmount the overhang to a jug. Finish over some easy but loose blocky terrain.

name: Alligator Wall
description: Start with underclings until you reach the large roof, continue up to the left of the roof, layback to overhang and finish on face to top.

name: American Beauty Crack
description: The American Beauty Crack can be found just to the right of the Pacific Ocean Wall and Seven Seas.  The crack sits on the inside of a 35-foot slightly overhanging right angle dihedral and is perfect for practicing your lieback moves or handjamming.  The crux is at the slight overhang about halfway up the route.

name: Broken Foot
description: Broken Foot is an appealing looking short crack on the east side of the Old Sandstone climbing area. If you've done all the classics, or want to try a fun and easy lead, this is your route. Although it's short the route combines a lot of different climbing into a mere 40 feet. Start out with some finger and hand jams down low, move up to the layback flake feature (which is a very cool feature) and then stem your way up to the top. Anchor at the top on some trees.

name: Chez's Chimney
description: Chez's Chimney is easily located.  Just look for the sizeable chimney on the west-facing wall as you approach the area from the trail.  The chimney is easily scaled using huge jug holds, palms, and plenty of friction smearing.  This is a great climb to get a beginner acquainted to sandstone.  May not be the best for leading because there's plenty of stuff to hit in a fall.

name: Chez's Chimney  variation
description: This route is right inbetween Chez's Chimney and Alligator Wall. There is a face on the right side of the chimney. Climb up that towards the chimney. It goes about 55 feet up and then turns into the chimney. Follow up the right side of the chimney to the top.

name: Climber's Arrogance
description: This route climbs like a typical modern comp. route in that it starts off easy and gets harder the farther up you get.  Start on the two little bulges and reach (or jump) for the 2/3 finger pocket on the left to start the route, staying off the detached block to your right.  Never go farther left than the pocket (as in this is a face climb and don't use the flake that gets farther and farther away from the finish as you get higher up) and don't ever get closer to the dihedral than about 4 feet (pebble level with last move hands is therefore "off"). Sure it's a bit of a squeeze job but it makes the route indefinitely more interesting. Crux is the last few moves for a great finish ending in either an all out dyno from interestingly smeared feet or a long reach depending on your height. Definitely worth the extra little bushwhack if you're in the area.

name: Curving Crack
description: The Curving Crack is a great moderate climb that requires some tricky jamming towards the top of the route.  Start out with some blocky moves and move up along the crack, curving towards the right.  About half way up the route have the option of using only the crack (harder) or using a shallow dihedral to the right to stem up.  The top of the climb holds the crux where you seem to hit a dead-end.

name: Dancing Madly Backwards
description: Dancing Madly Backwards is a great route to try if 5.9's are starting to get less challenging.  There's good friction on the sandstone, and the wall isn't quite vertical.      Start the route below a rather large bulge.  Climb up under the bulge and work your way right and up to the left end of the obvious roof.  Traverse right under the roof using underclings and foot smearing.  Once the roof runs out reach up to find small holds (crux 1).  Stand up and over roof.  Continue up to the shallow dihedral.  The last few moves are on small holds (crux 2).  A delightful climb!

name: Deceptive
description: Climb a few feet right of "Curving Crack". Move up on small crimps to rest ledge and overhang. Move through overhang on nice jug and layback to top.

name: Dirty Little Secret
description: It looks simple but gets tricky as you move farther up, since the chimney opening becomes smaller as you near the top of the climb. There are some nice flakes and crimps on the inside face to help you move up. Be prepared to get really dirty in this one.

name: Everleigh Club Crack
description: A little finger crack, a little stemming, until you hit easier ground about halfway up.  Just to the right of American Beauty Crack.

name: Freaky Face
description: This is a classic climb. A face climb with 2 variations. The 5.10a being the rightmost climb. There is a 5.8 variation on the left of the face.

name: Gargantua
description: Gargantua is a fun climb with an interesting start and finish.  Start out under the right side of a sizeable roof (this roof is shared by Sepsen Wall, Uberschmitt, and Tarantula).  Work your way up and out on the overhang, palming a rounded point on the edge of the roof.  Swing your right foot above the roof and power over in one move to the dihedral above.  Proceed up the fairly easy dihedral until hitting the "summit" block.  Use fine face holds to surmount the block and top out with a mantel.

name: Girls Named Sue
description: Well to the right of swordsmans bulge, shallow ramp corner, first ascent misappropriated in CMC guide (required extensive cleaning before FA.)

name: Half Crack
description: Start up the crack, pull through the awkward slot.  Then head straight up the flakes rather than continue in the crack.

name: Has Been
description: Has Been exists in the face between Wobbly D and Chez's Chimney. It is an exceptional route considering how often it is overlooked. Basically the idea is to thrutch up the face towards the giant cobble 2/3 of the way up on the left side of the route. Once the cobble is attained the route softens, but until then it is a stiff endeavor.

name: Mammalary Magic
description: This is the first route that you find to the left (west) of the Old Sandstone area. A nice slab with multiple pebbles embedded on it. Start by climbing straight up in the middle of the slab up to just below the biggest pebble. There are two ways to solve the crux move: one going straight up to the big pebble and the other by moving a little to the left (easier). From big pebble continue straight to the top.

name: One-Upper
description: Rhoads spotted the line, Remo TR'd it right quick, Rhoads solo'd it, hence "The One-Upper".     It's a cute little boulder problem with "two sweet moves". There is a cool direct start we were working on, maybe V6 or V7.

name: Ptooey
description: "Ptooey!" is the sound the rock makes as it spits you out of the deceptively easy looking corner crack. Climb up about 10 feet into the corner using good holds and a two-finger undercling. Place some small nuts, take a deep breath and then figure out the trickery to unlock the crux sequence. The small embedded pebbles on the right side wall will help. Once you reach the good horiztonal rails on either side walls, place some more gear to settle your stomach and finish up with hand jams. Mantle out on slopey but good ledges for an exciting finish.

name: Sepsen Wall
description: This route starts to the left of the boulder below Gargantua. Ascend the easier slab at the bottom and head towards the large notch in the roof.  Pull through the notch on positive seams, then above the roof move up and left on progressively smaller holds.

name: Sherlocked
description: This is a very tricky, crimpy face climb with the crux being right at the first large, sloped crack/ledge and having to get up onto that. There is a nice 3-fingered undercling crimp at this area that can provide some fun in getting up.   Aside from the first large crack and a second, less sloped one about 7ft after it, there are mostly scattered crimps.    Be careful not to go into the dihedral on the left or the obvious crack on the right. There is a quartzite knob on the left, near the crux, that is part of the dihedral route, not part of this route.

name: Swillbillies
description: This is route #12 in Sven's Book. The route starts behind an oak tree to the right of Freaky Face. Move up the corner and crack onto a decent rest ledge. From there place good gear and then get into the crack to your left using good sidepulls and finger locks. A few tricky balancy moves up the crack lead to a good finger lock and mantle move onto a sloping ledge. Scramble to the top and shake yr ass like a drunken swillbilly.

name: Tarantula
description: Tarantula offers a left hand start into the same crack system as Gargantua.  This route makes a great onsight proposition with nice rests and plenty of protection.  The overhanging start throws the hardest moves soon off the ground, and the pumpy hand traverse that leads into the obvious crack is just as exciting.  The thin crack above is as fun as it looks, but keep your shoes race-laced for the top out.

name: Team Arturo
description: Undercling? Undercling? Where art thou undercling?   Start with some sweet underclings and laybacking, end with a typical Old Sandstone smearing, sloper crimping and sidepulls.

name: Wobbly Dihedral
description: Wobbly dihedral is definantely one of the best 5.9 leads at DLSP. The gear is excellent and the crux is more balance than power. Climb up the clean, arching left facing dihedral 10 fett left of chez's chimney. once you reach the end of the crack you will be at the crux. A couple of exciting moves out and up lead you to easier terrain to the top. The only complaint with this climb is that the dihedral doesn't continue for another 100 feet. Gitt onn itt!

name: Donkey On My Mind
description: Donkey On My Mind is the clean cut overhanging dihedral on the left side of the wall.  It is the best protected .12 in the park, as well as one of the purest crack climbs despite the lack of much jamming. The start takes some effort and leads quickly to the crux which will force you to drop the clutch/crotch.  While cranking the feet up to your ears may be easier for shorter folks, the near everlasting reach above will keep things even.  While this route is a one trick pony, it is also one of the best tricks you will do.

name: High Traverse
description: Starting on the far left side, traverse the bottom of the crag through several tough crux sections.  This thing is pumpy and 1 and 1/2 times longer than the routes.  Enjoy amazing features and unbeatable landings.  Beautiful sending, as well as training. It is also harder going right to left.  Once upon a time there was also a low level traverse which was much more difficult.

name: Kingsbury Cruise
description: KB Cruise is a DL classic for the grade and climbs the right facing dihedral on the right side of the wall. Work up incipient jams which seem to get further apart the higher you climb, then move straight out the roof on jugs!

name: Kingsbury Non-Alcoholic Arete
description: Start up the same middle arete feature as for Shaking...Chimp.  Keep working up and right along this line to an obvious long move to a protruding jug.

name: Laser Beam
description: This is the left most line on the wall and easily distinguished.  Delicate, slopey moves will lead to decent crack.  Good solo.

name: Shaking Hands With The Chimp
description: One of the few .13s to be lead at the Lake. Dave’s gear consisted of two wires and filed down TCU to make the unit fit the placement. An inspiring feat!     Starting out on the arete in the middle of the wall work your way up to the right side of the slab. In the middle of the slab move left on good holds to the small dihedral/arete.  Climb up on big holds until just below the roof and the crux.  Powerful, bouldery moves out the roof lead to the inevitable mantle...  This one is sure no Ice.

name: Wet Paper Bag
description: This is just right of Kingsbury Cruise.  Start up a seam with delicate laybacking heading for the left facing dihedral at the top.  Climb into the upper corner then out the right side of the roof or straight over.

name: The Chopper
description: Good stances to place gear in this crack system with some nice hand jams. Follow the crack slightly left.

name: Equinox
description: Right-slanting crack.

name: Fall Is Near
description: Crack.

name: The Fang
description: Really fun crack with a nice crux at the end.

name: S Darko
description: Nice crack that sucks up pro, not that you will need any!

name: Bill's Beta
description: Short but difficult, not a lot of solid holds, tiny knobs mostly. Really takes some thought to figure out the problem. Old Timer named Bill got every climber up the route, but without his help we all kept falling.    #11 on page 60 of 3rd Edition Climbers Guide to Devils Lake

name: Bread and Jam
description: Fun finger crack on the first half that widens to hang jams at the top. Finish straight up the crack or go right at the ledge halfway for a more secure bouldering finish.

name: Crack 1.3
description: # 20 in Climbers Guide, farthest right of three cracks.

name: Double Fin
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: February 29
description: Eh, it's a warm up. Left wall is off. Go direct for better climbing in the same grade just right of the corner.

name: Flying Fish
description: Crux right in the middle as the wide crack zags right. Good warm up.

name: Hong Kong
description: You start on a rounded corner which seemed more slab than corner, and finish in the groove above. Very straight forward, fun climb. Left of Phooey. Route was not named in "Climber's Guide To Devil's Lake" so I gave it this name. Since it sits next to Phooey, these two climbs become "Hong Kong Phooey."

name: Leap Year
description: Low crux while pulling around the roof and eases off towards the top.

name: Phooey
description: Start at an inside corner crack, climb like a dihedral. Crack leads to an awkward overhang, the crux. Get past that and it's smooth sailing.

name: Squirrel Nut Project
description: A good find, pulling the roof seems to be the hard part.

name: Stride Right
description: Crux right in the middle of the wall.

name: Warm Up Groove
description: No crux really just a fun 25 ft of climbing.

name: First Aid
description: Start on the left side of the face. Traverse along the crack as the face gets steeper and the feet get smaller.  Fire up the final crack on somewhat rounded holds.    When you reopen the deep gash in your finger (from a kitchen accident), you may need aid to finish this route.  You definitely need your fingers for this route.

name: First Make a Wish
description: Up the surprisingly tenuous crack - you seldom have more than one good hold at a time.  At the break, cut left, right, or go straight up (the latter is probably the least appealing option).

name: Three Wishes
description: Three variations to this, go left for 5.6, pull the over hang for 5.10+ and go right for 5.5

name: The Ungotten
description: Found on an isolated little buttress above and left of the main U-Haul area at the same level as Alladin's Castle but more to the east.  This climb is just right of the route "First Aid".  Climb a neat fractured rib up the level of the bottom of a nice fist crack which the climber shifts right to gain.  Climb the fist crack and move right slightly again and pull the various edges and slopers above to finish off the last 15 feet.

name: Grotesque Features
description: Climb the right side of the distinctive rib that makes up Rickety Rib formation or as well climb the left side of the eastern exposure of Rickety Rib. Start just right of the large tree at the base of the formation. Climb consists of many great jugs, flat edges, pistol grips, and positive side pulls. Great fun and truly unique/unusual climbing for Devil's Lake. Gone is the expected pink quartzite uniformity we are all so used to. Truly grotesque features here.

name: Avis
description: Scramble up the chimney, then find your way to the bottom of the crack on the left side of the central face.  Once on the big ledge, continue angling up and right through the break in the overhangs.

name: Budget
description: Nice hand crack with face holds.

name: Free Mileage
description: A fun romp up 2" wide edges.  Swartling & Mayer describe some contrived 5.7 start, but if you are leading, the obvious place to begin is the crack system at the right end of the formation.  Continue up edges on the east facing wall, near the edge.  At the top, add some more free mileage by shifting right to the crack before topping out.

name: Hurts
description: Climb the broken overhanging crack just a few feet left of Budget, resisting the urge to bail onto that climb.  Though it is short, this climb packs quite a punch, and Swartling's 5.8 rating feels like a hefty sandbag.  It seems like very solid 5.9.

name: Rent-a-Wreck
description: Scramble up the chimney, beside "Avis".  Once past the crux of "Avis" you can step across to the big ledge, then head up the crack left of the corner.  Alternatively, keep going up the chimney.    There is a fair amount of loose rock on and around this route - make sure your belayer is in a safe location!

name: Condor Corner
description: If you bushwhacked your way to Condor Corner, you may as well get on this.  The crux is about 1/3 to 1/2 of the way up and is well protected.  Watch for loose junk since this route isn't exactly well traveled.

name: Fun One
description: Clean and straight, very nice.

name: Got You
description: The difficulty depends in part on how fat your fingers and hands are:  I find it too thin for my hands, but a bit rattle-y for my fat fingers.    Short but very sustained.

name: The Joker
description: A fairly direct little line.  You'll end up using the crack less than you expect, because there are several incut rails you can curl your fingers around.    And keep your feet outside the niches, or you will make things awkward for yourself!  The biggest foothold is not necessarily the best foothold.

name: Just Missed the Fun
description: Easy, except for the hard move.

name: Pete's Nemesis
description: A couple of moderate moves, then coil up and reach high for the crux holds.  (Figuring out which crimp to use is part of the crux.)  Somehow get your feet up onto the good foothold, then continue on to the top.

name: Salt Peter
description: Fun finger to hand crack just right of condor corner. This route would be classic, but you can easily bail into condor corner, making it somewhat contrived. Rib on the right is on at the start, then traverse over into finger crack.

name: Jerry
description: #2 in Sven's. Climb corner to bench. Continue in wide crack, finish on upper corner on top.

name: Mouse Crack
description: Worth doing? to get on the upper face.  "Tom" and "Jerry" provide better starts, I think.  No stars for this start, unless you are a true mountaineer, but three stars for the finish.    Grovel up the big holds and the crack, crawl through a shrub.  On the clean face above the ledge is a gorgeous, thin crack.  You can access it from the left across blocks, or from directly below.

name: Mouse House
description: Climb crack or just right of crack, 12 feet left of West Pillar (routes 7) Route 8 p.45 3rd edition

name: Mousehole
description: Best line on the wall. Climb a nice crack system with plenty of jugs.

name: Tom
description: Thin crack 4 feet right of Mousecrack route on Mousehole Buttress -  East of the Quarry rocks.  Share the same fine finish as Mousecrack or climb overhang above middle ledge and wander right around corner to finish upper section of Mousehole route.

name: Arm Overture
description: Crux at the bottom, pulling through the hand-crack.    Nice moves, but the upper crack funnels dirt.  Wear goggles.

name: Arm Symphony
description: Crack five feet right of Arm Overture

name: Encore
description: Start on a large flat rock, move up to the flaring slot.  Where a large crack cuts under the bulge and heads right, continue straight up the seam.

name: Largo
description: Start out on the left hand corner of Bandshell's west (left) buttress.  At about 10 feet, swing around to the right side of the corner.  Continue up, eventually shifted back out to the corner.    There is a variation to the start, by beginning on "Encore" and bumping left to "Largo."

name: Minuet
description: A delightful little crack system, slightly steeper than you expect it to be.

name: The Rattle
description: Climb face past a 3-foot flake 10 feet up on the right.

name: The Bishop
description: The crack that diagonals lower right to middle left.  Classic Devils Lake edges with less than you'd like for your feet.  It climbs a lot like the upper part of "Chicago".    You can stop at the shoulder where the crack ends, or continue up to the right.  It's easier to find an anchor up higher, under the cedar.

name: Close Call
description: A dihedral that will have you either stemming or squirming.  The initial section reminds me of "Lost Temple Crack."    For the upper portion, you can either finish left of the dihedral, or move right ... if you are leading, go right.

name: No Vacancy
description: Short, but every move is sweet.  From the big tree in the gulley, scramble up and left to the steep crack.  Pull up to and over the overhang.  Continue up the too-thin crack.    If you have extra small fingers, this will probably be easier for you!

name: The Pawn
description: Climb inside corner and slab. At 20 ft, switch to crack on the left wall. Finish right of summit block.

name: Sickle
description: The best route here at Prayer Wall!  Classic edges and sequence.  Starts at an incipient crack in the middle of the face, jogs left to pods in another incipient crack for a couple of moves, then moves back right to the 'sickle' shaped slot.  From here follow the gradually improving holds straight up along the crack.

name: This is a Six?
description: A very obvious hand/fist crack on the left hand side of Prayer Wall.  Classic!  Very smooth and even, with good hand and footholds along its outer edge on the upper half

name: Get Around
description: A fun little exploration.  Up the left side of the juggy lower face.  For the middle, step around the corner to the left and use the crack in the dihedral.  For the upper step, use the left edge of the face (easier than it may look) or go around the corner to the left and easier ground.

name: Three Step
description: A good route, in three distinct parts.  The lower face is juggy, but not without a puzzle.  Above the first ledge is a gorgeous crack (with an old fixed nut).  Above the second ledge is a face.  Go left for 5.8, right to the corner for 5.9.  Straight up the middle looks challenging!

name: West Siam
description: Good warm up.

name: American Dream Roof
description: There was a photo of American Dream Roof that hung above the bar at the now-defunct Conway's Pub. Inspired by the photo, many beer addled climbers hatched plans to hike out and climb ADR only to see those plans evaporate when the hangover set in. If you do make it out there, ADR is a must-do DL lead.      American Dream Roof climbs the conspicuous overhang on the right side of the buttress. Start up the easy inside corner and traverse to the roof. From here, place your entire rack of cams under the roof (when I first led it, I placed 5 cams) and climb, using dynamic moves, to the top.     Though it is possible to stop and place gear above the roof, I thought it added too much difficulty to be worth it, but make your own call.  ADR is basically a boulder problem protected by a bunch of gear that you put in from a great stance; therefore, it may be the easiest 5.10 lead at DL.

name: Face Value
description: Starts with a desperate crimpy boulder problem to a horizontal around 16+ feet off the ground.  From here, go more or less straight up the face with heroic moves on jugs and edges.  We did not use the right arete.

name: Left Turkey Foot
description: Chimney at the left end of the crag

name: Mother and Apple Pie
description: Use the crack as much as possible, liebacking to the left.  Ignore the guidebook and use the corner where it feels natural to grab it.

name: Pay Off
description: Route #3 in the guidebook for Bird-foot Buttress. A mediocre face that is slightly more fun than it appears. The guidebook rates it at 5.7 but it gets much easier if you are somewhat tall.

name: Right Turkey Foot
description: Chimney just right of American Dream Roof.

name: Squeeze Play
description: A clean, easy chimney, that chokes off 2/3 of the way to the top.  The crux is right where you think it is, and more awkward than it even looks.  A one-move climb.

name: Barefoot Bomber
description: Un-named in the guide book this is a nice route to access the top ledge and set TR for "The Blackboard".

name: The Blackboard
description: Smooth face below high point of buttress. Is the left arete on or not?!?!?

name: Chalk
description: Climb just West of the corner.This is a longer route than most in the area. Beware of loose rock in the upper part of the route.

name: Annie's 8
description: A big start to cool crack system leading to right of a thick pine tree.

name: Count your fingers
description: Inside corner crack with a very, very sharp edge.

name: Finger Fun
description: Start 5 feet right of count your fingers. Finish in crack above. Good climb with nice ledges and a good crack system. Fun for all your fingers!

name: Jam Crack
description: Jam up the obvious hand crack

name: Charlie Brown
description: Ok warm up, mostly small ledge pulling.

name: Escape from Nowhere
description: Up the crack of Nowhere Man to the ledge.  Then up out of the alcove and left across the ramp.

name: Fern Man
description: Start up crack on left side of the wall, Nowhere Man.  At the ledge, step right and use an unlikely-looking series of sidepulls and crimps to get to the top.    The hands end up being better than they look from below, but there isn't much for the feet most of the way.

name: Peanuts
description: It's a route!  Thin cracks to left of arete.

name: Pine Sap
description: It's a route!

name: Squirm
description: Inside Corner. Very awkward. Number 17 page 82 3rd edition

name: Faith, Hope, and Tension
description: Hand traverse from near the start of "The Doom" to the corner.  Continue up, staying on or just left of the corner

name: Furious Funnel
description: Over on left side of Lost Temple Rock mini amp area, left of Lost Temple Corner.  Climb broken rock to ledges then left up into "the funnel" and up rib to top.  Climber is forced to left of rib just a bit to make moves on upper section.  Difficulty rises if you stay right on rib or even right of it.  Upper moves of this rib part of the climb are unique.

name: Lost Temple Corner
description: Hug the initial pillar, stem the smooth corner, and then easier climbing with great finger & hand jams to the top.    Among the best 5.6s at the Lake!

name: Pitchfork Chimney
description: Chimney in the middle of the tower. A couple moves to the top.

name: Pitchfork Face
description: Start on route 13 (chimney). At 8 feet, step out of chimney and climb left corner and face to the top.

name: Deception
description: Wide, left-leaning crack.   #11 in the devils lake guide book 3rd edition. page 85

name: Ladybug Layback
description: Left-slanting crack in a prow of rock

name: Lamb & Eggs
description: Unlisted in the most recent edition of Swartling and Mayer this chimney/gully seemed like an obvious natural line and was most likely ascended in the days before recorded history and then wisely forgotten.    Easier, low-angle climbing with excellent rests leads to a steeper crux  near the top. That crux involves a disconcerting reach-and-step to the right to attain the final slab that guards the route's finish.     A muddy, horizontal hand jam between a large boulder and the dirt beneath makes the final move to the belay more comfortable.

name: Lost Arrow Spire - NE Ridge
description: Two moves.  Begin out of the notch between PI Wall and the Spire (okay, you have to scramble this far).  The first move is the crux.  The guidebook calls this move 5.6, but the difficulty depends on your inseam.  I'd say 5.6-5.8.    Don't forget to stand up on top.

name: No-Deception
description: Step up to flaring out notch. Step up to good hand hold. Follow cracks and locks to the top. Fun climb overall.

name: Ramses I
description: Like Ramses II, a burly little crack with an awkward move and an overhang at the top.

name: Ramses II
description: A burly little crack.  To do this with grace requires keeping your body away from the crack, but the brief fist/off-width moves will try to suck you in.  Overhangs a little at the top for full value.

name: Under the Bottle
description: Good hard route. Distinct crux. Ignore the guidebook suggestion that the upper left corner is off. Same grade and much more pleasant with it on.

name: Bloodshed
description: Good holds in the dihedral with fun laybacking. Climb the lower face to the grassy ledge and then go up in the dihedral to the roof, then go left into the next dihedral. Try the direct which goes right at the roof and uses the arete above the roof.

name: Breaking Away
description: Crux is first 20 feet. It's steep but with a lot of options for the feet and large jugs.  Make slight step left (into upper part of "Look Ma- No Hands" route after the crux to make it more protectable and easier).

name: Cutting Edge
description: Dirty start, good gear, fun moves, and maybe a bit under-rated in Swartling's guide.  Crux is obvious slight overhang.

name: Elimination
description: Easy crack climb with somewhat dubious rock quality. Makes for a descent warm up.

name: MANcation
description: Good moves all the way.

name: No Problem
description: Climb the flaring crack, looks harder than it is.

name: October Country
description: Big ol' crux to gain the slab! Climb the "down-sloping projections" with thin corner crack to gain the slab, then traverse left to a nice no hands ledge then up a small dihedral to the top.

name: White Wasp
description: Start under overhang , interesting moves lead to an easy finish in the dihedral.

name: Wounded Knee
description: Cool route that is sporty right at the crux.  Dirty start to ledge then make odd move into short corner with nice crack.  At big horizontal the business begins.  Make stiff moves either right or left up into tricky side pull and sketchy three cam placement.  Stay right of arete above.  There is a nice finger lock above that's nice for a gear placement too (just below top).  Semi jugs to be gotten above the crux but it is still hard due to little feet.

name: Double Jeopardy Cracks
description: Two laser cut cracks in a gently overhanging prow of rock.  One is finger size, the other is a hand crack.  Which one you gonna choose?    What you hoped "Via Apia" would be.    Not to be confused with "Double Jeopardy" near the Great Chimney.

name: Duracell
description: Climb face between Missing Piece and Magic Mushroom.

name: The Energizer
description: Hand crack through a small roof.  Add the steep face at the top for extra fun.

name: Gram Cracker
description: A couple of cool jams with excellent pro.

name: Gyno Cracks
description: Hard start and finish.

name: Missing Piece
description: A short clean line.

name: The V (aka The Vulva)
description: An unusual opportunity to exit a bomb-bay chimney via an offwidth.

name: R C Crack
description: This may be one of the hardest short crack climbs in the park, climb overhanging jam crack.    FYI  R C stands for Rectal Crack,

name: Aku Aku **route collapsed**
description: A series of high steps and side pulls.  On the upper part of the tower you have a choice of either using the left edge or the right edge (easier).

name: Civilian Stripes
description: Climb consists of 2 small corners stacked up on one another with a rest at the 1/2 way point.  Bottom corner is really nice stemming and small holds in the corner and out right within reach.  If you use the left rib holds and edges it is a bit easier but it doesn't add any security to a lead attempt.  The upper corner is steep and straight in but also has edges to utilize.

name: Easter Island
description: Scramble up on top of the pedestal-like block. Tip-toe up and make a committed bounce for the big ledge up and left - this will be very reachy if you are short.  Continue up big, flat holds to the horizontal seam and reach the crack that comes in on the right for your first gear.  Continue up the crack, harder than it looks, to the top.    An alternate start is to follow the crack that comes in from the right!

name: Purple Stripe
description: Climb up the set-back to the ledge, or climb a crack on the right and hand-traverse left to the ledge (more contrived, but more fun moves).  Step up on a decent foothold out on the face, and work your way through a serious of strenuous small holds up the seam to the top.  Clever footwork pays dividends here.

name: Unsatisfactorily
description: Up the prominent hand crack.

name: The Byrd aka No Sweat Overhang
description: This is on the first out cropping on your way up the trail, so it's a convenient spot to drop your pack and consume some of that cheap swill you have been carrying.  A small roof that use to be aided on pins. Bring lots of r.p.s and small wires.

name: Mongo Fury
description: Sweet and very fun 30 feet of climbing positive but intense vertical to overhanging arete (and crack just right of arete) up into rest and big horizontals then final steep exit crack and edges.   Crux is at mid height moving off positive horizontal hand match to pull on small side pull above to get into large jugs/ledges and protruding flake rest.

name: The Mongo Mantle
description: Found to the left and around corner from the route Mongo Fury.  Climbs small rib via small but positive holds up to large horizontal then up crystalline flake to crux mantle move and then final odd groove above.  Route appears as only a number in guidebooks and is very short but well worth an on-sight lead attempt.

name: No Sweat
description: Easy climbing to a difficult pull into a open book dihedral. Utilize slopers on the right to gain access to the book.

name: Annie's Overhang
description: A nice 5.7 with plenty of pro.

name: Barefoot Crack
description: This is a fun face and crack route.  Ample protection for a beginning leader but building an anchor on top could be exciting for a beginning leader.  This could be the third pitch of a Guillotine ridge route.

name: Beginner's Chimney
description: Climb the obvious chimney to the right of Broken Boulders.  Not as good for the grade as Broken Boulders but still fun.  I should give it one more star because the climbers in the photo are clearly having a good time.

name: Broken Boulders
description: Starting just to the right of a 5.7 corner follow the line of boulders to the top.  A good variation is to start to the right on a slanting ledge and join the main route.  A fun easy route.

name: Dirty 30 Tower
description: Start in front of the tower. Pull a flake for the start. Choose either the right crack or left and pull the overhang leading to the summit. Down climb the back side to get off and walk back around.

name: Guillotine 49
description: Corner on South-East side of Guillotine. This is #49 in Swartling/Mayer book 3rd ed.

name: Labor Pains
description: Labor Pains is the route located on the central portion of the Guillotine wall and begins on a precarious platform. Start at a jug with feet under the roof, pull up on crimps to a mantle move and follow crack systems to the top of the wall. The crux is low and not well protected.

name: The Layback
description: Climb the offwidth crack to the right of Broken Boulders. Guide book says 5.4 if you jam your left leg in the crack, 5.7 if done as a pure layback.  I have climbed approximately 60 routes at Devil's Lake so I know the ratings are stiff here, but this route is in the running for one of the hardest 5.4's on the planet.  I will go back and lead it before passing final judgement.

name: Levitation
description: Levitation is an inside corner system on the left side of the Guillotine wall- the corner system to the left of Labor Pains (5.10b). Get off the ground, crux, and move through the series of low roofs using good jams and stemming. A 5.9 variation goes up the left face after pulling the first roof. This climb is a good lead for those just breaking into the trad game. Dare I to say that this might be harder if face holds aren't used and only jams employed to move over the roofs?

name: Levitation Right Side
description: Step up on the initial, big footholds, then wonder what to do next.  A devious puzzle.    The answer seems to be:  use crimps and foot-chips to get your foot into the large, sloping incut.  Stand up and reach for a large hold at the top of the slab.  Get your fingers in the horizontal out on the right face (the first good gear!), and continue straight up or move over to the right.

name: Makeover
description: Probably the best of the short, unnamed routes on the east side of the Guillotine. Start by laying back or jamming the crack, gain a small alcove, then use face holds or jam your way to top.

name: The Pike
description: #52 on page 99 of Climbers Guide to Devils Lake. Described as: "Narrow face with small holds". Everyone agreed this was a 5.8+++, it's harder than most Devils Lake 5.8s. Do not use either corners of the face or you are off route. It's a bare climb with small holds, two ledges to rest on, nothing more.    I named it The Pike as it's part of The Guillotine, and what's left to do with a decapitated head? Put it on The Pike.

name: Poison Ivy
description: Corner with small holds at first.

name: Rhus Toxicodendron Radicans
description: This route starts about 15 to the left of Levitation. Climb to the right of the corner by about 6 feet. Use small sidepulls and crimps to gain a decent ledge then follow thin crack to another ledge and take it to the top.

name: Also Close to the Thing
description: Start in the trail, where it passes between the wall and a tree.  Your belayer will have to keep an eye out for hikers (there is room to step off to the side).    Use juggy holds to get up on the bench.  Work up the thin seam until you can move right to the corner, and finish up to the top.

name: Body Snatcher Variation
description: Up the short wall, just left of the "Body Snatcher," then up the crack and flake.

name: The Bodysnatcher
description: The Bodysnatcher is a finger crack leading to an OW crack is a box, capped by a roof. Climb up cracks and exit around the roof to the left.     The Bodysnatcher Direct: 5.10c, Climb the beginning of Bodysnatcher to the roof and pull straight over the roof.

name: The Monster
description: Crack through the steep wall to the left of The Flatiron. Crack starts out steep with good finger locks and abundant gear placements. Avoid stepping off to ledge on the right as it defeats the purpose of surmounting the lower moves.  Bottom portion of the route ends at a large jug.  From the jug place large cams and get ready to pull hard 5.10 laybacking and/or offwith.  Finish is tricky and strenuous but not as difficult.  The whole route barely makes 35 ft., I think, and it is strangely stout.

name: 30 Second Crack
description: Climb the crack in the corner to the left of Ship's Prow.  No surprises here, plenty of protection and straight forward moves.

name: Cemetery Wall
description: Short climb but fun and challenging for the grade.  Basically climb the center of the face.  The crux for me was getting on to the ledge where the climber's hand is in the photo.  Too short to warrant more stars.

name: Darkness At Noon
description: One of the most sustained squeeze chimneys to be had at Devils Lake.  Move up the chimney without getting stuck until you reach some chockstones, do an exposed move out and around the chockstones, and top out.

name: Easy Overhang
description: As the name implies, Easy Overhang is a straight forward climb up monster, positive holds.  However, those lacking upper body strength may need some artful footwork just below the overhang.  Start behind the large block left of Last Gasp and go up to a ledge.  Follow the crack on the right up to and over the roof.    In the photo below, the overhang is near the very bottom at the left.  Last Gasp on the corner to the right.

name: The Grand Traverse
description: While not nearly as grand of a traverse as its namesake in the Tetons, the Devil's Lake version of the Grand Traverse offers an interesting alternate start to Last Gasp. Instead of starting in the pit below Last Gasp, start on the good holds around the corner to the right, where the vertical wall meets the roof of Zschiesche's Roof. Traverse up and left to the corner, and finish on the upper section of Last Gasp.

name: Last Gasp
description: Last Gasp is an aesthetically pleasing line up an obtuse outside corner just left of Darcy's Wall.      The true ascent line starts just left of the corner in a depression which in days of yore was called the "Snake Pit."  One can start more easily even farther left behind a standing block and traverse back to the corner on a ledge, however this is considered an anathema and doesn't make the ascent that much easier anyway.     Continue more or less straight up, or a little left of, the corner to the top.  Unless you are a real hardman you will know at the top why it is called "Last Gasp."

name: Ship's Prow
description: Climb the corner just to the left of Cemetery Wall. If you miss some key holds or cannot reach them, this route will feel a bit harder than its rating.  The crux for me was getting past the roof.  This route like Cemetery Wall is short but fun.

name: Zig-Zag
description: Between the boulder and the wall, do a move up to the big horizontal ledge.  "Zig-Zag" continues more or less up the crack in front of you (while "Easy Overhang" traverses right and up the other crack).  The crux is the first few moves off the ledge.  Zig left up into the alcove, then zag right back into the crack.    Until 2007 or so there was a large basswood tree (see the photos of "Easy Overhang") that pressed you against the rock at the crux, and provided a convenient point of protection as well.  Now that the tree is gone, this route has a much different feel at the crux....    Feels similar to the move left on "The Rack" to me, so I've called it a 5.7 instead of the traditional 5.5.

name: Zschiesche's Roof
description: Short powerful movement through the roof at the base of Darcy's Wall. Toproped first,.. the led with a piton for protection.

name: All The Way
description: Do you want to lead a 5.12 at the Lake? I'm talking about a "real" 5.12--not some obscure short climb at Horse Rampart or some corner over at Sandstone. I'm talking about hard moves, tricky pro and mandatory runouts in groundfall territory. I'm talking about a 5.12 that is a hair's breadth away from the mythical routes like Bagatelle whose leads only live in the memory of a few crazed souls. Yeah, you guessed it, I'm talking about going All the Way.  As with all 5.12 leads at DL, the stories about All the Way abound. Of course there was Deutchler's first ascent, which I didn't witness (I was two years old), but which I imagine taking place with a bunch of DLFAers sitting around, saying "Whoa man, that was groovy." Tommy's ascent did pave the way for other groundbreaking ascents of the era, Bagatelle included. Then there's the time that Zschiesche headed up the climb with no gear, and asked bystanders to throw him up the needed pieces. This technique never seemed to catch on, as the hassle I'm sure outweighed any weight savings. And finally, there was the time when I punted off the start crux moves, crashed into the arms of my spotters and may have broken, or seriously sprained, the finger of one willing spotter.  To start the climb, locate the funky corner to the right of Congratulations. Climbing from the ground to the obvious hourglass hold presents the crux of the route. I thought it felt about V6, but I used spotters and crashpads, so feel free to judge me as not a true trad climber. There is no real pro until you stick the hourglass hold. Once you stick the hold, however, you must steel yourself for some heady climbing to reach the belay ledge of The Pedestal. This section feels 5.11ish, and you pass a welcome horizontal that offers a good rest and some nice pro. Above the horizontal, a small stopper protects the final hard move, which is just tenuous enough to keep your attention as you reach The Pedestal ledge.  I'm not sure how the original route finished, but I like to think that Deutchler forged straight up the wall above The Pedestal ledge. On my lead, I tried to stay true to the line and I headed up steep rock above the ledge up to the long-forgotten mini-route called The Trick. This 5.8 wall is a harder ending to Lower Diagonal, and in my eyes, is the natural ending to All the Way. Climbing on that upper wall, I think I felt the "real" Devil's Lake 5.12 lead experience--moving up beautiful 5.8 high above your gear, but feeling solid and psyched because you've already passed the crux below. You did it, going All the Way to the top.

name: Angle of the Dangle
description: Climb from the ground Directly to the pin on Upper D.    Follow Upper D for 10' I think(Someone who's done it lately will be more accurate) Then take off straight up following Micro-Edges all the way to the top.    I had Tr'd the thing repetedly for weeks then one day, sntached up somebody's climbing partner and bam led it.    Or should I say soloed it, as there is NO gear on the actual route itself. The last piece possible to get is a Piece right before you leave Upper-D.    Don't fall at the crux unless your comfort level includes a 50 footer...

name: Assume the Position
description: Surprised this isn't added already. How many times have I walked past this? Probably 1000. Great moves with three distinct cruxs. End with the layback crux of Rich and Famous.

name: The Beginning
description: The Beginning is found between The Stretcher (route 31) and Chimney's End (route 29).  It is easily identified as the v-shaped dihedral to the left of Chimney's End.  Climb up the dihedral using the crack and face holds.

name: Birch Tree Crack
description: Birch Tree Crack is found just off the CCC trail on the southeast side of the Pedestal Buttress.  Climb up on blocky terrain about 5 feet to access the crack.  The crack starts out with you in a small alcove.  Step up on a loose block and perform a tricky sequence to ascend the first section of the crack (the section with less features and lots of white chalk).  Once above this crux continue on slightly easier terrain.  Try to jam the crack instead of using the features on the face.  It makes things more interesting.

name: Blow-up
description: Blow-up begins by following Sometime Crack until about 2/3rd height where an obvious horizontal cuts left from the rest jug. Follow this horizontal by traversing left all the way to the corner, where you will be greeted by good holds and jams to the top.

name: Chimney's End
description: Chimney's End is about the best example of a squeeze chimney you'll find at The Lake.  Climb up the blocky rock in the corner below the chimney.  Once you get to the chimney do some scissors/stemming moves and inch your way up to the top.

name: Condolences
description: A wandering line near the left-hand edge of Campus Wall.  Jam your way up the initial crack - getting around the bulge is the crux.  Join "The Pedestal" in time for the move around the nose to the left.  Belay in the crow's nest, or continue left and up through the upper part of "Congratulations".  Watch out for rope drag if you try to do this in one pitch! Location Where the CCC trail comes up below the East Rampart and turns right, start in the crack a few feet right of the nose.

name: Congratulations
description: Congrats is a classic among classics. A striking 5.10 finger crack positioned at the crossroads of climbing on The East - it is the 5.10 to climb at The Lake. Congrats is considered by many to be the bar for 5.10 at Devil's Lake - climb it on TR and you are a 5.10 top-roper, lead it and you are a 5.10 leader. You might get lucky on the likes of Mouse's Misery or Callipigeanous Crack, but Congrats earns every bit of its 5.10 rating and so do you...if you send. It's also a great place to see and be seen, since just about every climber on the The East will walk past it (probably at least twice) during the day. Time your send right, and you might draw a hearty "Congrats!" and the offer of a beer from some grizzled local in the overflow lot at the base of the CCC later. But that sword cuts the other way as well - your wobbler-filled flail sesh will not escape the eyes of the masses either. In the end, Congrats should not be missed by anyone.

name: Creation Crack
description: This pretty delightful crack is found on the north facing inside wall right by Chimney's End. Follow the hand crack and finger crack all the way to the top. Obviously, using the opposite wall would be cheating. Don't fall! Pretty solid hands, fingers and a bit of liebacking all packed into 40 feet.

name: D.L.F.A
description: didn't know where else to put this classic photo of the D.L.F.A. circa 1981.  will post pic when this route makes it to data base.

name: The End
description: This route is well worth doing whether ya lead it or toprope it.  On the far left side of the Sometimes formation,by the chimney.  Start off the block, or do the direct start.

name: F4 Ledges
description: Follow the wide crack system to the right of Birch Tree Crack and just left of the dihedral (the Beginning 5.7).  This is basically a variation of the Beginning, but is listed in Mike Farris's book (Rock Climbing Minnesota and Wisconsin) as a 5.4 called F4 Ledges (pgs 75-76).

name: Flake Route
description: Flake Route is the quintessential Devil's Lake climb--thin technical crimping on a vertical face.     Start up the center of "Campus Wall" directly underneath the alcove on Upper Diagonal. Climb straight up to the alcove, where you will find a fixed pin and a sneaky no-hands rest. Next, cast right and up, following small square cut crimpers up the center of the wall.    This climb is actually better protected than it looks if you place gear (.5 and .75 Camalots) on Upper-D, a few feet above the alcove.

name: Golden Ledges
description: this is another classic lead. fuk-nes moves with the possibility of hitting the ledge type pedestal should you blow it ,which i have seen people do.we use to put a pack on the pedestal to pad it.

name: Hourglass
description: Hourglass begins by climbing into the crux of Birch Tree crack and when you've finally reached a decent hold on Birch Tree, cut left onto the face a few feet using crimps. Deadpoints on marginal crimps bring you to a decent rest ledge. From here fire straight up on super dooper thin crimps and make another long deadpoint to a decent hold and continue on good ledges to the top. A thriller of a route and if this gets ya goin... try the Hourglass Direct. I think they call it Hourglass because the pump timer is ticking...

name: Ironmongers
description: 15' or so to the left of Congrats    Start at the base of the tree, Climb into alcove.    Do SWEET layback moves to get you into the crack & to the top!

name: Ironmongers Super Direct
description: This is the face 5 feet left of Ironmongers.  Sven says that everything except the corner is on, but I found the grade to be accurate only if you stay on the face and don't use any holds in or to the right of the crack on Ironmongers.  A bit of history and clarity from Jim Erickson:  "This 20-foot, very contrived boulder problem was, in 1966, the hardest lead at the Lake. It was done by Sheldon Smith ground up, placing 2 soft iron, knife blades in the first ten feet with no chalk in a pair of Spider kletterschuhe. He didn't fall, but lowered off once after pounding in the first pin. He then went back up, placed the second one and sent. None of us could follow, despite many attempts. It goes straight up the thin crack to the bucket on Ironmonger's. Within reach, but not allowed, are the huge right arete side- pull and 2 fairly good edges within 6 inches of the arete. A year later, the amazing Tom Higgins easily top-roped it on his first try, chalkless in a pair of Kronhofers! It took me about 15 tries to top rope it over the next 4 years "

name: Lethe
description: Lethe, the river of forgetfulness of the five rivers of Hades.  If you're climbing this route you may have forgotten that there's better routes very nearby.  That said, its not a bad route, just not much to it.  Climb the slab and overhang left of Evelyn, and follow the easy crack from the ledge to the top.

name: Lower Diagonal
description: Lower Diagonal starts just to the right of the big dead tree stump.  Climb up the crack to a ledge.  At the ledge, follow the lower diagonal crack (less defined than the upper) to the corner of the buttress, then climb up the corner to the top.

name: The Pedestal
description: The Pedestal is a fun climb that is typically done in two pitches to reduce rope drag.  Start by the flake near Lower Diagonal.  Climb up about 15 feet then traverse left on top of flake (psychological crux) and around the corner.  Belay stance is in a comfortable notch.  The second pitch continues up and left toward the pine tree.  Finish up on a ten foot wall with a one-move crack.

name: Pine Box
description: Nice thin corner to the left of Congrats, somthin to lead when all of the bumblies have the other routes plugged with weenie (i.e. top) ropes...

name: Sometime Crack
description: Sometime Crack is found on the monolith of rock that sticks out between the Pedestal Buttress and D'Arcy's Buttress.  The climb faces southeast and is overhanging.  Start out on a slabby piece of rock that is rated about 5.6.  Climb the 10-15 feet to the top of this slab and you'll be standing on a ledge at the base of the crack.  Climb the crack using jams (it's the only way in this case, so don't try to layback or you'll get spit off).  At the top of the crack the route goes to the right on a less defined crack/ledge for about 10 feet to the top.

name: Sometime Direct
description: A superb climb. Start same as Sometime Crack but at the niche half way up, continue straight up the face instead of angling to the right. The holds are good on the face, until the last move...

name: Sometimes Right
description: Found in the shadow of Sometimes Crack, this often overlooked and scrappy line is a good lead for the grade, though somewhat in your face at the start. Climb thin steep crack into the finish of the regular route.

name: Sweatshop
description: Sweatshop climbs the diagonal face between the two striking lines Upper Diagonal and Lower Diagonal. Start on the left side of the pedestal that is the start to Upper D and go left towards a jug and then crimp the rest of the way to the top left corner of Pedestal Buttress.

name: Upper Diagonal
description: One of the best routes Devil's Lake has to offer. The name says it all. When facing the right side of Pedestal Buttress this route slices up and left from the ledge at the base of Birch Tree Crack. Stay on the higher of the cracks, as the other is obviously Lower D. Good stopper from finger locks and at times insecure feet lead to a pleasant topout. Also easy to TR, but a swing is inevitable. Better to swing low than high. That's what she said.

name: The A-Frame (aka Uranus)
description: The A-Frame is a dirty chimney that climbs up through a tight hole from the base of the Gills Buttress mass, up to the top of the  pillar where Acid Rock, Peyote Blues, etc start.       From the base of the climb you'll see an obvious large, left leaning block called the Shaft. Climb under the Shaft to the left, up through the small hole, and continue on through the tight, wet, but surprisingly not-dirty chimney through a few actually fun moves. Because of the wetness there is practically no friction in the A-Frame - even by Devils Lake standards.

name: Boy Scout
description: This route is best is best when simul-climbed or soloed, unless you are a boy scout.  It is the big chimney and slab in the corner to the right of Brinton's Crack and left of Gill's Nose.    Good first simul-climb, watch for pigeons, and be sure to kiwi-coil rope.

name: Gill's Cheek
description: From the DL guide:   "GILL'S CHEEK, 5.11d/12a. Climb wall between Gill's Nose and Gill's Crack, avoiding holds on other climbs."

name: Gill's Crack
description: Gill's Crack is a strenuous route up the steep west face of Gill's Buttress.  Start out by climbing about halfway up the slab of Boyscout (rt 57).  When you reach the waterstained rock with a faint crack, begin your ascent up the face to your right.  Thin moves near the bottom transition into finger jams and laybacks about 20 feet up.  The crux, in my opinion, occurs just before the depression in the rock that leads into the hanging dihedral.  A fun route!

name: Gills Nose Direct
description: The more straight up variation of Gills Nose, this is one of the finest routes on the bluff. Climb the first half of the route and continue straight up instead of left to a jug for Gills Nose regular. Some people use the arete, some don't. The sequence for the top is always seeming to change. Gain the ledge and then a few trivial moves for the top out.

name: The Spine
description: This short, but appealing crack/chimney, protects well and would make a good introduction to climbing or leading.  Start in cleft above tree using both walls to ascend.   Variation 5.6: Start from the Acid Rock start ledge and diligently avoid the right-hand wall while focusing your attention on the crack in the left-hand wall.  If it was longer and not an eliminate this variation would be a four star route.

name: Twin Cracks
description: These twin cracks follow either a right facing dihedral or left facing dihedral just to the right of Fantasy & Weasels Ripped My Flesh. Relatively interesting and sometimes dirty.

name: Berkeley
description: This route shares the same start as Chicago but traverses right below the triangular niche.  After traversing right the crux comes when pulling back to the left on some steeper terrain.  The route finishes in a chimney/gully to the right of Chicago's  finish.  A classic.

name: Brinton's Corner
description: Climb corner all the way to the top, avoid reaching too far right and using Brinton's crack.

name: Brinton's Crack
description: Brinton's is perhaps the most classic among the many classic moderates at Devil's Lake. The elegance of the line, the interesting moves, and the exposure are unmatched.     Follow the main weakness on the left edge of the buttress. This will take you to a cramped alcove. From here, traverse to the right across good footholds, but miserable hand holds. Many consider this the crux. Protection for the traverse is "adequate."     After the traverse, climb straight up a short jam crack (crux #2) to a blocky, airy finish.

name: Brinton's Direct
description: Brinton's Direct is an excellent variation to the mega-classic Brinton's Crack. Rather than traversing right at the alcove (a la Brinton's Crack), Brinton's Direct forges a bold path straight up the face. These tenuous and airy moves lead directly (hence the name) to the top of the buttress.     On lead, the climb protects fairly well, but it's just run-out enough to give it that unique Devil's Lake feel. All in all, The Direct is a very worthwhile route on one of the best chunks of stone in the park.

name: Cheap Thrills
description: Cheap Thrills is a former aid line freed by Pete Cleveland (imagine that). It follows the impressive step face right of Britons Crack.    Also of note is Cheap Swill by Rich Bechler(do Cheap Thrills and at top traverse to right for more hard climbing).

name: Chicago
description: Chicago is an old school bold lead that has been tamed significantly by the advent of spring loaded cams and better small gear.  Start up the crack system with good gear options on the beautiful vertical face.  Essentially the same start as Berkely, although perhaps a touch left.  At around 20 feet you come to a perfect triangular niche.  The crux of the climb is exiting this niche.  Once you commit to the moves to take you above the niche, a few more insecure moves deposit you high up on the wall where you can breathe a sigh of relief and take in the scenery.

name: Evanston Township
description: Climb up ledges to the left of Chicago (start of 5.6 chimney). As ledges end, move on to the face following the finger crack left of Chicago.

name: Evanston Township Direct
