name: Jungle Gym East Face
description: This is the crack on the east face of Jungle Gym Tower (Route 33 "Climber's Guide").  The route starts near the bottom of the gully between Devil's Doorway and the tower, and ends on the top of the tower.  It was used as our 3rd pitch on the route "Jungle Gym."

name: Mary Jane
description: Mary Jane is located in the same area as the Jolly Roger and Angel's Crack.  The climb is 50 feet of vertical, well sustained 5.7 climbing with the 5.8 crux at the top.  Climb up using horizontal cracks and ledges, avoiding the corner to the right.  Near the top you will find a ledge to stand on and above it you will see a vertical crack.  To finish the climb, reach up with both hands and finger jam in this crack while stepping up with a smear on the smooth rock at knee level.  It's a really fun crux if you've got the reach.    To get to the top of Mary Jane, hike along the Devil's Doorway Trail and take the short scenic trail that dips down to the famous Devil's Doorway formation. There is a staircase that passes between two short walls of rock on the east end of this short trail. If you walk down these stairs you will see an outcropping straight ahead and an outcropping to the right (west). Mary Jane faces south off the end of the western outcropping.     To get to the bottom of the climb from here, walk back up the stairs discussed earlier and take a right (east) down the slope through the woods (before you get back to the main Devil's Doorway Trail).  This is the gully that sits between the Major Mass and Minor Mass. Hug the rock on your right and pass right (south) through the first "saddle" you see. Go through the saddle and turn right again (west) with the rock still to your right.  You are now on the ledge that separates the Upper and Lower bands of the Major Mass.  In Swartling's book on diagram 33E, page 141, you are standing somewhere between the words "Access" and "Angel's Traverse".Scramble west about 150 feet until you get to the base of the climb.  For reference, you will see some dead brush and a large, flat-topped boulder to your immediate left (to the south of the wall).  The climb is just past this boulder.

name: Rosemary's Baby
description: Located 8 feet left of Mary Jane is a route that's very similar to Acid Rock on the East Bluff. Easy access and TR make this an easy afternoon send!

name: Three Kings
description: Work up the pleasant blocks above the access trail for the Upper Band.  At the penultimate shelf, move left to the off-sized crack in the dihedral.  Either attack this head on, or, after reaching up and placing your gear, do a strenuous layback.

name: W.A.R
description: Listed in Sven's book as a variation of Ceder Tree Crack this is a nice independent line.     It starts with some excellent jams and pro but ends with a head game.     Named after the cutest damn baby in the whole wide world.

name: A Cheval
description: Starts hard on a sharp arete and then eases off with good pro.

name: B-minor Mass
description: B-minor Mass is located on the South Tower of the Minor Mass of the Doorway Rocks.  The lower half of the climb starts out on the south-facing buttress of the South Tower.  Climb from here up to the ledge using nice easy holds.  From the ledge traverse left and climb up through an easy overhang.  On the final ledge ascend the inside corner to the top.

name: Disinclination
description: Disinclination starts out at the ledge gained by climbing Obduracy (route 5).  Locate the trunk of the dead pine tree to the left of the dirty gully.  Climb up to this pine tree.  Once at the tree make your way to the right of the tree and climb up the dihedral behind the tree to the top on easy ledges.  When this climb is linked with Obduracy it makes for a nice long climb.  It would be more highly rated if some of the brush weren't there.

name: Empty Nester
description: Like the routes to the right, the start is harder than it looks.  Very thin bit to finish directly to right at the top.  Like Mr. Wizard there are good edges on the upper face.

name: Flotsam and Jetsam
description: Flotsam and Jetsam are two climbs on the east face of the Minor Mass of the Doorway Rocks.  They can be easily located by finding the large pine tree that lays across the chimney below Pigeon Roof.    The right variation of the route is the longer of the two.  Make your way up to the "Saddle".  From the saddle climb around so that you're above the fallen tree at the bottom of an inside corner about 10 feet above the "Saddle".  Climb up the inside corner on easy holds to the south face of a small tower.  Use ledges to gain the top of the tower.    The left variation climbs up the chimney that contains the fallen tree.  This variation is the more awkward variation and is less recommended than the right variation.

name: Great Mass in C Minor
description: The hardest moves are right off the starting ledge and the there is a  a tricky little musical sequence above pulling over onto the first prominent ledge.  The upper half is even 5.5 tempo.

name: Green Ledges
description: Very nice varied line.  Starts out as steep slab with a series of ledges and mantles and barely adequate small pro.  Second half of climb ascends steep and somewhat devious steep groove and final sorta sketchy small overhang and grooves.

name: Green Slab
description: Start at the lowest part of the main wall on the west side of Minor Mass. Climb the rounded slabby nose. When you reach the upper overhang, stay right and climb the face on the right side of the overhang to the top.  If you set a toprope from the very top of the Green Slab/A Cheval "tower", it'll use almost all of a 60m rope. There is a secondary ledge below the top that could be used for a shorter rope, but it is not trivial to reach it. Actually, I set my 60m rope from the very top and climbed A Cheval first, then with minimal change to the anchor at the very top I rapped down to the secondary ledge and set a redirect to the climbers left which put the rope in a better position for Green Slab.  (This is S/M #19.)

name: In the Heat of the Sun
description: In the Heat of the Sun is located on the east face of the South Tower.  Climb up the center of the face on small features to the top of the tower.

name: LadyFingers
description: LadyFingers starts on the ledge gained by climbing Obduracy (route 5).  It follows the groove and crack found almost directly behine the large oak tree.  Climb from the ledge up to the groove using small holds and horizontal ledges.  Try not to get spit out when you reach the groove.  To surmount the groove reach up to the finger crack above and pull past the groove.  Finish using the crack to the top.

name: Manhandler
description: Crux is pulling the roof move.  Nice crack, edges, and roof line to the left of Green Ledges route.  Low down start in left most crack (another route if you stay in this crack) then after maybe 10 Ft maximum make rightwards move utilizing small but sharp and positive pulls up and under the roof.  There is somewhat of a sucker rest standing on a major horizontal under the roof.  Above the roof the crack continues with major horizontals for the feet and one passes near an old tree stump sticking out.

name: Mr Wizard and Tutor Turtle
description: One of the taller routes at Minor Mass.

name: No Stranger to the Fist
description: This route is located on the east face of the Minor Mass of the Doorway Rocks, to the left (south) of the large oak tree.  The route is about 80 feet long. To climb the route start out by making your way up to the "Saddle" using easy ledges.  Once on the saddle climb the face directly below the roof using small, balancey face holds.  At the top of the face surmount the four-foot roof and continue up to the top with easy moves.

name: Obduracy
description: Obduracy is a short route to the right of an oak tree and left of a steep dihedral.  Use ledges to gain the top of the climb.  The climb is used to access the ledge above, from which the routes Disinclination, Power of a Good Haircut, and Ladyfingers are climbed.

name: Off Width His Head!
description: Get whatever you can fit into the narrow off-width and squirm and chicken wing up as the crack gradually widens. Shove yer whole self in and chimney up until the roof tries to lop yer head off. A good side pull and hand sized crack around the roof will help you escape on to the top ledge. Bailing early on to the first ledge will get you sent straight to the guillotine.

name: Oofdah Left
description: Any easy route with that can be climbed several ways. Start by climbing the large detached boulders 10 ft left of the arete, go up about 10 ft and step across. Climb up the blocky face left of the arete, wandering left or right as needed. End just left of the top of the arete. A variation starting off the smaller block closer to the arete is a little harder.  (This is #26 in the Swartling-Mayer guide 3rd ed.)

name: Oofdah Right
description: Climb the face on the right side of the arete. Starts out easy, following an inside corner angling up and right (or stay on the face left of the inside corner). The climb gets interesting on the top half where you have to choose to climb the arete on the left, the vertical crack 4 ft right of the arete or a 2nd vertical crack 3 ft right of the 1st crack. Alternative climb is to follow the point of the arete all the way up.  (This is #25 in the Swartling-Mayer guide 3rd ed.)

name: Pigeon Roof
description: This route climbs the big crack on the east face of Minor Mass.  From below the roof looks imposing, but it is surprisingly easy.  Above the roof ... is the crux!    An initial, scrambling start on the left (west) side of the lower wall takes you to the big ledge system that runs under the upper face, from the saddle on the left to the gully on the right.    A few strenuous moves in the dihedral get you established on the wall.  At the overhang, keep your eyes peeled for holds beside the crack.    Once past the overhang, a combination of arm bars and tiny face holds allow you to progress further.

name: Rainman
description: Faint crack system on the face right of pigeon roof.  The climb is hard off of the ledge, and  the crux involves some tricky movement through the overhang, finishing on the face to the right of the arete next pigeon roof.

name: Saturday Forever
description: This route follows a prominent crack line up the minor buttress on the right of Minor Mass right side.  It's more or less where route #1 on page 158 (marked on diagram 34E page 157) of Swartling/Mayer 3rd Edition "Climbers Guide to Devils Lake".  The crux hits the climber directly off the ground with steep tricky moves to gain a small first ledge but there is a minor crux pulling through the finger crack section above onto a second ledge.  There is a steep and thinly protected short wall to surmount above the second ledge to gain a third huge ledge (watch out on the moves pulling over - all downward sloping) then a final poorly protected final slab wall (or nearly not at all if climber takes the face strictly).  Climber can utilize a large crack on he right for gear for this upper section and there is fixed pin as well but it is not a direct route of ascent.

name: Bill
description: Left-slanting crack. Number 13 page.162 3rd edition

name: Inside Corner
description: If your climbing here you are probably looking for easy routes.  So you might just as well do this one also.  Not a bomb, but definitely not more than one star.

name: Ledge Jam Crack
description: Climb ledges and cracks up the face.  Fun little climb.  Just follow the line of least resistance.    Staying tight to the left corner is 5.8.

name: Red Rocks Chimney
description: The Red Rocks Chimney ascends the dihedral/chimney behind the large tree just above the gap in the Red Rocks.  Climb using the dihedral crack and ledges (not the tree) and finish by squeezing through the converging chimney at the top.

name: Southwest Dihedral
description: Climb the southwest dihedral as shown in the photo.  Nice little route to an island summit.

name: 6 foot, 7 foot, 8 foot, Ledge!
description: At the base of the climb, Tree and a half men are to the right, this is just around the corner to the left.

name: Tree and a Half Men
description: Corner rock that can easily have a TR set up with a BD #1, #0.75, and #0.5. When looking over the edge, to the right is Tree and a Half Meters, to the right is 6 foot, 7 foot, 8 foot, ledge!

name: 12 5.9 dihedral
description: page 168 "climber guide to devil's lake" #12 unnamed 5.9   Start from dirt and rock slope on left side of the gully. Climb wall a few feet right of inside corner into a shallow dihedral to top.

name: 13 5.4 Corner
description: page 168 "Climber's guide to devil's lake" unnamed 5.4 corner.  Climb inside corner of of large ledge past protruding chockstone

name: 22 5.8 face climb
description: Page 168 "climber's guide to devil's lake" unnamed 5.8   Start an arms reach from west end of wall. Climb horizontal edges top, or traverse right on large horizontal to roof with crack running through the middle.

name: 6.63 Smoots
description: Between the inside corner of New Box and the outside corner of Mr. Neutron is a four foot wide face.  This climb goes right up the middle using no holds of the other climbs.  This is a very continuous climb with almost every move a 5.7 or tougher.  You could lead it by putting pro in the New Box crack.   The name is because it is 37' high.

name: AAHRG
description: AAHRG! is located about 5 feet left of Sunken Pillar and just right of Red Pulpit but stays off of both. The crux, in my opinion, is the start. The first couple of moves on smaller edges and sidepulls to gain larger holds are an exercise in balance and power. Be sure to stay out of the crack on Sunken Pillar and off the large ledge of Red Pulpit. Finishes on large, open ledge.

name: Basswood Chimney
description: Easy chimney climb on jugs. There's a short variation in a crack on the right after climbing 15ft to a ledge 5.5

name: Beer and Booty
description: Friend John Markestad and I have been working the face between Fear and Trembling and Red Pulpit. This is a truly lovely 5.10a/b unleadable (at least we wouldn't try it) climb and my favorite on the whole Balanced Rock Wall. The first crux is getting off the ground (no surprise there) and the next is a simple looking little bulge about 12 feet up. Ignore the juggy holds on the left higher up and you have a climb that every move is at least a 5.8. All moves are small face stuff with no cracks or large holds. Very elegant! We are calling it "Beer and Booty" since it took me 3 beers before I could pull the second crux and John found a #5 hex while setting the top pro.

name: Bifurcation
description: Locate a short, right facing corner with a chockstone at the top of the corner where it hits a ledge/alcove.      Climb the slab, pull past the chockstone (crux), stand up in the alcove and turn the corner on the left.  Jaunt up the crack and top out.

name: Der Glotzenlinks
description: The wall between Der Glotz and Sunken Pillar is a superb face climb and would be done more often if it was given a name! The route starts in the same spot as Der Glotz but, where that goes up and right, Der Glotzenlinks goes straight up. There are several solid 5.8 moves on this very pretty route. This doesn't use the same holds or cross and other route.  It has been done many times but has never had a name.

name: False Dilemma
description: False Dilemma is the clean cut off-width crack above the chockstone on Bifurcation. There are two ways to get to it: climb bifurcation or; climb Moondust and step right onto the chockstone once you've topped out on Moondust. I used a handstack to get into the crack, from there chickenwings and smearing with the left foot brought me to the top for the iconic Devil's Lake sloper top out.

name: Indigo Billy
description: This is the arete between Fear and Trembling and New Box. If you aren't humping the arete, you are off route. Crux is about 11' up at a "roof"; a block about one foot square.  Lots of 5.7 and 5.8 moves on the climb.

name: Invitation
description: Start near the left side of the wall at the large crack.  Climb the crack straight up to a ledge about 20 feet up.  Either walk off left or continue to the top.

name: Invitation Direct
description: Climb the small crack left of Invitation. The crack moves left as the climb continues. Crux is near the top.

name: Law and Gospel
description: This route starts directly under the "pulpit" on the Red Pulpit and goes straight up over it.  Above the pulpit, keep going straight up to the right of the Red Pulpit crack route.  The first 12' are the crux.

name: Moondust
description: Hand jams and finger layaways to the top

name: Morning After
description: Locate the thin, discontinuous crack to the right of Watermarks. This is Morning After, and in my opinion, the best route on the wall. The crux involves switching from laying back one side of the crack, to laying back the other. The movement on this climb, the tricky footwork,  forces the climber into an elegant vertical dance.

name: New Box
description: New Box sits just to the right of the dirt and rock slope in the inside corner.  Climb the inside corner using either the crack or ledges.  Once the corner diminishes into a crack, either continue straight up on the crack (harder) or move slightly right to the ledges on the face (easier).

name: R.S.V.P.
description: Fun but short climb that features mostly layback moves up a medium-sized vertical rail. The crux is moving off the rail and grabbing a small bulge of rock to the left.

name: Red Pulpit
description: The Red Pulpit sits slighty to the left of the oak tree that sits near the southeast half of the Balanced Rock Wall.  You can identify the route by finding the "pulpit" sticking out the of the rock about 15 feet up.  Start out just to the left of the pulpit on a very thin crack (the crux is getting off the ground).  Climb up the crack and pass the pulpit on your right.  Stand on the pulpit for a rest, then continue up the crack to the top.    Want a lovely variation? After the first crack, keep going staight up; don't go to the pulpit. You have a couple of very nice, balancy 5.8 moves. You'll like it!

name: Sunken Pillar
description: Sunken Pillar is directly behind the Oak Tree between Der Glotz and Red Pulpit.  Start out on either crack (left is a little better quality).  Use blocky hand and foot holds to climb up.  Once the cracks diverge follow either crack up.  The upper half of the left crack is really nice for side-pull moves.    To set up the Top Rope for this climb the biners should be to the northwest of the Balanced Rock.

name: Switch Cover Crack
description: Follow an obvious crack starting in an inside corner up the face past a diagonally wedged chockstone.  Stay on the left side of the chockstone.

name: Unnamed Short route
description: The crux is a slight transition from the inside corner to a large ledge.

name: Watermarks
description: Watermarks is considered by many to be the ultimate moderate climb at the park.  This may or may not be your opinion.  The route has some nice moves and fun sequences, and it is easy to get to as it's right on the trail.      Watermarks is easily located by finding the water stains on the southeast end of the Balanced Rock Wall.  Climb easily up to a small ledge.  Traverse right carefully on this ledge until you reach the two triangular pockets.  Use the two triangular pockets to make your way up to a slight bulge in the rock.  Use the crack and small face holds to surmount the bulge (crux).  Continue up crack to the top.

name: Watermarks Direct
description: Watermarks Direct is located just to the right of Watermarks.  Start to the right of the small ledge on Watermarks, with the two triangular pockets directly above you.  Use small side-pull face holds and foot ledges to ascend the route up to the triangular pockets.  From here the route links up with Watermarks.  Climb the vertical crack to the top.

name: Watermarks Traverse
description: Starting on the right (east) side of the downhill facing Watermarks Wall on good ledges near a tree cluster, pull on and traverse left about 50 feet encountering many fun and balancey moves along the way with plenty of good rests. Once you hit an obvious left facing corner with a crack, you can step off. If you stay low it probably adds a grade.

name: Balanced Climb
description: It is a nice face climb.  There is no defined crux.

name: Box top
description: Long climb at the mouth of the Box Canyon.

name: Hitch Hike
description: The crux is over the small overhang 3/4 the way up the route.

name: Jam Crack
description: Short jam crack that leads to Balanced Rock

name: Whamus
description: unknown

name: Kranz
description: Start in the crack below the left side of the pillar.  Pull a move, then continue with easy climbing up to and beside the wide crack on the West face of the pillar.

name: Liederkranz
description: This is a neat route with a interesting traverse that ends on the west corner with a tough mantle. Gear is good, bring some smaller cams.    I also tried going straight up the face from the big horizontal break but it was very hard, a project for a future crew.

name: Dirt Cheap
description: A bit heady for 5.5, and protection isn't quite as good as you might wish, but it's all there.  #13 p172 Swartling

name: Dirty Deeds
description: #12 p172 from Swartling.  Not super memorable, but easily protectable and a couple committing moves on this one.

name: Don't Lean on the Tree
description: Climb the gently overhanging finger crack just left of a large pine tree.  As the name suggests, it is possible to bail from this route by leaning back onto this tree, though this is fairly easily avoided while actually climbing.  Avoid reaching out left to the large flake system.  Complete the climb with a kind of scary mantle (pro beneath your feet with the tree waiting right behind you).

name: Grand Finale
description: On the left side of the wall. Start on jugs. Climb up the the vertical slashes on the clean face. From a prominent triangle slot make a big move up and left to a jug to easier climbing above.

name: Head Like a Hole
description: Start in awkward crack with a couple moves to the shallow chimney, not worth the trek out here but if you're here anyway...      #11 p172 Swartling

name: Hole-In-The-Wall
description: More of a highball boulder problem this climbs some fun moves on good gear to the "hole" and straight up.

name: Rodin's Inspiration
description: Nice start in a very shallow right-facing corner.  Above is some nice stemming.

name: Effie
description: Named for Effinger Beer once brewed in "The Boo".   You will get some true jams, so rare at DL.

name: Evil Twin
description: Thin moves on smaller holds, gets interesting the higher you go.  Committing moves to the top.      The Swartling guide briefly mentions two 5.4 routes on a slab below the Effie above the talus, which doesn't seem like it could be describing this one, leading us to believe this isn't in any guidebook.

name: Vulture Committee
description: Nice dihedral climbing and decent protection as well.  A couple moves felt pretty committing; overall a worthy climb right next to another classic.      The Swartling book briefly mentions two 5.4 climbs on a slab below The Effie formation -- this definitely is not on a slab and not 5.4 leading us to believe this isn't in any guidebook.

name: Cherry Blossom
description: A sweet little corner.  Start in the alcove, under the trees.  Move up onto the shelf on the left - probably the crux.  Step right and move up the dihedral to the top.

name: Cherry Pit
description: Start on the right side of the alcove.  Pull up into the hanging flare.  The first 12 feet is fairly sustained, after which it become fairly easy.

name: Flying Squirrel
description: A devious line - it can be hard to spot the next good hold.  Begin in the dihedral just left of the main face.  Climb to a horizontal break and traverse right into a shallow dihedral.  Continue straight up.

name: Skinny
description: Start to the left of the skinny rib.  Pull onto the rib and exit up the crack above.

name: Squirrel Party
description: The wide chimney on the north face.

name: Squirrel's Hole
description: A chimney with a roof.  Looks more ominous than it is. (60 year old?) piton tucked up under the roof - don't clip it!

name: Squirrel's Nest
description: The main slot is lined with the hollowed out remains of a tree (in 2020).  Fun climbing with a unique, wooden crux.  Once past the crux, there are several exits at the top.

name: Varmit
description: Yet another great moderate!  Left of the rib, through the alcove, up to a crack, and exit.

name: Catenary Crack
description: catenary (n): The curve assumed by a cord of uniform density and cross section that is perfectly flexible but not capable of being stretched and that hangs freely from two fixed points.    Catenary Crack is a terrific line up the north wall of the Railroad Amphitheater.  Start out on the slightly overhanging bottom section (crux).  The hard part is getting started, and this is made worse by the fact that the rock here is often wet.  Once off the ground follow the crack up between the roof on your left and the staggered overhangs on your right.  If you can get up this one try some 5.10's.

name: Cop Ripper
description: Cop Ripper is named for its location between Jack the Ripper and Cop-Out.  Crappy name, hard climb.  Climb the face between the previously mentioned climbs by crimping on small face holds while trying to stay on the slightly overhanging wall.  Finish up by surmounting the mid-size roof near the top.

name: Cop-Out
description: Cop-Out starts about half-way between Snedegar's Nose and The Pillar.  Climb up the slightly overhanging wall on finger cracks until you reach the inside corner under the mid-size roof.  Once under the roof step out of the corner and onto the face to your right.  Use vertical cracks to ascend to the top.

name: Heisenberg Cheese Danse
description: Climb starts in the middle of the wall on a lovely finger jam (this is right of the finger jam for the Pine Tree Step across). At the top of that crack amble over to the roof that is the crux of Pine Tree Dihedral. Go straight over the roof (crux). There is a nice finger ledge in the middle of the western face of the roof.  I can just barely reach it with my left hand (I'm 5'8").  I do a one arm hang (Great looking "hero" move!), match hands, and do a pull-up with two small nubs for feet on edge of roof.

name: Jack The Crooked Cop
description: A sure to be neo-classic this is my favorite line on the wall linking the meat of "Jack the Ripper" with the best part of "Cop Out".    It starts with a tricky boulder problem and follows a thin seam to a no hands rest. Then an airy traverse into a perfect dihedral and through the roof on good holds.

name: Jack the Ripper
description: Jack the Ripper is a short route near the west end of the north wall of the Railroad Amphitheater.  Find the diagonal crack about 5 feet left of Snedegar's Nose.  Use hand jams to ascend the slightly overhanging crack.  Finish on the ridge to the left of the mid-size roof.

name: Lumby Ridge
description: An old mountaineering classic.  A pleasant outing on clean rock.    The first pitch is the hand/layback crack in the center of the buttress. 25 ft, 5.3.    Walk back across the platform under the large pine tree.    The second pitch is the chimney in the next buttress, to the right of "Old Shoes" and "Face-Off".  The crux is moving up around a cluster of chockstones.  35 ft, 5.4    Scramble back/up to the buttress that includes the Turret.  If you are creative, you can turn this into another pitch!    The third pitch has a few options.  (1) The classic is to work your way up across the ledges to the left of the chimney; or, (2) Go up the chimney.  35 ft, 5.3 up the chimney.

name: The Pillar
description: The Pillar is a fun easier climb that's great for beginners.  Climb up the pillar by either using ledges on the pillar itself or by using offwidth moves up the chimney between the pillar and the wall.  Once on top of the pillar either go to the right of the staggered overhangs and up the face, or traverse left (or jump) under the overhangs to a pocket in the upper section of Catenary Crack.  Whatever you do, don't get stuck under the overhangs.  This variation is no fun.

name: Pilloried
description: Will you be subject to public ridicule?  Sure!  but do the climb anyhow, it'll be fun!    Climb the pillar one of several ways.  Where "The Pillar" steps left and "Tang Shwang" heads up, you step around the bulge and follow the crack up to the right.

name: Pine Tree Dihedral
description: The Pine Tree Dihedral is an easily protected route that is excellent for novice trad leaders.  The route follows the inside corner that sits below the teenaged pine tree growing out of the rock near the top of the wall.  Climb this route by jamming the crack of the dihedral up to the overhanging block midway up the wall.  Proceed to the right of the overhanging block and continue up the dihedral, passing the tree on your left.  Duck under the tree branches and follow the inside corner to the top of the wall.

name: Pine Tree Step-Across
description: The Pine Tree Step-Across is more a mental challenge than a physical one.  The climb is located just left of the inside corner that leads up to the sizeable pine tree growing out of the rock near the top of the wall.  Climb up this face until you reach a large overhaning block just left of the pine tree.  Surmount the block using a mantel.  Once on the block lean into the blank face and step across the abyss to a small landing pad for your foot.  While stepping reach with your left hand for a hidden hold.  Continue up to the top of the wall.

name: Railroad Offwidth (aka Birch Tree Dihedral)
description: Railroad Offwidth is the inside corner just to the left of Old Shoes, which follows the nose of the buttress.  To climb the route, use the crack in the corner and easy ledges to ascend.  Near the top use layback moves or simply jam the crack.  Either stop at the large ledge or climb to the top using the walls on either side.

name: Right of the Eye
description: "Right of the Eye" is the inside corner that starts about 10 feet right of Pine Tree Dihedral.  The route starts out with blocky moves, then makes its way up into an inside corner.  Near the top you will pass to the right of a large block with an overhang (this is the "right" eye, while the block above Pine Tree Dihedral is the "left" eye).  Stay right of the overhang and climb to the top using the crack in the corner along with some ledges to get to the top.

name: Snedegar's Nose
description: Snedegar's Nose is one of the few true "ridge" routes at the Lake, making it a unique experience.  Climb up the obvious ridge using the corner and ledges.  Protection on lead can be a little sparse, but using a top rope sets you up for a nice big pendulum fall.

name: Spectacle
description: Head up the grassy ledges to the right of "Pine Tree Dihedral".  At the first big crack, head up, or continue farther up to the right for an easier time.  Pull the little step onto the ledge to the left, the scene of many a beached whale move from "Pine Tree".  Pass the pine tree on the right, and continue up the crack to the top.

name: Tang Shwang
description: Start on the frontside of the Pillar (not the chimney side), using the wide crack to ascend to the top of the pillar. From there, move up the small roofs above. Use some good underclings and come out of the roofs on the left face to topout.

name: Working on the Railroad
description: Head up the meaty looking crack just to the right of "Right of the Eye."  Although it looks like it could be wide, it is mainly a hand-crack.  A the Eye's brow level, keep heading straight up.  For an extra five feet, finish up on the last moves of the Eye.

name: Charlotte's Web
description: Hard start. Climb the crack system going left or right at the top corner.

name: Disappearing Ledge
description: Start on the low angle rock to the right of Waterfall Chimney. Make your way up and around the the corner to the right and then to a ledge. Continue climbing up and to the left small overhanging corner and top out.

name: Waterfall Chimney
description: Climb the inside corner and chimney in middle of Waterfall wall.  Ok route, but it was just horribly dirty and seems like the main water runoff for the cliff.

name: Waterfall Crack
description: Start up the right diagonal ledge then climb up crack to ledge then up through the notch in the overhang.    Good for learning how to effectively use a hand jam and a mantel.

name: Crows Nest
description: Start inside the corner. Follow crack system to just under the overhang. Once at overhang traverse left to ledge. From ledge go straight up to top.

name: Lumby Ridge (pitch 3)
description: Scramble up into the chimney, then exit to the left toward the top.    The cruxes are bypassing chockstones.

name: Turret
description: A blank looking face above leads to feature that seem to come out of nowhere!

name: Big Jim
description: There are a couple of ways to climb this, but the climbing is easier to the right. It's unnamed in the Swartling and Knower guidebooks, but was given a name for the online database.

name: Birthday Chimney
description: Birthday Chimney sits in the corner between Birthday Crack (route 9) and Caesarian West Face (route 11).  The route isn't really climbed as an offwidth chimney.  Climb this route using face holds and ledges on the wall to your left and the tower to your right.  Step up on ledges with your feet, using an occasional stem between the face and the tower.  For novice leaders there are plenty of nice resting spots, making this a good route to try out the sharp end.

name: Birthday Crack
description: The Birthday Crack is one of the better-known climbs at the Lake.  It is a fun and challenging climb with a pretty sustained crack.  Start out to the left of the Birthday Chimney (route 10) below the junction of a vertical and horizontal crack.  Climb up the vertical crack into the pocket at the junction of the two cracks.  Don't get yourself too far back into this pocket or you'll get stuck.  Reach high (real high) with both hands and pull up on a juggy hold to get above the pocket.  The top half of the climb is slightly easier with a nice sustained 20-foot crack to the top.

name: Bowing to the Undercling
description: A fun balanced hard route with good pro all the way.

name: Caesarian Tower
description: The route Caesarian Tower follows the western of the two southwest-facing dihedrals of the Caesarian Tower.  Start the route at about the same place as the route Caesarian West Face.  Climb up onto the large block to the right, then make your way up to the right of the sharp corner.  Finish the climb by ascending the slightly overhanging corner and crack.

name: Chester's Chimney
description: Chester's Chimney is an offwidth chimney about 25 ft tall near the northwest (lower) end of the Birthday Rocks formation.  It isn't listed in Swartlig's book, but it is a decent climb for practicing offwidth (not much of this at Devil's Lake).  To climb, scrape your way up by any means possible.  To make it a true offwidth you should avoid using any holds on the face.

name: Doublemint
description: "Double the pleasure!"    Up the face between the Twins, to a vertical crack that begins above the horizontal seam.

name: Flux Capacitor Crack
description: This route is next to #2 (Flying Delorean) in Climber's Guide to Devil's Lake at Birthday Rocks by Sven. Climb up either the smooth face or lieback crack at the left detached flake. Gain good horizontal ledges for a few balancy moves. From here move up to a solid horizontal crack and on to pinnacle feature using both aretes like a big bear hug. The name comes from a feature in the face that looks like the Flux Capacitor- it will make you charge up the aretes with 1.21 Jigawatts of power.

name: Flying Delorean
description: Flying Delorean is a fairly continuous crack system on a pinnacle shaped feature just north of Birthday Crack. The pinnacle alone is easily identifiable but the crack system that runs up the pinnacles right side cannot be missed. Start on dirty ledge at base of wall, climb crack on right side of wall all the way to a comfy ledge. Finish as per "Flux Capacitor Crack" by straddling and slapping both aretes for an airy, exciting finish.

name: Great White Hope
description: The Great White Hope can be found between the Birthday Crack (route 9) and the Right Twin (route 10).  Climb up to the large horizontal crack using small ledges.  Above the horizontal crack the climbing gets very thin.  Use delicate moves on small face features to ascend to the top.

name: Horner's Corner
description: Horner's climbs the tall and distinct arete above the 10 ft crack. Climbing is mostly on ledges and crimps, with a couple of balancy mantle moves near the top.

name: The Left Twin
description: The Left Twin follows the shallow inside corner up to the small overhang.  Once at the overhang either climb to the right and finish in the nook shared by The Right Twin, or climb the obvious outside corner to the left using ledges and cracks.

name: Mitzvah
description: Independent line between "Birthday Crack" and "Birthday Chimney"...  do not touch either.  Crux is right off the bat and is steep and a bit tricky to gain small ledge. Climbs cool edges, side pulls, and intermediate cracks.  This is a legit seperate line, is not listed in any guide, and I have always thought it should be.

name: Peal Off
description: Climb cracks near corner to a short dihedral. Climb the dihedral and finish on the left side of the same summit block as Bowing to the Undercling.  This is listed in both the Swartling/Mayer and Knower books.

name: The Right Twin
description: The Right Twin climbs up a left-trending inside corner.  Use ledges and cracks to ascend up to a slight overhang.  Climb through the overhang and into a nook to the top of the climb.

name: Special Delivery
description: This is the right dihedral on the SW (lake) side of the Caesarian tower.   Start by climbing up to large ledge. Facing the tower, you'll see 2 obvious dihedrals. The left one is Caesarian Tower and the right one is Special Delivery.  Combine this climb with Birthday Boulder for some interesting variations.

name: Unknown
description: This route is nice easy climb with a number of ledges where the climber can rest. The route is in the inside corner to the right of Flying Delorean. The route starts on the same ledge as Flying Delorean. Stay in the corner through the route. The top 10 feet is class four.     If anyone knowns the name of this route, or who did the first assent make a comment and I will edit.

name: Unknown2
description: The route starts 5' to the right of the ledge Flying Delorean. That is not on the ledge but 5' to the right of it. The bottom section has some nice blockly hand and foot holds that go straight up. Midway up there is a ledge. At the ledge move back toward unknown route. There is a narrow  squeeze. You have a choice to go in the squeeze or above it. The crux is a small overhang just past the squeeze. The crux holds are good. The last 10 feet is class four.

name: First Step East Face
description: Scramble and mantle on ledges, right of the pine tree (on the North side of the East face, toward Birthday Rocks).    We used this as the descent route.

name: First Step West Corner
description: Up the crack and squirm around to the right, then up to the summit.

name: Stump Crack
description: Beside the stumpy rock pillar, follow the fist crack.  You could start either left or right of the stumpy pillar.    (In Smith & Zimmerman, this is the "NW Corner".)

name: Third Step
description: Up the wide crack behind the pine limb, then straight up the final face.    You can skip the final face by squirming to the right - easier.

name: Two-step
description: A very thin crack with some juggy steps that are just far enough apart to be interesting.  Harder and more intricate than it looks!

name: AAA
description: AAA can be found near the north end of the Horse Rampart formation.  The route follows the west-facing outside corner up through the overhang and to the top.

name: Horse with No Name
description: This route isn't listed in Swartling & Mayer, and doesn't get much traffic. It's got a few good moves that go at 5.4 or 5.5, the rest is easier stuff. Start on the wider crack, then scramble up on lower angle terrain towards the obvious hand crack/dihedral and finish with some nice jams.

name: The Horse
description: The Horse is found on the northwest-facing wall near the middle of the Horse Rampart formation.  The route is named for a flake about halfway up the route that has the appearance of a horse's head.  To climb, start behind the large tree and climb up either the inside corner or to the right of the corner, making your way up to the left side of the Horse flake.  Climb onto the flake and finish the route by climbing the corner to the top.

name: Lechery
description: Lechery (n): Inordinate indulgence in sexual activity. Good luck finding that on this climb!    Lechery follows a handcrack for 25 feet up to a ledge.  Once at the ledge use the finger crack to finish the climb.

name: Moby Dick
description: Moby Dick is a 30-foot climb located on the north end of the Horse Rampart formation.  Coming up from the Birthday Rocks it will be the first climb you come to.  Climb up the slightly leaning corner using small ledges and some cracks near the top.

name: Monarch
description: Monarch is located near the inside corner/gully on the northwest-facing wall near the middle of the Horse Rampart formation.  Start left of the big tree and climb up slab to the steeper wall above.  Make your way into a shallow inside corner and follow it to a crack.  Climb the crack to the top.

name: Mother Smucker's Jam
description: The bottom 15' is a walk up, 5.2 maybe.  After that there is a nice crack to climb.  The crack is about 20' long.  It is challenging.

name: Mung
description: Tricky and overhanging crack followed by jugs higher up. The crux is avoiding pumping out at the right facing corner below the small roof but it's far from over after that. Skinny fingers come in handy. Fun route.

name: Overlooked Corner
description: Start up the slope, climb the corner crack system, then move 3 feet left into the wide crack system with a few good layback moves. You can stop here on this ledge or continue ~20 feet to the top of the bluff.

name: Peanut Butter
description: Climb the lower face to the ledge.  Continue on the left corner.  The crux of the route is the section past the ledge.

name: Plethora
description: this is a fun little route with two contrasting sections and good gear to boot.also nearby is Mung 5.9 +

name: Primak's Surprise
description: Primak's Surprise is found at the inside corner to the right (south) of Debauchery.  Climb the inside corner using holds on either side.  Once near the top either skirt under the shrub or climb up and left to finish using the top of Debauchery.

name: Pullman Car
description: Pullman Car is a challenging route on the corner between Archery and The Horse.  Climb the corner using small holds up and to the right of the "Horse" flake.  Continue up the obvious crack to the top.

name: Roger's Roof
description: Roger's Roof is a well known climb at Horse Rampart.  When approaching Horse Rampart from Birthday Rocks, Roger's Roof is located near the left corner of the formation about 50 feet past the top-rope access "gully".  To climb this beauty, start to the left of the alcove at the base of the wall.  Follow the wedge-shaped rib up to the hand crack in the roof.  When you get to the roof, reach above it and jam your palm (you will bleed) into the crack while keeping your feet high on the face below the roof.  When your hand is sufficiently jammed, swing your left foot above the roof and propel yourself onto the face above.  Follow the crack to the top.

name: Scavenger of Human Sorrow
description: Un-named in the guide this is a good warm up for access to the top to set up TR. Some loose blocks to contend with.

name: Sugar-free Jam
description: A fun scramble up a pretty, clean section of rock.  The rocks in the crack are mostly solid.

name: Teetering Tower Chimney
description: Teetering Tower is a massive pillar balanced on a tiny base, and leaning back as if it might squash anyone foolish enough to chimney up between it and the main cliff.    So that's where you go!  Finish on top of the Tower.

name: Treachery
description: Treachery is located to the right of the alcove of Woger's Woof Wightside (route 9).  To climb Treachery, follow the rib/inside corner up to the chimney above.  Climb through chimney to top.

name: Uncrustable
description: Follow a series of good holds to a ledge with a tree. Head right, climbing a crack just before the wide chimney to the top.

name: Via Apia
description: Located at the Eastern end of  the Horse Rampart (the last climb on the continious cliff line before Teetering Tower), this jam crack poses interisting moves that will have you wondering why you havn't found this rout at the lake earlier.

name: Wolf Dog
description: This is a unnamed 5.7 in the guidebook. It's a pretty good warm up.     Start in the cracks on the west face to the right of AAA. Exit right to the ledge at the overhang then go up either the South face (has pro) or step left onto the West face (no pro) and finish left of the capstone.

name: 5.7 Right of Two Cracks
description: Cracks and face to the right of Two Cracks (5.10a).

name: Clearasil Spattered Fantasies
description: Starts in the small alcove on the South face of the North buttress of Elephant Rocks.  Then follows the thin crack to the top.    Variation (5.8):  Also starts in the alcove, but follows the crack that diagonals up and right.

name: Dumbo
description: Climb lower inside corner to pillar above, avoiding (in typical DL fashion) anything that would make the route easier than 5.9, particularly the ledge on The Trunk(5.7) its neighbor to the right.

name: Elephant Crack
description: Climb the wide cracks left of Dumbo.

name: Inside Corner left of Transcendental
description: Obvious easy-looking inside corner to the left of Transcendental Disfiguration.

name: Out of the Closet
description: Fingertip layback to the level of the "Tomb."  Then continue up the outside corner to the right with another layback move or two.

name: Tomb of the Unknown
description: Climb the crack and chimney system to the top.   (aka "Tomb of the Unknown Homo")

name: Transcendental Disfiguration
description: Interesting outside corner with a crack.

name: The Trunk
description: Right of Dumbo(5.9), climb up pillar to ledge, and continue up inside corner to top.As a leadable variation, climb the left crack of Tomb of the Unkown, then continue into the upper corner.  You'll miss the "trunk", but still fun.

name: Two Finger Cracks
description: Great route that follows two finger cracks and some face holds up the face.  Don't wander too far right or you'll be off route, as you would be on most routes at Devil's Lake...

name: हात्ती (Hati)
description: The forked chimney at the south (right) end of Elephant Rocks.  Head up the initial chimney, then surmount the small bulge between the upper chimneys to the final hand crack.Pronounced "hot tea", with the accent on the first syllable - Nepali for "elephant".

name: Dumpster Diver
description: A chimney with lots of features inside.

name: Foil
description: Nice moves.  The crux is getting off the ground:  either start flat-footed with a very long reach, step up on the block to your left, or work up a few face holds a little to the right until you reach the horizontal crack.  Get your first piece of gear here.  The upper crack is much easier, and pretty straighforward.

name: The Open Wide Burger
description: Nice OW crack climb. The route is fairly short, but too tall to boulder. Stay in the crack and practice your OW skills.

name: Rainbow Crack
description: A gorgeous crack!  Starts off with steep fingers and hands, then turns into an off-width struggle at the top.  Reminds me of "Via Apia".

name: Rusty Crack
description: A nice mix of hand crack and face climbing holds.  A high step low, a bulge up high ... this little climb actually holds a nice variety of problems.

name: Shady Corner
description: Clean little corner.

name: Thumbs of Steel
description: Really enjoyable crack climb.

name: Axeman
description: Perfect hand jams.  The final jam may be a bit dirty.

name: Brave
description: Looks like there should be more to work with than there is.  Start just right of the crack - the wall is just barely overhanging.  Move left and up into the crack.  Where the "crack" widens (but seams out), move further left and continue fighting your way up.

name: Jay's Jaunt
description: This route is about 5 feet to the right of Tomahawk crack. The start is about the same as Tomahawk then it moves farther right. The route accends the easy broken terrain.

name: Puzzlement
description: That puzzling size that is a bit wide for off-width, but too narrow to chimney.    As is typical for our quartzite, you might use some off-width holds (arm bars, heel-and-toes), but you don't really have to make any off-width moves - there is always an edge someplace, if you can figure out how to use it!

name: Tomahawk Crack
description: The route starts at the corner and shift slight to the right. There is a large crack that goes straight up. Follow the crack. The crux of the route is a small bluge. Once you past the bulge the route is much easier.

name: Unnamed Crack
description: This is the far right crack on the northern end of the farthest north rocks of Tomahawk rocks.

name: Winnebago
description: Climb the right facing flake to the ledge. At ledge shift left and climb the thin crack.

name: Astroboy
description: An older variation of the Rifle guidebook describes The Chain Gang,  a series of routes in the single-pitch Arsenal, as the best multipich sport climb in Colorado, marred only by the fact that you have to lower to the ground after every pitch.     Well, I would call Astroboy one of the best multi-pitch trad climbs in the country, marred only by the fact that you have to walk back to the base after every pitch. Astroboy is arguably the classiest of the numerous Devil's Lake linkups.     The rule is pretty simple: Lead 10 different 5.10s on the East Rampart. But wait, you say, I can think of 5, 6, even 7 good 5.10 leads on the East, but 10, how can I find 10 leads? Therein lies the difficulty of Astroboy. You have to lead some routes that, let's be honest, you wouldn't normally think of leading. When was the last time you led The Monster? Or Mongo Fury (Burt, you don't count!)? Or Pine Box? And maybe consider adding Thoroughfare, because, I don't know about you, but I'd rather lead Thoroughfare than, say, Big Deal.     Here's the order I chose for Astroboy:    1. Mongo Fury   2. Sometimes   3. Flake Route   4. Congrats   5. Pine Box (DON'T tell me it's 5.9+)   6. Thoroughfare   7. Callipigeanous   8. Mouse's Misery   9. Cheatah   10. Alpha Centauri    But that's what I chose. Page through the guidebook, talk to your partner, and make your own plan. And then be prepared to change your plan when your chosen route is swarming with Boy Scouts. Also be prepared to hang out in the Cool Lot (is that even still a thing?) after your long day. Over beers and beta spray, casually remark that you climbed Astroboy, and that Pine Box wasn't so bad, and that Mongo Fury is a neglected classic, and that you just had one of your best days at the Lake. Ever.

name: Balanced Rock Ridge
description: Begin by picking a route on Balanced Rock Wall. Then, depending on your choice of route on Balanced Rock Wall either select a route in Box Canyon, or gain the ridge proper immediately to the northeast of Balanced Rock. After the pitch above Box Canyon the route becomes a combination of short, blocky, steps mixed with the occasional "gendarme". The exposure on the upper ridge is never tremendous, but there are some high consequence areas. Top out just below where the Balanced Rock Trail Joins the East Bluff Trail.

name: The Big EZ
description: A tour de force by Eric in the late 90s, and perhaps the single most impressive day of climbing ever done at the lake.  Climb the big three of Rubberman (5.13b), Ice (5.13), and Dyslexia (5.13c), and tack on 9 more pitches of 5.12 for good measure.  I don't know all the pitches that Eric climbed when he did it, but good options include:  The Dog (5.12a) Angle of Dangle (5.12a) Acid Rock (5.12a) Crosstown Traffic (5.12a) Assume The Position (5.12b) Welfare Line (5.12b) All The Way (5.12c) Cheap Thrills (5.12c) Bagatelle (5.12c)  Happy cranking!

name: Chivalrous Arches
description: Want a casual day on the move? Training for the mountains? Learning the terrain for your new guiding job? Warming up for Noble Arches? This linkup is an amalgam of the East Rampart's best easy terrain. Toprope or lead all of these things, in a day, in any order you'd like. I've avoided most of the routes on Noble Arches. For the real "work at a guide service" experience, build toprope anchors on each route, rap in, and climb out in your approach shoes.ZigzagDarkness at NoonChimney's EndPuff n' Grunt ChimneyFull StopSchizophreniaModerationDyspepsiaAnemiaLichenVerticultureDouble OverhangBalconyMezzanineSecond BalconyCerebrationUrve's FollyFoliageGravel PitDrunken SailorCrackin' UpChicken DelightBeginner's DelightDeath & TransfigurationBucket Brigade

name: Eastbound and Down
description: Eastbound and Down is a contrived linkup combining the eight recognized areas found on the East Bluff of Devils Lake State Park (1. Sandstone Area, 2. East of the Quarry, 3. West of the Quarry, 4. East Rampart, 5. Potholes Area, 6. Balanced Rock, 7. Railroad Tracks, and 8. North End). Any climb can be used in each of the eight areas, and the order in which you visit the areas is completely up to you. Focused less on the climbing, and more on route finding abilities, risk management, and one's ability to endure a long day of constant movement, this linkup makes for a creative day out.

name: Massive Major Multi-Pitch
description: A nice little way to link a few pitches below Devil's Doorway.  Pitch 1: Kenosis (5.4) or Dippy Diagonal (5.7). If you take Dippy; you can stem left near the top and finish on the upper-section of Kenosis to build an anchor on the ledge above Kenosis (which is far more convenient for the next pitch than topping-out on Dippy proper). The large pine at the top of Kenosis serves as an excellent belay anchor, but there is an alternate (and probably more convenient for the next pitch) anchor that can be built in a horizontal on the right wall before crossing the gully to the next pitch.  Pitch 2: Goodbye Youth (5.5) or Mindless Dribble (5.8). Cross the gully from the belay ledge and choose the next pitch. An aesthetic way to do pitch two is start up Mindless Dribble and then traverse into Goodbye Youth with your hands at the upper-horizontal. This traverse can be reasonably protected (for the second as well) with a BD X4 #0.1.  Pitch 3: Angel's Crack (5.6) or Jolly Roger (5.8). Move the belay 10-15 meters West to the base of the tower and climb either route to a great finish with excellent views of Devil's Doorway.  Of course many variations are possible beyond those listed here, but these pitches make for a nice outing that flows relatively well.

name: Noble Arches
description: Named for the classic Royal Arches, Noble Arches attempts to approximate the amount and difficulty of climbing on its Yosemite namesake. Noble Arches links approximately 1600 feet of climbing over 25 pitches at an average grade of 5.6.   Noble Arches is great training for any long, moderate, route - just about anywhere. Completing it will require careful planning, efficient climbing and efficient changeovers. Be prepared for a long day of varied climbing. Aside from being a great training piece, Noble Arches will take you on a tour of some of the Lake's most classic routes, some of its obscure gems, and some its best grovels.    The linkup consists of the following 25 pitches:    01. Easy Overhang   02. F4 Ledges   03. Birch Tree Crack   04. The Pedestal (pitch 1)   05. The Pedestal (pitch 2)   06. The Spine   07. Boy Scout   08. Brinton's Crack   09. Berkeley   10. The Rack   11. The Grotto   12. Vacillation   13. Full Stop   14. Anemic Ladder   15. Peter's Project   16. Michael's Project   17. Horticulture   18. PushMi, Pull-Yu   19. Coatimundi Crack   20. False Alarm Jam   21. Double Overhang   22. Foreplay   23. Northwest Crack/Arete   24. The Pretzel   25. Charybdis

name: North Shore Lunch Circuit
description: If you've got a half hour, you're on the North Shore, and you want a good 5.10-5.11 workout session try this linkup:    Up Eubank's Lady Bits   Dn Confidence Booster   Up I Don't Know, B   Dn Confidence Booster   Up The Tullamore Dew Arete   Dn Confidence Booster   Up Welcome Face   Up Purple Bud   Up Welcome Crack 2   Up Welcome Crack 1   Up Welcome Chimney   Up Welcome Crack   Up Wild Turkey   Up Special K   Up Office Building   Up Emily's Naptime   Dn The Grenadine Corner   Up Oil Can   Dn The Grenadine Corner    Your mileage may vary with respect to time, but this is a great way to log some mileage and get a quick workout in.

name: Pseudo Ridge
description: Are you bored? Maybe training for the mountains? If you answered "Yes!" to either of these questions, then Pseudo Ridge might be for you.    Begin by choosing a route on 13: Four Brothers for your first pitch.    Follow that up by moving the belay and climbing The Pretzel.    For the third and fourth pitches scramble up a two-tiered ridge forming Pseudo Skyline to the the top of 15: Pseudo Hawk's Nest. The third and fourth pitches go at 3rd and easy 5th class respectively.

name: DL 3
description: The DL3 is a triathlon that is swimming, climbing & running at the Lake! clocking in at just over 5 miles, this is for the true, all around athlete to test themselves and move fast!    Start at the large tree between the northernmost parking spot and the trail over the RR tracks at the South Shore. Run to the electric fence along the RR tracks and ditch your shoes in the boulders there.    Jump into the lake and swim directly across the lake to the base of Turks Head.  The swim is quite big at 1/2 mile.    Find a pair of runners that you had stashed from before your start in the boulders and run/climb Turks Head Ridge to the very top of the bluff on the West Bluff trail. Turk's Head Ridge beta    Go north on the trail up to the North Shore.  Cut across the picnic area, and find the East Bluff Woods trail.  Up the Woods trail (and a steep, gravel hill climb) to a 4 way intersection, turn left.  Run a bit more to a three way intersection, turn right and eventually see the edge of the east bluff.  When you hit the Eest bluff trail, turn left (east) toward the CCC trail.      Run down the CCC trail and turn right on the Grottos Trail back to the south shore.  The clock stops at the tree you started at.  For bonus points, grab your bike and head east out of the park to Hwy 113. turn left, climb the hill and turn left again on DL.  Cross the North shore entrance road and turn left onto the South Shore road, up and over the west bluff hill climb and then down the awesome twists back to the lake and the South Shore parking lot where you started.

name: FVBT-Full Value Bluff Tour
description: At just over 6 miles, this is one of the most classic climber runs at the park.  A great way to keep your training up by doing the run after a day of pulling down!    Start at the Ice Age trail sign on the north shore of the west bluff, where the trail starts from the small parking lot on the north shore entrance road.    Run south on the West Bluff trail and join the South Lake road.  Run the road east to the CCC trail (do not cut off the south shore beach).  Up the CC trail to the top, turn left and go to the Potholes trail.  Down the Potholes trail, then a right on the Grottos Trail to the Balanced Rock trail.  Up the Balanced Rock trail to the top.    From the top, catch your breath and take your first left onto the east bluff trail back to the North shore.  Once running out of the woods and into a parking lot, head straight, then cross the creek at the bridge and run across the North Shore picnic ground and then up a gravel path back to where you started.    James's Blog link  committeddaily.com/p/blog-p…

name: The Rich Bechler Memorial
description: Named after the President of the DLFA, and endurance runner Rich Bechler, this classic DLSP trail run covers the Ice Age trail from east of the terminal moraine, to the lake back east to Parfrey's Glen.  At 14.5 miles one way and (an (almost) 30 mile return trip total distance, this is The Ultra known through the climbing circles.    Start at Roznos Meadows parking and take the trail west out of the back of the lot.  Cross the South shore road, up the first hill and left onto EAst Bluff trail.  West to the Balanced rock trail, down to the beach and up the West Bluff.  Cross the North Shore picnic area and stay on the Ice Age Trail (hard to find), through the campgrounds at the tunnel and left right after.  Continue East on the ICe Age trail north of Hwy DL, then crossing the road just east of 113.  Take a quick left after crossing DL, and back into the woods and a notoriously wet/muddy part of the trail.    Take a left to cross HWY 113 and head east to Parfrey's Glen. 4 miles remain, with the last ~2 all downhill.

The 10/10/10 is another fun contrived day at DL. (I am not an advocate of unroped climbing). Boulder 10 problems, lead 10 routes and solo 10 pitches. East bluff works well for this but I'm sure there are other areas that it could work out well also...

name: Devil's Lake Ridge Run
description: Climb multiple ridges throughout the park.  It ended up being approx. 30 pitches for us.  You could do more or less depending on how you link your pitches.    West Bluff:   1. Twin Ridges- North and South Ridges   2. Turks Head Ridge   3. Cleo's Ridge via Southeast side   East Bluff:   4. Lumby Ridge   5. Lothar's Ledges   6. Balanced Rock Ridge via Sunken Pillar   7. Minor Mass Ridge- via B-Minor Mass into Flotsam and Jetsam

name: Half Century Scrambler
description: [Also known as "the old man's birthday challenge"]   I'm putting this entry here as a place-holder.  As more people complete 50-route days, I hope they will add their lists of routes in the comments.    What could be more pleasant than going for 50 routes in a day, all ground up?  This challenges your capacity for climbing logistics, your ability to keep focused and moving, and is also a pleasant work out.    Should take climbers of moderate ability about 10 hours to complete.

name: The Pentaverate
description: The Pentaverate, is an admittedly arbitrary and contrived collection of five of the best "ridges" Devil's Lake has to offer. Alliteration aside, this linkup is great tour of the park, good training for moving fast in the mountains, and a fun way to get whole-body workout in.    1. Pseudo Ridge (4 pitches)   2. B-minor Mass & Flotsam and Jetsam (2 pitches)   3. Balanced Rock Ridge (3-4 pitches)   4. Lumby Ridge (3 pitches)   5. Turk's Head Ridge (7-8 pitches)    The preferred style for The Pentaverate is to start at the CCC parking lot sign, hammer out the four ridges on the East Bluff, run the tracks to the north end of the Lake, grab an ice cream sandwich at the Chateau, bust the the Tumbled Rocks trail, do Turk's Head Ridge, then sprint back to the CCC lot via the West Bluff Trail and South Shore Road. The watch (if you're timing it) starts and stops at the info sign in the CCC lot by the iron ranger pay box.

name: Turks Circuit
description: Solo or lead all of Turks Ridge(doing the wiessners chimney/Wiessners crack finish), run down the west bluff trail, around the south side of the lake, past the main beach, run down the railroad tracks till you reach the trail going up to birthday rocks at which point you swim back across to where you started at the base of Turks Ridge

name: West Bluff Towers Circuit
description: This is a list of towers and tower-like objects on the West Bluff that can make for a fun circuit. The towers are listed below in a potential south-to-north circuit that is somewhat close to optimized for minimal travel time between towers - you may choose to do them in a different order. Virtually all of these towers can be climbed at 5.8 or easier.     Thanks to Adam Remus (Remo) for the inspiration and James Mutschler for help compiling the list and climbing with me. There are a few towers on this list that I have not climbed - their information comes from the 3rd edition of Swartling and Mayer's guidebook for Devil's Lake. So do the GPS coordinates.

name: Jan's Lament
description: Jan's Lament is found on the east end of January Wall.  Start out on the route by reaching high for good hands and smear with your feet.  About 5 feet up use the crack/flake to do a semi-layback and ascend to easier territory.  Climb to the top on small ledges.

name: Lincoln's Chair North Arm
description: Climb up the center of the north (climber's right) pillar on Lincoln's Chair.  This route is more pleasant and less dirty and loose than the south arm to climb.

name: Lincoln's Chair South Arm
description: Climb the left (south) corner of the south arm of Lincoln's Chair.  In early July this route was very dirty and had lots of spiders and loose rock.  It might be a good destination if you want to tick this feature, but don't go there for good climbing.

name: Back 9
description: Nice easy climb that has some height to it. Also, it can be climbed with several interesting variations from a single top rope anchor. This is the back half of route #18 in the swartling book 3rd edition. Great place for beginners, or anyone looking for an easy climb.

name: Front 9
description: Very easy short climb. A good spot to take a first time climber, but thats about it. This is the front half of route #18 in the swartling book 3rd edition. I split #18 into 2 separate climbs (Front 9 and Back 9) because it just makes more sense to me, especially if top-roping them.

name: Joseph
description: this route starts just left of the brothers.Lots of steps,continue to chimney and up in crack to top.

name: The Niche
description: On the northern outcrop of Stettner Rocks.  At the south end of this outcrop, there are two small dihedrals, each about 5-6 feet deep.  This route follows the right/north dihedral, next to the pedestal.    Work up the dihedral and into the niche.  Reach or stem up to grab the edge to the left.  From here there are two finishes.  The 5.4/5.5 hand traverses straight left, around the corner and almost around the next corner again.  Once you have a good foot, clamber up.    The other finish stems straight up the crack.  Scum with your hip, and maybe even sit on the ledge!  This is about 5.7, and would be the most obvious way to lead this.

name: Paul
description: The crux is about 10' up.  Past the crux it is a highway.  This a great route for new climbers.  There are nice ledges to rest upon.

name: Paul's Variation
description: The bottom 20'

name: Paul1
description: Southwest corner of Stettner Rocks.  There is a small overhang just to the left of the corner of the outcrop approximately 15 feet up.

name: Stettner  16
description: Wide crack, crux is getting off the deck.  Nice short climb to work on fist jamming.

name: Stettner 7
description: Scramble up a few blocks, follow inside corner until it ends, then finish last 10 feet on the face above the inside corner.

name: Unknown
description: This route is not listed in the guide book.  However, knowingly is not a First Ascent, rather a "new" route.  In terms of "new", meaning not listed as route info has been lost through time, or very hard to find.    In the guide book, the route is to the right of route #6.  In between #6 and #7.    Just North of the Southern most mass of Stettner Rocks, there is a face divided into three by two large, four foot ledges.  Route height is approximately 25-30 feet, with a ledge at six feet, then again at 12 feet.  On the second ledge, there are two pine trees.  The route follows the crack approximately four to five feet to the left of the pine trees from the base to the top of the route.

name: Untied Shoes
description: Climb thin finger crack just to the left of the prominent arete using only the crack- no stemming out left. Follow this up 10 feet, crux, and then make good moves on decent edges and horizontals to the top. Protects pretty well.

name: A Soft Pillow
description: #8 in Sven's. Follow good holds left of center on The Pillow. Escape right at the overhang. A fun little warm up climb.

name: False Perspective
description: Is the false perspective from the climber on the route or from those who say it looks too easy?  Start in an inside corner on the center of the face to the left of the Pillow. Climb a crack through a small sloping roof to the top.      This climb is a bit harder than it looks, but takes gear very well for a lead.

name: Fat Man's Misery
description: Fat Man's Misery climbs inside the "cave" at Misery Rock between Wailing Wall and Pillow's Edge. Use the west face at first and then onto solid corners of "the pillow" to get into a body sized chimney. Don't go too far into the chimney otherwise you'll feel the route's namesake. Finishes on top of "the pillow."

name: In the Way
description: This climb shares the start of route 14 from a "Climbers Guide to Devils Lake" up to the large tree on the ledge.  From there route 14 goes to the right up the arete and hand size crack on the right side of the crack.    In the Way goes back into the chimney behind the tree, and then traverses out into the hanging offwidth/chimney

name: Life of Jam
description: If you start this climb as a skinny toddler and climb very, very slowly with really long rests, you could potentially climb on nice jams all the way up.  Unnamed 5.4, route 13, in Swartling & Mayer's 3rd edition.

name: The Pillow Right Side
description: This route climbs the edges and thin crack up the right side of the pillow block

name: Pillow's Edge
description: It's the edge of the pillow, duh. Start near (not on) upward protruding rock that looks very unappealing in the case of a fall. Use the arete to gain the first horizontal and place a good cam. From here you have options... and you have to find those options. Place marginal gear along the way and try not to fall. Finish in cool finger crack at the top to a pleasant mantle finish. A true sportsman wouldn't bail into the chimney of Fat Man's Misery...

name: The Pillow
description: This formation varies in difficulty, both in the climbing and the ability to protect.  South edge (grabbing the edge is off) is a balancy slab with many high steps, as you move north the climbing gets easier and the pro gets better.  Either route comes back to the left (south) to pass through the small roof at the top.  On lead, the climber is looking at a fall onto the slab until well past the roof and into the finish moves.  While these moves are easy, the fall potential should not be taken lightly....

name: Smoke Hole
description: Fun "adventure" climb - start deep in the dark cave that holds Fat Man's Misery and chimney to the opening at the top, maybe about 20 feet up. Emerge on the outside and build an anchor or continue up another 10 feet or so.

name: Tree Slot Chimney
description: This climb starts in the 5.2 block access route on the right side of the pillow block, but climbs slightly right into the chimney between routes 12 and 13

name: unnamed route to left
description: The crux is at the bottom of the route.  It is the at the first 15 feet.  After that the route is around 5.0.  It is a fun route to practice placing gear.

name: Meat Grinder
description: Climb up slabby corner directly to the climbers right of the start of Thin Fingers/Ohh Rats.  Jug city as you walk your way up slab to tight squeeze finish.  Walk off climbers right...    This is route number 5 in this area, in the Swartling Guide.

name: Oh Rats
description: Climb overhanging dihedral with crack, to overhang traverse right and around corner to short face(crux)   Var, 5.11d , pull overhang directly,

name: Sun Spot
description: Starting from the ledge/ramp, move up just left of the right corner of this buttress, into the right-facing corner system.  Follow this to the top.  (Route 13 in Swartling & Mayer.)  You could also start from near the base of the Pooper, and add 15 feet below the major ledge.

name: Thin Fingers
description: Fun lead that shares the start to Oh Rats. When you get to the top of the large ledge (referred to as the "second ledge in Swartling), head South West (climbers left) up short 4th class scramble to thin crack to top out. Walk off climbers left.  This is route number 3 in this area, in the Swartling Guide.

name: Under the Pier
description: Inside corner on the left side of this buttress, to a deep corner behind the projecting block.  Finish directly up the overhang on huge jugs.  (Route 12 in Swartling & Mayer.)  No gear initially, but great once you get to the deep corner.

name: Bowsprit
description: Great mind bender. Run out sections culminate with a very committing move to a mantle top out.

name: Can Can
description: One of the better 5.5 leads at the Lake:  nice moves, good pro, wonderful summit.    On the Southeast side of the Frigate, a crack system heads up between the two summits.  From the base, move up a dihedral a little to the right, find some good pro, then move left and up into an alcove.  Kick high!  Getting into the alcove is probably the technical crux.    In the alcove, get some more bomber gear.  Kick high!  and pull around the little roof.  Head up to the summit on the right (North).

name: Flying Dutchman
description: Delicate and burly at the same time.  The crux is exactly where you think it will be, the face above has good, sharp horizontals, and then there is a final throw to the top.    I've seen two different strategies used successfully:  ease up the flare, and power layback.

name: Frigate "walk off"
description: A quick scramble to the top of the Frigate, great for setting or retrieving topropes.    Scramble up to the saddle between the Frigate and the main bluff. Step across to the left - there are a couple of places to do this, all about the same difficulty. Move out onto the exposed East Face, and work your way up to the top, with a few 5th class moves as you move up from ledge to ledge.    The easiest moves could be hard to spot when you are coming down from the top.

name: Galleass
description: Route #19 page #238 3rd Edition Climber's Guide To Devil's Lake by Olaf and Mayer.   Route lies just right of "Can Can".  Surmount short steep blockish thing to ledge then climb great finger crack/layback fissure to slabs and ledges above.  Belay (or TR anchor) at top mid section of "The Frigate"

name: Jasek's Project
description: Start right of the chimney (can use the chimney for easier variation, but the chimney is not part of this route). Climb is mostly slab past the first 15 feet.     Belay space is very limited and bushwacked.   This route is not listed in the guide book

name: The Jib
description: Starting left of Flying Dutchman this ascends the corner on small holds and a tricky step right over the center overhang. Then up buckets to a tricky throw on the left corner of the formation (same as FD).

name: The Pooper
description: If you use Spider Mitts you're going A0    It's tape or nothin'    One of the hardest 8's you'll ever climb

name: The Stern
description: Starts with a boulder problem on the right face of the South arete.  You generally follow this corner up, avoiding the main crack of Can Can.  At the top, move back onto the South face into a seam.    The hard part is spotting the crimps - there is usually no chalk on this route.

name: Unnamed route 20
description: The crux of the route is after the garden ledge there is a large crack that can be fist jammed or done via a lay back.  This part may be harder than a 5.3.

name: When Life Gives You Lemons...SQUEEZE THEM TO DEATH!
description: This is a two part climb. Part one (When Life Gives You Lemons...) heads up easy terrain left of the crack to a nice stance, then traverse right with a tricky sequence, to a BOMBER hand jam, take it to the top.    Part two (SQUEEZE THEM TO DEATH!) heads up using the crack and big holds on the left but goes straight up the crack utilizing a wicked one knuckle pinky jam and a heinous pinch on the arete to the same BOMBER hand jam as part one.

name: North Wall
description: There is no specific crux.

name: Pantry Corner
description: A fun sequence of jugs and steps.

name: Pantry Cracks
description: Easy climbing up broken rock with multiple vertical cracks. As the name suggests, pick any crack to the right of Bread Board and go. This is a named route in the Knower book and is #25 in Swartling/Mayer.

name: Pantry Right
description: The bottom of the route is has small holds and foot chips. It is delicate.

name: Pantry Shelf
description: step up to sloping shelf on bottom part of wall(crux)then continue straight up the overhanging slab near right corner.fun route for a shady spot.

name: Root Cellar
description: (A variation of Pantry Shelf.)    Pull up into the narrow dihedral to start.  This is awkward.  Above, crawl up through the chimney, and finish either ducking under the chockstone to the right or moving left to climb directly over it.

name: Skil Brum
description: Speed route, evenly spaced ledges and cracks.  (Originally submitted anonymously, this appears to be the route just left of "K2" and "Special K".  "Skil Brum" is the peak just to the west of "K2" in the Karakorum. - DH, 2020)

name: Special K
description: This climb is a combination of crack, chimney, and overhang climbing. Although it is 5.6 it will test your endurance.  End the climb on a ledge near the top of small tower.

name: Unnamed 5.1
description: There is no specific crux. It is some fun stemming up large jugs.

name: Bacon Breath
description: Climb the Wide crack using some face holds.  The crux  is climbing through the widest part of the crack. Crack ends at a ledge, follow easy ground to the top.  This route could only be made better if the crack was longer. Eliminating face holds would increase the difficulty considerably.

name: Blarney Stone
description: Easy climbing up a broken chimney. This is a named climb in Swartling/Mayer and is not listed in Knower.

name: Hissing Vulture
description: this route is number 38 in your guide book.when we first did this route,my buddy rappelled down,and heard a loud hissing noise coming from the cave right below the climb,turns out it was a injured turkey vulture trying to scare us away.Start right under the overhang and continue up the crack to top.

name: South Corner
description: Climb the left corner of the Dungeon Wall. This is a named route in Knower and #35 in Swartling/Mayer.

name: Static Stretch
