description: This is route number 38 in the 3rd Edition of Swartling's and Mayer's guide.    "Face opposite small tower.  Start on left side of face, then angle up and right to small inside corner.  Climb to upper ledge, then up crack or right corner to top."

name: The Bone Variation
description: The crux is the last 10'.  It is very slabby with crimpy holds.  There is no place for protection on the last 10'.

name: The Bone
description: The Bone follows the slanting inside corner on the right (north) side of the obvious "Porkchop" face.  Start out on the manhole cover sized chockstone at the base of the route.  A few strenuous moves will get you into the inside corner.  Follow the corner up to a converging overhang at about 30 feet.  Climb through the gap in the center of the overhang, then follow a crack for about ten feet to a ledge.  Carefully traverse right on the ledge for about 15 feet using well-hidden hand holds.  Surmount another slight overhang to another ledge, then climb up a five foot chimney to the top.

name: The Entrance
description: This is the entrance to the sweatbox.  Start on left of rock face and finish by topping out where the sweatbox starts.  I would recommend going straight from the entrance into the sweatbox. The main problem is a lack of footholds and a sloper.

name: Jacob's Ladder
description: Jacob's Ladder is the inside corner on the left side of the "Porkchop" slab.  Climb the inside corner using the crack and other features.  At about 35 feet there is a slight overhang.  Climb past overhang on the inside corner and face to the left of the corner.

name: No Exit
description: No Exit is found to the right of "The Bone" (route 50) in the dark inside corner below a large overhanging block.  Climb up the inside corner using cracks, ledges, and some stemming moves between the walls on either side of you.  Once near the overhang move to the smaller left crack and perform a strenuous pull past the overhang and up onto the ledge on your left.

name: Phat
description: Phat starts on the same inside corner as Jacob's Ladder (route 49).  Climb up the inside corner for about 10 feet, then move right onto the slanting south face.  Climb up nice face features and mantel onto a foot-wide ledge at 30 feet.  Continue up on the outside corner to your right.  At this point the climb continues on the same path as "The Bone" (route 50).  Climb the crack of The Bone for about ten feet to a big ledge below a bulge.  From here continue straight up directly over the bulge using small fingertip holds to the top.

name: Pork Loin
description: Climb the crack just to the left of Jacob's Ladder. When you get to the ledge, contine up on the face to the left. The crux is in the last few moves. Finishing on the top left section.

name: Pork Loin variation
description: Start on the second crack about 20 feet left of Jacob's ladder. Go up the crack through the first overhang to the second overhang (crux) until you reach the big ledge 25 feet up. Continue on the face to the left of the ledge. Finish on small holds to the upper left of the face.

name: Spiderfighter
description: This climbs starts with a really neat finger crack in the left side of a box/chimney feature that exits left at its top then climbs steep rock up into an alcove at which point the climber moves leftwards to a broken rock section followed by a final steep section of rock with interesting big but sloping edges and flared cracks.  The opening finger crack has nice square edges here and there for the feet keeping the grade low.  This climb makes for a great on-sight that protects very well.  Named after the abundance of live arachnids and all their web trappings found along the way.  This route is seldom climbed.

name: Sweat Box
description: Sweat Box is found on to the left of the outside corner between The Bone (route 50) and No Exit (52).  Climb up the thin crack to a ledge, then ascend the outside corner using face holds.  Move up under the slightly overhanging block and delicately pull straight over the block to the top.

name: Unnamed BP
description: Nice sized boulder problem just below the base of the bone. Straightforward climbing near the corner on small edges.    If any one has any info on FA , or maybe the true name of this i would appreciate it.

name: Wobbly Block
description: If you go to Porkchop Buttress you will find a nice flat rock with a surface of about 10 feet by 30 feet.  You will probably end up putting your pack here during your climbing and you will eat your lunch here and relax here throughout the day.  On the southeast face of this rock there is a crack called Wobbly Block.    Climb the short 20 foot crack using jams and face holds.  Look for the wobbly block near the top.

name: Dark Side of the Moon
description: The Dark Side of the Moon ascends the "Split" in the tower.  The chimney is very easy and very straightforward.

name: Half Moon
description: Half Moon climbs the southeast corner starting below the round overhang.  Start by climbing slopey holds.  Climb a hand crack through the overhang, then move slightly left to finish the climb on the rounded southeast corner.

name: Moon Face
description: Moon Face is the face on the northeast portion of Split Tower.  Climb the face using delicate moves to get off the ground.  Throw some pro in the crack and continue higher to easier terrain.

name: The Flue
description: Chiropractor is the chimney found on the west tower.  Climb it using armbars, kneebars, headbars, and other assorted moves.

name: High Draft
description: Funky Boss starts on the south corner of the west tower.  Climb the corner about halfway, then traverse right about 6 feet to the northeast corner of the west tower.  Continue to the top.

name: The Shaft
description: The Shaft is the chimney between the east tower and the main rock. Climb the gap using stemming moves and features on the face and corners.

name: Smoke Shelf
description: Kishore Kumar is located on the east face and corner of the east tower.  Climb up about halfway on ledges and face holds, then move right onto the corner and continue to the top.

name: Smokestack
description: Start on the SE corner of the W tower in a short dihedral. Get to the horizontal and traverse left to a nice vertical crack with a perfect yellow C4 placement.

name: Blades of Crass
description: Squeeze job between Chair Bivy crack route to the left and 2 Dead Ducks to the right.  Climbs kind of like "Orgasm Direct" or "Cul De Sac Exit" over at East Bluff.  At the start work from right off of tilted block (start of 2DD's) across the face on really cool positive rails to the left to gain a series of really great large flat square cuts and a funky pistol grip flake for the right hand then up into very nicely positioned    side-pull\under-clings at a bulge where the feet are jacked as high as possible.  Grab the jugs above the bulge then prepare to mantel up (with zero feet) in order to let go with the right hand and find and pull down on an awesome crimp....the crux! Climb the short blank section to the yop off the big horizontal making sure to not venture left or right at all.  This climb is a eliminate for sure.

name: Chair Bivy
description: This problem has now been sent as a route that goes to the top. The start can be done three ways providing three different variations. A V2 off width problem to start , a V1 layback problem to start, or a stand start that still goes at 5.8.     Either way, once past the initial start, the crack is wide and it goes to the top. Some mandatory 5.8 off width was required here. We thought it was enjoyable, and I even threw in a foot stack or two.     Unlike most DL off width cracks that are surrounded by blocky ledges this was legit crack climbing.  (INFO on original boulder problem below)   This problem is super fun, and is one of a kind at the lake. OW roof crack problem, which we found best to climb feet first.     Starts on juggy flake inside crack. Finishes out and around roof about 10 feet up on an obvious jug.     Chair Bivy would be 4 star problem if not for two reasons: OW climbing could be by passed by lay backing the flake with low feet.

name: Two Dead Ducks
description: This route follows the edges up the face just to the right of the Chair Bivy Crack. Starts out steep, then gently slabs out for the upper portion of the route.     Continuous 5.9 climbing up the entire feature. The route is more technical than it is pumpy. Really enjoyable little face that actually protects.

name: +ULFBERHT+
description: A new route that climbs the wall just left of Colostomy route. Climb up dirty, lichen covered, and mucky big edges to a big horizontal. Reach straight up and side pull the neat little mini arête with both hands then bring the feet up as high as possible. Stab for the obvious little left hand in-cut found in the next small horizontal cleave - match hands - shift feet and finally reach over into the hanging crack to the left. Jam and side pull up the cool fissure to the ledge. Pull the small edges on the outside corner and hoist up to the finishing platforms all while staying away from the small tree and grassy ledge to the left.

name: Barndoor
description: Starts out with 15 feet of broken rock (large detatched block)and easy moves to a large ledge.  Off ledge climb crack and edges trending left to left side of square buttress top.

name: Better When Dry
description: Right side of lichen covered face. Climb straight up passing diagonal crack on upper right end.

name: Colostomy
description: The repulsive inside corner.  It is the inside corner to the left of The Plank by about 10'.  Devil's lake guide book list it as route 26, grade 5.7.

name: Curved Wall
description: This route starts on the rounded edge of the descent gully and leads you to a ledge.  From the ledge, move left and continue up to the top ledge.

name: Hang Dog
description: Climb face to overhang with crack

name: Jack of Spades
description: The wall is to the right of the gully that runs right and up of Queens Throne. The route is the prominent diagonal crack on the face. The crack runs for around 25 feet and ends on the bottom left side of a small _headwall_. This small _headwall_ (around 10 feet) is the crux of the route and what makes it interesting. Climb it just right of the corner on small edges.

name: King's Throne
description: This one can be as hard as a 5.8 for shorter people as it is quite reachy. Just to the right of Minnie Mum on the area that faces East there is a wide crack. Climb to the left of the crack to the top on horizontal cracks and ledges.

name: The King's Valet
description: Start below the shelf of Mickey and Minnie Mouse. Climb up a series of downward sloping ledges, to top out slightly to the left (just barely around the corner).

name: Mickey Mouse
description: To the south of King's Throne there is a ledge and two short cracks start from it.  The left crack is Mickey Mouse.  The right crack is Minnie Mouse.  They are good hand/foot cracks.

name: Minnie Mouse
description: To the south of King's Throne there is a ledge and two short cracks start from it.  The left crack is Mickey Mouse.  The right crack is Minnie Mouse.  They are good hand/foot cracks.

name: Minnie Mum
description: This is the last of the routes that end on the ledge on the south side of King's Throne. It is the inside corner. No specific moves as it is low rated and a little boring. Just get into the corner and use what is around to make the easiest ascent.

name: Minnie Mum Variation
description: Climb the face between Minnie Mouse and Minnie Mum.

name: Missing Link
description: Climb is about 5 feet right of Minnie Mum. The meat and potatoes is getting onto the second ledge. Use the small fissure and breaks to work your way up the face to the nice ledge above.

name: Pinko
description: Start in crack leading to smooth face, balance up face on small holds.

name: Queen's Face
description: This is a nice route to do after leading the Queen's Throne (which is an easy and really fun 5.4). Lead up the Queen's Throne. Use some webbing to anchor yourself around the spire at the top. Topside belay your second and have him clean the pitch.  Then dump a #7 cam in one of the big cracks by the belay stance.  There are some smaller cracks closer to the edge that should take a #4 cam. Use the webbing around the spire for your bomber anchor and equalize the two cams for a backup.  I'm sure there are plenty of other ways to set up this top rope, but this worked well for me.  Throw your rope over the edge that faces the lake, rap off, and you're all set to climb.     Queen's Face is a wake up call at 5.8 after Queen's Throune at 5.4...but that's a good thing.  Climb the two parallel flared cracks that go almost all the way to the top.  Expect very thin, balancy foot holds.  The crux is pretty close to the ground, around the fourth or fifth move.  There is a real positive rest hold about half way up.  After that, shoot for the top.      You could probably lead this, but like I said, the crux is awful close to the ground and it's really easy to set up a top rope.  It's up to you.  Overall, a real nice route. It's worth doing a couple of laps on it.

name: Queen's Throne
description: This one is easy, but it is a whole lot of fun. It is about as perfect for leading as climbs get at Devil's Lake and swallows gear so it is good for the begginner leader. Climb the left facing corner to the right of King's Throne. There are two corners there so climb the one on the right. It is a very vertical crack and ends to the right of the tall rock spike atop the climb.

name: The Queens Clam
description: Climb the crack until your entire body fits into it. Chimney to roof and pull roof via thin hand crack.

name: Throne Room
description: The wide crack to the right of King's Throne. Follow it and it has two finishes. Either the North face or the East face. Fun crack.

name: Tilted Tower
description: Climb the left side of the overhanging face of the tower.

name: Unnamed 5.3
description: Wide-angle inside corner.  Climb left chimney or right crack.

name: Unnamed 5.3 Corner
description: Short inside corner crack left of Queen's Throne(41), and right of Throne Room(38).  A bit wide at the bottom,  so bring a bigger piece (#4 C4), to protect the bottom, or you can just run it out a bit.

name: Cleo's Needle South-Central Dihedral
description: This is perhaps the easiest *well-protected* route to the summit.  Step up into the dihedral.  In the middle of the dihedral use plentiful face holds on the face to the left.  Finish with the standard summit block - at least two pieces of gear in horizontals are available here, too!

name: Cleo's Needle Southwest Dihedral
description: Start in the Dihedral on the Southwest side of the needle. It is the left most crack on that side. Continue up through overhang. Make an awkward move or 2 and continue up to the small ledge at the base of the summit block. Move around to the left (west) and continue up on easy holds. There is no pro for the last 15 ft here. Move up and clip the big ring on top. Don't forget to stand up and enjoy the view.

name: Cleos Needle-Southwest Rib
description: This route is on the opposite side of the regular route up Cleo's Needle. The route starts below an overhang between the two obvious cracks. Surpass the overhang by climbing the right crack. Once over the overhang follow the rib up to the ledge below summit block. Traverse left to another ledge at same level. Once on this ledge climb to the top on small edges and right corner (crux of the route). Belay at the top from the summit ring.

name: East Comfort Route
description: East Comfort Route is located on the East side of Cleo's Needle.  Start at the base of a pretty obvious dihedral.  Make your way up the dihedral by stemming and using the crack.  The dihedral is very relaxed and continuous.  The dihedral gives way to face climbing about 15 feet from the top.  Climb up the final summit pinnacle using nice face holds.  Once at the top either sit on top to belay or go around to the other side of the needle to stand on a nice big ledge.  Rap off using the ring at the top.  Be sure to notice the wobble of the summit block.

name: Northwest Side
description: The Northwest Side of Cleopatra's Needle starts out on the lower sloping ledges and ascends the Needle on mostly horizontal features to the top.  The crux is just below the summit.

name: Southeast Arete
description: This is a climb in two parts.  The lower arete has very little gear ... but good gear where you step up around the overlap, and huge holds everywhere else.  Once on the ledge at mid-height, walk over to the summit block.  There is decent gear again for the final few moves, where you are feeling most exposed.

name: A Point of Balance
description: An off to the side gem! Mantle on a large flake to a face crimp or two and balance to the nice horizontal under roof. Plug gear and enjoy the ride to the top.

name: Belly Flop
description: The route has exposure and protects well.     Description from Sven's guide: " Northeast ledges and overhang. Climb northeast side of Turk's Head to ledge beneath wide overhang. Reach up in central notch and mantle onto ledge above overhang. Walk around south side for easiest way to top."    "Variation - 5.6- Surmount overhang by crawling onto shelf at north end. No one has ever looked good doing this."

name: The Green Slime
description: Nice 5.10 splitter crack that runs up the middle of just off vertical green colored face.  Lots of green colored lichens either side of the crack but doesn't effect the climbing one bit.  Crux is right at mid-point where crack shoots straight up and becomes smaller (small fingers) and slightly flaring.  There is a nice face hold just left of the crack edge that helps to reach past the flared portion and to reach a great right hand ring finger lock with a just barely usable opposing thumb push (makes the lock a bit more solid).  There are two possible finishes- one tops out on ledge to left at top, the other climbs through steep crack and broken rock to higher ledge over to right.  The right hand finish makes the climb longer and more fun.

name: Turk's Head
description: Turk's Head follows the southeast facing corner of the Turk's Head formation.  Start out with some reachy moves on big ledges.  As you climb up the corner, head for the overhang straight above you.  When you reach the overhang do the crux move to get around the left side of the roof.  Follow the path of least resistance to the top.  To get off the tower lower yourself off the west end or downclimb the crack on the south side.

name: Turk's Head Ridge
description: An alpine route at Devil's Lake?  Turks Head Ridge, with the Wiessner Wall finish is seven to nine pitches long.  Sure the pitches are short, but its all we've got.     To approach, walk north past the cabins on Tumbled Rocks Trail until you can see a tower about 50 yards above the trail. This is the first pitch (5.3).  Descend the tower, and continue on long, mostly unbroken ridge to the base of Wiessner Wall.  Continue up Wiessner in two pitches and complete the longest route in Wisconsin.    Pitch two (5.6), an ugly wide inside corner, protects well with big cams. The third pitch, a left slanting finger crack is the crux (5.8) and difficult to protect.  It is short, though, and the 5.6 face to the right might afford the leader some respite. After this, it is 5.4 climbing to the top.    For what it's worth, I have usually climbed the ridge in this order:    Pitch 1: The Tower, 5.2     Pitch 2: The Dirty Inside Corner, 5.6     Pitch 3: The 30 Foot Wall, 5.8 or 5.6     Pitch 4: The 15 Foot 5.1 Groove     Pitch 5: The 40 Foot Inside Corner/Ridge, 5.4     Pitch 6: The short Rightward Diagonalling Crack, 5.4     Pitch 7: The Double Cracks, 5.5     Pitch 8: Wiessner's Chimney, 5.4     Pitch 9: either Wiessner's Face, 5.7 or The Crack Above The Tree, 5.2    I feel as though, when climbed this way, you maximize both the quality and the quantity of the climbing. There are, however, numerous variations possible.

name: Turks Tooth
description: A Pleasant climb to the top.

name: Zor the Mantle
description: This climb is a variation of the 4th pitch of the Turk's Head Ridge route on the north side of that particular buttress. The climb tackles a very nice crack on this steep exposure up into a niche then out of the niche exiting right. There is a unique lie back section above where the crack is a bit too small for the average sized hand to jam that takes you up to where the crack ends and the climber is forced to climb left up onto a ledge via a very brutish mantle move (no feet). Above the ledge the difficulty eases way off but the fun factor stays high with neat moves up steep smooth slab but good holds on the rib over and left. Great route I think!

name: Two Overhangs
description: Easy climbing with plenty of pro. Climb left or right of either overhang, same rating.

name: Whitney's Crack
description: Nice crack with ample pro.

name: Whitney's Rampage
description: Burly DL 5.8+ Starts with a tough layback to a nice ledge, a few crack moves, and then a second crux in an off-width crack.

name: Fritz
description: This route is eight feet to the left of Stinger. Start on the face then traverse left to a thin crack a short way up (about ten feet). Climb the crack to the ledge above. You may continue from the ledge, but beware the loose blocks in the alcove above.

name: Hambone Arete
description: Located between the top of Wiessner Wall and Cleos Ampitheatre is a very nice prow with excellent moves. A natural sds is best way to send this little gem.

name: Stinger
description: Just left of the Wiessner Chimney.  There is an alcove 15-20 feet up. Climb to gain the alcove then make a move left then back right again to gain the tree. The route ends here, but continue from the tree with the Wiessner Face.

name: Upper Left Crack
description: This route starts on Weissner ledge and climbs the left-most crack/weakness in the upper wall. Start 6 ft left of the base of the pine tree on Weissner ledge. Climb the vertical crack about 8ft up to a smaller ledge. About 10 ft above this smaller ledge there is a small roof that's split thru the middle by another vertical crack. Climb this crack to the top.  (This is Swartling/Mayer unnamed #6)

name: Upper Wiessner Crack
description: The hands and wider crack that leaves the ledge above the lower left side of the Weissner Wall.

name: The Wasp
description: Somewhat of an awkward start. The places you would like to have a hold for your feet are not there. Start on the far left of the wall on large blocks. Climb the corner (pretty easy) up to the overhang. Go right around the overhang to access a crack. The crack is the crux. Follow the crack to the large ledge above and viola, you're done.

name: Wiessner Boulder
description: Located on the approach trail from the west bluff trail is a nice little boulder with a couple of worthwhile problems on it. The best being the big roof/ prow. We simply called it the Wiessner Boulder due to its location. Probably was climbed before us in the 70s; regardless a nice distraction in a great location.

name: Wiessner Chimney
description: Up the chimney to the right of the alcove and Stinger. Use the chimney to gain a slab and traverse to the tree. Finish the route using the crack above your position at the tree. This one is easy, but real fun. The guidebook I used to find this climb recommends this as well; Please belay in a position that doesn't damage the tree.

name: Wiessner Face
description: A Devil's Lake 10-star, mega-classic! Perched on the airy right-hand side of one of Devil's Lake's most impressive and imposing walls, Wiessner's Face starts on the right side of Wiessner's Ledge, and negotiates blocky terrain up and right to a good stance above the pine tree. From that stance, it links (at a moderate grade) edges and horizontal cracks up what appears from below to be a blank, improbable face. Each move up is an exercise in faith, but rest-assured, the holds will present themselves, and you will not, despite the nagging feeling, fall all the way to the lake waiting patiently, hundreds of feet below, if you fail in finding them.

name: The Blade
description: The right hand corner of the Blade wall.    Step onto the corner from the block on the N side of the arete.  Make of couple of moves up to a fixed pin (needs to be replaced).  Move left onto face and continue up to the large horizontal break.  Either move right and grab the arete, or follow the shallow crack in the face to the top.    There is a fair amount of gear, but it is mostly small gear in shallow placements.  There is just enough good gear to make this pitch worth leading.

name: Dear Ann
description: Crack and face to overhang on the left side of the Blade wall.    Start in the crack with the pine tree growing out of it.  It's easier to pass the tree to the left.  Continue straight up.

name: Stiletto
description: Climbs the face moves between Dear Abbey to the left and The Blade proper to the right.   Joins the variation left crack of The Blade route as described in 3rd Edition of Swartling/Mayer.   The crux is at the 10 foot mark.  Very thin pulls with sketchy feet to better holds above.

name: Surehand, Surehand
description: Face and Crack between routes 4 and 5 (as noted in Swartling's guide).    An attractive, nice line that does not appear in Swartling's guide. They were done in the spirit of "fair play" and were duly documented.

name: To the Hilt
description: This route will test your crack climbing skills, it has no mercy, there is no time for rest.  It might be short, but let me tell you I was knackered after the first 10 feet.  It's slightly overhanging and off width, so watch out for the barndoor.  Hint rap down and clean the route before climbing, it can be a little dirty and web infested.

name: Big Head
description: The free standing pillar, First Tower. When you are by Sun-Top tower, the pillar looks like a big head. This may be the descent route for First Tower.  Start at the south west corner.  Climb ledges to the top of the pillar.

name: Cracker Barrel
description: A fun climb in two parts:  the lower dihedral, and the upper face.  The upper part is a little harder (5.8) if you stay by your gear, a little easier (5.7) if you traverse out to the right toward the nose.

name: Garden Path
description: This is a nice route but the gear is a little funky(Hard to place WELL)    But it has...Great location, Beautiful Views, & Sweet Climbing. What more could you want?

name: The Great Crack
description: Great Crack is a nice long climb on Great Tower in the Prospect Point Towers formation.  Start on low angle easy rock and climb up to a nice ledge.  From the ledge head left up inside corner.  Do a tough layback in the corner crack and pull up to another good ledge.  Follow the path of least resistance to the top.

name: Greatest Generation
description: A climb from the Old School.  Muscle your way up the wide crack (a couple of fist jams help).  Above the ledge, reach just around the right corner for a fingery layback/sidepull.

name: Greatness
description: Intricate and delicate face climbing.  Start up the thin crack.  Where the holds peter out, step right into the chimney (5.7), then back onto the face or figure out how to lever a very long reach (5.9 or 5.10?).  At the small tree, continue straight up.

name: Greatness Chimney
description: The first problem is squeezing in behind the twin pine trees and making your first move off the ground in that cramped space. There's actually two chimneys stacked on top of each other separated by a narrow slit that you have to climb around to get from the lower chimney to the upper one (minor crux). The bottom chimney is easy stemming using obvious features. The upper chimney is more awkward with fewer features for stemming. Finish at the level of Cracker Barrel or continue up and finish right of Greatness.  (This is a named climb in Knower and is #15 in S/M.)

name: Moon Rock
description: The crux is past the lower overhang.

name: North Chimney
description: Not so much a chimney climb as a climb in the back of a huge chimney.  A fun scramble.

name: Rock Garden
description: Tricky pro on this one but easier than Garden Path.

name: Smoooth Bush
description: Smoooth Bush has a couple of bush/tree traverses.  Climb corner to overhang, then crack to the top.

name: South Chimney
description: This is the chimney that's tucked in behind the Great Tower on the south side. There are many harder options you can climb, but to keep it at about 5.2 start in the right corner at the bottom and once you get almost up to the wide chimney and keyhole, step left and go up easier holds. The wide chimney itself is a good climb but harder than 5.2.  (This is #20 in S/M, and is also named South Chimney in Knower)

name: Steak Sauce
description: A classic and fabled roof problem that probably gives no favors to shorter or taller climbers. The free climbing of this former aid route was unlocked by local legend Pete C. on TR a long time ago... The first bold leads of the line came from influential DLFAers Rich Bechler and Steve Sangdahl.  Start at a seam below the obvious roof with a crack running through it. Thin moves will take you to a small bulge and a large hollow flake. The thing is pretty solid though, and on lead you are sticking wires in behind it. Some big moves through the roof to the jug is the crux boulder problem, and holding the swing was the most terrifying part on lead. if you blow it here you will get hurt no questions asked.

name: Basket
description: Basket starts underneath the prominent roof on the left side of Picnic Wall. Ascend the dihedral to the roof and, improbably enough, exit to the right side. Scramble to the top on solid buckets (or baskets, as the case may be).

name: Crack a Beer
description: After a hard day on the rocks it's time to chill out, open that picnic basket, and crack a beer. Climb the large crack to a small chimney and then finish on or near the corner. (This is #25 in S/M, and Inside Corner in Knower)

name: No Picnic
description: Boulder the blank-looking face to the left of Track Cracks, using a series of good hidden holds.  On lead this section is a bit spicy, but the landing is good if you blow it.  Once you reach the break, place gear and head up a fun overhanging jug-haul to the top.

name: Track Cracks
description: My very first day climbing wound up here & I couldn't do the route.    Years later I went back to lead it, went so easy I turned right around and soloed it.    Not that I advocate soloing or anything, but this one is just slightly over a boulder problem in height, and WOW what a great landing!

name: Can't Can't
description: Can't Can't is located on the left of Suntop Tower.  You can start it up ledges or to the left around the corner is a semi awkward (but good) dihedral which adds climbing.  Work up to the roof which turns into a dihedral where some burly left palming gets your feet up over the roof.  The next part is an interesting slanted crack which leads to the top.  This is a great route to get used to trusting little wires at a reasonable grade.  May feel a bit physical...

name: May Fly
description: Hmmm....I've never climbed it, but I had a good picture!   Sven says: "Overhang/crack. Go up and right past overhang to ledge at 20ft."   A direct version starts the same but at the niche move left to overhanging flake, then up and right to ledge. Finish in upper May Fly crack. 11d.

name: Moon Beam
description: Moon Beam is a fairly classic route for the grade, and not your typical DL face climbing. Climb the line of conspicuous horizontals in between The Sucker and Sun Top. A dramatic dropknee at the top makes an otherwise stopper move quite doable.  Nice holds.  Pretend your in the Gunks for a bit.

name: Northeast Ridge
description: Climb the ridge/arete or just left of the arete on the right side of Sun-Top Tower.  Start at the Northeast tip of Sun-Top Tower (right side as you approach from below). Climb up the ridge. When you get to the ledge half way up, climb the wide-angle inside corner to the right of May Fly, or the arete just right of that.  (This #8 in Swartling/Mayer)

name: The Sucker
description: A wee romp up the easy crack just right of Can't-Can't. A fun little route.

name: Sun Top
description: This is a great little lead and warmup.  Climb the obvious crack/weakness towards the right side of the wall.

name: Creamy Caesar
description: Creamy Caesar is a nice alpine-esque climb north of Prospect Point Pinnacle.  Find two cracks about three feet apart, about 8 feet left of a small chimney.  The first crux comes at the steep start.  The left crack is slightly easier.  Ascend broken dihedrals to a steep headwall about 15 feet from the top.  The second crux is getting up this headwall.  Good pro is easily found for lead.

name: Dire Prospects (aka Unnamed 5.10a)
description: This is a short, though cruxy, climb behind the Prospect Point Pinnacle.   The guidebook description: Overhang with two cracks above.    The route begins under a low, deep overhang.  Begin with an undercling and a sidepull.  A nut can be placed from the ground, and another can be placed from the first move.  After this, protection is difficult/impossible, as all those beautiful-looking finger pods are actually flaring downwards and outwards.    A series of liebacks and hand bumps leads to a couple weird crimps, then the route follows easy (5.6) blocks to the top.  An OK cam can be placed in the obvious large crack near the top.

name: Good Prospects
description: Thin face moves.  There are more of the sharp sidepulls that characterize Prospect Point Pinnacle.

name: Hard Sell
description: Hard Sell is a fun little climb on the south face of the cliff band that contains Prospect Point Pinnacle.  The crux is a very steep jam crack that you must tackle right off the deck.  Get off the ground, pull through this crack, and climb up the dihedral over terrain that gets easier as you ascend.

name: Poor Propects
description: Small corner and crack just right of Good Prospects Route which is as well just right of first portion of Prospect Point Pinnacle II (5.8) route on the lower wall section.  Good Prospects and Poor Prospects are not found or indicated in any of the established guidebooks.

name: Prospect Point Pinnacle - East Face
description: Climb the lower face (Swartling and Mayer provide a good photo of your options), then climb the pinnacle proper using amazing incut sidepulls, an obscure knob on the left arete, and once established on the South ledge a throw to the summit plateau.    This would be "great" and not just "good" if it didn't have that huge ledge in the middle.    Setting this as a TR is a real trick!  Good nuts and finger sized gear in the summit block.

name: Prospect Point Pinnacle - West Face
description: I thought I was going to scramble up this, but after soloing out onto the South ledge, I went back for my gear!    Scramble up to the saddle/block between Prospect Point and the Pinnacle.  Establish yourself on the West Face.  Mantle onto the summit block.  Finally (you are not done until you do this) stand upright on the very top.    To descend, you will have to downclimb the route or leave gear/webbing.

name: Second Day Air
description: Second Day Air is just north of the Prospect Point Pinnacle.  The start can be had up either a challenging chimney or a more shallow diagonal ledge/crack to the right of the chimney.  Ascend the first wall to a large ledge, then follow the broken corner to the left up to a ghastly squeeze chimney.  Inchworm up the chimney to top out.

name: Short Sale
description: Smaller hands will find this problem easier.    Choose one of the two starting cracks.  The direct crack baffled me (a long reach?), so I started in the crack to the right.  The start is more awkward than it looks!    The bulge at the top has a good stance to the right.    (unnamed route #3 in Swartling and Mayer)

name: Son of a Bush
description: Son of a Bush is the first obvious dihedral you'll encounter on the south-facing wall near the climber's access trail near Prospect Point Pinnacle.  This is a nice route for the new leader with good stances and pro.

name: Missing Crack
description: 25' down dark wall. After Chimney Climb on face with thin crack. Climb thin Crack to top.

name: Soul Food
description: 40' Down darkwall... This is the face just past the first recess. Climb the faces starting on the lower right up to a small ledge 10' up. Then climb up thin finger tip crack to a jug. Then finish using the double cracks and finish at the top.

name: Unknown
description: 35' down dark wall there is a recess in the wall. Climb the short crack with small ledges on the right side of the recess.    Climb isn't that fun couple of bushes and shrubs exist.

name: Unnamed Crack  in recess
description: 35' down Dark wall there is a recess. Climb the left corner crack of this recess.    Fun short little trad climb. Good warm up.

name: Big Toe
description: Start behind cobra head-shaped tower and climb the corner to large platform.  This is a named route in Swartling and Mayer. Not listed in Knower's book.

name: Big Toe Left
description: The left line of 2 lines that ascend the North (or NE) face of Big Toe, just right of the Big Toe route on the corner.  This is a named route in Knower's book and is unnamed #27 in Swartling/Mayer.

name: Big Toe Right
description: The right line of 2 lines that ascend the North (or NE) face of Big Toe, just right of the Big Toe route on the corner and left of the obvious 5.2 chimney.  This is a named route in Knower's book and is unnamed #28 in Swartling/Mayer.

name: Coup de Gras
description: It is of a sustained 5.9 nature of climbing.  Pulling over the little ledge near the top is maybe the most physical move.  Resisting stemming over to the left hand wall is the mental crux.  The climbing is a bit harder if you don't stem over and keep both feet on the right wall.  Nice finger locks in the crack section at 3/4 height  below the little ledge with the angular shaped block sitting on it.  The first 30 feet has some very mildy loose flakes and somewhat fragile rock but it is for the most part OK.  This climb is "named" due to the similar nature of the rock and the rock climbing to another well know DL classic albiet quite a bit easier.

name: Double Jeopardy
description: Double Jeopardy is just south of the Great Chimney and is somewhat easily located.  Look for the most inviting dihedral amongst about 4-5 dihedrals on this wall.  About 25 feet up there is a large tree growing from a ledge.  Start out on easier terrain.  Once you reach the tree the angle steepens.  The first real diffuculty occurs below a hanging chimney.  Go left of the chimney and surmount a large ledge with a dead fallen tree trunk on it.  Pass the trunk and find the crux, a steep face which can be a bit of a puzzle to figure out.  If leading, be sure to use your slings wisely to avoid rope drag.

name: Fois Gros
description: Climb the inside corner between Mr. Lucky and Coup de Gras. Dirty climbing on the lower inside corner leads to a large ledge and cleaner inside corner climbing above the ledge.

name: Grand Illusion
description: In Swartling's guide the route is shown as starting of ledge DD at Prospect Point Rampart.   This is true but a better and more fun option is to climb the route from the ground via the 5.10b variation start that is a goody in itself (although can be wet and gooey right at the base).   The upper Grand Illusion part of the route proper is a gem too.  Very nice crack up into a overhanging crack/groove.  Well protected and classic stiff 5.9.  The crux here is pulling through the overhanging crack via locks and a throw to sharp jugs (all after hang'n out below it and placing gear).  If you fall - no problem- it is pure air.

name: The Heel
description: Climb the northeast corner of the tall blunt buttress. Is it called The Heel because it is located behind the Big Toe or because, as mentioned in Swartling, the climb involves an interesting heel hook?

name: Homo Erectus
description: Ascend ledges 15ft to the tree and climb the obvious weakness in the middle of a steep face. Scarce pro on the bottom, decent small pro just before the crux. Sizeable runout through the crux. Little tricky but fun moves overall.    Not sure what the name is and whether this has been led or TR'd before or by who. Any info would be appreciated!

name: Illusion Chimney
description: Climb the chimney on North side of the pointy nose. Climb ended 20 feet early due to the vegetation.

name: Modern Life is Rubbish
description: The crux is an overhanging crack that climbs up into a notch chimney, a   nice hand crack leads to big jugs to get climber into the notch above at a reasonable grade.  The small chimney has a hand crack at the back that leads up and climber escapes to ledge on the right and surmounts a final nifty but short corner.

name: Psamead Ghostdance
description: This was a old aid line, called Bivouac Ledge 5.7 A1, starts about 10ft left of the start of SOGC, climb up to ledge with boulder below overhang, pass overhang and move right to crack to Bivouac Ledge, then work your way to the top,

name: Stuck Knee
description: Start in the north inside corner of the recessed section, climb 15 feet to the first ledge. Then up a crack to the base of a narrow chimney. Climb Chimney (crux) to the ledge above. Pull up over the overhanging ledge and finish in 12 foot inside corner

name: Unnamed 5.7
description: Climb cracks in shallow left facing inside corner to small roof. Surmount roof and finish on the overgrown top of the pedestal.  This is #44 in Swartling/Mayer and is listed simply as "Unnamed 5.7" in Knower.

name: The Bastard Chimney
description: This is the obvious long and tall splitter chimney on the backside of the "Coup D' Etat" formation. Starts off as tight ( really tight) squeeze chimney and eventually flares into a nice width.     Long clean cracks like this perfect for practicing technique aren't very common at the lake. Get on this!

name: Coup d'Etat
description: A climb with a blend of thin crack climbing, fun face moves, and a desperate dynamic to finish.  It'll make you sweat! Thin crack offers solid gear placements through entire climb.  Route starts just to the left of a flaky crack (Handle with Care, 5.5), and can be accessed through Great Chimney (actually more of a gully and the bottom can be tricky).

name: Cracker Jack
description: An awesome crack route with a huge ledge in the middle that makes it fun to do in two pitches. The bottom crack let's even the most clueless face climber sink perfect jams. The only negative is it tops out near the "survey marker" on the West Bluff and is often crowded with hikers checking out the stunning view.

name: Get Jacked
description: This is an unnamed route in Sven's book. Get Jacked starts to the left of The Good, The Bad & The Jacked but not on the detached block. Climb a jam crack for 20 feet into a cramped little alcove. From here use the sharp layback flake to a nice stance. Have fun with the decent amount of run out. On top of this platform, you're almost to the top, wonder if you have the right gear to protect the last move (Red BD C3), place it, and do a strange mantle to top out. Variations are certainly possible. Alternatively one could eliminate all features and focus solely using the offwidth just to the right (Hot Beef Injection). Possibly harder than 5.6 but better protected.

name: The Good, the Bad, and the Jacked (Direct)
description: On-Sight Beta:   Climb straight up the face directly beneath the roof that marks the beginning of The Good, the Bad, and the Jacked. Move left to a thin crack and continue to the top after the big move on the original line.     Flash Beta:   Powerful, sustained, and unprotected climbing leads into the original line put up by John Scott. A fall before establishing on the flared vertical just above the roof is certain to be unpleasant. A very shallow yet good #1 C4 can be placed in the flare and protects the climber while pulling the roof. A piton waits above. Marginal, micro gear is available just before the big move ahead and a good placement is available right after. After the big move, do a short traverse left to a thin crack and prepare for a third crux section.

name: The Good, the Bad, and the Jacked
description: "The Good, the Bad, and the Jacked" climbs the blank face roughly 30 feet left of Cracker Jack. Start at the toe of the huge flake underneath a shallow corner with an old fixed piton. Ascend the flake rightwards to the ledge, place reasonable pro (#2 or #3 cam), move left and make exceedingly desperate moves up a shallow corner. Pass the fixed piton and veer slightly right to an OK rest where it's also possible to place small pro. From here execute a burly move to a horizontal hold (pro), traversing immediately left for another in-your-face section in a thin crack.  This is a 5.12 on steroids. I'd give it 5.12c. Hats off to the first ascensionist, regardless what grade.

name: Handle With Care
description: Crack to the right of Coup D'Etat.    Although unimpressive looking, this is one of the better 5.5s at the Lake.

name: Hiker Envy
description: Start on right side of the face near the 5.6 chimney and carefully move to the left onto the ledge.  Alternatively, you can also do a direct bouldery start onto the ledge (more fun).  Follow the very thin crack to the ledge and finish up either side to top out.  Smile for the crowds (hence the name).  Crux is definitely the face leading up to the ledge...some very delicate, balancey "5.8" (by DL standards) moves.

name: Hot Beef Injection
description: This is a line Andy Hansen spied and coined "Hot Beef Injection".  I finally got on this; it was fun and easier than it looks.

name: Match the Snatch
description: Starts up in notch to the right of Son Of Great Chimney.  On the right arete, it comes out swinging and finishes the same way SOGC does.

name: Overlooked
description: There is a wonderful hand-crack hidden just inside the chimney - great for pro and great for holds!    In the corner to the right of "Whipping Boy", is a chimney behind a tree.  Overlooked by everyone who scrambles up and down the gulley, it is clean, protects well, and has nice moves.    It ends at the overlook.

name: Pale Rider
description: Climb around the thin seam left of Wild West Homo staying on the face to the right of Cracker Jack. Some tricky moves with small pro to the horizontal, then up and left onto the arete, followed by a run to the top. The route flows nicely with some cool moves.

name: Perverted Inspiration
description: I chose to start with the same beginning as "Whipping Boy" as this adds an additional 15ft of climbing. Once through the initial 15ft continue diagonally up and right to the obvious ledge.  From the ledge you follow the arete using underclings and insecure climbing to the top.  Expect the climbing to get harder as you progress with several small cruxes.

name: Practice Chimney
description: Short splitter, perfect to practice some chimney technique.

name: Son of Great Chimney
description: Son of Great Chimney is an inspiring and intimidating line for the grade. Start on the left side of the north face. Off balance moves up the arete will lead you past pins, and into the middle crux and a few big moves. Make your way over to the right side, and finish up the right hand arete. Don't forget to enjoy the view.  It is true that Pete's onsight lead in 1968 was one of the single greatest moments in the history of climbing in the United States. Few routes across the country could compare.

name: Son of Great Chimney Direct
description: Do the first half of of the regular route and finish up the shallow dihedral left and center on the buttress, climb the center face instead of the corner. Climbing is sustained with a mantle/dino at the finish.

name: Whipping Boy
description: Dually cracks up a small tower type feature.  The bottom is a little dirty, though the upper section provides good movement.

name: Wild West
description: Wild West sits high atop the West Bluff, and overlooks everything from its poignant perch. This slightly overhanging line is not your typical DL 5.11-, and is an excellent, though short lead for the grade. However the spice is the real deal, and committing to some of the more bouldery moves may make you sweat a little. Luckily the holds are surprisingly good, and the sequences are fairly straight forward.   (Also known as "Wild West Homo" - a comment on some people's attitudes toward the lycra-clad climbers of the 80s, I think - DH.)

name: Clout Buster
description: Clout Buster is found to the left of Lost Face (route 67) in the corner behind the large block.  Climb up the corner using chimney moves for about 20 feet.  At 20 feet, exit the chimney by standing on top of the pointed block (this should bust your clout pretty nicely, especially on lead).  Continue straight up from here or move right onto Lost Face.

name: Look Ma No Hands
description: Climb the seemingly blank face in between Lost Face and Lost Face Finger Crack. Work your way up through some small ledges and delicate feet before reaching a solid pocket where you can finally catch your breath. Continue upwards through some easy climbing before reaching the second blank face and the crux of the route. Grab on to the last large feature on the face, pull hard to gain balance, and trust your foot and you push up saying “Look Ma No Hands”. Continue upwards through some delicate moves before reaching the junction of Lost Face and Lost Face Finger Crack. This route gains full value when avoiding the  Lost Face and Lost Face Finger Crack crack systems.   After reaching the junction top out with Lost Face, or Lost Face Overhang 1 or 2   This route is NOT well protected but gear could possibly be placed in the adjacent crack systems on either side.  The route can be top roped from the same anchor point as the rest of Lost Face

name: Lost Face
description: Lost Face is a very sweet climb.  It was actually one of my first climbs at the Lake.  The approach is a bit tricky.  I never found a way to hike to it, we always had to rap down.  It's a fun 5.6, not to mention it's the longest climb on the West Bluff.  It's a great lead, with not a bad overhang for the crux.  You won't need any large gear...Tri-cams and Hexes work the best for me.  When leading there is a great ledge to sit on and anchor off.  The ledge is above all the trees and it has to be one of the best views at the park.  Climb it in the morning.  When the sun is rising it paints the Lake in this awesome glow, plus you get to see a ton of hawks flying just above your head...Well worth the early wake up.  I want to try this variation.  First top rope the climb at the ledge that I mentioned earlier, or lead it.  Start the climb over to the right at this thin crack that shoots strait up.  Then you hit the crux traverse over to the left to the overhang and continue up to the ledge.  The crack to the right is listed as a 5.7 and the overhang is a 5.8.  I didn't get to climb it this last time so do tell me how it turns out.  This is a great spot to get you acclimated to the area, which sees little crowding.

name: Lost Face Finger Crack
description: The most well protected and classic lead on the face.  Ascend the obvious finger crack to the right of the normal Lost Face route.  After 35 feet or so this route joins the standard 5.6 just below the roof.  Any number of finishes is possible from here (5.6-5.8 see Lost Face and Lost Face Overhangs I & II for descriptions)

name: Lost Face Overhangs I & II
description: These are both variations of the normal Lost Face Route (5.6).  Basically Climb the 5.6 version of LF up to the overhang, which can be surpassed in two ways.    One variation ascends the left hand crack through the roof.  The other goes up to the right of that on good holds.  The two variations join again above the roof and ascend a more central crack (crux if you miss the holds).  They both continue straight to top.

name: Lost in the Woods (Unnamed Route 5.7)
description: The crux is the lower 1/3 of the route.

name: Noah Vail
description: Climb left side of Lost Face on delicate holds with out use of corner. Surmont Lost Face Overhang II and up.    I can't say for a fact that these are indeed First Ascents. I can only state they are attractive nice lines that do not appear in Swartling's guide. They were done in the spirit of "fair play" and were duly documented.

name: Rich Bechler Memorial Route
description: This one is in memory of Rich Bechler RIP.   This is a completely ignored and recently un-earthed little gem.  I lowered down it and was moved to clean alot of lichen, moss, plants, and dirt from some of it's ledges and cracks.  I am quite sure this climb has been never touched but I am not absolutely sure so chime in if need be.   The crux is at 3\4 height where the is a mild run out and you climb into the little top corner.  The holds are somewhat down sloping and in-obvious here so move quickly.  The lower moves are tricky and a bit off balance moving up the crack if the climber stays right of the crack and slighty easier and more secure if the climber works up the left side of the crack utilizing a few side pulls off the arete on the left.  There are a couple of neat pistol grip holds on this climb.

name: Unnamed 5.7
description: Rightmost of 3 climbs on separate wall right of Lost Face proper. Climb crack at north end of small overhang.  This is Swartling/Mayer #73, and is named "Unnamed 5.7" in Knower.

name: Unnamed 5.8
description: Leftmost of 3 climbs on separate wall right of Lost Face proper. Start in niche. Climb overhang and crack.  This is Swartling/Mayer #72, and is named "Unnamed 5.8" in Knower.

name: A Baraboo Thing
description: A sweet line between routes 7 and 8.Crack in middle of lower wall, hang up and right, work back left to good ledge, then power back right to top. (Note: a much tougher line is present if one does not work towards ledge. I'm confidant it is doable for some other DL Hardman.)

name: Flaky Tower
description: On the buttress just left of the main wall. Climb east corner to base of small tower. Balance up left onto south corner. Climb corner to top of tower, then step over gap and climb short wall above.   This is an unnamed 5.7 in both Knower and Swartling/Mayer guide books. I decided to give it a name since another unnamed 5.7 is just a few feet right of this one. The route description is right out of S/M.

name: No Flakes
description: Start by climbing the inside corner on the left side of the wall. The guide books differ on the finish - both are worth doing. (This route joins with Two Flakes at the 25' ledge.)  Per Swartling/Mayer - climb crack and V-chimney 25' to ledge on right. Retable to next ledge. Continue up and right to third ledge, then to top.  Per Knower - climb the deep inside cleft and continue to the top (finishing more straight up and a little left of S/M).  This is an unnamed 5.7 in both Knower and Swartling/Mayer guide books. I decided to give it a name since another unnamed 5.7 is just a few feet left of this one.

name: North Side
description: Climb inside corner and deep awkward crack, which is wide enough at the crux to be considered a small chimney. Easy to protect until you reach the crux. A small lateral crack is hidden out of view within the small chimney and it can be hard to reach from the stance below, but it's a bomber small nut placement. The crux consists of making the committing and very exposed move out left before moving up into the crack. After another step up or two, there's a large handhold and a good placement for a #3 Camelot if you think you still need it, since at that point your one step below being able to grab the top of the tower.

name: Pine Tree Crack
description: A few strenuous moves in a hand crack to a bear hug on a giant pine tree take you up to a sharp and exposed arete.

name: South Chimney
description: One of the nicer routes in this grade.  No chimneying required.    Stem up the cleft at the base, arriving at a ledge with a monster pine tree on the right.  Work you way up the dihedral formed between the Tower and the cliff.  The crux comes in the middle, about where you can look through the hole in the tower to the Lake.    At the top you have several options: scramble up on the boulder to the left (best place to set a TR), walk back away from the cliff (easiest), or bust a move up the crack in the headwall to your right and finish on top of the tower (one 5.6-5.7 move).

name: Two Flakes
description: Climb the sharp flakes left of the pine tree located on the wall. Some interesting chimney and mantels to follow. Angle left on the path of least resistance.

name: Amazing Grace
description: Climb onto the detached block below 1st overhang, pass the overhang on the right, pass upper overhang on the left.  There is a variation that traverses right at the top.

name: Amusing Bruce
description: Climb the inside corner until it ends about half way up. Then it's easy climbing until you get to the finishing moves at the prow on top.  It's an interesting route, just not an amazing one like its neighbor to the right. The route is unnamed in the guide books - S/M #17, Knower #5.

name: Dead Tree Corner
description: Start at the end of the corner and climb up to the stump. Follow the corner to the top.

name: Dead Tree Crack
description: Two cruxes....  One low getting through the initial steep crack section to reach ledges and holds under the second harder crux which pulls the devious moderate overhang past the "Dead Tree", now actually a rotted stump.  Very exiting and no give away for the grade.

name: Dr. Who
description: Distinct from and separate route just right of Tardis.   Climb broken rock and cracks just right of Tardis finger crack start up to horizontal.  Climb face right of the middle crack section of Tardis trending rightwards to hanging crack with very sharp finger lock (you will know when you get it).  Exit onto slabs above and climb the final upper moves of Tardis utilizing the fixed pin for pro.

name: Fecal Maneuvers In the Dark
description: Climb Amazing Grace to upper overhang pull it directly and a few hard cranks and you are over.

name: Grassy Ledge
description: Begin on the outer corner that marks the left edge of the ampitheater.  Climb up beside flakes on the left, to the top.

name: Tardis
description: Not to be missed!  10 Ft. right of Dead Tree Route.  Crux is the first 15 feet- a thin tips crack with tricky smears for the feet on left and toe scum in crack opening on the right.  Stab for jug above.  Excellent pro abounds. Then follow very interesting crack and edges line to top.  There is a second and mid way crux when making move from large flake on left up to cool mantle ledge.  Upper moves are stellar as well and the whole thing is OK protected... there are a few spots one has to go a body length without protection.

name: Waltzing Mary
description: Start on the inside corner.  At the ledge at mid-height, head up through the slight overhang into the crack on the left.  Continue to the top.

name: The Clamshell
description: Up a corner to a large V-Notch then stem left and up the face.

name: Hangman Towers Offwidth
description: Belay is within a bowl at the start of the crack, be cautious; there is loose rock and the sharp corners of the tower blocks. The crack starts out about a foot wide with a flake to the left with a crack in it that takes gear well. Moving up the crack, it gets smaller above the flake and then larger once again. When you are above the flake, you should be able to use a #3 BD cam and some hexes to protect. The crack constricts at the top, be careful not to get stuck here because it is easy to wedge your chest between the blocks. Mantle over the top and there is a tree you can use as a quick anchor.

name: The Porpoise
description: Climb up the narrow, fin shaped ridge at the lower end of rock band.  The rock seems bad and loose, but every hold is solid and trustworthy.

name: Sharks Tooth
description: Stem with an off-finger crack to the pinnacle summit.

name: The Beast
description: Climb up obvious corner crack to gain the upper "Beast" pinnacle.  Stay on the northeast corner of pinnacle to top(run-out).     Room for one on the top, and just bring slings for the anchor.

name: Knobby Pillar
description: Start at South corner of pillar and climb up.   Climbing the small overhang on Northeast corner is 5.8.

name: Cake Walk
description: Start with a boulder problem to a horizontal with pro. Move left and ascend the crack system. Looks easy for the second half, it's not.

name: Der Schnozzel
description: A fun and technical climb with decent gear.

name: Go-Go
description: Climb the southeast corner of tower.  Fun laybacks up high, and bring small wires.

name: Tower Right of Go-Go
description: Climb up east face of tower.  Really easy climbing, but fun.

name: Arm Power
description: Start in a nice left-slanting crack, then up a blunt corner to the overhang. Pass the overhang directly.   This is listed as 11d in Sven's book but to get that you would have to dutifully ignore some pretty good holds.   Short crux about halfway up with gear at your feet. A short running belay will keep you off the deck.

name: Heavenly Mist
description: Start behind big block. Climb to right of the corner using small jugs and small ledges. Continue to top. Variation: Traverse left 2/3's of the way up to cramped ledge. Hand jam crack to the top.

name: Last Great Project?
description: Starts off fun but casual. After the horizontal crack small crimps and hard lock offs lead to a mantle onto a ledge. I see the moves but couldn't pull them. A trophy to be won in a place with few trophys left.

name: Pearls Before Swine
description: Start a few feet right of the small dihedral capped by a small roof at about 10'.  Climb more or less straight up the slab to a stance below the obvious roof and hanging arete.  Continue straight up the arete to a mantle onto the ledge.

name: St. Peter Says "No"
description: Whoa, total sandbag as 5.7 as listed in Sven's guidebook. Sven says to start the route right of the corner. Total crap idea. Start up Pearly Gate and traverse right to the corner and straight up. You can also bypass the crux of Pearly Gate by stepping back left onto the sloping ledge.

name: St. Peter Says "YES!"
description: It's a warm up. Unnamed route #5 in Sven's guidebook.

name: Access Route
description: Simple and direct, this route gives access to the top of the tower. The vertical crack on left can be used as a variation.

name: Bowlers Grip
description: start on west face of tower,continue up the crack to the left handed bowlers grip, then gravy the rest of the way.

name: Delight
description: Up the buttress, to the right of the alcove.  An easy romp with nice exposure.

name: Flying Indian
description: Would be three stars if it was taller but there were some great finger locks.

name: No Trouble
description: Climb thin crack past small overhang. To the right of flying Indian, Page 296 #21 in 3rd edition DL guidebook

name: Tree Tower
description: Start at lowest point. Climb northeast ridge on nice ledges to a sweet lieback at the top. Be careful of loose and brittle rock near and on top. Descend at route 3.

name: Tree Tower Crack
description: Follow the obvious crack that has a bush half way to the top.

name: North Twin Ridge
description: Done in 4 to 5 short pitches, with climbing ranging from 5.4 to 5.7.     Starting at the very base of the ridge, climb first two towers and upper wall to gain a nice ledge called the Lunch Spot.  From there continue up short wall with big crack or take another option and summit the pinnacle of South Twin Ridge.

name: South Twin Ridge
description: Done in 2 to 3 pitches.  The South Twin sits south and up hill from the North Twin by 50 to 100ft.  The fist pitch starts in large chimney, then moves up and left on south corner to gain the upper block.  Summit pinnacle on this is worth the climb.  Super fun.

name: "The Gap"
description: The Gap is listed in Sven's guidebook as starting in "The Gap" between the south wall of T Tower and a blank face. I started the route on "No Way Down" and belayed my partner to the ledge to do the rest of the route. The 5.8 version goes up a layback crack then right to the corner, a 5.9 version goes straight up (not recommended).

name: Last Crack
description: HIDDEN GEM ALERT! I would have given it 4 stars but for a potentially reachy move at the top. Laybacking through a technical crux in the middle to a double-gaston has you staring a meager foot smears and a dynamic lunge to a finishing sloper.

name: Lone Pine Diagonal
description: Follow the left angle diagonal crack.

name: No Way Down
description: Wow. Best way to the top of the tower. Easy to the north platform but from there unprotected climbing up the face, slightly left, and to the top. Unnamed route #3 in Sven's guidebook.

name: No Way Down Direct AKA "Tyrolean Tower"
description: This is the direct finish to "No Way Down". A double direct version is in Sven's guidebook as "Tyrolean Tower" and starts at the "Southeast rounded corner" of the tower and is rated at 5.10d. I looked at the corner and didn't see any pro whatsoever so I led this version instead.

name: Coffee Break
description: Warm up for the area.

name: Pee Wee's Innocent
description: Nice boulder problem to a slabby top half. FUN moves!

name: Rock Divot
description: Thin crack line with an interesting crux. Go right at the top for a full value variation.

name: Use Your Feet
description: A very good middle section with off-finger jams. Go either left or right at "the nose". Left is better. Finish straight up for the full value.

name: Flake Fun
description: #8 in the Climber's Guide. Climb wall with three large flakes.

name: Never Again
description: Off-fist crack to finish an easy scramble.

name: Sasquatch
description: Listed as #9 in Sven's guidebook this is a hidden gem.    Climb the rib on the left side and through the notch in the overhang.

name: Star-maker Chimney
description: Will you be a star, or will you be seeing stars?    Requires almost no chimney technique:  look for little ledges and sidepulls inside the chimney, and feet on the face outside.

name: Your Name in Lights
description: The nicest route on this little buttress, some nice moves.    The crux, as usual for Devils Lake, is at the bottom above a rocky landing.  Definitely height dependent - easier if you are tall.

name: Block party
description: Follow the wide crack up to the block party and finish at the big tree.

name: Divergent Crack
description: Look for a wall below the weakness in the upper face. Follow the crack as it goes up and to the right.

name: North Country Corner
description: #8 in the Climber's Guide. Start on left leaning corner to small overhang and continue left while staying on the corner the top.

name: North Country Crack
description: A clearly defined vertical crack system that just begs you to scramble up!    The crux might be getting off the ground.  Higher up you contend with an off-fingers sized crack, and footholds that disappear under little bulges.

name: Slap Arete?
description: The obvious arete right of Divergent Crack.  It's labeled route #4 in the new Swartling/Mayer guide.   The description in this guide is accurate but I think the difficulty is a bit under-rated and especially if one attempts to stay strictly on the left side of the arete and doesn't reach over right around the corner (maybe mid 5.11?).  If one climbs the arete straight on utilizing holds left and right it's possibly 5.9.  If one traverses around the corner after making the initial moves up and off the block then utilizing the projecting horn then its 5.6 to 5.7.  Finish this variation by stepping back left after avoiding and getting above the hard strict arete moves.  I ended up on-sighting the easier variation on lead but worked the arete itself on TR.  This thing is short and really just a protectable boulder problem but to boulder it  only would be nasty in the landing (big pointy rotten tree stump).  It's a fun and worth the effort route I think.

name: The Slot
description: #9 in the Climber's Guide. Start on small ledge and follow wide diagonal crack 3-4 feet left of the corner.

name: Sore Toes
description: A sweet looking vertical crack ... but on closer inspection it's pretty short and often within reach of the easier line to the left.    Still, if you are a Devils Lake local you are accustomed to gently focusing your mind on the holds immediately in front of you, and letting the rest of the world drift away.  There are some good moves here.

name: South County Crack
description: Start in the crack and follow it up and slightly left. The top has little to no protection.     Either set an anchor before hand or finish to the right.     Ends in same place as North country corner and the slot.

name: The Vicelord
description: Climbs the faint crack line left of the more obvious "North Country Crack".  The crux is pulling up and past the major horizontal via a nice but maybe a bit insecure side-pull and then long reach to secret hold and a cross-over move all with the gear at your feet.  The more broken rock above the crux is sustained 5.8.

name: Cannon Fodder
description: Pretty fun.. seemingly the line to do here from what we saw, so get after it.Start sitting with a pinch for the left and a cobble-like undercling.  Climb out the steepness up and right.

name: Oracle Bone
description: Boulder up and over bulge that makes up highest point of mega boulder I am calling "Red Horn".

name: Pinagigi
description: 30.25 ft (Ha!) splitter crack.  5.10 with a sequence of somewhat painful finger locks through the overhanging crux.

name: Sparks
description: This climb ascends the overhanging cobbly wall 30 right of the prominent crack line of Pinigigi and start is just left of big tree. Only 25ish feet but every move is slightly over your head except maybe last 3ft pull.  Small sharp rails and cobbly holds here and there!

name: Big Time Big Tom
description: Stand start, up the middle of the Big Tom Boulder. Starts on small, two-finger pocketish hold in the crack for the right and crimper at roughly the same level for the left. Bump to good left-hand pinch, throw right for the break in the lip, make a few moves to establish on the lip and mantle out. The mantle is easier than expected.

name: Happy Birthday Big Tom
description: SDS off two good crimpers on the right-hand side of the Big Tom Boulder. Follow the arete up and left on increasingly larger holds, and mantle out. A fun route, that is not typical of Wisconsin Quartzite. What I assume is the first ascent was done on my dad's 62nd birthday, hence the name.

name: Release and Catch
description: SDS from the obvious low jug and/or crimp in the alcove. Throw for a good crimp and top-out the arete using whatever you can muster.

name: Helen
description: Use a fingerlock to sit-start from the block at the base of the left-slanting crack. Progress up through a hand jam, possibly a chicken wing (if you can get Helen to open up the kitchen), a knee lock, and then back down the size range through hands to finger locks. Top out on jugs leading left of the bulge on the next rock tier (watch for some loose rock at the top).

name: Mental Helen
description: Start on the jugs of Mental Shelf, skip the mantle, instead head right and slightly up using a Gaston to get to the wideness on Helen. Take Helen to the top.    A fun linkup of two lines.

name: Mental Shelf
description: Start on the big jug, mantle it using a slopey sidepull on the right-leaning rail. Climb straight up to the top on easier ground above.    It's possible (and perhaps preferable if one doesn't have a spotter) to bail left after the mantle.

name: Mental Shelf Sit
description: Sit start on dubious holds that leads into easier climbing on Mental Shelf.

name: Rail Rider
description: Do the mantle on Mental Shelf. Then ride the rail up-and-right to the jug on Helen. Finish on Helen.    Fun linkup of two lines.

name: V0+ bank flank
description: its all good climbing, even in street shoes.  Don't do it to impress your friends when leaving rascal's, you'll get hurt

name: Conway's Side - Broadway Rail Bridge
description: The bridge where the railroad crosses Broadway (just down the road from Conways) has some splitter cracks going up the cement abutments. The Conway's side crack is very thin and very hard.  Tape is recomended, as is a lookout for the prowling cop cars at bar time.

name: Pool Side - Broadway Rail Bridge
description: The bridge where the railroad crosses Broadway (just down the road from Conways) has some splitter cracks going up the cement abutments.  The Pool side crack accepts fingers, though the cement is pretty sharp. Tape is recomended, as is a lookout for the prowling cop cars at bar time.

name: South Shore Bathroom
description: Devils lake southshore bouldering area- there is a bathroom, to the right if you're looking at the boulders from the parking lot. Around the back there is a door with an overhanging roof. SDS climb up the door hindges, and work your way under the roof using either of the 4x4 supports,(light is off) throw for the roof, and hold on. after that, heel hook and mantle. if you miss you land flat on your back. Crazy route!

name: Archway
description: The large and only archway starting at Dayton Street near the football stadium.   I don't know the crux, but it's doable.

name: Is it Art ?
description: There are two sections of art (football players' helmets carved into the wall near gate 8 and 9) reaching 10 feet high and 20 feet long each and you could boulder them.    Edges, crimps, and pinches are everything.  Bring some shoes and a spotter.

name: Nail's Tails
description: I thought it was concrete, but I was wrong; it has some on it but it's a rough plastic.  But I would say you could climb it or at least up to the tower of footballs and be alright.  Bring lots of pads.   It will take a lot of attempts to do anything.  If you have a long reach, this may help you.

name: Into the Light
description: Climb up face of pillar directly right of Living Slightly Larger arete.  Get up high enough to top out to the right on the railing, using the light for a solid right foot.

name: Living Slightly Larger
description: Climb up arete to top out on the top of the Pillar.  Committing moves at the top.  Definite highball...

name: Balcony Mantel
description: Come out next to the shrub wall and there is a huge balcony out there.  Jump up on the point and make your way up and mantel trying to avoid using the railing that is right there until you are up on it.  (beached whale)

name: Bathroom Break
description: On the upper level of the shelter, you'll see the restrooms. Just to the left of the men's door, there's a wooden frame on the wall. Start to the left of this, and make your way to the right. You'll cross the wooden support, the men's room door, a drinking fountain (...bubbler), and then the women's room door.    Try not to touch anything except for the wall! There are a couple pipes and exhaust vents that may get in your way, but you have elegance and grace enough not to use them.    This route has crimpy holds and not much to offer for feet. Keep moving, and trust the friction on the porous rock.

name: Big Inside Wall
description: Right behind the upper fireplace there is a long wall packed with ledges and edges.  Easy warm up and fun.  You could do it in your sneakers like me.

name: The Cave
description: The Cave is a little bit tougher problem than most at the Garner Park shelter.  The traverse is located above a long bench built into the wall.  The bench is off (don't use it for your feet) so the height of the wall that's climbable here is about 5 feet high.  Traverse the wall following the bench using a lot of crimper holds.  This will make your hands very tired.  This is a great problem to try if you want to work on hand and forearm strength.

name: Shrubbery Wall
description: Shrubbery Wall is located on the west side of the Garner Park Shelter.  Start out above some boulders in the mulch garden and traverse right on the less-than-vertical wall.  Once you reach the shrubs, go up a bit higher to clear the shrubs or stay low and go through the shrubs (for a true Devil's Lake experience).  Towards the south end the wall gets short (about 4 feet high).  Try some layback-type moves here using the capstones of the wall.  The traverse is probably 30 feet.  Try it round trip for more endurance.

name: Upper Fireplace
description: You can start off on either side of the fireplace, make your way over the door and fireplace to the other side.  Try not to use the top edge of the wall when you get to the right side of the fireplace.  Easy warm up.

name: Wave Traverse
description: The Wave Traverse is located on the south side of the Garner Park shelter.  The wall starts out low (about 4 ft high) and less than vertical, and then transitions into a higher wall (10 ft high) and becomes vertical.  A very nice warmup problem.

name: Big Wall - lower area
description: I think the start would be the hardest.  This is a traverse, and you hug the wall while going around it.  About 50 feet front and back.  Very good warm up.

name: Hang On - upper
description: If you like little edges and crimps you will have to try this.  It is at the upper shelter.  Either of the inside walls with fire places.

name: Over and Up - lower area
description: Outer side of the shelter right by a fence.  Start inside, and traverse low and then topout at the end.

name: School Wall
description: If you are at the upper shelter, look over to the school. Follow it to the back and you have a great wall to traverse back and forth.  Easy warm up.

name: Is the Route Included in the Price of the Condo?
description: This route consists of large, rectangular limestone blocks laid in a brick pattern. The wall encloses the recreational path (Oak Leaf Trail) running through the east side, and aids in supporting the Lafayette Ave bridge. The route is just north of the bridge, on the east side of the recreational corridor. The wall is dirty & crumbly in some areas so test your holds before pulling or stepping up on them. The whole climb is simply a series of awkward jugs, large, crimp-friendly slopers, or vertical cracks between blocks. There's no true crux to speak of; the climb is consistent from base to summit.     Unless you're bouldering, be aware that you may look suspicious fooling around in the bushes while you're setting your anchors, so be cautious. This is a high-traffic area, so expect numerous passers-by, both from above and below. Comments and an audience, if only for brief moments at a time - especially from the residents of the twin-tower Park Lafayette residence opposite the bike trail - are not uncommon.     Bring a towel to dry your climbing shoes prior to starting the route. The base lies in some tall grass, and water often seeps out of the wall and puddles just to the south, under the bridge.

name: Redfield
description: Located across and under the bridge from "Is the Route Included in the Price of the Condo?", this wall is composed of a different type of rock block and is also not as vertical as the aforementioned climb.
