Just as the other climb, the rock quality is shady in some places. Use caution if leading.

name: Coronavirus Corner
description: Sit start in the corner next to the men's restroom and work up to the roof.  Traverse left to the arete and continue up to topout.

name: 2550 Warm up
description: It's a pretty nice and easy warm-up set to set you up for the Burrito Wall boulder 3 blocks down. The first move is a mantel up a concrete platform followed by a brick wall with aided apparatus. The last move is the crux with a 2 ft reach and a hop over the garden plaza above.

name: Burrito wall
description: Just to left of Qdoba wall, this wall packs in some great edges, crimps, and i even found jugs and underclings.  This would be super fun.

name: Qdoba wall
description: Just a nice long traverse right next to the parking lot of Qdoba in Unversity Ave.   Good rock, nice feet, plus food next door.

name: The Green Spot
description: Start matching ledge with a small green smudge on it.  Nice quality crimps all the way up. Use a ledge between 3rd and 4th hold.

name: Bridge Column
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: The 5th Element
description: This is the boulder problem on the adjacent face right of "Washboard Abs" on the northeast face of the northeast pillar. Use flake on left and arete on the right. Reachy, but positively stimulating, moves to a nothing short of exhilarating top out with a view of the Earth Day celebration and Rugby or Cricket games.

name: Baby Shark
description: Start with a left hand side-pull on the arete and a right hand 2 finger undercling on the right face. Work up the arete until you get to the incut crimps on the arete, at which point it’s in the bag. Avoid using either adjacent aretes as well as the cutout ledges towards the top of the left face

name: Ball Bearing
description: Start compressed on both sides and work your way up using sidepulls and some crimp rails

name: Barndoor 0.002
description: Start with a right hand on the arete and a left hand on the crimp on the face (shown in photo). Climb up the arete using the right sidepull and crimps on the face until you get to the top where a right side-pull can be used on the right face to top out.  Both adjacent aretes are off

name: Between a Rock and a Hard Place
description: First off, you have to be tall for this one. You start pressed between the south and east Sentinels. Topping out is pretty sketch, so be careful and don't die.

name: Chicken Little
description: An arete focused boulder with limited foot-holds on the face.  This route is on the same block as Washboard Abs (to the left of it).

name: Circles and Arrow
description: Its going to be all sidepulls until you get on the "arrow". Trust your feet placement as you go up. The arrow is a super nice hold. Reach up to a nice crimp and heel hook to top out.

name: Deathstar
description: Start on either side and compress to the top. Be careful because the edge above the polished dish at the top is sharp

name: Frosted flake
description: Start with both hands compressed beneath the flake. Use good feet on both aretes to work to the top

name: I Can't Believe it's Not Buttered Logs
description: Don't forget to traverse the Buttered Log. Watch out for cops.

name: Lizzle Dis Bizzle
description: Start on the right crimp on the face and a sidepull on the left

name: One Good Feet
description: Compress using sidepulls and smearing feet to work up the face. Easy once u hit the jug

name: Quaranteenie
description: Start with left hand at the bottom of the left flake and right hand compressed on the slopey pinch next to the arete. Move up using the left flake and a right hand incut sidepull until you get to a diagonal ledge and a right crimp in the face at the top. Both aretes are OFF. A bit subjective where the right arete so refer to the photo for clarification.

name: Smudge the Mirror
description: Start with a right hand on the flake, the left on the arete, and some good feet on the left face. Climb up the arete using any features on the flake or either face. Both aretes marked in red are off.

name: Stand up guy
description: Climb the arete using the crimps on the right face and compressing the left face. Get a high foot on the arete and shoot for the crimp beneath the polished dish. The flake on the left face next to the arete is off.

name: Stick your fingers in Gabby
description: crux probably toward the top, have to smear with your right foot to top out.

name: Tootmaster McGee
description: Start at the bottom of the left flake and a side pull on the left side. Use the flake and heel or toehooks to work your way to the top. Left arete is off

name: Tootsie Pop
description: Climb up the face using moderate crimps. See photo for start holds. BOTH ARETES ARE OFF

name: Two-Step
description: Two crucial cross-steps to a slopey side-pull.

name: Washboard Abs
description: Route is rhythmic and consistent. It has the appearance of a ladder and is one of the easiest of the Buttered Logs routes.

name: Pass The Sauce
description: Follow the pockets up the the top

name: Beet Soup
description: Crimpy route with a couple large lockoffs.

name: Cheese Touch
description: Nice easy warm up with match on solid sloper for finish. If you finish the problem you have the cheese touch.

name: Just Got Pickled
description: Simple dyno up and left to the top.

name: No One's Slick as Gaston
description: Start low on a solid edge before traversing into a crimpy gaston. Follow crimps up to the match on a hand jam as the top hold. The hand jam is super solid and not very sketchy when you find the right spot. You can finish on the top as an easier finish but don't top out.

name: Pinchers Paradise
description: Short boulder with comfortable top out.

name: SC-etchy
description: South Wall. Simply using the large cracks to get to the top. Toping out is recommended easy way down (steps). Rock is often moist but not wet. Cracks are extremely dirty so if your are doing this route bring a big brush.

name: Sly Dawg
description: Series of small holds and big moves that work your way in a "C" shape.

name: Soy Sauce
description: Start low on the angled sloper, traversing your way to the right before dynoing (if your short like me) to the top.

name: Sticky the Clown
description: tricky start with finger pocket and big pinch followed by traversing a small edge before crimps and topping out.

name: Under The Bridge
description: North Wall. Simply using the large cracks to get to the top. Toping out is recommended easy way down (steps). Rock is often moist but not wet. Cracks are extremely dirty so if your are doing this route bring a big brush.

name: RadioShack Offwidth
description: 5" - 4" OW, get ready to bleed.

name: Gatoriod
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: Salt and Light
description: Largest face on the Coprophagy boulder.  Start bottom right end and at highest point of boulder. Both aretes and re-bar are off.

name: Jizz Chips
description: This is a nice splitter between two brick buildings. Starts off with a tipped out #3BD and then gets ever so slightly smaller from there. Make sure to be a hardman and solo it or wait till dark. Brick quality is good.    Makes good practice for pure crack technique as there are no face holds.

name: Bolton Traverse
description: This is located in and and near the enclosed walkway connecting the Student Union with Bolton Hall. The indoor section runs the length of the only solid wall in an otherwise glass walkway, while the outdoor section runs to the west along Bolton Hall's south wall. The outdoor plaza (under construction) is accessible via double-doors from the walkway.    This problem can be approached and completed in dozens of ways. The climber is limited only by his or her imagination. This is really more of a whole buildering location than a single route, but given the sporadic patterning on the wall, well-defined problems or routes are hard to codify or repeat. This traverse, in my eyes, is best utilized by climbing laterally - without using the ledge at the top - to build endurance. Individual problems or routes could be mapped out by climbers upon arrival .     Indoors or outdoors, the climber may choose to sit-start at literally any point and climb vertically or traverse laterally to the heart's content. The edges are ~3/4 to ~1 inch deep, with a small lip to the climber's advantage in many spots. There's a deeper ledge running the length of the wall at the very top.    Inside, the otherwise unbroken decorative wall is split by a vertical gap roughly 2 or 3 inches wide running the height of the wall. This can easily be lay-backed & flagged for a modest crack-climb. The gap is maybe 6 - 10 ft from the Bolton Hall doors and barely visible in the "detail" indoor photo. It runs basically parallel to the line in the floor all the way at the end.    As of the summer of 2012, the small plaza between the Union and Bolton hall is under construction, and a large swath of the outdoor wall is enclosed behind construction fencing. Technically, the entire section is still accessible.     Lastly, many of the edges in the indoor section - because they're not exposed to the elements - are quite dusty, adding an additional challenge when traversing indoors.

name: Enyinyering
description: Run and kick off the wall to start with a side-pull/undercling on the concrete awning. Work up to the top and throw up a heel to mantle.

name: Match Maker, Match Maker
description: If you're facing the wall, it takes up the entire far left section.  Begins with a three point start (standing height), one move up/right, and the rest take you horizontal right (over the bench) to end the problem on the top rail (behind the support beam).     It was well marked in blue chalk from start to finish on 6/10/12.

name: Southeast Arrete of the EMS Spire
description: This problem is on the EMS spire and ascends beautiful and gritty concrete. It is without a doubt one of the best problems available to looped out students anywhere on the UW-Milwaukee campus.  Sit start is recommended.  Begin on the southeast arete of the spire and traverse clockwise to a gnarly high foot/ full on mantle to the platform on the west side of the spire.  Those who dare to go to the top of the spire get bonus V points, but it is strongly recommended against due to the structurally degraded concrete up there.

name: The spire roof problem
description: This problem begins under the south roof of the sculpture with a sit start under the southwest leg of the sculpture (see beta photo). Love the roof!

name: Chamberlin Rock East Arete
description: Sit start and work your way up the arete using holds on both sides of the corner.  Top out.  In my opinion this is the best problem on this rock.    I posted this under the buildering area, but this is a natural rock, so I suspect you are less likely to get into trouble for climbing it.  I would just stay away from the plaque.  This boulder was apparently found down near the lakeshore when one of the dorms was being built and was moved to the top of the hill because it looks nice there, must have been quite an effort!    Variations:   Stand start: V2 (can move right for this with no added difficulty)   Face to the left (north face): sharp and crimpy V3 stand start.   West arete:  V-easy route to the top.

name: Chamberlin Rock Traverse
description: Start at the very left (southwest) corner of the south face. Traverse right on progressively smaller holds then top out at the very eastern corner of the boulder. The arete and the top of the bouler are off (until you top out obviously)  Variations: V2 Same start and deletes, but you top out at the hump in the center of the boulder.  V0-1 Arete and top are on, traverse left to right along the top of the boulder. Great warm up, focus on the footwork!

name: Glacial Chowder
description: Start with right hand on a bomber side-pull just under the plaque, and feet under the overhang. I like to start with my left hand on a low crimp far left, but it really doesn't help that much. Move up and left, then top out on the northeast corner of the boulder. The unnatural ledge under the plaque is off. The key beta (spoiler alert) is a hidden pinch with your left hand, your thumb sits on a piece of pink quartz.   Variation: V1-2 The unnatural ledge under the plaque is on.

name: Park St. Bridge
description: It is all straightforward. About 70 feet long on each side.  There are two sides of the bridge (north and south) and there are large edges and squares cut out of the stone that's holding up the railroad bridge.  It's right off of Dayton street.

name: Science Hall Arete
description: Feel around for any holds, should start low on a left hand undercling on the corner and a crimp around the arete on the right. Continue crimping up to the second floor and drop down.

name: Trust Fund Traverse
description: Traverse the west-facing Statesider wall (coplanar with Potbelly's). Start at the north end and work your way south. Due to the staggered bricks you've a million good crimps to work with, so some good creativity is encouraged. You have to be quick, though, since the security guy will come out to yell at you.

name: Turbulent Juice
description: Start with a side pull above the top left corner of the plaque on your right hand and an arete on your left, go up with your left to another side pull and move your right foot up. Then move your left hand up to a small hold about a foot below the top ledge, do a single hand dyno to the top ledge and haul from there.

name: Van Hise Building - Left side wall
description: in the middle 10feet up.   Mostly edges and small crimps.

name: The Nose
description: Follow the line up the obvious nose arete.  This is the tallest section of the retaining wall.  Steady crimpers the whole way up.  Don't biff it at the top, which is a no fall zone.

name: BFB Left
description: Start sitting on block at base. Look for good foot at base. Left Crack and all crack features are off. Left start hold is sharp chip. Stand up and move right onto face. Power thru crimps and rails to top.

name: crack the whip
description: the crux of the crack is near the top, keep to the right near the top of the crack the jug on the left is off

name: hinky
description: the crux is about half way through the climb. good landing zone. This is a very good warm up.

name: pinchers of power
description: the crux is near the beginning of the problem a sit start on small crimpy sidepull on the left near the bottom of the problem and open hand pinch with the right hand on the big flake follow the flake up to sloping sidepull topout

name: project
description: the crux is the half way point through the climb very slopey ramp.

name: snuckles
description: the crux again is about half way through the climb, follow the ramp up to the point go straight up from there the crack is off.

name: sunrise warmup
description: if there is a crux it would be at the start.

name: too short traverse
description: the crux is near the beginning of the problem.

name: Vamanavataram
description: the crux is the high step onto the ramp into a series of crimps to the top

name: Satans Sandbox
description: Crux is pulling up on sloper at the top, fun overhung start

name: Antichrist Arete
description: Start with a sit on the furthest left (low) side of the boulder and follow the holds up and right to the highest point on the arete. Pull onto the low angle face above.

name: Box Car Full Traverse
description: Route starts on the NW corner of the boulder. Without using the upper lip traverse down the west face, around the steep narrow South face, then uphill on the East face. Crux is the very last two moves before you reach the corner (no top out necessary).

name: Box-car Scoop
description: Climb up the scoop around the corner from the steep face on the Box-car Boulder.

name: Ocean Spray Slab
description: Squat start on some jugs. Only using the face, choose from various sharp crimpers and sidepulls until you reach the ledge. Move into a hidden pocket up high then find some good top out holds.

name: Age of Ondra
description: Start with both hands on the nice down-pull right of the slot with both feet on small holds below down-pull. Move left foot to the lower slot and then put your left hand on the baseball hold protruding from the arete to the left, then bump the left hand up and right to a nice crimp. move left foot to the upper part of the slot, then bring the right heel on to the starting hold and move right hand up to fin above the start hold. Move your left hand to the sloper towards the left of the arete. Left hand to crimp and then top out.

name: Corner Problem
description: Start low and climb corner, top-out right on jugs.

name: Cross Cube
description: Start as far toward the man-eater boulder as possible on the face opposite the trail,(south side). Traverse to the right staying low and not using the top edge. Climb around the corner and top out using either the slot or keep going to top out using off the pocket.

name: Cube Traverse
description: Left side of boulder from the corner problem, start low on large flake and work your way around the boulder moving left to right.  Most people top out above the slot climb, but for a greater challenge keep going all the way and end on the easier far corner.

name: Cubic  Consuela
description: My apologies for mudding up the system more with additional traverse problems on this boulder, but this line is definitive and good quality starting on the S face of the boulder and finishing on the NE arete.     SDS on large jug flake left of the corner and move up and right though crimps.  Hit the arete pinch and round the corner staying low and matching the large angling flake.  Make the long reach to the vertical slot/pocket and continue moving low and right matching in the slot/pocket.  Make a final crux sequence using side-pull edges and a pinch to get you to the NE arete with jugs and flake that leads to a juggy top-out.

name: Layed Back
description: Starting on same jug as Slot, climb straight up using fins.

name: Left Face
description: Start low on the left face of the Cube boulder.  Straight up, one big move, top out.

name: Off the Pocket
description: Using deep pocket for hand and low pocket for foot, climb straight up boulder.  A bit more tricky.

name: Off the Pocket Sit
description: Sit with feet at a low rail, right hand in lower slot, and left hand on an intermediate. Bump through a sharp hold and up into the upper pocket. Match, get high feet, and move out right to a rounded crimp. Make a cruxy stab to good holds above and cruise to the top.

name: Right Corner
description: Climb right corner on Cube.

name: Slot
description: Start matched with good hold.  Throw left into deep slot.  Top-out

name: Leaning Boulder
description: Climb up obvious leaning boulder.  Not very hard, but you can have some fun with it.

name: Right wall traverse
description: A great upward traverse on the boulder on the right(east) side of the chamber. Keep off the very top of the boulder and anything else is on. Begin sit style down far and move up to an obvious crux which involves a powerull huck left to crisp crimps.

name: Fat Man Corridor
description: Located in between the #2 & #3 House Bouklders is a corridor which has a number of new problems on both walls. The lines are tall committing as well as a couple of 40+ft traverses which are great!

name: House Boulder   3
description: Climb up the central buldge on the east face of house boulder#3. Great pocket pulling leads one to big jugs and big air potential. Classic!

name: House Boulder  1 East Face -" Hollowlander"
description: Climb up the center of the east face using anything in reach. the crux is the obvious blank section in the middle of the problem. This is a classic problem on par with the Jesus Boulder. (Pics to come soon)

name: House Boulder South Face Traverse
description: Start on the first of two detached blocks on the left side of the south face. Foloow slopers to a good hand jam and drift rightward into intense pocket pulling to a crux near the gently overhanging arete. Classic pockets!

name: Head Screw
description: Climb up the mossy face on the leading end of the ridge. Giant holds appear everywhere as you ascend, but PLEASE CHECK THEM CAREFULLY. Large loose features abound, and if one of them pulled out while you were standing on it, it would ruin your day.

name: Cowboy Messiah
description: One of the more unique problems in Wisconsin. Start by getting on the saddle-like boulder under the center of the boulder. Use toe hooks and core tension to establish one's self. A sick catch of a left rail and Big throw to the slopping lip brings you to the engaging mantle. There ain't much for holds, but the friction's off the charts!- super fun, git on it!

name: Jamming the Forbidden Fruit
description: Start under the belly of the boulder, with left hand jammed and a right hand undercling, near Cowboy Messiah is a rail for the right foot. ascend the crack utilizing Jams, underclings, and face holds.

name: Jesus Boulder Arete
description: Start on low holds on right side of boulder and drift up and left following a series of fantastic slopping holds to an extremely exciting finish! Grab one of the few postive holds, throw a heel up and rock over- Amen!

name: Jesus Boulder Direct
description: Climb the overhanging east face of the Jesus boulder, starting on the low right side and climb up to the top left and top out as with the Jesus arete. Steep and powerful, this line looks like one of the best in Wisconsin, like the other routes on this amazing boulder. If you have not been on this you are severely missing out- its worth the drive alone. Pure sickness!

name: Left Corner Problem
description: Climb left side of boulder.  Start low and go for deep pocket.  Match on football pinch and hit baseball pinch with right hand,  Top-out

name: The Man-eater
description: Climb crack in middle of boulder.

name: Right Corner Problem
description: Start low and work your way right to nose feature on side of boulder.  From there, squeeze hard and climb up corner.

name: The Rock Biter
description: Starting low and right of the Man-eater crack, work your way up steep, powerful middle section of boulder and top-out same as Right Corner problem.

name: Around the Horn
description: Starts deep in the wide crack.  Rock below you on the ground and the face to the right are off.  Climb out of the crack and around the horn to top out.    Caution: the is a nice fin on the right side of the horn.  DO NOT USE THIS.  It's getting a bit loose and could probably break.

name: Crack Problem
description: Start with your left hand in the crack and your right hand on the crimp.  Use the crack for your feet and head all the way up, top out to the left.  After the crack the top out rock is gritty

name: Arete
description: Climb up corner of boulder.  Lots of variations to this route, SDS, use this hold or that, etc.

name: Easy Breezy
description: Climb up slab left of corner.

name: Easy Slab
description: Climb easy slab on the back side of Arete boulder.  This is the down climb for the other three problems on the boulder.

name: Face
description: Climb face right of corner.  SDS makes it maybe V5

name: Penguin Right
description: A few variations possible.  Decent hands and feet throughout until you lodge youself in the 'V' going to top out on Penguin boulder.  Wide reaches.

name: Problem 1
description: First thin face climb you see on wall.  Start with weird sidepulls and head up.

name: Problem 2
description: Climb thin face using any holds you can.  Very hard and has seen few repeats.

name: Problem 3
description: Climb face with good holds between Problem 2 and crack problem.

name: problem 4
description: Start on the same opening holds as TSD but instead of climbing up and left, climb straight up the wall on positive but reachy holds.

name: Project
description: Climb up face with obvious 1 inch hole at the 8 ft mark and climb up using whatever is within reach. This has been tried a bit but mainly just talked about getting sent.

name: Thin Crack
description: Climb thin crack on far side of wall

name: Turbo Sexaphonic Delight
description: Start on problem 3 and throw out left to small slopey crimp from good side-pull.(See Eric's beta bellow),and Top-out.  It helps to be a bit taller for this one.

Seemed like 5.8 climbing up to the roof with manky gear. The rock is a little sugary. Seemed the bolt was pretty solid and fairly new 10 years ago. It seemed 10+/11a to pull the roof but it was hard. 1 star. This area may get a little better with some traffic...

name: Slider
description: Start on the southwest corner of the boulder on the obvious low holds with left heel or toe hooked on the same shelf as the left hand. From this inverted position (The crux is moving from underneath the boulder onto the face) follow the pockets and rails on or near the corner to the lip, rock over and follow the low angle slab to the top.

name: Sonic Crack
description: Like Sonic Youth in Clear Creek Canyon, the Sonic Crack is a pretty unique feature.  It is different in the sense that it is an overhung dihedral/crack on an arete.  SDS on two good holds and move up using the crack only.  Bust out of the dihedral to a large bucket and bulbous feature.  Hand/foot match on the bulb and slap up top for the slopey top-out.  I would say best warm-up or beginner problem in the park, and would easily be worth 4 stars if it wasn't for the boulder right behind the problem. GET ON THIS!

name: Stack Boulder
description: Start low under boulder and figure your way up the middle line.  One or two power-moves but not too bad.

name: Beer Goggles
description: The first challenge is getting the feet up and establishing ones self on the slab, then climb the slab between the features created in the short seam(used in Tall Boy)in the center of the slab and the corner on the right. Top out over the crest at the top. Creates a delicate yet powerful experience.

name: Tall Boy
description: A beautifully exposed highball slab with the crux in the middle and good holds up high prove this to be a fantastic moderate problem. Follow the good holds up the center of the slab and top out just left or over the crest, avoid being drawn to the big dirty holds out left as they may break easily and draw you away from the good climbing. This may have been top roped or bouldered before me, but I have not heard of any activity prior to my efforts around 04', 05'.

name: Diggin' Deep
description: Start low under boulder.  Climb up an out the right corner using corner and small crimps of face.  Contrived but fun.

name: Slope Style
description: Hands on slopey rail and foot low in thin pocket, work way up through cool dishes.

name: Slope Style Right
description: Climb right side of face and top out right of slope style

name: Sloper Problem
description: Around the corner from slope style right, start low and climb up slopers to short finish.

name: SA FA
description: Pretty easy slab, nothing spectacular but lots to play around with

name: boulder traverse
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: half crack
description: This crack starts about 8 feet above the deck and ends before the main ledge on top.

name: Half German
description: Route climbs Slings and Things to large chicken head; sling the head and down climb to prominent center horizontal crack. Traverse entire front face on same crack; climb each vertical crack to get pro high enough to prevent cratering. Exit up right corner on George Bailey.

name: Left Crack
description: This crack is on the left of the main crack.

name: main crack
description: This is the ass crack of Central Wisconsin climbing.

name: Slings and Things
description: First climb on main face. Follow line around vegetation and up only using chicken heads and flakes for pro.

name: Trojan Man
description: A route smack dab between Slings and Things and Left Crack. I'm sure this has been climbed many times before, but I'm finally going to put a name on it. If you haven't climbed Main Crack do it and you'll learn how this route got its name...

name: Trojan man meets George Bailey
description: Ascend Slings and Things; lasso the large chicken head, descend to set of horizontal cracks on right, traverse right using large ledge for hand holds. Place protection in thin vertical cracks or extend across large ledge to use horizontal crack.  Takes cams and hexes nicely.

name: Beached Whale
description: Starting Underneath, work yourself up in a humping fashoin to beach your portly self on top.

name: topside traverse
description: Starting on the face head to the overhang and around to corner to top off

name: Back Corner
description: Climb up steep part of corner on Main boulder.  Left of the Main face.

name: Corner Bulge
description: Climb corner bulge of Main boulder.  Very much like HP 40.

name: Direct Line
description: A Classic!  Middle of steep face, start on jug and get high up to small crimp, establish and gun for the lip.  Super fun problem with stretchy moves.  Seen few accents.

name: Left of Corner Bulge
description: Just left of Corner bulge.  Start low and get up into dirty crack and top out.

name: Side-Pull
description: Left side of steep face of main boulder.  Stand start of good holds and keep bumping hands up side pulls and cracks in rock.  Another super fun problem.  SDS makes it V5+.

name: Traverse
description: Start at Direct line jug and traverse left across boulder into Side-Pull.  Pumpy!

name: Warm up
description: Climb up backside of Main bouder.  Easy warm-up.

name: Beached Whale
description: Climb short slopey bulge on boulder just right of House boulder.  Really fun and the top-out is the crux.

name: double scoop
description: Start with booth hands on sloper ledge and heel hook up to mantle and top out straight over middle of pinch side pulls

name: Down South Raven
description: Sit start with left hand gaston on large rail, right hand on good crimp.  Stand up with feet out right and then kick in a good right heel hook.  Continue straight up with a series of difficult bumps on small hands.

name: Hasty Retreat
description: Sit start on a great ledge. Hand/heel match and follow some bigger moves on jugs to the top. Gentle overhang. Got the name due to the log full of hornets nearby. Bailed shortly after the send.

name: Mammoth
description: You can stand start on good right hand side pull and left hand on arete and move up left side to top. For full value sit start on two lowest right side pulls and move up to right side pull from stand start.

name: Mammoth Project
description: Try and climb center line on small hands and feet.

name: Mushroom Roof
description: Up hill from house boulder on rim of bluff, the mushroom is a cool boulder that is steep with good holds.

name: Pi Way or the Highway
description: A really fun 15 foot tall near vert slab (like as close to vert as you can get). About 25 yards North of the house boulder with a slightly angled landing, you can't miss it. More technical than powerful so it is hard to rate, but the crimps are pretty small. Start in the middle of the wall pretty much right under the overhanging tree. Find a small two finger crimp/pocket and start with right hand in or around there, and left hand on a crimp about a foot or so to the left. Stand up. Get foot/feet higher and reach for sharp crimps up and to the right. Reposition feet, stand up and reach for a good crimp up and to the right, or a crimpy v thingamabob just to the left of that (be careful because that v thing wants to be broken). Reposition feet and go for the top. Be careful because some of the top out holds are thin and might break easily. This problem is great because from the start, you slowly work your way right and towards the jugs on the arete, but you don't end up using them until the top out when they make for good feet. Also, there could be a good line that starts on the left side of the slab.

name: Red Rocket Arete.
description: Climb short, north-west corner of House boulder.  Trickier than you would think.

name: sharks tooth
description: climb Crack with left hand and right hand on arete and face.

name: Sharp Lad
description: stand start. Follow sharp crimps to the top.

name: Warm up 1
description: On the west face of the House boulder.  Climb up left side.  Pretty easy and a good warm up.

name: Warm Up 2
description: On west face of House boulder, climb right side with fun features.  Great warm up.

name: Warm Up Center SDS
description: Start sitting with right hand on undercling/rail and left hand on a solid roundish crimp out to the left. Put feet anywhere below the rail, pull up, and swing/lunge up to a sweet left hand crimp. Reposition feet and bump right hand up rail and/or to good hold above the rail (or any of the ok but not as good holds). Find a good foot and have fun the rest of the way up.    This start has probably been done before but I thought that it was a natural and fun way to start. It adds a couple of good moves and some difficulty to a great warm up route, so I thought it deserved to be listed separately. You can sit start the left or right side of the face of the boulder too, but those starts don't add much to the routes. This center one definitely does and it is really the only good way to sit start in the center of the boulder.

name: Warm Up Crack
description: Start on warm up 2 and pull around the arete to gain the slabby crack.

name: Warmup 3
description: Start on lower left and traverse up and right on good holds.

name: Kutcher Krack
description: Pretty good off-finger crack. Originally done as a boulder problem but I led it on gear.

name: Kutchers Butt Krack aka K.B.K.
description: Climb crack to top

name: Sidewinder
description: Nice outer corner route using holds on both sides. Would recommend top rope since this is an area starting to show chossy areas.  The route is solid and complete; typical chossy top.

name: Blood Bath
description: Lots of blood shed on this one from a number of folks.Start sitting, match in an undercling as for Hocus Pocus.  Trend right through the face, the crux probably being a hard shouldery move in the middle.  The end has a few methods to it, the easiest one for me used a knee bar.

name: Can't hang
description: Just up hill from Project.  Scramble up to large ledge, problem is tall featured face to the right.  Another really fun but tricky problem.  Holds have changed over the years, so I'm not sure on current conditions.

name: Chaos
description: Problem starts with a bomber ledge for feet off to the right of start hands. Thrutch out left to increasingly good crimps. From there head up to increasingly better holds to top out.

name: Cottonmouth
description: First striking crack as you enter the climb up the east hill behind the main cliff; opposite side from Venom and Timber Rattler climbs.    Great crack to start the climb and then face and thin finger crack to finish the top section.

name: Diamondback
description: Great starter crack; takes cams, wired nuts, and hexes nicely.    There's an overhanging oak tree that aids in a top rope set-up to keep your rope off the rock.    Climb lower crack left of Cottonmouth and mount the large ledge, step around right and continue corner crack.  When the crack becomes too large for pro, finish the last ten feet on the right face.

name: Dicey For A Deuce
description: Start down and left on pockets.  Move up and right to the ledge, traverse right to corner and topout straight up.

name: Dicey For A Tres
description: Start on two pockets on the right side of the face. Make a long throw up left to a good sidepull.  Traverse right to corner and topout straight up.

name: The Fun Route
description: Just left of the Project.  Climb corner with fun features and good top-out.

name: Hocus Pocus
description: Starts on descent holds and moves up into no-mans land with horrible feet.

name: In Decent Exposure
description: Start on the sloping ledge and traverse to the left. From there make a bigger bump to a jug and use smaller holds to a sloppy mantle. Beautiful views, but a nervous punt could land you off the top of the bluff.

name: Jump for Joy
description: Starts with left hand on the good sloped ledge and right hand in good slot/crimp.  Goes left hand to a decieving slopey sidepull. Then throw to a bomber slot/jug. Keep it together for the topout.

name: The Perch
description: Sit start on obvious edges and climb straight up the gently overhanging face.

name: Project Cave
description: From east side of bluff walk south past project wall.  Head up to the rim of bluff and look for boulders laying on top of each other.  Climb out from the cave here is the project.  Pads and spotters needed for sure.

name: Smack Down
description: On the right side of the Chaos wall, start standing left hand in a gaston pocket, and right hand on a good part of the arete out right.  Do a couple powerful bumps and a fun jump to the top.

name: Anniversary
description: Half crack leading to a challenging crux move to gain the horizontal ledge for foot placement. Continue up and left on sloped friction ledges to gain final finish straight up nice spaced hand and foot placements.  I solo'ed this on a petzl shunt and top roped it five days later with a friend.  The name derives from my ascent on my parents 58th wedding anniversary on August 24th.

name: Black Hornet
description: This route coined the name from a hornets nest that had to be removed half way up (half way down on rappel), and from the remains of the black charred tree trunk at the start of the climb. This is a fun zig-zag crack with lay-backs and jamming. The last ten feet are slightly overhung and finishes on good hand holds.

name: Block off the Old Chip
description: Sit start with left hand in a two finger pocket and right on a sharp edge. Follow left hand side pulls and right hand jugs to the top.

name: Chossoholic
description: Chossy crack climb. I went to OS this one day but bailed when the choss started to consume me.

name: Criminal Mastermind
description: Sit start on large holds. Move up to thin sidepull, get your feet up and huck for another large hold, move up and grab arete on right, gain crimp or sidepull and make large move to top.

name: Dihedral Dance
description: Interesting tight dihedral climbing.

name: Easy Arete
description: Between two bluffs in saddle look for vertical boulder with easy climbing.  Good warm up.

name: Fists and Fury
description: Old school cool fist crack. Solo up easy terrain then plug bomber cams in a hand crack. The crack gets wider and harder as you go up. Fists to arm-bar.

name: Lupara Bianca
description: Start with your left hand on the clean arete, and right with a low, obvious undercling.  The opening move is the distinct crux.  Climb the striking arete, finishing on an obvious ledge.  If you jump start the first move it is a fun 4/5.  A groove chimney left is not a bad way to downclimb.

name: Massasauga
description: Great crack climbing with an exposed top section.  Climb starts with an off-width crack leading to a shelf.  Step across to the mid-section on smaller finger cracks and limited foot holds. Make the reach to the bucket hold and finish on the top latticed face. Step up onto the final boulder and shout "MASSASAUGA"!

name: Pigmy
description: Upper tier chimney climb with three inner cracks. Great beginner lead climb.

name: Slab Crack
description: Excellent hand jams lead to a sloping top-out on jugs.

name: Slither
description: Nice balance climb on thin holds leading to lay-backs on big sloper jugs; up the left arete face and stepping across to finish the blocky top face.

name: Snake Eyes
description: Short crack to the right and in the corner from Snakes on a Plain. Short jam crack with some overhang angle in the middle.

name: Snake Pit
description: Route starts by mounting the overhang and clambering to the ledge as in Massasauga.  Step to the right above the long overhang and mount the exposed wall and climb nose to the top.

name: Snakes on a Plain
description: Overhanging finger crack leading to a loose chock stone, finishing on nice holds, leading to the bus stop on top. I used the left corner arete to aid in the climb. Turkey vultures like to perch on top in the warm fall sun.

name: Solo Crack
description: Nice crack line with many stances and pro.

name: Speaker of the House
description: Start as for Speechless, on the left side of the arete, with an undercling for the left hand and the arete for the right.  Climb the left side of the arete.  For the record, Speechless moves right around the arete about half way up.

name: Speechless
description: Starts with good holds and move up to a large blank section. The right arete will help here. Strong and burely. Holds can be seen, but havent figured out how to get them or use them.

name: Timber Rattler
description: Excellent short route accented with a mix of short pulls,lay backs, balancing, and cracks.  Would be a great second pitch to Solo, Anniversary, Black Hornet, or Slab Cracks. Named for the timber rattlesnake found in the area and the dead pine felled off route face. TIMMMMMBERRRR!

name: Upper Tier Dihedral
description: Excellent dihedral climbing with a finger crack.

name: Marshmallow
description: Start from a sit matched on an obvious low rail.  Climb left up the arete through thin holds and tricky moves then mantle at the apex.  The seam behind the arete doesn’t come into play until the end.

name: Sawyer Jumps!
description: Plant your foot and jump for the nice sloper above, smear and layback to the top.

name: Sawyer's Climb
description: Tough sit start to an easy top-out.

name: Sawyer's Mantle
description: Nice boulder problem with true mantle.

name: Weekend Whipper
description: Sit start below the short but aesthetic arete, with a slot for the left on the arete and and edge on the arete just above.  With some difficulty establish on the wall and gain the sweet sloper above and mantle.  A sit start to Sawyer Jumps!

name: Blue suede shoes
description: Start on same left slot as Graceland and move right on up buldge

name: Graceland
description: This is a super fun problem. Start on good left hand slot and right under cling and move up to two left pockets and slam dunk the good upper ledge and move up to sloper top out.

name: Star destroyer left
description: Start on best hold in center and move left with worsening right heels.

name: Star destroyer right
description: Start with both hands near last good hold near center and campus up to heal hook and move right on lip to end of lip and then up and over.

name: Take me to your sloper
description: Stand or jump to two decent slopers and hold on, continue up and either traverse out right or drop down. A full topout is doable but hornets and suspect rock make it very unappealing.

name: Trust the sand
description: easy and fun warm-up with a cool jug at the top.

name: Summit Tunnel Route
description: Basically the easiest climbing/spelunking route to the top.      Boulder up to the small tunnel on the south face of the bluff.  Squeeze through tunnel and emerge on the north side of the bluff.  Ascend ramp on your right to top of bluff.  This will deposit you on the "summit plateau" of the East side of Shiprock.    To be sure you actually summit, locate the large boulder near the east end of the summit plateau.  Attain the summit by scrambling up the West end of this boulder and walking all the way to its Eastern tip.  If you have not done this you have not summited Shiprock.  Warning: the "summit" may cause extreme vertigo.

name: A.D.I.D.A.S.
description: If you park at the pullout nearest the overlook but not at the overlook and take the trail down it is about 100 yards past Particle Man.  There are two routes in that section, its the route on the left.

name: Everything Zen
description: After reaching the first bolt, the climbing is thin and sustained until the end. The thin holds make this a slow pumpy lead.

name: Freehander
description: Sustained route, some long reaches. No real distinct crux. Move left after the last bolt onto great pinches, then finish out with a pumpy/stemming anchor clip. Use caution when clipping the anchors as the fall does not look very forgiving.      After putting up a TR on this route (in the cleaning process) the first ascentionists were approached by a hiker. He asked what they were up to, and they replied "climbing".  He looked at the ropes and harnesses, shrugged and said something to the effect of "thats nothing, a few years back I freehanded that". Thus it came to be known as Freehander.

name: Golden Shower of Hits
description: Climb up to big pocket then to the right on crimps. Crux comes as you move your way out of the vertical terrain, and onto the slab.

name: Lather Boy
description: The start moves up through a unique horn/jug, to a crux at the first bolt. The moves afterward become easier, but due to the bulgy nature of the route it actually becomes pumpy. The routes crux comes at the top and includes surmounting a slopey bulge, and a low angle undercling in a large hueco. Cool route, well bolted.

name: Let Your Pimpness Shine
description: Excellent route, with fun flowing moves. The is a crux low just past the first bolt, and one high just after the last bolt. Clipping the anchors can be a tad pumpy as well.

name: Randalls One Trick Pony
description: Really cool moves, awesome lie back on a protruding flake halfway up. Sweet route. At the top you can stay on face and make it 5.10 or move to the right for a slightly easier finish on the top slab.

name: Trophy Husbands
description: Good holds separated by thin powerful moves. The route culminates with a thin slab top-out after a rest in  a large hueco.

name: Wehrmacht Stable
description: Fairly sustained 5.8/9 to a crux before the anchors. Staying left of the bolts is easier and going right is a little harder.

name: Yeti Traverse
description: Not a bad route at all, fun traverse, good feet.  A little run out.      Here is the Beta   1. Clip first Bolt on Free Hander   2. Clip first Bolt on Everything Zen    3. Clip Second bolt on A.D.I.D.A.S (I think)    4. Clip 3rd bolt on A.D.I.D.A.S (take off second bolt to prevent drag or run it out to here.    5. Clip 4th bolt on A.D.I.D.A.S (Stay Right on crimps)   6. Clip bolt across on 'let your pimpness shine'    7. Clip last bolt on lather boy, finish off on crux of lather boy.      I thought the route was fun, it did not feel like a lot of drag either, fall may hurt...  The crux is between #6,#7 of the description.

name: Bling Bling
description: Line of bolts on the right hand side of wall to chain anchors. Stay right of the flake after second bolt...it's all there on slabbish climbing.

name: Bukaki
description: First bolt is a little high but easy climbing up to that on good ledges...This route has 2 crux sections and is well protected for those moves. Be a solid 5.9 climber to lead this route.

name: Donkey Punch
description: This route is located about halfway between the Mushroom wall and the Meader wall. The wall has 3 sets of top anchors and Donkey Punch is the bolted route in the middle. The rating has been changed due to a hold breaking.

name: Drill Ho
description: Follow quarry drill hole. Short but fun.

name: Powerhouse of the Cell
description: This powerful and bouldery route will have you fighting to get past the crux section. Climb beneath the horizontal roof and peel the lip to encounter some difficult climbing. After the fourth bolt trend left and finish up on "Ride the Donkey". A nice addition to the wall

name: Priapism
description: Sport line on the left end of the Donkey punch wall. Easy climbing to hard 5.10 crux up high.

name: Ride the Donkey
description: Climb up the corner between D.P and D.H., though multiple overhangs. Finish by climbing the final two bolts on DH.

name: Bump and Grind
description: Start with your left hand on the circled ledge, right hand out to the right at about eye level.  Put your left foot below in the undercut area and move your right foot out into a heel hook.  From there, bump you’re right hand up then move your feet up and throw your right hand up for the jug and top out.

name: Dynamite Traverse
description: Top Ledge is off limits for traverse. Pumpy, cryptic, and blind. Stand start on ledge of Dynamite Boulder.

name: Dynarête
description: A sit start, with good low hands and your left knee folded up towards your chest. Left hand moves to around the corner, right moves to a big pinch, right foot to a ledge. stand up and its an easy top out after that.

name: Illuminati Dynosaurs
description: Simple problem, start with hands in the 2 best defined pockets and jump for the top

name: TNT Shuffle
description: Another dyno, but this time with a little more work on the set up for the jump. In this problem the left hand starts in the pocket for the right hand on Illuminati Dynosaurs, and the right works up the arête before the dyno.

name: Astral Plane
description: Route climbs right of the Vine Street Dihedral with 7 bolts and a chain anchor. The crux has 2 options being straight up the corner or traverse right onto Astro boy for a few face moves. We protected with good movement

name: Astro boy
description: Face climb to the left of the inside corner crack.

name: Boogie
description: Start just to the left of George's warm up, and climb up and to the left. Stay low while moving left then move up at the highest point on the boulder

name: Double Overhang
description: Climb up center of wall to 2' overhang, move right and climb up diagonal undercling crack through a water stain. 5.9+ if you pull the overhang.

name: George's Warm up
description: Climb up the right arete

name: Particle Man
description: Drop rope down from V-notch on the large table-sized block on top. Climb up plumb line. Chicken out right to The S--- Stain.

name: Shapeshifter
description: New route to the right of Particle Man. Need some cleaning but climbs well with big holds and ledges. Chain anchor with fixed hooks.

name: Vine Street
description: Follow inside corner, hand and finger sized...astro boy is the face on the left of the corner...for newbies this is often the second route done at the bluff    left side of dihedral is solid, right side shattered

name: Wombat Combat
description: This climb is loaded with enjoyable moves and nice jugs the whole way. Just when you think it's over the crux will pop up with a nice deadpoint. This line is a great warm-up for the area!

name: Ultimate Hombre
description: Only line of bolts on this wall. Lots of right handed clips...stays left of bolts. Kinda slabby at start.

name: Grand Slam
description: Send all the routes on Grandad Bluff in a day.

name: Meader Wall Slam
description: Send all of the routes on Meader Wall in a session.

name: Patent Pending Speed Lap
description: Boasting the only known sub-zero degree ascent (G Forge, B Ingman, and T Melin (2007)) and the only known naked ascent (G Parker (2009) at Grandad Bluff, Patent Pending (5.10d) also hosts a friendly speed climbing challenge.    Times are traditionally counted on toprope. Start behind the log and finish when the chains are slapped.   HistoryBen Ingman: 0:43Colin Treiber: 0:40Travis Melin: 0:38Ben Ingman: 0:36Travis Melin: 0:33Travis Melin: 0:30.1Travis Melin: 0:24.5

name: Big Man on Campus
description: Not a standard route for the wall... as in not sustained. Well defined crux at the small roof (15 foot mark) featuring double, wide horizontal pinches and a stab to a decent hold. Great 5.11 climbing to the anchors.

name: Brown Reason to Live
description: Tough route -- very sustained.  Has gotten easier over the years as holds have broken.

name: Cohesion
description: Bouldering traverse of the bottom of the Meader wall on ledge system. Good fun. Usually done left to right then back again. Keep going until you're pumped or bored.

name: Hawaiian Bill
description: Best route at Grandads Bluff.  Fun, powerful moves - my best onsight.

name: Macroputz
description: Line left of microputz. The line of weakness starts at the 1st bolt on microputz and traverses up and left to webbing anchors on bolts. The route is still dirty/loose and could use some T.R. action to clean it up.

name: The Man In The Black Pajamas
description: Sustained, long, and progressively more powerful pulls on thin holds quickly lead into a burly undercling, and finally a crux stab at a good pocket.  All this made more exciting as the crux throw is made with the bolt below your feet...(dont worry its a good fall:). Rest up in the cave at the top, as there is still a slopey V2 move to get the anchors clipped.

name: Micro Putz
description: Furthest right route. Also the shortest. Starts on top of the flat top hill. Being the easiest of the bolted routes at the park, it has been the site of several gumby epics. Climbing outside is not the same as the gym, even if the routes are bolted.

name: Nihilist
description: Easy 5.10 climbing leads to a rest ledge at the second bolt. Take a good rest cause its business from here to the top. Progressively more difficult pulls lead you through a hueco to some excellent crystal pockets and finally to easier terrain at the top. Dont let this fool you though, most everyone falls from indecision just past the last bolt. Many equally magninal feet and crimps will surely have you wondering....what was the sequence again?    Originally graded 5.12d this route has seen a lot of change due to weathering, general use,  and perhaps "aggressive cleaning", making past difficult moves far easier. Nowadays this is one of the first .12's done by Lax locals.

name: Patent Pending
description: Starts on the far left side of the bluff. Follow first four bolts to some big huecos. The climb is pretty straightforward to here. The next couple of moves between the fourth and fifth bolts are very sequency. Look for a crystal pocket just below the fifth bolt. After clipping the fifth bolt continue along through a cave to the sixth bolt and the anchor. Watch for loose rock.

name: Pork Tornado
description: Another phenomenal route on the Meader wall at Grandads Bluff.  Vertical to overhanging. Very powerful climb, perhaps harder than Brown Reason?

name: Alpine Gin
description: Small exposed face with a well defined ledge. Start far right on the ledge above the small evergreen. Traverse left heal hooking your way through. Top out at the jutout. Crux is at the end of the traverse moving into the upclimb.

name: Birth Canal
description: Start on chossy sloper rail and reach for an amazing 3 finger pocket then make your way to the canal. Suck your belly in and squeeze through the canal. Be careful of your head while falling

name: Botched Crucifixion
description: Start low in shallow crack system and make big move to a jug. Continue up obvious slopey jugs to the top. With some cleaning this route may become easier

name: Close Quarters
description: start with a big move up to the jug, then make powerful moves out right. Set a high heel and top out.

name: Countrytime Lemonade
description: Start on the right side of the boulder in the big pockets and your feet on the pebbles on the underside of the rock. Heel hook and power your way to the two crimps above and top out.

name: Joy Ride
description: Start on lowest set of jugs and make your way up to the fun and commiting top out! Super chill with an amazing view of the Mississippi Valley

name: Loose Lips Sink Ships
description: Start on the same hold as Countrytime Lemonade and then traverse left across the lip. Catch the jug far out left and top out.

name: Pimple Popper (Project)
description: Work through a fallen boulder covered in small sandy dimples. No defined good holds.

name: Raccoon Reach Around (project)
description: Start on left side of face and move right making powerful moves with a couple left hand heel matches. Jug in the middle of routes seems suspect use with caution.

name: Rosie Traverse
description: Sit start on right side of boulder on good crimp rail and then traverse left. Top out at about the middle on the boulder

name: Three Strikes
description: Start on the left side of the boulder following the obvious edges to the right. When you reach the top traverse to the point and top out.

name: Tit for tat
description: Start left low as possible on lip and right on jug. Work your way up the lip and tip out lip to the left. Any jugs to the right other than start hold are off

name: To be Announced
description: Match on jug to the right of blue rectangle. Pull right and follow crack system

name: Cockblocker
description: This route is the one on the right. Still new and dirty but a nice route.

name: Polish Route
description: Obvious crack in the middle of the wall. This route is now bolted, though it has been lead with trad gear. There are ample gear placements,but the quality of rock in the whole area is not solid enough to make any safe, trustworthy trad placement. Thus the bolts.

name: Seven Bolts for Betty
description: Middle bolted route on the Mushroom wall. Excellent route!

name: The Stalker
description: Left route on the wall. Pretty tricky; can be made a little easier by going right at the roof.

name: V Randall
description: Cool route with a short mantle crux just above the roof. A little crumbly at the bottom, but will quickly be solid with a little traffic.

name: Alone in the Orchard
description: An overhanging traverse with possible topout onto a ledge on the right.

name: Combat Engineer
description: Crux comes immediately after clipping the second bolt.

name: Dismal Tide
description: Hard to nail down the exact crux...probably after the second bolt...this route is somewhat sustained.

name: Ozzy traverse
description: Traverse length of wall...    Distinct routes can be found if you stay 6", 18" or 36" off the ground    Is a little harder than Meader traverse, but easier than the addidas wall traverse

name: Randyland
description: Meandering on smaller holds inbetween larger ledges is how this one goes. Feels a little off balance the whole way.

name: Uptown Bar
description: Some may find this hard to start but some good edges lead to a good ledge to clip the first bolt. The crux comes after the second bolt which tends to slightly overhanging the rest of the way to the anchors.

name: Psycho left?
description: First 5 feet are a bit chossy. Follow the closely space bolts more or less straight up to the anchor. A balancy crux comes around bolt 4. Fun.

name: Psychobitch
description: A 90 degree change from most of the area routes, few horizontal crimps here. Side pulls from old blast scars mark the crux at about 2/3 height.   Ends with some slopers after a mantle onto a ledge.

name: Quarry Master
description: Crux right off the platform starting ledge, 8 bolts plus chain anchor for lowering or top-roping. Great route for beginner leaders or starting climbers as it is well bolted.

name: Burned at the Stake
description: A very bouldery route. 5.10 moves to a high first bolt just before a rest. The second bolt is very hard to hang draw on. The meat of the route is a very short very powerful/bouldery 7 move sequence.

name: Strongest Man Alive
description: Furthest left route on the wall, just right of the fist sized crack. Features some fun commiting moves.

name: Warm-up Route
description: This is the furthest right route at the cauldron. Although the first bolt is 15 feet up, the route is PG13 for the glass on the large easy ledges that lead up to the first bolt. A better variation (5.10) takes the pockets on the painted face to the left, and then up to the ledge. The bolts follow an obvious right leaning crack up the face from there.

name: Yeast of Burden
description: This route would be classic at any Wisconsin crag. Climb first 2 bolts to an OK rest, a couple crux lie back moves take you to the left and up on crimpers to a jug just below the anchors. The real tough guys clip off the ledge just above the anchors.

name: Aarons slab
description: Start at the bottom and work up and left on the slab.

name: Anthony's folly
description: Sit-start laybacking the right arete and continue upwards.

name: Anthony's kryptonite
description: Start with matched hands on lowest ledge and work up and left into the easy overhanging arete, top-out. A bit contrived but adds some fun moves.

name: Arete problem
description: Start on the arete just to right of sex muscle. continue up using the overhanging juggy arete

name: The Black Spot
description: Start on the large ledge down and left on the overhang, continue up on edges and gun for the lip. Take the lip around the corner and up to the top.

name: Blinded by the light
description: SDS on edges, move up and right and figure out a way to reach the good sloper jug. Try and climb this early in the day or you'll probably discover the name sake of the climb.

name: Blue Balls
description: Sit-start with with hands on the side pull and high feet. Cruise while staying on the face, another decent warm-up.

name: The Cesspool
description: Start with feet on the block below and hands on low left crimp and right sloper, work your way to the top. Would get more stars if not for lowball sit start.

name: Cletus
description: Sit start on the large crack on the right side of the boulder. Follow the crack and jugs to the top. The last few feet are a bit harder but all in all its an easy send.

name: Hillbilly Highball / Mosstown
description: Start on the horizontal crack on the biggest face of the Hillbilly Highball Boulder between the arete on the left and the big ledge on the right. Stay just to the right of the arete for most of the climb. Skip the jug on the right about two thirds up and everything on the volcanic looking bulge on the arete except for the pinch right at the top of it.  Top-out delicately on either of the two slopey holds at the top.  Crux is right at the start but it just gets scarier from their. Watch out for wildlife in the sideways finger pockets.

name: Jebediah
description: Short little finger crack and an arete, three moves or so. It gets a little tougher if you climb just the crack.

name: Moonshine
description: Sit start with hands on the obvious rails, left foot around the arete on a mossy chip almost all the way under the boulder, and right foot on the face. Bump up into one of the many pockets and follow the left side of the face to the top out.   *The crack and large pockets on the right hand side of the face are OFF**

name: Muckraker
description: Extremely crimpy route.  There are likely better holds buried beneath the moss but I figured it looked cool that way so only unearthed some crimps.  Only what is on the mossy face is on and anything else (to either side of the mass of moss or on the edges of it) is off.  If my memory is right there is only one hold (a microjug) after the start that isn't a crimp until the topout.  Start on two microjugs beneath horizontal crack - move up to edge directly beneath crack and work the crimps to the topout which consists of a big edge, a sharp little crimp/pinch, and a crimp higher on the little face perpendicular to and on top of Muckraker.

name: Poop Jokes and Jesus
description: Start low on a horizontal finger crack and a juggy shelf. Work you way up to a balancy crimp at the crux before you top out. Be careful not to lose your balance as just around the corner of this boulder there is a shear drop about 20 feet.

name: Pootie Tang
description: Sit-start with hands on the obvious lower left feature. This and Blue balls are decent warm-ups.

name: Red Storm Rising
description: Red Storm Rising surfs up the side of one of the biggest boulders at Area 51. It starts on the far left side and works all the right to the apex of the boulder and tops out for a "true" ascent.     This route is very crimpy, with some sweet body tension and heel hooks. It never gets very tall, unless you consider the walk off top out.     It generally gets very dirty from all the trees around so a good brush and some elbow grease are essentials.

name: Rest in pieces
description: Work your way up the good seam and use the right arete to get to the lip. Then execute hair-raising mantle to finish.

name: Sex Muscle
description: Sds with matched hands on large ledge and make your way left and then up to finish out on the top right corner. A hard extension starting around the corner might be possible. Would be better if not for the talus close to the left feet.

name: Sex Muscle corner project
description: This is an old project Alex and Anthony spent some time working. SDS in the small scrunched corner roof and find a way to climb into Sex Muscle. Bit of a squeeze job but it would add a couple of hard moves.

name: Sex muscle slab project
description: Work some wizardry and pull onto the slab face, top-out.

name: The Thumbercling
description: Sit start with good left and right hands. Place a right heel toe cam and move up the face. Might be a bit height dependent.

name: The "Right" Touch
description: The route starts out with a 5.10 start up to the first bolt staying on the right side. Then proceeds in becoming about a 5.11 crimps (the holds are there, look for them to the right again) to the 2nd bolt.  Then the crux is between the 2nd bolt to the 3rd which is a high 11 or low 12 move (depends on your technique)which involves sidepulls/crack/flake and a thumbpress right above the 2nd bolt to the overhang dish which turns up the pump and setting your body from the right side and moving to the left of the last bolt and using a heel hook on the dish to pull up to the ledge under the anchors.  The route is technical to start and then gets pumpy in the end with a rewarding heel hook which you can put your toe into the top part of the roof and it secures the foot/heel to pull you up to the anchors.  This route has been completed by 5'3 to 6'0 so all heights seem to be able to complete this route.  Just remember to look for the holds and STAY OFF THE CRACK the bolts are too far to stretch and the swing will not be fun if you think you can just extend over from the crack.

name: 5.6 dihedral
description: Good beginner route in the ledgy corner.

name: Backseat B-lay
description: This short route follows a series of bouldery moves on positive holds to a slightly overhung bulge.  Using the juggy pockets and good crimps to get over the bulge is super fun.  The big moves and interesting holds are reminiscent of a route in the Red!

name: Balls on a Kite
description: Starts on solid hands, transitions to cruxy vertical crack system.  Enjoy the easy overhang until you reach 2 deep horizontal cracks which may require some dynamic moves.

name: Bio-Degradable
description: Start 5 feet right of arete, 10 feet left of Organic Matter. Climb to base of tree, pass to the right and follow crack to the top. Stay left of the chimney with the pine tree, making use of the arete and toping-out inline with the arete.

name: Booze Pigs
description: Booze Pigs is the bolted route on the far left of Zig-zag Crack wall.

name: Cascadia
description: Cascadia is between Swiss cheese on the left and manic depression on the right. If it was raining it would look like a cascading water fall. Finish above manic depression. Be careful of dead tree on the left. The crux is about 2/3 the way up.

name: Curse of the Drill
description: The route starts approximately 5 ft left of "End".  Climb low angle start then pull bulge on good holds.  Work up the face more or less in line with the bolts.  At the over hanging flakes, look right then climb up and left of small tree to the anchors.

name: Drink to Forget
description: You already walked over here - why not? Earn major style points gaining an initial ledge, then continue up a dihedral.

name: Drink to Puke
description: A route named in honor of the D.L.F.A guys that developed much of the Hollow. An obvious face climb that turns into a horizontal roof crack about 20 feet up. A series of long moves to good edges until the roof section. Traverse right on underclings/crack system to get to jugs above the roof. A fun lead, get on it! Pics to come.

name: Drink to Remember
description: A ledgy slab (careful with the loose blocks on the left) guards a steep bit, a finger crack, and an acute dihedral.

name: End of the Innocence
description: This is the first route you will come across after passing the south end of the bluff.    Gain the first bolt after 15 ft of easy climbing. A longer draw on the first bolt will hang better. Climb the increasingly steepening face (slab-near vertical) right of the bolts using horizontal seams and face holds.  The route finishes with an interesting lie-back/undercling move to gain ledges right of the anchors.

name: End of the Innocence variation
description: Climb to the left of the bolts on "End of the Innocence", right between "End" and "Curse". Avoid all holds on "Curse of the Drill". Move straight up on crimpy holds and small feet. Climb straight through overhang and work your way back into the finish of "End of the Innocence" finishing with the same layback/undercling to top it off.

name: Generation Gap
description: Generation Gap climbs the blunt arete just left of Swiss Cheese. The route offers a very powerful, bouldery start to progressively easier climbing. Stick clip the first bolt.     Begin "The Gap" by matching the patina edge/feature on the wall above the drop-off. Shorter climbers may have to stack some stones to reach this hold (stacking too many stones might negate the crux, however). Do a pull-up to place a foot on the wall and make powerful moves up to the second bolt. After a couple of pesky hard moves near the third bolt, romp up the less-steep arete to the top. Top out on the ledge and traverse a few feet  right to the chains on Swiss Cheese.

name: Her Spidery Chamber
description: The rocks to the right and behind this route are off. Start on large under-clings and go right as they turn into side-pulls. Move up into a gaston and crossover into a mono pocket, the crux. Move out left to a Swiss Cheese like hold and continue up the face following a small crack. Using the rocks to the right/behind the route is a much easier variation, probably 5.6.

name: High School Romancer
description: Mantle a ledge, reach around the corner and dead point for the next ledge. Follow the corner to the top. Some fun moves.

name: Lady Patina
description: Climb on jugs past the choss then jump right into a low crux which is well protected with a high clip. Resist the urge to use the 5.5 crack out to the right to keep the ascent pure and the enjoyment at full value! Continue up the bolt line into the beautiful patina features that seem to be sculpted by the big man upstairs. If only these thin crimps would continue all the way to heaven.  This being the first route you encounter upon arriving, as well as being one of the tallest at the crag makes this climb a great addition to the hollow. The tricky crux and steep, thin face climbing provides a stout onsight opportunity for stronger climbers, as well as a great top rope project for beginners. Happy sending!

name: Left Side Dihedral (aka Corner Crack)
description: this akward climb is a bit dirty and tastes of pine needles. fun little ditty and is only recomended to be climbed once in you life time.     you can finish/bail on top of the 5.6 to the right and rap off the large pine or continue up to the top, with two more moves.

name: Manic Depression
description: Locate the wall to the right of the classic Swiss Cheese. Manic Depression climbs up past four bolts on the left side of the wall. The route is steeper than it looks from the ground, and it's a bit less tweaky than other routes in the area.     Stick clip the first bolt. Start with difficult, thin balancy moves to gain a stance on the right below the second bolt. Then move slightly left, past a cool sequence up to the third bolt. Continue straight up to the top past another bolt en route to the anchors.     The left crack/weakness is definitely off, though when climbing the bolt line, these holds don't seem that tempting.

name: Pagan Rituals
description: Pagan lies immediately to the right of the classic Zig-zag crack. The route is difficult and sustained, with varying climbing. It starts by using medium edges to balance onto the initial bulge and attain the horizontal flake a the lip of the giant roof. From there hard pulls on small edges take the climber over the roof and into the hanging dihedral above. Here, some tenuous counter-pressure moves leading to another hard pull on a small side-pull pocket and undercling deposit the climber at a decent hold and a chance to grab a dab of chalk. After this brief "rest" the climber heads out of the dihedral to the right and follows a few more difficult crimps eventually ending in the upper crack of Zig-zag crack.    All-told it is fun route with interesting movement.

name: Penitent Crack
description: Penitent offers fun climbing. For the first half of the climb it's easy moving. When you reach the main crack about 20 ft from the top, that's where it gets a bit harder. The crack offers good finger and hand jams.

name: Pine Tree Crack
description: All I really remember about this route is that it was relatively moderate and across the canyon from most of the climbing

name: PWB Arete
description: This route climbs up the well-defined arete on the opposite side of the canyon from Swiss Cheese. If you look closely, you will find the scatched-in initials "PWB" near the first bolt. You will also see a shallow hole from what looks to have been a  long-ago aborted bolting attempt.     Anyway, climb up to the first bolt. A .75-1" cam might offer some protection getting to the bolt, but really the climbing isn't that bad. Then climb delicate, slabby, rock past four bolts to the tree. Top out on the ledge and clip the anchors.    PWB offers very cool, thought-provoking climbing up a beautiful feature on perfect rock. If it was longer it would certainly warrant more stars.

name: The Repentance Crack
description: Dirty, dirty, dirty. The line follows the crack system about 5 feet left of "The Curse of the Drill." The crack terminates near the anchors of "Curse," as well. The crux was high off the ground, probably around 10 feet from the top with a lieback. Either that or just figuring out the gear. Definitely kept me on my toes. Did I mention it was dirty?

name: Sex Weed
description: A delicate slab leads to a bouldery overhung seam. Climb the over hanging crack, and place good but small gear. The crack leads to an exciting finish topping out on a shelf. Protects and climbs extremely well. Get on it!

name: Strong Faith
description: A short strong climb located on the South side of an independent block. The climb feels similar to the Pine Tree Crack. It has a strong bouldery start, probably the crux, going up the crack and getting a little easier on the top.    Josh Olson and I originally projected this climb in summer 2011. I'm hoping more people get a chance to try this climb out and let us know what you think?

name: Strongman's Cooldown
description: I'm calling this climb the strongman's cooldown because the climb is just to the left of the hardest climbs at the Hollow. Most strongmen who climb those routes probably would never bother with this climb--or they soloed it as down climb or access route.    I'm putting it up because I think it's a good easy climb and trad lead. I never noticed this climb before this spring and when I saw it I grabbed some gear and climbed it on the spot. In its current state its more of an adventure climb then a beginning climber would like--its dirty and there are some weak rocks. I'm hoping to get it some more traffic and clean it up a bit. It was a fun easy climb with some nice dihedral moves and no real crux (consensus from three climbers was 5.5-5.6).

name: Sunset Ascent
description: Starts left around corner from Pine Tree Crack. Different style of climbing from many of the bolted routes at The Hollow. I believe it is harder than PWB Arete, But Easier than Pine Tree, so the rating could use some input.

name: Swiss Cheese
description: Swiss Cheese was the first bolted line one encountered upon entering the canyon proper (before all of the new bolting).  Generally speaking there is a pile of cheater stones at the bottom of the route to assist in the direct variation.  The stones are there to overcome the overhang, and avoid tumbling into the hollow/cave below.  These cheater stones may be considered a sage tactic by some, and in my humble opinion are more sketchy than pulling the move outright.  The actual route starts in the corner (getting up the corner and over to the first bolt is the crux) to the right and traverses into the route.  The route proper is slightly off angle and follows a line of great patina holds, that seem to define the phrase "great patina holds" - up the beautiful sandstone wall.  This is a great route, especially for someone learning to lead.

name: Sy-STEM of a Hollow
description: A great addition for beginners and can vary from 5.7 up time a 5.9 depending how you choose to climb this.  The 5.7 way involves using the wall behind.  After that, choose your own adventure.  Great spots to clip and permadraws at top to make climbing and top roping this route fun and easy to clean.  Enjoy

name: Turkish Revenge
description: Turkish Revenge is the bolted line just left of Zig-zag Crack. According to first ascentionist Dave Groth it is 5.13a if one avoids the crack, and climbs the wall straight on, but if one uses the crack the route becomes 5.12b.

name: Two Hands of Prayer
description: Two cracks broken up with some ledges, first crack 10-15 feet, second crack around 15 feet. First crack is about fist sized, fun and interesting, exciting mantle moves to leave the crack. Second crack is more hand sized, and a lot more fun. Topping the route wasn't too bad, but this thing needs some loving. Get on it.

name: Zig-zag crack
description: This is a great route that follows the Zig-zagging crack on the South facing wall of the canyon.  There are lines of bolts on both sides of this route.  It starts to left of what could be called a cave, but still surmounts an overhang in the beginning.

name: Crazy Bird
description: It's small and simple, but rather than spending hours looking for another rock to climb, use this one.

name: El Cielo
description: The crux of the climb is the first move. It has a tricky top out as well.

name: El cielo (SDS)
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: baby cakes
description: this is to the left of knights rights very simple problem

name: donkey kick dyno
description: the crux is the dyno itself the bad thing is it has a littlt rock protruding where the pads lie be careful not to bruise a heal...

name: knights rights arete
description: it is a solid problem that is quite fun. my grading isn't quite right on.

name: The Metamorphosis (sds)
description: The crux is the lower half of the climb. The landing   has a few small boulders, so make sure that you bring a couple of pads. This is a really fun climb to figure out. With side pulls, crimps, and a hand jam how could you go wrong.

name: the nose
description: the crux is the short dyno to the big hidden jug!!

name: The sound of fury
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: crawdad hop
