description: The crux is dynoing from the wide pinch to the top ledge it is a good short problem that is a lot of fun the bad part is that it is to short just a couple of moves

name: el cielo
description: Climbing up the left side of the arete the crux is probably the first move, the throw to the crimpy sidepull

name: The Keeper SDS
description: The SDS for the Keeper.

name: The keeper
description: This is a very juggy problem. Using a sit start adds a bit to it.

name: shadow tricks
description: It is a pretty slappy problem. The crux is probably throwing for the last hold. It is kind of hidden.

name: Feed the beast
description: The crux is the exit moves on the climb, in the hgh area be on the look out for loose blocks, most are pretty obvious.

name: Siddhartha
description: The crux is near the top of the climb, exit left about half way up to make it a little harder.

name: Pit fall
description: The crux is coming over the lip into the slab. There is no falling off of this climb or else you end up in the small rocky pond behind the boulder.

name: fresh press
description: The crux is the start of the problem. The sit start makes the problem a little harder. This is a problem that has to be climbed when the water is low.

name: Barely Regal
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: Jiminy Crankit
description: The crux is the dyno for the topout. It has a really bad landing zone so bring multiple pads.

name: Blufflands Traverse
description: Climbs well from left to right. Start left around corner on shallow scoops, climb right around the corner and stay on the lip. Do NOT mantle over the lip until the very end, otherwise the problem is much easier. Lots of heel hooking. Top out.

name: A Really, Really Bad Idea
description: The Ryan Hansen guide book says: "Try this really, really bad idea by climbing the face of a lone pinnacle."

name: Jug Haul
description: Found on the 30 Degree Wall. Follow obvious good holds up center of wall. Top out or traverse left at second horizontal break. A sit start increases the difficulty.

name: Lardass Traverse
description: Found on the 30 Degree Wall. Sit start on corner at the right end of the wall. Climb up to sharp V hold then traverse left to far left end of wall.

name: Mr Canoehead
description: On the river side of the "Mr Canoehead" spire is the route Mr. Canoehead.

name: Mrs Canoehead
description: Shorter and easier than Mr C is Mrs C.

name: The Sawblade
description: Where Mr. Canoehead meets the west face. The arete is filled with ledges and jugs. A nice easy route with the potential for top belaying following beginners.

name: Boulder without a View
description: Short, widening crack that ends at a flat ledge (crux)  Can be climbed on gear at about 5.7. If a rope is used you can walk back to a large tree to bring up a second and rap. I used a yellow torquenut as a chockstone to keep the rope out of the depths of the crack.

name: Climb with a View
description: A short gear lead using the face and a thin crack system in an obtuse dihedral.

name: Late Night Chalk Show
description: Scramble up the boulders to the right of the main block and pre-clip the first bolt from there. This route is short and very intense - significantly harder than Whiskey a go go (ultra classic...), but shorter. Grading is difficult due to the length, yet the crux (moving from the second to third bolt) is both sequence specific and powerful. Flex your huge muscles really hard and follow the arrette to chains. Then go have a beer.

name: Ponyboy
description: This is the left-hand route on the block that follows three bolts to rusty chains. The climb is quite dirty (usually), but a fun (and potentially exhilarating...) fight up a sloping arrette.

name: Pretty Piece of Flesh
description: Scramble up some ledges and pull onto the slab. The rock quality is impressive for the slab, and the moves are fun. Move up the increasingly steep rock to the joint of the overhanging arrette/fin. Clip the last two bolts in the overhang, and bust through a burly boulder problem, following the line straight up from the last bolt. Safest to stay off of the fin 6 feet to your left - the rock seems a little more rotten there (although it would probably make for easier climbing, but the obvious line is harder, more fun, and on good rock).    Once you've reached the top, traverse right to the anchor. Let out a good yell to show the locals how strong you are.    If you're lacking the cannonballs to lead, the TR isn't a good idea. If you blow it above the last bolt (at the crux) you're going to smack into the dihedral on your right. Probably a better idea to just enjoy punting into space on overhanging glue-ins.

name: Riverboat Gambler
description: Slab to a cool roof pull.  I TR'd the route but busted slightly right (See pics) before the last slab bolt and pulled on good fairly solid jugs over.

name: Solo Crack
description: Great crack climb.

name: Who is Bernd Arnold?
description: Short route with some fun moves. Cool holds on the top half.

name: Aimless Foreshadowing
description: Follow the thin crack to the right of the Chucklehead/Phallus (P2) on the direct face follow up the crack until it runs out(crux). Good pro for the crux but runout after, until the big ledge. Next, continue up the face as it becomes slightly overhanging on jugs (Large Flakes) to the chains up top. Should be pretty solid at 5.9 for the the runouts I found little adequate pro but the climb is all there.    Also be weary of the thin suspect flakes on the upper part.

name: Air
description: One of the area's classics in my opinion, Air should not be missed.  The crux is around the first bolt, and from there to the top you get to enjoy fantastic exposure and massive holds.    Start in the dark dihedral on the southeast corner of the Air Spire with the first bolt about 15 or 20 feet up.  Some stemming and jamming gets you past the first two bolts, then it's a low-angle jug haul to the chains, which are about 15 feet below the summit on a large ledge on the southeast corner.    Air is found on the southeast corner of the second main spine.  It's labeled in a picture on the main Necedah page of this site.  The first bolt kind of blends in to the dark rock, and you might have to look a little higher than you'd expect to see it.

name: Chucklehead Crack (aka Spike's Crack)
description: Pitch 1: Has a tricky start. Follow crack for 45 ft. Then 4th class angling right to a one move pull to a ledge. On the north end of the air spire are 2 bolt anchors. 5.8~55 ft.   Pitch 2: From belay anchor look right and take the chimney to the top of the spire. Two bolt anchors at top and allow for rappel to base just barely with a 60m rope. Tie knots on the ends and aim just right of the tree on 4th class ledges when you toss your rope. The anchors at the top of this climb are not the same anchors as "Air". 5.6/7~45 ft.

name: Littlefinger's Coup
description: Start the climb on face holds and lie back crack then come up into a thin finger crack that continues for 20 feet or so where the gear is good but small. Follow up and eventually find some less vertical terrain. Finish with some final committing moves on a steep section below of the Air anchors. These final moves in combination with the committing finger crack it makes for a great climb!

name: Moss Man
description: Road side (west face) of Air Spire, this 2 pitch summit line begins on a low angle ramp in a left facing dihedral (easy 5th class).  1st pitch (~40ft): Ample protection in the piney crack system brings you past a pine tree on the left and up to a ledge on the right with a slingable boulder. This is the belay stance. Could probably also be done with several crack variations right of the ramp for a more difficult direct start on the 1st pitch.   2nd pitch (~45-50ft): From belay boulder move right onto the ledge and begin in a finger sized crack in the middle of the face. Surmount this bulge and gain clean but licheny 5.6 climbing on solid rock to the top out. Climb the face for the best movement, placing gear in the left crack. Top out and set belay off another slingable boulder. Rap off of chains for Phallus in Wonderland.  This climb seems to be one of the easiest ways to gain the top of Air Spire. (I'll add pics next time I'm at the bluff!)

name: Phallus in Wonderland
description: P1. For those who want to do an "Air" variation... Start on "Air" then climb to 3rd bolt. Climb about 6 feet higher, look left and see a keyhole cave. Go through it to a set of 2 bolt anchors immediately to the right after emerging from it. Put a piece high in cave to help with rope drag. It's fun. 5.6     P2: Take chimney to the top. Look for two bolt anchors slightly to the right (north) at the top. You can rappel to base just barely with a 60m rope. Tie knots on the ends and aim just right of the tree on 4th class ledges when you toss your rope. 5.6/7

name: Return of the Chucklehead's
description: Pitch 1: Another tricky start to the crack that goes straight then angles right to the crux. Good gear stance to fish in small wires before the crux move. Then 4th class angling right to a one move pull on a ledge. On the north end of the air spire are 2 bolt anchors. The anchors at the top of this climb are not the same anchors as "Air". 5.9  Pitch 2: From belay anchor look right and take the chimney to the top of the spire. Two bolt anchors at top and allow for rappel to base just barely with a 60m rope. Tie knots on the ends and aim just right of the tree on 4th class ledges when you toss your rope.   Good fun climb. 5.6/7

name: Unknown (The Line over Lucy?)
description: A line that wanders a little bit, but I thought was a blast to climb.  Starting up on one of the boulders, find the thin crack in a shallow dihedral that continues for about 20-25 feet.  This section is the crux, but the gear is good (blue to yellow metolius TCUs).  When the dihedral ends, pull onto the platform that is up and right on bigger holds.  Continue up on a couple more obvious ledges towards the left arete, then up a thin crack, and finally up the last 30 feet on jugs to the top.    A fun line that gets your attention at the start, then offers great holds, good gear, and decent exposure all the way to the top.  Descend by downclimbing to Air's anchors and rapping, or walk to the north end of the spire and rap from there.

name: Anita
description: This is the short route on the left.  Some thin almost bouldery moves will take you up to a horizontal.  Here you need to have some 3/4 inch cams (yellow and orange Metolius).  Then up on more thin holds to a burly mantle move and the anchors.  The route could have gone higher and maybe someday will.

name: Anthrax
description: The right hand bolted route. If you climb right on the bolts at the bottom using thin crimps, as Schmidt intended, the grade is 12c.  If you climb the nice arete to the right and stretch out to clip the bolts the whole thing will feel about .11a-ish.  This last way of climbing it is really enjoyable and I would give that 3 stars.

name: Anthrax Dihedral
description: The dihedral and roof to the left of "Anita".

name: Death Wish
description: Good protection ends with a loose finish.

name: Fistful of Metal
description: The better protected and better movement of the two face routes around the corner from "Anthrax".

name: Harvey Dent AKA Lichen You
description: There's no pro for the first ~15' so it's PG13 unless you scramble up on the right side to place a piece before starting.  First half is a steepening slab with ample edges and ledges amongst the lichen. Pull up and right onto a ledge and a steep start to the crack. Great jams and pro in the crack, some friable rock outside.  I imagine this has been climbed before. Anyone know the FA and real name?

name: Persistence of Time
description: Tricky slab. Gear is ok but spaced out. Do not fall! At the second horizontal plug in all the small cams you got and gun for the top.

name: Sound of White Noise
description: Crack climb!

name: A Slippery Slope
description: This is the second route to the right.  Some big moves on nice holds leads up just to the right of the arete.  There are some nice holds on the arete towards the top.

name: Schlickery when Wet
description: This is the first route you encounter on the left.  A few thinner moves lead to jugs at the top.

name: Step by Step
description: Definitely the best line of the group and a quality express route. Big moves lead you past a series of four natural breaks in the wall. Great holds all the way up. You can go straight up the face or use the right arete in the middle.

name: The Dalai Lama (aka Viagra)
description: Climb slightly overhung side of tower, seems like it could be done a few different ways.

name: Hydroponics
description: Climb obvious cracks on the river side of the tower. Most people start this from the notch between the tower and main bluff line and traverse into the crack. To add an extra bit of difficulty do the V1 crack that start at the very base of the tower.

name: Hydroponics- right crack strictly
description: Climb the right crack only of the two cracks that make up Hydroponics.  Climb directly up to this crack from underneath avoiding the leftmost start of Hydroponics.  Short but super fun finger crack sequence.  Cool small two tips lock at crux near top.

name: Post-Coital Snuggle
description: 2 bolts protect the low crux with another 2 bolts protect the high crux which are both about the same grade, although a different style.  A balancy few opening moves to a thought-provoking ever so slightly reachy move at the second bolt lead to a slab above.  Clip the third bolt and do a power move to gain the small roof with a high step.  Climb over the roof on the left for the proper send, or traverse right onto Foreplay to not enjoy the snuggle...  Like most sport routes, consider a stick clip if 5.9 is your leading grade.

name: Unnamed
description: Cool problem that rarely sees any action. SDS or SS in the middle of the face on  the crack. Climb over roof on the left side, once your feet are above the roof move right to letter box and top out.

name: User Friendly (aka Foreplay)
description: Climb the right side of the south face of the tower. A single bolt protects the opening moves, then 2(?) more to the anchors above.

name: Fire in the Sky
description: A long mixed trad route with good exposure once you break the tree line. Good climbing throughout, though the middle section is probably the highlight. The name stems from the sometimes fantastic afternoon light which can set the top of the spire ablaze in contrast to the shade shrouded base.  Start up a vertical finger crack system on the north part of the wall, just before the slabs. Once the crack ends move right to a water runnel and a #1 Cammalot placement. Move straight up to the bolt and climb the left side of the blunt arete for four bolts with the crux coming just after the second bolt. At the last bolt turn the corner to the right side, then climb steep jugs and hollow thin cracks to the top.

name: Thread the Needle
description: Mixed line for first 25 feet   Start on The Window crack for 20 feet then find a bolt with a good stance. Climb on perfect crimps and jugs for the rest of the climb. Finish climbing arete and clip into anchor. This route will be great once completely cleaned off  Top out on the detached block above if your feeling adventurous

name: Two Pine Pinnacle
description: From the Ryan Hansen guidebook: "Follow the path of least resistance up the corner and upper face for the easier version, or take a more direct line for a 5.11 version."

name: The Window
description: Features a roof, and then a dihedral. Tell your partner what you see through the window mid-way up.

name: Friction Addiction
description: This boulder lies directly behind the Y-Crack wall and Coyote Tower. A lot of fun problems and eliminates including the classic Friction Addiction problem.

name: Blind luck
description: Start in steep fractured groove.  Not too far up is the first crux which is regretably no fun, though hard.  The second crux comes moving left under the roof with some out of place holds.  Go straight up to jugs after 4th bolt?

name: Blindsided
description: This is the left tending extention of Blindluck.  It offers a few more big moves which may or may not justify doing the lower crux.  Watch out for the anchor.  The fixe sport anchor biner is a bit stiff...

name: Dick and Jeanie
description: Locate the next bolted route right of Self Mutilation. The climb is identified by thin cracks up a steep wall.      Perhaps the best bolted 5.11 in Wisconsin, Dick and Jeanie features a steep start and a bouldery crux. The climbing remains asthetic despite its short height. A popular project route, given its straightforward moves and beautiful position.

name: Glass Balls
description: Named for the ball-bearing-like lichen found on the arete, and originally led as a trad route with very little (if any) protection - this route has largely been ignored since its first ascent. Because of its odd position on a sloping arete, even toprope ascents have been considered somewhat sketchy. Recently, with the blessing of the first-ascensionist, five bolts and anchors have appeared making this an enjoyable sport route in a classic position.    The upper anchors were placed to facilitate rappelling off the Hell Wall (aka Quarry Wall) (west/climber's left) side of the arete, rather than rappelling or lowering directly down the crest of the arete (a disconcerting proposition at best). Even topropers might be well-advised to make use of the protection bolts as directionals given the sharp and sloping nature of the arete.

name: Glass Dihedral
description: Climb starts far right of Hells Wall near left of Glass Balls. Begin by climbing inside corner. Move to high right facing dihedral. Top out near Glass Balls.

name: The Green Lantern
description: Right hand bolted line on slab.  More consistent climbing than its neighbor to the left.  Originally done with some gear though it has been retro-bolted not too long ago.  You can still do it either way.

name: Hecks Arete
description: Arete climbing.

name: Jabba Roof
description: This route offers moderate climbing with enjoyable moves on stellar rock. Follow up incut side pulls, crimps, and jugs until you reach a roof that resembles Jabba the Hut (with enough imagination). The Jabba roof is the Crux of the route. Great warm up for the area

name: John's Dihedral
description: Dihedral climbing. Finish on D & J's anchors or top out.

name: Kevin's Dihedral
description: A few layback moves up the crack and then some chunky moves to the anchors.  An excellent climb for the beginning leader - way more fun than it looks.

name: La Fin Du Monde
description: This route climbs the obvious free standing fin/arete directly behind One Hit Wonder. Take the path of least resistance up the arete, avoiding some hollow rock in the middle of the climb. Pro is a bit spacey but the terrain is mild enough not to make you nervous. Top out, natural anchor, then walk off to the right by hopping a shallow gully.   This could easily be done as an R rated highball boulder, but in my opinion is better suited as an easy beginner trad lead.

name: Mercy F**k
description: Far right side of the wall is a short line.  Start up slabby terrain on good edges to the roof. Climb out and left to the anchors.  The move to the anchors is height dependent, but still not a big deal.

name: One Hit Wonder
description: The left hand bolted line on the Hell wall slab.  A v2 move will take you past the first bolt and into .10-ish climbing to the anchors.

name: Self Mutilation
description: Self Mutilation climbs up to and around the right side of the big overhang. The 5.11+ version begins in a crack on the left to gain the roof. (Climbing the face/corner directly to the roof would definitely make the climb much harder, probably 5.12+.)     Technical moves below the roof quickly give way to thuggery, as the climber strains to reach the anchors. You can see this line from the highway.

name: Spider Chimney
description: Starts cool, gets cooler. Off-width skills needed. There is a great belay station at the top.

name: Against Medical Advice
description: A south-to-north traverse of the entire Petenwell Ridgeline. This enjoyable outing makes an excellent training route for navigating alpine terrain. Climbers are forced into a variety of problem-solving situations requiring creativity (possibly even shenanigans) to negotiate. For the most part, the climbing is at a moderate grade, and, where the technical cruxes are, it can generally be well-protected. The real crux of this route is in the route-finding and risk management choices climbers will be forced to make. Variable and high-consequence terrain makes for a challenging day. A familiarity with one's risk-tolerance as well of the risk-tolerance of one's partner(s) is essential.   This is a challenging route unlike much of the climbing in the midwest and it should not be underestimated or attempted by climbers lacking the sufficient knowledge and experience to negotiate it safely.

name: Aswan Dam Crack
description: Two cruxes.  One moving past first bolt and one pulling above third bolt onto upper part of the route.

name: Confused
description: I started in the corner beneath an orange colored wall with some very easy climbing and then traversed left and climbed up a slightly overhanging crack(crux).(see pictures)

name: East Face Summit Ramp
description: Classic rockaneering up the river side of the main massif. This is probably the easiest way to the top of Petenwell Bluff.    Pitch 1 (3rd/4th):    Scramble up-and-to-the-right on an obvious ramp from the base of the massif to a saddle. At the saddle, move the belay (if you used one) by heading west across a slight gully falling away to the northwest.    Pitch 2 (Easy-5th):    After crossing the gully, you will find yourself deposited on a nice flat ledge at the north end of the main massif. Mantle onto the summit plateau and walk south to the summit block.

name: Give a Little Bit
description: Soon to be a moderate grade classic.  Imagine you are on the big walls of Yosemite and do the climb in 2 pitches or push to the top in one swoop (70m rope recco).  Pitch 1:  Straight up through the 3 bolts using the side pulls and shallow pockets.  Belay at rap anchors on the spacious ledge ( 5.9+ - 40' ).  **Stick clipping the first bolt is recommended**  Pitch 2:  Mantle up on to 2nd ledge to first bolt.  Stay straight on the face of the bolt line and follow the line to the airy finish. 6 bolts + Chain Anchors ( 5.6 - 60').  The anchors were set to prevent climbers from using the rings and chains for top roping.  If you plan on top roping either of these climbs, please extend your rigging with your own runners and carabiners.

name: Leap of Faith
description: A mixed climb to the right of Aswan Dam Crack.

name: Leap of Faith Step Across
description: Classic tower step across.

name: Mildly Entertaining
description: This climb starts in the corner under the orange colored wall.  Shares the same start as Confused but traverses up right where Confused goes left.  Climb up and around a corner to a ledge.  Pull up over the ledge and your on top.

name: Discontinuum
description: This climb starts on a 20 foot pillar feature which will force acouple committing moves on the sharp end. Then work up a number of discontinuous crack moving from left to right.  There is a no hands rest before the Crux which is well protected with big cams. Crux offers excellent face climbing

name: Twenty Feet of Meat
description: Short sport route.

name: A Dish to Pass
description: This is the contrived-looking route to the immediate left of Y-Crack. Thin moves lead past three bolts to one bolt with a quick link (the anchor).     I thought little of the route (it doesn't even go to the top of the wall) until I got on it. I found a very difficult move passing the second bolt followed by some long moves, almost lunges, linking crimps.    The rock is perfect and the moves are engaging. By the time I reached the anchor, I was happy that it was only three bolts long. Take that for what you will...

name: Blinded by Lust
description: This route, originally put up on natural gear by Rich Bechler, is a lesson in sandbagging. Since the route has been aggressively labeled a "squeeze job" and it lacks discernable natural placements at the crux, it was long forgotten and was subsequently covered in bird sh*t, lichen, and broken rock.Recently rediscovered and bolted, it took some community involvement to figure out the route's roots. Many holds were broken in the process of cleaning the route - the instability of the original rock further confirms that Rich was more of a man than all of us internet types put together. The crux sequences now rely on smaller, albeit trustworthy holds. Expect a large fall at the crux, and (if you're sane and choose to clip the bolts) hang a long draw from the fourth bolt. By WI standards, some may still refuse to give this anything harder than 5.6+++, but the rest of the Nation would probably put it somewhere in the 12+ range.For credit, Nathan Nelson managed to put together the second-FA/whatever you want to call it now. A solid effort to bolt, clean, and send. Props to both Rich and Nathan.

name: Dakota Farms Cheese
description: The other bolted route on the main tower, this line ascends the steep arete to the right of the more classic 5.10 Tower Route.    Tenuous moves lead up to the second bolt. Here, the climbing eases in difficulty but offers a nice view up the exposed arete. End at the chain belay/rappel anchors at the top of the tower.

name: Death of A Salesman
description: Probably the first bolted route in Wisconsin, Death of a Salesman starts off the block immediately right of Whiskey a Go Go.     Bolts protect a thin seam that eventually runs out. Here, the route continues up Y-Crack (gear needed).

name: Eagle Rare
description: Move up slab on big holds toward hanging arete.  Pass hanging arete on the right and follow resulting inside corner to the top.  This is a great beginners route.  Easy, but unasthetic climbing leading to a beautiful view at the top.

name: Early Times
description: A surprisingly good line originally lead on gear and a bit wandery. The retro bolted version takes on the plumb line. The route offers quality moves on good stone and is also a good warm up for the harder lines nearby.  Some hard moves off the deck take you to some jugs and past the first two bolts. The third bolt is a horizontally reachy clip (hollow rock closer in...). Some crimps, a finger lock, and a good side pull take you up to some jugs and a mantley finish.  Early Times is a cheap whiskey and a subtle salute to the DLFA and the bravado of Rich who would lead anything back in the day whether the gear was there or not. Often with a belly full of swill. I think he’d be happy to see so many people climbing this line. And I bet it does see gear ascents every now and then.

name: Easy Tower Route
description: EASY trad route on the SE corner of the tower to the chains up above "The Tower".  Good way to access "The Tower" if you are feeling lazy.  Good beginner trad climb.

name: Ezra Brooks
description: This route is the obvious crack on the south end of the Y Wall just to the right of Rebel Yell.  The crux is not far off the ground at the small roof.  After that there is better gear as you work your way up to the shoulder.  From here climb out and left towards the top of Rebel Yell.  Good exposure here and a great view. Continue to top.

name: Green Zipper
description: Brent and I put this up at the same time we put in Dakota Farms Cheese. It was later removed by somebody and that was not a problem for me. The route was a bit ill concieved (can barely be led on gear I think) and a crucial hold broke up at the crux (above the top bolt position) and kind of rendered the whole thing dumb. We called it "Black Toe" and it was around mid to hard 5.10. Somebody didn't like the route and cut the studs. I have been meaning to still mix a little rock dust with epoxy and cover those stud spots.     The route more or less stays right of the corner now then drifts a bit further right at the top and climbs through the little flap right of those old bolt locations. Originally we had it going straight through the bolts but hold broke and really it was a contrived line at that. I have led this thing on gear since myself and more or less understood the folly...

name: Little pine
description: Start 7 feet north of early times, climb straight up toward little pine and end at early times bolts.

name: Pigeon Crack
description: This is the obvious chimmney left of Whiskey A Go-Go.  Climb up on good face holds (Gear?) to reach the cleft.  There are good holds inside and out on the left towards the top of this section.  After that's over, work up two cracks to the anchors of Whiskey A Go-Go.  This is a really cool pitch for the grade and the rock quality is good throughout.

name: Rebel Yell
description: A classic lead origanlly done with only the two SMC bolts and gear. Dave added a bolt higher up which makes the route safe. Start up ledges towards a seam to a small overhang. Crimp past the overhang on the right and work into the scooped out face on right never straying too far from the arete. Move left at the glue in ring bolt around the corner into high crack to finish on the left of the arete. Good moves throughout and some decent exposure as well.

name: Straight No Chaser
description: this great variation to y-crack(aka old and in the way)is a classic lead ,takes good gear and will pump you up.i remember rich got bamboozled into leading this right after he broke his finger in the ditch on zodiac because he thought some rookie was gonna do it before us.great picture to follow.

name: Ten High
description: This is second trad line left of Whiskey. Start out at parallel seam/cracks on the right side.  Do some strenous moves to get to small hand slot 12' up or so (#.75).  Continue up into the stem box section climbing on the right.  At the ledge find some gear, and then climb off and just slightly to the left using an undercling to reach for bigger holds.

name: Tower Route
description: This is the main route up the center of the tower behind Y-Crack Wall.     A hard start gives way to easier climbing, angling leftward to the corner (it is harder than 5.10a to bypass the corner and continue straight up). The bolts eventually bring the climber back out on the narrowing face. Here the climbing is very special: the holds become patina-like, and the lichen stands out in technicolor splashes.    Upon completing the route, the climber is treated to one of the best summits in Wisconsin (behind Cleo's Needle, of course). From the small point of the tower, the climber can look out to the Petenwell Lake area or gaze with wonderment at the harder routes on Y-Crack wall. A rap from the two bolt anchor completes the experience.

name: West Face of Tower
description: Climbing is great, don't do this if you aren't SOLID leading 5.8

name: Whiskey a Go-Go
description: Whiskey a Go Go climbs the wall just left of the saddle between the wall and the spire. The climb follows discontinuous cracks up the steep face.     The bottom of the face is heavily featured and offers 5.10ish climbing up to the second bolt. The features eventually run out and force the climber into exceedingly thin and dynamic moves to link the widely spaced cracks. Once past the crux, some welcome pockets await; however, they offer little reprieve. A classic top out deposits the climber on a ledge with anchors.     All in all: 50 feet of climbing, increasingly strenuous moves with no rests on perfect, beautiful sandstone. I call it the best hard route in Wisconsin.    Note: Dave Groth (FA) intended for the last bolt to be clipped and for the climbing to remain on the face the whole way. Bailing left before the last bolt and climbing easier rock to the top is considerably easier and is NOT the original route.

name: Y Not
description: This is the obvious link up of the two overlooked (but worth doing) sport lines on the face to the left of Y-Crack.  Crimp your way up A Dish To Pass, but instead of doing the final deadpoint to the jug, traverse left through the gray streak to gain the crack on Death Of A Salesman.  Climb the crack until you are forced back right onto the last section of Y-Crack.  All in all, a really nice and continuous climb up one of the finest walls in the state.

name: Y-Crack (aka Old and in the Way)
description: If you were handed the keys to a Ferrari 488 gtb ( 660 hp and 0- 60 in 3 seconds) and told "Go ahead , wail on it !"  What would you do? Wail on it of course. Sending this climb is akin to wailing on that Ferrari. Up the straights and thru the curves. Super car super climb. Channel yer inner Mario. To summarize....3 words to describe this climb , " Line of kill ".  2 words , " obvious crack " . 1 word....." Ferrari" .    On a side note: nothing unusual about the First lead ,Lemon was day dreaming about drinking wine with the Dali Lama which provided the extra incentive for me not to fall. At least he was good for that.     Also nothing special about the route name, just a classic blue grass song we listened to way too much. Probably one of the best climbs in Wisconsin.

name: Blazing Star
description: From slopey holds dyno up to the slopey break.  Drop off.

name: Prairie Rose
description: A drop off but a bad ass dyno in a cool setting.  From the edges jump to the two by four pinch out the overhanging scoop feature.

name: Bear Hug
description: Start with feet on the ledge below the water, use features on both sides of the bulge to top out.

name: Choss-rrito Supreme
description: Smear on the underwater portion of the wall until you can get a good foothold out of water (none underwater). Nice line of medium crimps and a finger crack to the top.

name: German Sparkle Party
description: Cool line, but not very difficult. Good for beginner climbers or for a warmup.

name: Grab Her Feet
description: Pretty fun, slightly more challenging than Swamp Booger.

name: Left or Dead
description: Stay out on the face and grab sides of rock to work your way up. DO NOT use the small rock coming out of the water on the right. Start in the water. Starting foothold is below water on the right.

name: Sandy Side
description: Get on to the blocks on the left, then go right towards the arête.

name: Sunny N Sandy
description: Start on the underwater ledge, and use the side pulls to get to a sandy topout.

name: Swamp Booger
description: Slightly positive with plenty of holds.  Stay to the right - there is another route, Grab Her Feet, that goes to the left.  A little sketchy because of the positive angle and height, but pretty easy.

name: Toe Jam Football
description: The crux is pretty early on, a nice sideways barefoot jam

name: $100 of Caulk
description: Sit start with a stellar right foot. Head straight up.

name: 6' but only 4"
description: This route is tall. Unfortunately tall doesn't always mean amazing quality. Pull one or two slightly difficult moves then cruise jugs for the top. Or start right and traverse left on ledge feet to decrease the difficulty.

name: 6x4 Right
description: Go up the right side of the face using the crack and left hand side pulls

name: Arrowhead Far Left
description: Same start as Arrowhead left but traverse left, then up the crack to the top.

name: Arrowhead Left
description: SDS on rail and climb left face of Arrowhead boulder

name: Arrowhead Right
description: SDS on double underclings, climb out from under the boulder and straight up the face (stay to the left of the crack)

name: Back Corridor
description: Sit/squat start on a rail. Find a nice undercling then stand into a big reach to a jug. Follow good holds up to the top out.

name: Back Touch
description: Squat start on two solid side pulls. Move up through incut side pulls and jugs to a slopey top out.

name: Beached Whale
description: SDS and get to lip.  Crux can be the mantle finish.

name: Bear Hugger Loop
description: SDS at the base of Low Ball and traverse through fun dynamic moves left to the base of cereal bowl, proceed up cereal bowl to the lip, then traverse all the way right to the tree working with difficult lip, then down climb a sort 2 moves to the starting position and run the loop again!

name: Bo(u)lder Landing
description: Starts on the vertical face just right of Sandstone Choss. head for the highest imaginable exit avoid using any of the Sandstone Choss holds. stick to the face and all of it's fun features. the top out is high but you will find large holds to take you up and out safely!

name: Cereal Bowls
description: Cereal Bowls start with perfect dish and moves up right to other dish.  Go for good crimp out left and mantle. Great warm-up.  Stay right on slopers and throw for lip makes problem a little tougher, V3

name: Cheese Tower
description: A nice warmup slab pillar, V0 and balance-oriented. Next to the Krampus problem.

name: Chickens Head
description: Climb up slab route with small iron holds and finish out with the help of the chickens head up top.  (The Chickens Head is a large iron deposit at top of problem)

name: Children of the Corn
description: A funky little Font style boulder.Start with a knob for the left hand and a sidepull sloper for the right at the same height.  Surmount the bulge via slopes and slimpers.A unique and technical problem that likely demands decent conditions.  A little more brushing might not hurt.A sit is possible and would surely add difficulty.

name: Derailed
description: Stand start, left hand in the crack, right on a low sidepull. Move up through some large chicken head holds up to a fantastic slanting rail before the top out.

name: Easy Highball
description: Climb up tall break in rock.  Top out is a little intimidating.

name: Edible Reject
description: Stand start, left hand side pull, right hand in the crack. Following jugs and sidepulls to the top

name: Frogs Face Traverse
description: Start low on block that has the shape of a frogs head.  Traverse right and climb up and around the corner to top.  Easier if you skip the low start and climb corner alone.

name: Frosted Flake
description: Sit start without using the block for feet. Climb up with a powerful first move to the flake then top out. Short but fun warm up.

name: GK (aka Backside of Pigs Head)
description: Awesome problem!  Start low on rail and climb up face using deep cracks and sidepulls.  Using the crack on right is off for this problem.  Watch the fall, the landing can be nasty.

name: Green Shell
description: Start on a jug, pull up through some crimps and underclings. Keep it together for the slopey top out.

name: Hard Slab
description: Climb much harder slab route just right of Near Sighted Gynecologist.

name: Heel Hook Problem
description: Start low and hug your way up corner of boulder, while sticking a heel hook for the crux move. Fun

name: Kings Face
description: Climb up thin face just right of Kings Throne.

name: Kings Face 2
description: Climb up face right of Kings Face

name: Kings Throne
description: Sit start on throne like rock chair.  Climb up corner of boulder.

name: Kings Throne Left
description: Stand start using a small iron hole for a foot, and bad hard to see sloping crimps, continue up nothing crimps to the easy slopers at the top.

name: Krampus Compress
description: Stand Start V2. Pretty fun little compression problem. Low stand V3. Sit start FA V4+/5 Andrew Jablonski

name: Large Flake
description: Start with lower crack and get up into large flake.  Top out.

name: Leaning Block
description: Climb up corner of leaning block.  Watch your fall, slab landing.

name: Low Ball
description: Start low and climb up slopy rails to tough mantle finish.

name: Mind the Gap
description: Start with a bomber right sidepull in the gap between the rocks, left hand arete. Head up on sidepulls and a pinch. A bit dabby

name: Modern 2
description: Sit start on the obvious jug. Find left and right hand holds then hike awkward feet up. Balance up to the finish. The rock on the right is off.

name: Moister
description: Nice compression moves up to a slopey top out.

name: Near Sighted Gynecologist
description: Amazing slab climbing.  Climb up left side of slab using cool slopey features and an up close and personal pod.

name: Nickel and Dime
description: Climb thin face with small iron pebbles.  Techy feet.

name: No Name
description: Sharp crimps and small feet is the name of the game. There are two large chicken head holds mid way up. Collect yourself and then keep your balance for the big finishing move off small holds.

name: The Nose
description: Squeezing and slapping, sds and climb up and over the Nose of the Old Man Boulder.  It's harder than it looks.

name: Nubbin but the Truth
description: Short and sweet. Sit start on side pulls and head up the face.

name: Off Target
description: Sit start on two decent holds then cruise up on jugs and sidepulls to the top. A nice warm up before doing the arrowhead routes.

name: Old Man Corner
description: Climb first corner you see on Old Man Boulder behind the restrooms.

name: Old Man Dyno
description: On face of the Old Man Boulder, throw for the lip from large rails down low.  (Two variation: a low and higher start.  The lower is much harder for the vertically challenged.

name: Old Man Traverse
description: Traverse the lower rail left and climb up corner with a slopey top out.

name: Old Man's Crack
description: Climb Crack feature on boulder.

name: The Oyster
description: Has some fun moves but is unfortunately moist more often than not. Sit start right hand on a sidepull and left in the crack. Follow some compression moves up. Good right heel hook potential.

name: Pepperjack Crack
description: Crack downhill to the right of Arrowhead and just to the left of Off Target. A little spicy, but solid.

name: Pigs Cheek
description: Right hand starts on bad crimp with chip out of it, and left hand either undercling or match with right and gun for slopey ledge. Top out

name: Pigs Head
description: Climb up two bulges on end of boulder.  From the side of boulder looks like a pig head.

name: Platinum Blonde
description: A gem.  The obvious line up the center of the tall, stunning and intimidating slab.  No contrivances, just climb it, and don’t exit left.Probably climbed many times before.One of the best and most intimidating climbs in the park.

name: Project
description: Slap up corner with no features.  Still open project I think.

name: Project 2
description: This problem has been tossing off the best for over a decade.  Due to a seeping hold that never dries, it remains nearly impossible.  I've seen it dry maybe three times over the years.   Figure out a sequence that starts on lower part of rock and gets through seeping crimp up to good ledge.  Top out.   Legend has it that the problem has been done from a stand start with a jump to the second hold.

name: Red Shell
description: Start on two solid finger buckets. Find your feet and go big for a rail. Then follow decent holds to a slopey and slightly heady top out. May be easier for taller people.

name: Right of Easy Highball
description: Right of Easy Highball, make balancey reach to small seem up left. Tricky, but with some static movement the problem goes easy.

name: Sand Box
description: Climb and traverse around on cool pockets.  Chossy!

name: Sandstone Choss
description: Climb chossy rock up to top.

name: Sidepulls
description: Stand start and do some relaxed moves on great sidepulls.

name: Single Serve
description: Sit start. Move up and right through a fantastic, though short rail. Keep it together for the goofy slopey top out.

name: Slopey Times or Westby Traverse low low
description: Start underneath the Project with the seepy hold and follow the break right all the way to the end.  I didn't use the upper boulder or the crack until the end to mantel out.  Could use some more cleaning.  Pumpy.

name: Squeezin Dairy Air (left)
description: SDS around left corner of boulder, traverse right to crack and top out

name: Squeezin Dairy Air (right)
description: SDS around left corner of boulder, see beta photo

name: Stage 3 Clinger
description: Sit start on jugs and make your way to the undercling. follow easy slopers to the top.

name: Thin Face 2
description: Climb thin face on opposite wall from Thin Face.

name: Tower Right Face
description: Mossy face climb around the corner to the right on the Cheese Tower from the Warmup slab climb. Good holds, possibly some choss. Climbs well.

name: Triangle Problem
description: SDS, and climb straight up.

name: Unnamed, Unclaimed
description: Start in the crack under the shield like feature and follow fantastic jugs and side pulls to the top.

name: V0
description: Climb easy corner.  Good warm up.

name: Westby Cheese
description: SDS with a good left hand pinch in the scoop feature and right hand in a sharp undercling. Bump the right hand through a series of pockets, and left hand through a good crimper and some side-pulls. Do a funky little mantle move and venture up the slab to the top.

name: Westby Traverse
description: Same start as Easy Highball, but stay low and move right cranking through fun moves along and below lip.  Finish up around the corner to the right.

name: Whole Milk Classic
description: start on some jugs then finish up the top on some gently overhanging slopers.

name: Zone 2
description: sit start with left hand on a crimp rail and a right hand side pull. Nice heel hooks on the left.

name: Chapter Four
description: Stand start to the right of the prow in the corner pocket above the sand-choss. Follow the holds on the right side of the prow out left. Jump out to the nose and then mantle up. Recommend stacking pads to brush the prow.  Topout is crux. Don't want to fall on this one, landing is sloped and you and/or your pads might be sliding down the hill.  Don't recommend trying unless you are very comfortable with the grade. Downclimb is also a bit dangerous. Once you topout, walk to the left about 10-15 feet and then carefully downclimb.

name: Corner Route
description: Starts in the corner to the right of the Lynx. Goes up to the jug hold that is usually used as a heel hook for the Lynx. Easier route, but not as fun.

name: Cougar Pounce
description: A fun stemming / mantle problem. Left side of boulder, sit start. This route has had some MAJOR cleaning since its first send.

name: Hell Kitty / Here Kitty
description: Start sitting or low on the bottom of the left side of the main roof. Climb up jugs to a mantle topout. Left variation is Hell Kitty, right variation is Here Kitty.

name: High Cat Left
description: High Traverse. Start as for The Lynx OR start all the way out right on the sidekick boulder - either way, the traverse is about the same grade. Traverse left from midway up the Lynx staying on the high holds. Continue traversing left around the corner, staying on the high rail and climb the boulder ALL the way to the far left side with small crimps at the very end. Top out.

name: High Cat Right
description: A great traverse and endurance tester - plus it's fairly high off the ground!! Start all the way at the very left end of the boulder on crimps - as far out left as you can possibly go. Climb all the way around the boulder staying on the HIGH rail to go around the corner into pockets and continue on the high traverse until you reach the Lynx.  Top out on the Lynx (or on the Snarly Arete - fewer moves but still about the same grade.. but I prefer the Lynx topout because then the route climbs all the way around the rock.  I suggest climbing the direct lines first and working the traverse in parts with pads, since you cannot possibly protect the entire traverse. Distribute your pads wisely when attempting the entire traverse. Consider placing a pad for the topout, and/or coming around the corner above "Here Kitty."

name: King Lynx
description: Start on the sidekick boulder, traverse into the main boulder and top out on Tiger King.

name: King Snarl
description: Start on sidekick boulder, traverse left and top out on the Snarly Arete.

name: The Lynx
description: Starts with right hand on main low jug start and left hand on low rail. Go up and right, making some decent-sized throws out to smaller pocket holds with good friction. go straight up and top out.

name: Lynxup
description: Start on the sidekick boulder all the way to the right. Climb left but do NOT climb on top of sidekick boulder. Heel hook and cross out into the holds on the Lynx. Top out the Lynx.

name: Scratching Post
description: Climb from the start of Cougar Pounce up to the rail that goes out left. Follow this to thin crimps and tiny feet and climb the topout at the very edge - the topout to High Cat Left.

name: Snarly Arete
description: Climb the main arete of the boulder. Between Tiger King and the Lynx. Straight up and top out.  V4 variation: Skip the holds just after the start (the next holds for Tiger King or those for Lynx), and go straight up into the big pocket at the bottom of the arete. Huge move, helps to cam foot in the rock.

name: Tiger King
description: Same start as The Lynx, on main holds. Instead of going out to the right, go up left to two large crimps on the celing. Climb up and out, to the left. Avoid the large jug to the right (this is Tiger King JR).

name: Tiger King Jr.
description: Same start / climb as Tiger King, but the huge jug on the left is on for feet and/or hands.   Huge jug might one day break off, seems solid for now but I wouldn't recommend a dead hang or dynoing.

name: Way of the Cat
description: SDS for Cougar Pounce, then traverse right on the low rail. Top out on Hell Kitty.

name: Way of the Wildcat
description: Low traverse, left to right.  Starts at the bottom of cougar pounce (the beginning of the low seam, on the left side of the boulder). Follow the low rail out right, and come around the corner into the cave area. Stay along the low rail, and finally go up from the start of the Lynx into the Lynx topout.  Variation: Can be climbed in reverse. Start low for the Lynx and go left. Same grade.

name: Wildcat Warmup
description: Starts on the "sidekick" boulder all the way right. Traverse left, then top out sidekick boulder. Step over left into the Lynx and top out.

name: A Brief Crack
description: Sit start at bottom of crack. Work way up using only hands and feet on crack section. Fairly sustained. Lots of loose rock on very top. I wouldn't top out.

name: Around and Up
description: Sit start. Move from starting holds to small pocket on right. Hand heel match on the left starting hold to move up the two crimps and around the corner. Make your way left using whichever holds are best for you and top out by the tree.     Crux for me is the heel hook to the first crimp. Around the corner has good holds but the moves are strong.

name: Bane of Big Ben
description: This is the crux of the Big Ben traverse and is most fun if started or finished near the end of Bulging Face. Traverse is high on the Sepulcher face and follows a line of crimps.

name: Bulging Face
description: Start matched on low crimp. Work through a slopey pinch and some solid edges to topout. Upper right block is off.

name: Cave Arete
description: Start on left hand side pull and arete. Climb Jugs to top. Topout (make sure it's clean, can be slightly sketchy). Right wall is off.

name: Cave Face
description: Start on right hand side pull and good ledge. Work through traverse on good holds into a side pull jug. Gain high feet to topout.

name: Full Cave
description: Starts on an obvious jug to the left and traverses right using smallish crimps and pinches. Crux move is getting to the high jug. Would not recommend topping this one out.

name: Sepulcher
description: Sit start on two low slopey edges. Work through crimps and a side pull to finish. Crimp circled in yellow is off.

name: Sepulcher Left
description: Sit start on two low slopey edges. Move left through crimps instead of right (as you would for Sepulcher). Finish on big block.

name: Campus Life
description: Campus start on east facing surface then stem up east and north faces to top out.

name: Hanging out
description: Explore the overhang at the point across form where everyone is jumping

name: Patient Zero
description: Start in the water and work your way up lake side of the alternative jumping location.

name: Slip and Slide
description: Climb North west corner of Jumping Hole. Difficulty varies depending on how wet the holds are.

name: Splash Zone
description: Climb just left of the main jumping platform

name: Tricky Top
description: Crux is at the top as you get some silly high feet and pull yourself over the lip.

name: Wet Dog
description: Little bit of a roof to climb above. Some "technical" foot work with some bomber holds.

name: Big toe Traverse
description: The crux of getting out of the cave is a V4. Everything else is V3 and below. The pump factor is real, especially if you do it barefoot. I found it a good place to practice horizontal hand jams and to improve my mediocre crack skills.

name: Cave Man
description: Hoist yourself up into the little cave like structure then scale the south most aspect of Jumping Hole Adjacent

name: Easy Out
description: immediate east facing surface around south corner of jumping hole

name: Stay on point
description: To the left of the point you traverse to get over water and can climb up face, stem up the corner or climb the sunny side.

name: Walk on water
description: Another great spot where you can climb down and explore different ways back up. At least 4 route possibilities either climbing down from edge or back up from water level.

name: Great Wall Warm Up
description: Sit start. Move up solid holds to the top. Sustained. Loose rock on very top. I wouldn't top out.

name: It's a Route
description: Sit start on solid holds. Set up good feet (they're a little hard to find) and do a big move up to the ledge. Follow crimps up and left to finish hold. Don't top out.

name: 5.8 Crack
description: The 5.8 crack is located on the north-facing cliff about 200 yards to the west of the Redbird statue. This route was originally described as a "classic 5.8". It is the leftmost route on a steep section of fair-quality rock.    Pull up through the obvious crack system to the roof. Move right and grunt through some jugs to the top.

name: Doloroof
description: Nice 4-5 move sequence with a below roof start.  Fun movements from under the roof following the crest of the nose.

name: Easy Corner
description: Goes up the corner to the ledge halfway up the route. Then traverse to the right of the overhang. Shares the same start as "Up and Over".

name: Fern Route
description: Bouldery start to the flaring crack.  Shimmy up the dihedral to the pumpy finish.

name: High Cheekbone
description: Starts about 5 ft to the right of Doloroof on the two hand holds about shoulder level on the flat part of the wall.  4-move sequence up and to the left ending about 10-15 ft off the ground.

name: Surprisingly Good
description: Route got its name because it looks like the rock halfway up will be choss, but it is actually surprisingly solid.    Make a stretchy move to get off the ground, and then climb the face on pretty enjoyable movements to a nice top out.

name: Up and Over
description: Climb the easy corner to the overhang directly above. I used the side wall for my feet but a climber could definitely increase the difficulty by staying off the side wall completely. The top out is dirty with soil and pebbles.

name: White Swan Drive
description: 20-30 ft to the right of the Red Bird Statue climbs at the obvious roof that's about 3-4 ft high. Starting on the north edge and finishes on the face. I stopped about midway up the face on a nice ledge.

name: The Curse
description: This route starts in the cave on the left face. It starts with the two pinches on this small face. Go straight out to the arete, follow the arete to the top-out. Don't use wall behind the route which will make it much easier.     This is a very cool climb and you'll get a lot of attention from all the hikers on the trail because they can't miss you.     When I climb this route it somewhat reminds me of the very popular route, "The Overhang" by the Pavilion.

name: Davey Jones
description: Sit start with right hand in a slot on the arete and left hand in a small crimp in the seam under the roof make tenuous moves out the roof. Detached feet to the right are not on.

name: Head Over Heels
description: Sit start on the white block to the left of the cave. Move up to the right of the crack, but then make a dyno up and to the right and hold on. Weird pocketed crimps run straight up from the "big throw" to a mantle top out.

name: Rain On My Fire Escape
description: This route follows a crack on the left side of the boulder. You sit start on the face just before it starts jetting back into the cave. Go straight up the crack and top it out. Not too much to it.

name: Walk the Plank
description: Start a little to the left of Rain on my Fire Escape then traverse right.  Using the top is off.  Not extremely hard but pumpy.  Finish out to the right of the finish for The Curse.

name: ADHD
description: Start sitting on large break and climb up through the roof to a large move to a shelf, continue on good holds to the easy topout.

name: Guns, Germs, and Steel
description: Start on a large horn jug at chest height, climb up the face to a pinch and then throw to a good edge.

name: King of the Swingers
description: Start sitting on a large flat ledge and work your way up too a long lock off out of horizontal roof, gain the large pocket and continue to climb out the roof on geometric block holds and top out at the crack at the lip of the prow.

name: Law of Nature
description: The Law of Nature is a beautifully looking crack with in a fierce looking roof.    The line follows the crack up to the roof. It jets out from here and then boldly forges straight up.     A great warm-up for the much pumpy routes to its left. Offers lay-backs, hand jams, and delicate foot work getting over the roof.

name: Barbed Wire Toprope
description: Fun face climb with a tricky mantle topout. Start low on staggered incut crimps, move up and right on good holds to a small three finger sidepull out right. Stand on the ledge and mantle your way up and over! For full value, avoid using the low shelf for feet

name: Dyno-mite
description: Start on large black left of solitude and dyno up to another large block and top out. Super fun

name: Rainmaker
description: Short and sweet face climb into a mantle topout. Start on two incut crimpers in the horizonal and move up to big slotted jug. Hike up the feet and go for the top! For full value, avoid using the low shelf for feet

name: Randy Lahey
description: Fun warm up to the right of solitude follow cracks up, there are tons of fun variations

name: Solitude
description: Start compressed on low block and slap your way up the arête. Some of the best quality rock in the park and an instant classic in my opinion.

name: The solitude chamber
description: Start matched low in small cave make your way out using some cool bike moves and make a few powerful moves to a hard mantle

name: Solitude left
description: Same start as solitude except make your way up the left arête and topout

name: The Sorcerers Apprentice
description: Start in two finger pocket and sloping crimp move up right to a weird crimpy sloping edge and than a powerful throw up left to the top. Super lowball but surprisingly hard and fun.

name: An Appropriate Name
description: Starts on a good two hand block to the left of Harappan Civlization. (About 50 feet to the left of calm like a bomb) First move is a big one to a large horn 4 feet or so to the left. A series of pockets and crimps to the top out above mono problem.

name: Aragog
description: Start sitting and matched on a left facing sidepull, climb up to the pockets under the roof and jump to a better pocket above the lip, climb up several more moves to a large jug at about the 15' mark. Hang and drop.

name: Big Man on Campus
description: Start sitting on two good crimps and work your way up to the roof, reach out and gaston the golf ball hold and gain the lip into Campus Problem.

name: Bison Corposantics
description: SDS low, with left hand in bison's mouth hold, which is a large slot, and the right in a small pocket. Work slight left, then up and right, through horn, sloper, mono, undercling, and then right on edges. Big move straight to the top.

name: Bison Lightning
description: SDS with left in Bison mouth and right in little circle pocket, same as Bison Corposantics. Work through sloper, mono pinch, flake, mono, ledges and out. This problem goes from bison head diagonal left to the top.

name: Calm like a Bomb
description: Walk down the steps to the east of the Redbird Statue and below the main pavilion area. The trail will take you to a huge detached block. Some good bouldering can be found on the downhill side of the block.    A blank roof crosses the right side of the wall. "Calm" climbs up a very overhanging prow that juts out from the right side of the wall, just right of the roof. Heel hooks and slaps lead to easier moves. The climb was topped-out on the first ascent, but this is not necessary as the top is tall, easy, and uninspiring.     "Calm" looks and climbs a lot like "The Buddha" at the Gunks.

name: Campus Problem
description: The Campus Problem climbs up the center of the big roof. Start with holds above the roof and campus and throw to better holds higher. Shorter climbers may have to jump to the start holds.    The sit start has been a project for years. This would involve climbing through the roof using only a funny undercling bulb.

name: Dayman
description: Start on large block and traverse right along rail using heel hooks and toe hooks avoiding the chossy feet below when you start to get near gorilla action make a couple of moves up to some crimpy pockets and link up with gorilla action to top out

name: Dry Your Eye
description: This isn't my problem so chime in if you have additional info.. This is cool because it's a vertical problem which is kinda rare at highcliff.  Start on the obvious start hold that looks like a frowning mouth, from there several variations are possible, work your way up to the juggy horizontal and then pull up to the first big ledge. You can either drop off from the ledge, traverse off left or top out the formation.

name: Edible Berries
description: Start with a left hand side pull and a right hand crimp, get a high left foot and climb up the face. This is a good climb to warm up for The Overhang.

name: Fighter of the Nightman
description: Starts 4 feet to the right of the star holds for dayman on ledge move up right to crimp then a bigger move up left coming out of small roof to slopey ledge, match then up left to bomber juggy ledge match and throw for top and topout

name: Finger on the trigger
description: Start on two low flat crimps. Bump a right up to an obvious two finger pocket on the face, work your way up to the horizontal crack and top out.

name: Formidable Forecast
description: Start low on a right hand good pocket and a left hand sidepull. Work your way up though good holds and hit a small hold at the lip and make your way to the better holds.

name: Gorilla Action
description: Sit start and climb, using good holds, up the wall left of The Overhang. Top out.    It starts on 2 solid blocks and moves to the right for a big move to some small crimps with your right. Once on the serious of small crimps one can heel hook left on the stating blocks or just campus the hell out of the remaining holds to the top out. Feet are uber-important on the top-out unless you enjoy cranking on shallow finger pockets on the top of the face.    The park service simply pushes the leaves from the grounds over the edge. This makes for a very squishy, friendly landing.

name: Gorilla Fighter
description: Start in the back of the cave on the starting block, bust out to the jug ledge then move left to the corner to the jugs of Gorilla action. From here bump right and heel hook your way along the lip to the top out of the Overhang and top out as for that route. Contrived..yes, but an obvious line with great movement and longer than most boulders in the park.

name: The Green Machine
description: Fun traverse. Start to the right of Calm Like a Bomb in the cave. Move out to the arete on a sloper, move to the giant rail and ride that to Local on the Eights. Gain the 2 crimps on the Local and make a big move out right to a jug. Swing over and finish up the slightly overhung face to the top of the ledge.

name: The Hangover
description: From the jug in the back right side of the roof, climb out the right side of the overhang.  The sidewall is not used to the right. Definitely a forced line but it climbs well.  The pocket out left in the middle of the roof isn’t used (it feels like that would make you climb left to me).  It sounds like this could be a post break version of the original Overhang mayyyyyybe?

name: Harappan Civilization
description: This is one of my favorite boulder problems at High Cliff. I don't know who the made the FA, but I call it Harappan Civilization.     It is located about 20 feet left of Calm like a Bomb. The climb starts where some graffiti is. It reads "Tumot off" or something like that.     Start on the white colored rock down and to the left of this graffiti. Work your way up and over the roof. It can just end when you are standing above the roof.

name: The Hour of Power
description: Slightly overhanging arete. Start on large block and make some technical moves slightly right, then continue up the arete. Crux for me was the bottom section.

name: Jelly
description: SDS on the obvious jug, then link the big, chalked-up jugs to the first ledge.    Downclimb or jump into the waiting arms of your spotters.

name: Local On the Eights
description: This is a pretty fun route that I call Local on the Eights. It is fairly easy but very cool.     When you walk down the stairs to get to the bouldering, it is one of the first routes.     It starts with a sit start, goes to the big ledge, and up to the little roof. After the roof go a couple moves more until a big ledge.

name: Mono Problem
description: Start sitting just to the right of the big face of Thrutch and Wiese and just to the left of the long low roof. Climb up the face using (you guessed it) a mono.    It is possible to continue into Thrutch and Wiese or forge your own way up the wall. Top out.

name: Over My Head
description: I don't know the real name of this route, so I call it Over My Head.    It is located right next to Harappan Civilization. It is to the right of the graffiti "Tumot Off." start right under the "Off" and work your way up to reach the obvious two-finger pocket. This is a blind move so good luck finding it. After you hit the pocket, work the roof and "top it out."     I haven't got this route yet but I know people who have.

name: The Overhang
description: About 100 yards east of Calm, The Overhang can be found in a leaf-filled corridor. Start sitting at the bottom of the steepest part of the corridor and climb directly out tiered roofs. The right wall is most definitely off.     The Overhang was attempted for years until a small block was pulled off with hand pressure. The removal of this block created a hold and allowed this problem to go. For a while, the block still sat at the base, and it was possible to put the block back in, thereby making the problem much, much harder. It was sort of like two for the price of one. These days, the block is long gone.      This is a classic problem on good stone with a worthwhile top out. When climbing on this, you almost forget you're at High Cliff.

name: Poison Berry
description: This route is located in the leaf-filled corridor. It is right by "The Overhang." It starts in the corner and uses the the right wall to gain the upper part of the roof. Climb through the upper jugs and top it out.    This route is a very fun "warm-up" route before tackling "The Overhang." It requires some intricate hand matches. The top-out is also not bad- a rare occurrence at High Cliff.

name: Sexytime Traverse
description: This traverse starts on the far right hand side of the crag, just as you get to the bottom of the stone staircase. Start on large jug that is about chest height.  Traverse left past "Local on the Eights" staying low using the large shelf.  Choose your path moving left through "Calm Like a Bomb" (You can go high or low through this section). Continue traversing left under the steep roof using pockets and small crimps until you reach the more vertical face of "Mono Problem".  Get a good no-hands rest here and go left past the crack through the last 50 feet of easier climbing. End on the far left corner of the crag.  A serious pump-fest!

name: Syzygy
description: SDS with left hand in the little circle pocket of Bison Corposantics, work up to large flake fin with a variety of good holds to get to the top. Straight line up.

name: Those are Combines Kickin' Up That Dust
description: Apologies to James McMurtry. This takes what I would consider to be the most "natural" and direct line up the face from the "Bison's Mouth". SDS from the "Mouth" and the righthand pocket(it actually helps) then take the path of least resistance straight up to the first ledge.    Downclimb or jump into the waiting arms of you spotters.

name: Thrutch and Wiese
description: Thrutch and Wiese climbs up the center of the face to the left of the long roof. This face is slightly overhanging and the holds are quite good. Top out. A sit start is possible but adds little difficulty.

name: The Traverse of the Gods
description: The Traverse of the Gods starts on the far left side of the wall and traverses rightward to finish on Thrutch and Wiese. Attempts have been made to continue the traverse across the long low roof, but each subsequent climber has been thwarted...much like those who attemped the Eiger Nordwand before its eventual first ascent.     As it stands now, though, the long traverse offers quite a pump and topping out on Thrutch and Wiese becomes a challenge in its own right.

name: We're Going Streaking!
description: SDS on the obvious rail in the streak, then climb bigger holds through easier moves to the first ledge. The crux is probably not dabbing on the first two moves.    Downclimb or jump into the waiting arms of you spotters.

name: What's the Difference Between Jam and Jelly?
description: SDS then combine face holds with perfect hand jams to ascend this aesthetic crack to the first ledge.    Downclimb or jump into the waiting arms of you spotters.

name: White Bruce Lee
description: This is an easy problem that is good for warming up your heel hooking prowess. Two jugs for a start and two feet under the "roof" lead to a right heel hook. From there two bomber wrap arounds on a block right in front of your face occupy your hands. From the wraps there are a few nice holds to the top, like I said, easy.

name: Star Destroyer
description: Start on two smallish crimps, one just under the arete and the obvious one out of the roof for the right hand. Put a heel/toe out and left and do a bump move to a pocket and up to the tip of the prow and topout.

name: Aimless Wanderer
description: Start sitting on good ledge climb up through good holds to two pods at the roof, hike a high foot and cross to the amazing 3 finger pocket, swoop to a block pinch and then quest up the tall face or drop once you are on jugs.

name: Blood Sucker
description: Start match on good large ledge move up through good holds to the roof, then grab a two finger pocket with the left and compress the arete on the right until you gain the jugs. Climb up and left on good holds being cautious that the holds in the top are solid.

name: The Botanist
description: Start under the middle of the roof, climb up to a some smaller incut holds under the larger roof and climb into the right arete, follow the arete to the apex of the boulder.

name: Deluge
description: Start sitting on jug ledge, climb up steep prow to a two finger pocket, then make a long move to better holds up high. This may have my vote for the best problem at High Cliff.

name: Fly-tipper
description: Start seated on a jug under the middle of the roof, crank a big move to the large block/jug and climb out the roof to the right on good holds and topout onto the slab up and to the right.

name: Fungi Shelf
description: Start matched on the lip of the roof and climb up to gain better holds above.

name: Gaslighting
description: Start sitting matched on undercling, climb up compressing the prow feature. Climb up to large jugs, hang and drop.

name: The Gentry
description: Start on good pockets just under roof, climb out through two miserable pockets on the roof to better holds above. Top out up and left.

name: Lagomorph
description: Start match on good ledge at chest height and climb straight out the roof using an awesome pinch and some edges.

name: Lost in the choss
description: Start on two horizontal crimps, bump left for another solid crimp. Find a way straight up for a big horizontal pinch. Then work your way up and to the right to finish. End Of the route isn’t a top out since we didn’t want to clean the bushes up there. Finish is standing on the last jug

name: Mono a Mono
description: Start on large sloping ledge under the right side of the roof, grab a mono on the roof (hence the pun) and pull to edges above the roof. Pro tip, tape you finger before grabbing the mono.

name: Nickel and Dimed
description: Start left hand pocket and right hand good edge. Climb directly up staying to the left of the large crack. Beware of some loose rock when toping this one out, or hang and drop from good jugs up high.

name: Nomad
description: Start as for Aimless Wanderer, but trend left along a series of good holds. The topout is unfortunately blocked by a fallen tree, so drop off once you hit jugs. A good warmup for the area.

name: The Resident
description: Start sitting on large jug shelf, climb up on small holds to easier climbing above.

name: Sadness
description: Start matched on incut crimp, climb out the roof using the incut holds to the right, the rock quality of the feet is less desirable as you exit the roof.

name: Sorrow
description: Start with both hands on an incut crimp, climb out and left through the roof using a series of jugs to the top.

name: Tierdrop
description: Start matched on the incut crimp, toss in a heel toe cam out right and climb directly out the roof.

name: Thanatopsis
description: This is also a very cool boulder problem. When walking down the trail, Thanatopsis is located in a little cove.     Start with a sit start and work you way straight up. Both walls are off (aka- no stemming). After pulling through the two small roofs. Either end after the big ledge or if you are on top-rope all the way up. I have never done it on top-rope because the boulder section is the best.

name: Access Route
description: Surprisingly fun for a glorified access gully.  This route is generally only climbed in order to set up a toprope for a neighboring route on The Stairway Tower.

name: The Bee's Knees
description: Climbs a broken crack system with jugs and crimps throughout the climb. 2/3 the way up is a dirty ledge with gravel.

name: King Louie
description: Start seated low and left on the juggy pillar, climb up and right to a large deadpoint for a loaf hold over the lip, continue to jugs up high.

name: Mowgli
description: Start seated on jug and follow the right side of bulge feature.

name: Shere Khan
description: Start low on two good holds and climb up to a committing dyno.

name: Eternity in the City
description: Sit start on the blocks to the right, climbing through the roof. Throw around the lip and follow good holds to the ledge.

name: Bobby's World
description: Start on crappy pinch and crimp up to good jugs then crux move to a one and a half finger pebble with left hand then up to sloper with right top out on obvious crimpers

name: Dangerous Music
description: The climb is pretty straight-forward. There are a half-dozen obvious holds. The crux of the problem is reaching for and getting past the big reach up to a crack on the overhang.

name: The green mile
description: Traverse from the corner of the boulder across from Bobby's world, to about five feet from the left corner and top out

name: midsummers night dyno
description: Start on rail in the back then dyno to big jug over the roof caution: super dabby feet. Use the crack systems to the right going up then to the two finger pocket bumping up to the flake. After that top out.

name: Minestrone
description: Pronounced "min-eh-strone-ee," this route starts on a decent pair of ledges, swoops left, and climbs straight up the face while staying off the right arete. Fairly sustained throughout on smaller holds, better quality rock than the surrounding area. Leave the bird's nest where it be.

name: Muscle up
description: Variation of Bobby's world instead of going right to the pebble you go left to a crack and under cling and bump up crimps to pocket and top out

name: Season Killer
description: Sit start the left corner of the overhang. This is the crux. Pull up on small right ledge and tiny left crimp just above your head. Large bump up to gain first legde. Pull up and grab sloper with left hand.  Move feet to get ready for huge move to gain main overhang. There are a few ways to continue. Once over the overhang, it's pretty easy moving to the top.

name: Spookier than Soup
description: Cool little arete climb with a seemingly-sketchy fall, but pretty safe if you stay on the arete and right face.  Starting on the obvious ledge under the mini roof, bump up on adequate jugs and sidepulls and get your feet over the roof (crux). Hug the arete, take a seat and rest a little. Pull up using a slopey crimp and a optional mono, then shoot for the horn and top out. To achieve the grade, use high starting feet; stay off of the mossy lower block (see pic).  Most importantly however, enjoy the outdoors.

name: spring green
description: Start just to the right midsummers night dyno lower in the roof. Traverse to the right then out over the roof then traversing left to link up to the top half of midsummers nigh dyno

name: Why not?
description: Start down really low on crimpy ledge work your way over on small jugs then huge crux move to sloper the hard part is trying not to cut feet or you hit the ground then another big move to ledge and top out

name: Vacant Fractal
description: When I first sighted this line, I didn't think I could do it.  After a few trips out cleaning other things, I gave it a legit attempt and discovered it was within the realm of possibility.  The super-low start is interesting, just wish it was a bit longer and higher.  Starting low and sideways on a bulgey sloper with meticulous feet out to the right, fire up to a crimp without losing sight of the proximate sloper.  Once established here, move up and left towards the upper jugs and top out.  First move or two is the crux.

name: Vessel in Passing
