description: This thing is sequencey to the max.  Tons of options, but string the moves wrong and you'll be double-checking the grade.  Once unlocked however, this route is a blast - just don't forget your beta between visits.  Starting on a light-colored chest-level chossy formation, move left through your choice of crimps and slopers to link up with the second half of Vacant Fractal, hitting increasingly better holds and topping out on ze jugs.  Crux is the move to the first shared hold, a sloper.

name: Acid Jazz
description: This climb begins will powerful moves on crimps and one finger pockets. Moving up to very balanced moves to the top. Sit start on small crimps to move up to a 2 finger pocket. From there bump up to another hard crimp on your left. Then gain middle ledge with right hand and move up to the sequency balanced section. Pull up on small vertical crack to gain some small crimps. Top out and your done. Avoid the ledges (left and right) on the upper face.

name: Avant-Funk
description: This route enticed me while cleaning Tribal Groove to the left, and looked difficult, a rarity for this place.  Unsure if I would be the one to bag the FA, I rap-cleaned it anyway.  Glad I did, because it's awesome - the beginning is meh which prohibits me from assigning 4 stars.  *DANGER DANGER: There is a slightly loose block stuck up in the arete that would make for an ultra-jug, so don't use it.  The route climbs better without it anyway, in my opinion.  Start low on a large block that seems like it may come off (probably won't).  Work your way through some boring little pockets and a matchable ledge until you hit the two equal-altitude pockets.  With seemingly nothing to grab at this point, throw for the left arete (crux, but some options here) in order to eventually strike the high slit pocket to the right.  Top out using your preference of dusty jugs.

name: Tribal Groove
description: This route involves interesting movement on some great features.  Might be a few ways to succeed on this one - the following description is what worked for me (WARNING: IMMINENT VAGUE BETA).  Starting with a left hand on a face dish and right in a slightly lower side pocket, move up to the large pocket and utilize a high sidepull and sweet crimp in order to shoot for an even higher pocket and weird pinchy thing.  Top out slightly to the left at first using jugs, but traverse to the right and up next to the chossy pillar.  Crux moving from big pocket.  Climbs better (and a bit harder) in my opinion if you stay off the tempting fern-covered left foot when in the pocket.  Ferns are cool, keep them alive.

name: Betty's Delight
description: Start in the middle of the face going straight up until the first ledge and then hanging a slight right on some good holds to the top.

name: Choss Chimney
description: Start to the right of the pillar and go up the chimney. Didn't break off any hold when I was there but there are some loose holds.

name: Cooper
description: On the right side of the Africa face is fun route with crimps and pockets flowing into a nice cross-over finish.

name: Cowboy Slab
description: Slab with deep finger pockets.  Don't use the arete that goes up the right side staircase.  Sit start on the right with finger pockets.

name: Dream Builder
description: Nice problem with big moves.  Sit start with right hand on the jug around the corner and left hand on the obvious sloper.  Top out in the dish on top.

name: High Traverse clockwise
description: Sit Start:  At down climb ramp.  Left hand on round pocket, right on large jug.  Then left hand to side-pull crimp/flake. Work your way left to pockets and move up, traversing lip of overhang.  Crux comes with left hand on shallow 3 finger pocket, right hand pinch, dropping down to a 2 finger left hand pocket.  Then stay low working your way around to the north side of the boulder, to a no hands rest.  Stay low and one last moderate move around the plaque to finish where you started.  The climb stays off the upper lip completely.

name: Humpty Dumpty Buffalo
description: Huge right heel hook sit start.  Hand traverse across the top of the dish overhang.  Connect up with Humpty Dumpty Buffalo Direct Top Out.

name: Humpty Dumpty Buffalo Direct
description: Sit start with left foot flagged and right foot on the arete.  Reach up left to the slopey dish and then follow the obvious arete and crack up direct.  Excellent knee jam halfway through so you can rest your arms.

name: Irony-Cross
description: Sit start in right side of alcove on south-west face.  Right hand on undercling, left hand on center rib.  Pop up to slopey dish, match.  Then only use holds in alcove, work your way into an Iron cross.  Hit the right hand crimper in the back of the cove and finish up and left.

name: Jacob's Ladder
description: Really juggy problem with an interesting top out, depending out how you do it.  Deep, Vertical pockets.

name: Jake's Alcove
description: Sit start on the lower X marked crimp and X marked pinch. Follow X's to the top lip. All feet that are between the two black lines are on.

name: Jungle Fever
description: Climbs the arete feature on the plaque side of boulder.I am not ultra familiar with boudlering grades but i think v2 is some what accurate. This problem could probably be done easier or harder, but i feel this way is one of the funnest. (Sit start to right hand undercling, match on sloper just above, bump right hand to good edge then bump again to slopy hold near top)

name: Jungle Gym
description: climbs the plaque side of jakes rock, but stays in the left alcove of the side. Another fun easy problem with eliminates to make it harder.

name: jungle juice
description: Sit start. Climbs right corner, making use of a left hand gaston on good edge. Hands are marked in photo. Any feet go.

name: Lay Low
description: Sit start with a right hand gaston in the corner. Layback traverse across ledge. Top out.

name: Pocket Protector
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: Ropes and Shovels
description: Start this gem with two hands on the flake and left toe in pocket. Work left to a tasty finger pocket and juicy under cling pinch to another hairy pinch up and left. Hit it with some fancy footwork and reach up and right for optimism and a soon to be send. Refer to pic for a trail map to this treasure.

name: Slap Happy
description: Short fun move. It may be more difficult because I have "reach" issues.    Start in corner, hugging arete, deadpoint to sloper at top of bolder. Match hands, raise feet, mantle.

name: 14 Days Later
description: A decent warm up for the other routes. Start with both hands on a solid ledge. Pull to a juggy protrusion top-left of the start. Make your way up to a solid jug by a vertical crack, then top out.

name: Cowboys in Limbeau
description: Two hand start on ledges. Right hand up to block, hand-foot-match left start. Left hand over top to small block. Hand-foot-match big block. Right hand cross under to small jug. Pull up with the right hand and left foot to finish left hand in slot jug and match.

name: EIN HEFTMACHINE!
description: WHAT'S ON:         Start with one hand pinching on the protruding rock toward the bottom of the wall, and the other hand on a small side crimp to the right of it. Then there is the pinch above the left starting hold, pocket above right starting hold, deep pocket to the left under the roof, side crimp immediately above that, pocket above and to the right of the last pocket and a crimp on the top roof edge. The crux is getting the two roof pockets. I marked the holds with chalk, so hopefully it's easier to find where I'm talking about ​ HOW I DID IT:         I started with my left hand pinching on the protruding rock by having my hand facing left on it and getting my thumb on the very small notch in the middle of the right side of it for a little leverage, the other hand was on the small side crimp, my left foot was on the small ledge directly under the left starting hold, and my right foot was heel hooking the ridge to the right of the starting crimp. Then I moved my left hand and hammered down on the pinch, did a sort-of gaston to the upper pocket, rocked my heel hook to standing on my toe, switched feet so my left foot was where my right foot was and my right foot is flagging out to the right. Then I grabbed the deep pocket, walked my feet over to where my left foot was on the left ridge(chalk on it) and my right foot on the left starting hold as I grabbed the pinch above the deep pocket, then I did a small Dyno to grab the pocket above on the side of the middle roof with my left hand while I hammered down on the pinch with my right hand to slow the momentum, then grab the other roof pocket with my right hand, right when I have both hands in those pockets, I get my feet back on the wall, move my left hand to the finish crimp, and lastly move my right hand over to match the finish.

name: The Gingerbread Man's Garage
description: Mostly good holds, gets a little rowdy on the roof hold and the pinch, but all around smooth. Start with right hand on square jug and left hand on sharp-ish side pole, move to small ledge, cruddy pinch, roof pocket, Guestimate a Dyno to the edge on roof, match on the top  Be careful to not hit your left leg when you're approaching the roof, both my girlfriend and myself hit our shins from our legs slipping there, doesn't feel good, but was still a fun route.

name: Love, Lindsey
description: Start on protruding jug about chest high, grab side pole, move feet up, grab small ledge, grab crack in rock, semi-hidden pocket in edge, then finish at top edge.

name: Threat Level Midnight
description: Starts with a mono and side pinch, then grab the deep slab above side pinch, match, grab a mini arete thingy, small Dyno to mini jug, Grab the hidden pocket, Dyno to finish on roof edge.

name: Chestnut's Day Out
description: Lots of crimps and and pinches for the designed route, but there are also lots of good holds around it to catch yourself if you are about to fall. The crux is moving your foot to the toe hook position while grabbing the right side crimp.

name: Chutbacca
description: Climb the middle of the wall using the two cracks.

name: Couples Retreat
description: Stand start with left hand crimp and right hand on prominent side pull. Climb up the bulge using good holds and compression then topout.

name: EZ Rider
description: Start the same as EZ Traverse. Find your way to a stance right above the ground and go for the top out.

name: EZ Traverse
description: A close to the ground boulder that can be done with your sleeping pad. Traverse right, starting with hands matched on the left most pedestal. Do some cool moves to avoid the wet and dirty feet. Finish by stepping onto the small boulder.

name: Family Therapy
description: Start on the right most jug and traverse left before finding a high foot and standing up on the large rail. Move up finding higher feet and slopers near the top. There is a big left and right hand jug that can be used for the top out. A heady problem for the grade. Crux is near the top.

name: Singing Sands
description: Start on the large sidepull jug. Climb up the arete using cool jugs and compressions.

name: Found in a Nightmare
description: Start on a horizontal edge beneath the dihedral. Climb through the dihedral, trending left to the face and top out using an awesome bread loaf jug.

name: Le Ledges
description: On wall just right of Lost in a Dream.. Not great but a warm up and kinda funky.  Start sitting with a hollow flake, bust big left to the slanting ledge and continue on through slopes and better holds.  Might be more fun to just start on the slanting ledge.  And that hollow start hold might just break.

name: Lost in a Dream
description: Start at the base and climb the massive compression feature. An exceptional problem.

name: Naptime
description: Start on the jug and climb up through the mini-dihedral.

name: Narcolepsy
description: pull up and over the roof. Pull through or around the tree.

name: Polysomnography
description: Start at the base and climb the other side of the arete/face of the Lost in a Dream boulder

name: Slumber
description: Start on good holds in the horizontal breaks and climb through more of the same.

name: 1-Up
description: Start right hand undercling, left slope.. Move right via a long reach and likely a dyno, depending on reach, into the center of the face and top out.  On boulder right of Baby Bella and same boulder (and finish) as Ascomycota.

name: Amphotericin
description: Stand start matched on a sloper. Follow sloper rail to the right, eventually reaching a tricky topout mantle.

name: Ascomycota
description: Starts on obvious lower right jug with a high left foot and climbs through the diagonal seam up and left to top out.

name: Baby Bella
description: Squeeze the mushroomy prow. Sit start with right hand incut slopey hold and left hand perfect half pad crimp. Thruch out left and start compressing.

name: Backyard Forager
description: Start on two edges in the horizontal rail. Do a long pull, then mantle the lip.

name: Blue Aster
description: Starts as for Wood Violet, but climbs straight up using crack and cool holds. The detached ramp is off.

name: Candida Goose
description: Sit start in the dihedral left of Death Cap with a jug left hand undercling and right hand on a small dihedral edge above the jug. Climb up the dihedral with tricky feet

name: Caps and Stems
description: Starting left hand on arete and right low on undercling/sidepull, move up prow to tricky top out.

name: Chanterelle
description: Sit start on jug break. Climb the striking arete.

name: The Cultivator
description: Start as for "Puffball" (left hand on arete, right hand on low sidepull edge on left side of the wall). After sticking the first move of that, traverse the slopey lip to the mantle of "Backyard Forager" on the far right side of the wall.

name: Daylily
description: Start on left hand side pull and right hand flat edge. Climb the tall slab. Stays on you the whole time.

name: Deathcap
description: Start on the jug at chest height. Climb straight up through good holds and interesting moves.

name: Fly Amanita
description: Climb obvious features to top.

name: Garden Variety
description: Start matched in the thin crack. Bust a big move left and proceed to negotiate the tricky lip mantle.

name: Goombas
description: Start lower rock move up the arete to reaching top out

name: Hyphae
description: SDS on sidepull rail. Climb straight up through crack systems to a tricky top.

name: Inocybe
description: Top side pull tricky switch grip

name: Lilac
description: Stand start on large sidepull jug. Climb cool rounded granite rails up the slab.

name: Lion's Mane
description: Start on good edges. Long moves lead up the slab.

name: Morel Compass
description: SDS on arete with left hand edge and right hand gaston. Climb the arete up and left, eventually topping out as for Deathcap.

name: Muscimol
description: Start on two positive vertical edges. Climb the slab.

name: Mycelium
description: Sit start matched on good edge. Climb cool features up the slab.

name: Nystatin
description: Stand start with left hand on arete and right hand with good edge on the face. Climb tenuous moves up the sloper arete and rail systems. Detached blocks are not used.

name: Prototaxites
description: Start in the break, with good feet. Climb directly up the blank slab to the right of the crack seam.

name: Puffball
description: An intriguing move that might just suck you in..  and with the pretty cool grips.  Start left hand on the arete on the best spot (about head height) and right on a low prominent sidepull.  Fire to the lip and move left to finish.

name: Rare Breed
description: Start the same as Garden Variety (matched in the thin crack) and do the first move, but instead of jumping to the lip, continue following the crack left.

name: Ringworm
description: Sit start with left hand on rounded arete and right hand sloper. Several slaps lead over the bulge. Pretty fun, for a dumpy boulder.

name: Saffron
description: Stand start on sloper jug. Climb sidepulls up gently overhanging wall. Detached blocks and wall to the right are not used.

name: Shiitake
description: SDS on left hand side pull and right hand crimp. Climb through the thin seam to a sweet sloper pinch and a huge dyno.

name: Shroomin'
description: Short but sweet route starts with obvious left hand side pull. Find a few more holds and then bust a big move to a good hold.. top out on juggy ledges.    Movement on here is good and the holds are all positive. V2 for shorter folks

name: Spore
description: Climb the cool compression feature to a tricky topout (for the grade). A classic warmup!

name: Thallus
description: Start on the large ledge. A delicate mantle leads to the lower angle slab, where cool holds and desperate moves await.

name: Thrush
description: Stand start on side pulls. Climb the short bulge.

name: Toadstool
description: Start on side pulls and climb the vertical features.

name: Tulip
description: Sit start with right hand edge and left hand side pull. Climb tricky moves up the slab.

name: Twenty Side Pieces
description: Start matched in the crack on a triangle block.

name: Wood Violet
description: Start on two edges. Climb left through awesome sloper rail features to an easing top. The detached ramp is off.

name: Amphibole
description: From a stand, climb the short slab and top out.

name: Blue Calcite
description: SDS on large jug. A few moves lead up the arete.

name: Celestine
description: SDS under the bulge with right hand on a faint edge and left hand on a scoop dish. Powerful and tricky moves lead up the bulge. Last move is a heartbreaker!

name: Kennebec
description: Stand start with left hand pinch and right hand side pull. Climb straight up over the bulge and top out.

name: Olivine
description: Start compressing the aretes and climb the pretty slab.

name: Pyrite
description: SDS in thin crack. Tricky moves lead up the face to the left.

name: Pyroxene
description: Stand start with left hand jug and right hand side pull jug. Climb the face using obvious features and top out.

name: White Potato
description: An elegant little climb..   Start with a right hand pinch and left hand below.  Jump to a sloper edge and finish it up.

name: Big Thunder
description: Start on obvious crimps and climb overhanging face, likely using a jug up and right.

name: Bone & Amber
description: Stand start with left hand on arete, right hand on lower jug edge. Climb directly up the tricky arete.

name: Elaeis
description: SDS on obvious rail/undercling. Climb the narrow compression feature.

name: Immortal Light
description: Start on top of the pedestal in the corner. Step out over the abyss and climb the tall slab.

name: Menhir
description: Stand start compressing arete below the break. Climb the cool feature.

name: Naphtha
description: Stand start on large block and do several powerful moves up the short bulge.   *Only accessible in the winter, when the water is frozen*

name: Reclaimed World
description: SDS on large edge. Climb several crimps to the refrigerator compression feature.

name: Terraform
description: SDS on jug and climb straight up through an awesome sloper. The sloper stays wet for a while after rain.

name: Tony's Dyno
description: SDS on sidepull rail. Hit a small slopey rail and bust right to a good hold.

name: Vanna White
description: SDS matched on good edge. Climb a series of crimps into the same topout as Vantablack.

name: Vantablack
description: Stand start with left hand edge and right hand sidepull. Climb the intimidating face.

name: Chris Harrison
description: Stand start moving into obvious shelf. Rock a high right foot to a committing mantel for a high right finger bucket. Get feet onto shelf and finish out left

name: Drew Carrey
description: Easy climb up obvious features left of the drill holes.

name: Panacea
description: SDS on two good edges. Climb straight up tricky granite holds. Large detached block is used for feet, but all smaller detached flakes under the boulder are not used.

name: Snake Oil
description: SDS on two edges (same start as Panacea). Traverse right through a series of slopers and continue up the right arete using a slopey jug and rugged crimp. The large detached block is used for feet.

name: Soggy Logs
description: Start left hand in runnel and right hand crimp. Climb thin and tricky moves to the break. Traverse right to the arete and continue to the top. The direct line is an open project.

name: Trebek
description: Crimpy route following drill marks up and onto hollow flake.

name: Eddy
description: Start with obvious edges. A dynamic move left leads to an easing top. A little morpho.  *Only accessible when water is low or frozen*

name: Moai
description: Stand start left hand on arete, right hand on gaston edge. Tricky and interesting moves lead up the compression feature.

name: Ripple Effect
description: Stand start with right hand incut jug edge and left hand on a very poor sloper pinch. Climb interesting moves directly up the arete. The upper section is a little tenuous.

name: Undertow
description: Start on obvious edges (same start as Eddy). Move right through a tough gaston move and up a series of edges.   *Only accessible when water is low or frozen*

name: Whiskey Sour
description: From a left hand sloper and right hand undercling, pull on and slap up the feature. Either step off the flake or choose your own adventure to finish.Detached blocks are not used.

name: Wisconsin Old Fashioned
description: Stand start on right hand edge, left hand on the arete. Climb the overhanging face and arete. Top is committing. For full value, starting from a sit on two blocks adds a few fun moves.

name: Flat Earth
description: Climb the left side of the overhanging face

name: Iridescent
description: Stand start on left hand edge, right hand sloper pinch. Powerful moves lead directly up the overhanging arete.

name: Opalescent
description: SDS on two sidepull edges which face the same direction. Bust a big move to the jug break, then continue up a series of crimps.

name: The Balducci Levitation
description: Stand start on the large edge and climb the aesthetic arete.

name: I Cannot Lie
description: Start on a hard sit start and climb crack to top out on some jugs. Crux is the crack just before the jugs and top out.

name: I Like Jugs
description: Start on left hand low jug, right hand high jug. Match before making long reach to high jug and topping out. Possible harder variation starting with right hand on a low crimp in SDS.

name: Mercury Fold
description: Stand start with good left hand side pull on the arete and low right hand undercling on the face. Trend upwards and to the right arete using tricky moves and cool slopers. Top out.

name: Moby Dick
description: SDS with right hand side pull and left hand crimp on prominent rail. Bump up to obvious jug and right hand crimp. Make a dynamic move to jug near the top. Tricky top out.

name: Psychic Surgery (Project)
description: Start on a good low jug to the left. Traverse the long overhanging crack to a jug. Top out. Probably not too difficult, but will require more cleaning and I have yet to see it fully dry.

name: Radium Girl
description: Jump start to good ledge, get a high foot and tech your way up the seam, reach out right to a good edge on the face and topout.

name: Real Magic
description: Start left hand on a nice jug edge and right hand on a side pull. After a large first move to the shelf, head up the obvious side pulls and a long reach to the lip.

name: Second Sight
description: Start left hand on an undercling and right hand on a lower good edge. Climb up through a cool granite hueco to thinning holds and a delicate top. Each move is more difficult than the last!

name: Tenkai Palm
description: Start matched in the cool granite hueco. A mantle move leads to better holds up high.

name: Trompe L'oeil
description: Start as for Mercury Fold but climb straight up the technical blunt arete using a series of sidepulls and slopers to gain the top.

name: Night Terrors
description: Start on a jug. Climb powerful moves up the aesthetic compression feature.

name: Nightwatcher (Project)
description: Find a way to climb the slab

name: Nyctophilia
description: Low start on good left hand edge and right hand on sloper rail. Climb straight up through the large black circle.

name: The Red Dance
description: Sit start on two jugs and climb through amazing polished granite aretes.

name: Swirling Sea
description: Stand start on aretes. Climb the squeeze pillar.

name: Weathered by Waves
description: SDS left hand thin edge, right hand on arete. Climb the overhanging face.

name: Black Locust
description: SDS matched on undercling jug. Climb left through a series of poor holds then straight up powerful moves.

name: Bristleweed
description: Start matched on the jug, then climb the compression feature

name: Buckthorn
description: SDS matched on undercling jug. Climb up and right through a series of very powerful moves.

name: Red as Rouge
description: SDS matched on large detached block. Climb interesting moves out of the overhang.
Stand start on horizontal break, then climb the slab eventually using two very poor pockets.

name: Buckshot
description: SDS on obvious ledge underneath the roof. Climb up and right through several good holds, eventually reaching a crux deadpoint to the lip off of a bad pinch.

name: Christ Almighty
description: SDS on low jug, using big blocks for feet. Climb through one very poor hold to a gradually easing crack system.

name: Cronus
description: Stand start on jugs. Traverse the horizontal crack, then top out.

name: The Cull
description: Sand start matched in the horizontal rail. Climb directly up through more of the same.

name: Flintlock
description: Start on left side of the wall. Climb tenuous moves on vertical crimps up to the horizontal break. From here, traverse right to the slopey arete, then top out.

name: Hera
description: Start on large block, then climb the crack.

name: Hyperion
description: Stand start on a jug (same start as Cronus), then climb powerful and tenuous moves up the diagonal crack.

name: Miss Saigon
description: Start matched in horizontal break. Climb more of the same to two mono pockets, eventually reaching a tenuous topout.

name: The Odyssey
description: Start on two good ledges. Climb directly up the center of the tall face using a series of rails and a small pod. Once at the high horizontal break, trend a bit right to reach easier terrain.

name: Over Under
description: Stand start on left hand undercling, right hand notch. Climb up and right through the sloper rail.

name: Pegasus
description: Start as for the Odyssey (on two good ledges near the center of the wall). Climb the first few moves to the first large rail, then traverse right to meet up with "Perseus." Top out as for that.

name: Pellet Gun
description: SDS on hidden left hand undercling, right hand sidepull. Climb the face

name: Persephone
description: SDS on vertical rail. Climb up and left through a series of small crimps and underclings, eventually meeting up with the arete/crack or "Hera". Top out as for that.

name: Perseus
description: Start on large jug. Climb straight up through rail and crack features.

name: Pump Action
description: Stand start on large sidepulls, then climb the arete, eventually topping out as for "Over Under"

name: Red Forest
description: Start low in the diagonal crack on a jug. Traverse the crack to the left, then head up awesome granite features to a highball topout.

name: Red Ryder
description: SDS on left hand sidepull, right hand on hidden horn. Climb the compression feature.

name: Rimfire
description: Stand start on diagonal rail. Several big moves lead up interesting holds.

name: Side-by-Side
description: SDS on obvious ledge under the roof. Climb up and left through compression moves, eventually reaching a technical seam.

name: Slug
description: Start low on two good edges climb up and left through tenuous moves to a small right facing dihedral

name: Sunfisher
description: Scramble up the ramp, then do several easy moves to a tenuous mantle that you wouldn't want to biff.

name: Theseus
description: Start on large undercling flake. Climb through the short roof and continue up the compression feature.

name: Year of the Tiger
description: Start low in the diagonal crack. Bust a big move straight up to a jug, then continue up technical moves on small holds. The topout is a horrifying smear mantle 20 feet off the deck.

name: Zeus Almighty
description: SDS on a vertical rail. Climb up and right through interesting holds to a crux deadpoint move off a bad sloper.

name: Astaroth
description: Start on the jug, then climb the thin seam.

name: Azazel
description: SDS on left hand sidepull jug and right hand crimp. Climb the aesthetic overhanging arete.

name: Enoch
description: Start matched on the obvious flake. Climb technical moves directly up the center of the face. An exceptional problem.

name: Hollow Moon
description: Start matched on an edge. Climb tricky and powerful moves up the overhanging bulge.

name: Nephilim
description: Start on the jug and climb through the diagonal crack

name: Bloody Ankles
description: Start low on good right hand side pull and left hand on corner.  Work your way up slaping the left corner and top out.  Powerfull!

name: Chippewa Blood
description: Sit start to Bloody Ankles.

name: Crimpin' Clint
description: Hard variation to Monico Steep.  Has seen few repeats.    Climb up steep boulder using only crimpy rails.  The arete is off.

name: Easy Ankles
description: Far right side of Bloody Ankles boulder-- follow rail up left to Bloody Ankles topout...  V1? V2?

name: Graffiti Face Project
description: Figure out a way to get up the first face you see when arriving at Monico Boulders...  I was working on the left side with a bit of the left arete and trying not to use the smaller boulder...  don't know what will go but it looks pretty think and fun.   Another way would be to start low on the right and follow the rail up left all the way.

name: Monico Steep
description: Climb steep boulder with good arete on right and jugs for the finish.

name: Project
description: Slapping and heel-hooking, climb up tall and holdless arete.       The first larger picture on the main home page is the project.

name: V0-
description: Climb small easy boulder.

name: Warm Up 2
description: easy warm up-- see picture section- sit start on low ledge and use vertical crack on right side.

name: Breed
description: SDS with right hand jug, left hand undercling jug. Climb a series of crimps up the steep overhang.

name: Estrus
description: SDS with large left hand left hand undercling, right hand low on the arete. Several tough compression moves lead up the overhanging block.

name: and God blessed the trees
description: Hug the cracks to get your feet up on the obvious shelf. Right hand moves up to a jam near the top, left hand grabs the broken chunks wedged in the first of the 3 finger-like cracks. Crux is then smearing up to foot pocket at mid-wall and toping out just left of the ferns.

name: Bring the blaze orange.
description: Follow a thin dirty lichen covered seam via a few well placed feet to the top. Just a little something for an afternoon finger burn if you're in the area.

name: CamelBak
description: Big juggy holds on the lower part suitable for slight lay-back start. Left hand moves up to a crimp. Right foot matches right hand on jug and right hand moves up to high crimp. Left hand moves up to large sloper top out.

name: Keelhaulin'
description: Start at the base of the prow/arête feature. Utilize good sidepulls and crimps on either side to gain the tree. Hoist yourself up and enjoy the view. You might want a spotter, as this one's right over the drink!

name: Gangster of Love
description: Sit start, big reach up to the nice hold for your right hand, reposition feet and move up the crack.

name: Space Cowboy
description: Stay on the cleaned area of the rock and climb up the first wall. For added difficulty, try not topping out on the first section and transitioning over to the second section from a hang. Be careful on the second section of the climb because falling leads to skinned knees and a little rockslide down to your crashpad. Top out on the second section has some decent holds and a big crack on the far right.

name: Low Wing Loaded
description: SDS and throw slap up left arete.  Mantle straight over lip.

name: Road Side Rock Band
description: Play around on all the features right across from the parking spot.  No real names and grades to this spot just some fun.  Can be dirty due to lack of traffic.

name: Short Boulder
description: A couple variations to this boulder and nothing tricky.  Climb all around it for some easy fun.

name: South Facing Rock Bands
description: Climb a number of problems along rock band that faces to the south.  Many good problems that area little harder, but mostly easy and moderate.  Another good area to check out if you have time and are in need to add some FA's to Rib Mt.  Can be dirty due to lack of traffic.

name: Emperor Penguin
description: Climb corner up to good left hand side pull.  From there get feet high and stand to small pocket up near top. Top out.

name: Emperor's New Clothes
description: The main attraction. Climb the direct face of this beautiful high-ball. Crux is at top, the throw to lip off good crimps.  It's a solid problem when with a couple good spotters.

name: Emperor's New Groove
description: Start low on Emperor's new clothes and traverse bottom of left wall.  Pull over bulge and top out.  Good problem with a lot of moves.

name: The Last Emperor (aka Emperor's last stand)
description: Climb face around right side of Emperor's boulder.

name: No Empire
description: Climb steep boulder up and left of Emperor's boulder

name: [Redacted]
description: Start left under bulge and traverse right along crack to face out right.  Mantle top out.

name: Between the Lines
description: Climb thin face between the two cracks.  Using cracks and large ledge on upper right doesn't count.

name: Bird Of Prey
description: Once called the project this climb has since been sent. The climb revolves around a set of small crimps located on the face of the boulder. The route climbs well and the feet are good.   youtube.com/watch?v=RXwWvFy…

name: Butterfly Jam
description: Climb Left Crack on wall.

name: Chubby McTugg'n
description: Climb the right side of the two cracks boulder.  Start on the nice undercling work up face and arete.

name: Dough Arete
description: Stand start with horizontal crack and work your way up the right side arete. SDS-adds a little more difficulty.

name: Fat Kid Slab
description: Climb easy slab left of Fat Kid Slap.

name: Fat Kid Slap
description: Down hill from the Dough arete, on a big over-hanging bulge.  Start under bulge and slap around the lip.  The mantle is the crux.

name: Headstone Traverse
description: Start sitting on ledge under Headstone boulder.  Begin with crimps in crack and throw for the lip.  Traverse lip up and left to top out.

name: The Headstone
description: Start low and work your way up arete.

name: Hug it out
description: Start with left hand sharp crimper on underbelly, right hand on the arete. Then squeeze your way to top.

name: Hug it out (sit start)
description: Sit start in the back of cave using good flakes and work on to suspended block and squeeze your way to the top. The wall on your left side is off.

name: The Mantle Problem
description: Start with good hold and work way up to the top-out.  The mantle is the crux.

name: No Reservations
description: Climb overhanging arete left of mantle problem.

name: None 1
description: Climb corner face of boulder.  Fun warm up.

name: None 2
description: Climb the south face of boulder using reachy crimps and pinches.

name: Over the Top
description: Climb face to the right of the right crack.

name: Pat's empty nest
description: Stand start on the nest hold and move up and left to a good pinch.  From there get high feet and throw up and right to good ledge.  Top out using good holds.

name: Path of Least Resistance
description: Start left of dough arete.  Climb up other arete on boulder not using the large crack on left.  A contrived but fun problem

name: The Raptor
description: Start with hands in crack (right hand jam). Get to small crimp on arete, figure out feet and throw for the slopey ledge up high(crux move) and gun for the top.

name: Right Crack
description: Climb right crack on face

name: Bat in the Cave
description: Start as low as possible in the little cave just right of High Level Mustache's and squirm your way up onto the face on the right of the HLM boulder for the topout.

name: Black Lightning
description: Start by matching low pinch and then move right to the lip and do hand-heel match on the left side move up surfing a series of slopers on arete. Problem is short but powerful.

name: Block Head
description: Sit down start with good edges.  Figure out problem to the top.  Large jug on upper right is off.

name: Butter my block
description: Sit start on good flake and work up right hand up the arete.  Get a undercling with the left hand, hike the feet up and throw for the lip.

name: Easy Face
description: Climb on obvious face.  Nothing tricky here.

name: Feels Like Butter
description: Start with good edges and move up to two finger pocket.  Work your way up to jug rest then up to  matching crimps in horizontal crack.  Hike your foot up high and reach for the top

name: Foot Loose
description: A no hands route for fun!  Using everything but your hands is key.

name: High Level Mustasche's
description: Sit-start on good jug and arete move up using both sides of the block, dyno to top.

name: The Knife Cutter
description: Climb straight up knife like arete.  A lot of body tension and squeezing involved.

name: No Additives
description: Start with good right hand jug and left hand in crack.  Using small two finger crimp move up and left of jug rails on right(they are off) to the top.

name: No Additives Right
description: Climb face to the right of No Additives, using good edges that are "off" of No Additives.

name: None
description: Climb right side of boulder on good holds and using right corner.  Good warm up.

name: None 2
description: Climb face on left side of boulder with good crimps and reachy moves.  Good warm up in the Jurassics.

name: One Move Wonder
description: Start low on bad crimps throw for the lip and mantle.

name: Pink Elephant
description: Start low and climb bulge using arete and pinches.  Good contorted climbing.

name: Frankenstein
description: Climb tall boulder that from the side looks like the monster from Frankenstein.  Crux is at the top.

name: The lonely boulder
description: Sit start and work your way up using the aretes and face holds. There are several different variations and eliminates that are possible. The face holds are surprisingly featured for quartzite and it would be classic if it were taller.

name: Mental Ninjitsu
description: Same start as Seth's Sacrifice, but throw up and right.  Top-out the right side of boulder.

name: No name
description: Climb easy diagonal route to the left of Frankenstein.

name: None
description: Climb easier problem just left of Seth's Sacrifice.

name: Seth's Sacrifice
description: A good 45 degree angle makes this problem one of the steepest in the park.  SDS from good slopey hold down low.  Get a good right toe hook and go for baseball sized pinch.  Establish yourself on undercling and throw for a good edge out left.  From there top out boulder.

name: Orange Sky Grey Gloom
description: Start on the right side of the block on good hold and move left on a series of slopers. Then slap left side of the block, and throw to a rail up and back of the arete. Top out using good pinch and crimpers.

name: Warm Up
description: Climb big holds on west face

name: The Orb (right)
description: Same start as The Orb, just move up and right to crimpers and undercling, then big move to the top.

name: The Orb
description: Start low and climb up over big bulges to top.  A must do at Rib.

name: Bluegrass Cat
description: Sit-Start on large jug and move up using crimpers.  Three different variations but all about the same difficulty.

name: By a Nose
description: Sit-start on big undercling move up using series of side-pulls and crimpers, good top-out

name: Cigar
description: Sit-start on good ledge and move through funky curved crack.

name: Iron Mule
description: Start at the base of the doughnut and work your way up and right.  Work the up the arete to good right hand hold, some heel hooks and good finishing holds.

name: Lumpy Stairs
description: Nice little roof/arete combo

name: Man O'War
description: Start on low left hand side of boulder and work right on crimpers to a pocket for left and a good rail for the right and throw up and right to bad slopers and top out.

name: Oak Nose
description: Climb the arete of the nose, sit-start on undercling and move up on arete.

name: No Name Traverse
description: Traverse wall opposite of Pimpin' wall.  Start right to left.

name: Pimpin' and Crimpin'
description: Start low on good crimp and side-pull.  From there get momentum and go up for the pimpin' crimp.  Match crimp and top-out.

name: Pimpin' Left
description: Same start as Pimpin' and Crimpin' but left crack is a good help.

name: Pimpin' Right
description: On main face, start low on small good crimp and side-pull.  Move to sharp flake out right and gun for the pimpin' crimp.  Top-out from there.

name: Pimpin' Traverse
description: Start way left on good low holds.  Traverse the boulder's lip and finish on Pimpin' and Crimpin'.

name: Birds Nest
description: Hard to find, might need a local.  But from Ranger Station, hike down and around the cliff band heading east.  Look for cool line that starts under a little cave and climbs up and out.

name: Dead trees tell no tales
description: pretty short, but plenty of decent holds on the arrete to the left. the top has a few slopers but it isn't too rough.

name: Frosted Flakes
description: It's called frosted flakes because all the holds besides the very top are thin and crimpy. Foot placement is crucial and there are only a few hand moves. The crux in my opinion is when you are on 2 foot flakes and a fingertip sideways crimp and you have to dyno to a top jug.

name: M Claos
description: Sit start with undercling and rail move face to crux on crimpers and moving to a side pull.  Top out through the groove.

name: Oral B
description: Stand start on two small seams and work your up the face on rails to an odd top out.

name: T Vulture
description: Start on pinch with right hand and sloper with left and work up the arete on edges.

name: T.V. Hooker
description: Sit start on good side pulls and work up on a series of side pulls and crimps.  The crux is the top out. (It's all there, just a little heady)

name: Thumbnail
description: Start on corner on good holds and work up arete on good holds and good feet.  Finish on big jug fin.

name: Slot Left
description: Climb the line to the right of the Slot Right problem, using the slot with your left hand.

name: Slot Machine
description: Climb easy face left of the Slot climbs

name: Slot Right
description: Climb face using the V-slot with your right hand.

name: Unearthed
description: Climb overhanging boulder to the north of the slot boulder

name: Cash
description: Sit-Start on low good side-pulls and work up on a series of side-pulls until you get a big rail with the left hand and work up and over the headstone feature.  (Avoid Ledge on right side)

name: Cool July
description: Sit-start on a pinch on the east corner of the metro boulder, work up thought side-pulls and top out avoid big ledge on left side.

name: Feel The Boss
description: Climb up problem left of Smell the Moss.  Low start and good holds with poor feet.  Work your way up to top.      Cool variation if you climb out on left corner, FA: Dobe.

name: Forgot to Floss
description: Sit-start on good rail, go left into gastons, work in in to slopers and follow the crack to top

name: Hipster
description: Work up face on crimpers and underclings

name: I Love Sandra
description: Powerful sit-start in a angled crack move up to left hand sloper and slap to a crescent shape crimp throw to top.  (weird mantel)

name: The Metro Scoop
description: Start in lower scoop feature.  Climb strait up corner to top.

name: Sandra's Crack
description: Climb the crack feature

name: Smell the Moss
description: SDS(V4) on good crimpers.  Move across boulder to right side.  From there move up and left to good side-pull.  Establish and throw for good slopey ledge.  A must do at Rib.  Stand start from right makes it a little easier (V3).

name: Jedi Mind Trick
description: Start low under boulder on right hand crimp and left hand pinch.  Climb up and out under obvious bulge to big horn.  Continue to top and exit on R2-V2.

name: No Name
description: Climb face on boulder just right and up from Star Wars boulder.

name: No Name Corner
description: Climb longer corner problem just right of Star Wars Boulder.

name: Queen Amidala
description: Great solo climb!  Probably the tallest in the park.  Climb R2V2 and just continue up steep face at top.  Do not fall because this is a tall problem.

name: R2-V2
description: A great highball problem.  Start on low jug on right, throw for big ledge out left and climb up middle face to an exit on upper left of boulder.  Jug on right of opening move is off.

name: Buddha Belly
description: Start on low sloper for the right hand and crack for the left.  Move up by squeezing the belly get to the big break one more move to the top. The problem may be shorter but is a must do!

name: Corner the Queen
description: Ascend the north corner of the Queen's Chair using pinches and crimpers.  Careful of the landing, big boulder under problem.

name: Warm Up  1
description: Start on underclings and good feet, move up through good rail and juggy top out.

name: Warm Up  2
description: Start on a two good slots and move through good crimpers and slopers to top.

name: Warm Up  3
description: Start on good hand and dyno to sloper horn

name: Cinderella
description: Climb left arete of boulder with the stretcher.

name: Fancy Feet
description: With feet only, climb up short slab to good blocks.  Walk to finish.

name: No Name
description: Climb easy route left end of Alligator Boulder

name: Stretcher
description: Climb boulder to the left of Alligator boulder stretching out to both sides and slapping up to top.

name: Wrestling Left
description: Climb slab face to the left of Wrestling with Alligators.

name: Wrestling with Alligators
description: Climb slab face with crack and right arete for help.

name: Crab Crawl
description: A great traverse

name: Slap Happy
description: Sit start on the left. Start slapping your way into the overhang. Continue slapping to top out.

name: Too Easy
description: A very easy route, but still fun.

name: Wolf's Face
description: Sit start

name: Wolf's Nose
description: Sit start. First 2 moves are crux.

name: Almost Wimped Out
description: its a triceps rout. Crux is getting onto the first overhang.

name: Belly Scratcher
description: This is a fun rout. You can start with your feet on a ledge in the water and scratch your belly on the way up to the juggy ledge or you can sit on your crimps pull and kick to first edge to avoid the belly rash. Crux is in the middle of the rout as you are reaching high for the last few holds.

name: Clamp to Pocket
description: Crux is a pinch with your left hand with a thumb in a pocket as you readjust your right hand into a pocket, before moving up the obvious edge.

name: Downgrade Traverse
description: From swimming, go up into the far right side of the crack. Traverse allllll the way left until the crack ends. Go up.

name: Moo Moo's
description: Near one of the jumping areas so be cautious. Consistent difficulty throughout climb.

name: Quick Shine
description: Start just right of Moo Moo's, climb towards Moo Moo's and then cop out by heading right toward the lower platform.

name: Here Comes the Bride
description: Gain the crack system from the water. Follow it to the reachable ledges. Send.

name: Maddie Foster
description: Huge jug starts you off. Pull up and right to a horrible pocket. Move up and left from there.

name: Plan Z
description: Start from swimming. Pull hard on the jug to the diagonal ledge system. Work your way up the ledges. Fire the finish.

name: Thunderstruck
description: A bit spicy. Traverse left. Pull the dirty ledges and use the slopey pockets. See photo.

name: Rash Leg
description: Start in water. Reach for obvious jug. Crux is the first move which is a hard cross out right with your left hand. Get high feet. Move the right hand over and pull hard. Easiest with dry rubber (unlikely). Real hard when barefoot.

name: Red Back & Rash Leg
description: Start in cave underneath Leg Rash. There are some great jugs underneath. There will be a swing. Your feet will likely be in the water. The crux is either shared with Leg Rash or it is the exhaustive groping done when searching for the jug outside the cave (long arms help). High quality and rough sandstone. Shoes help a lot if you are soft and your feet can't handle the friction required.

name: Happiness Lake
description: Start to the right of the overhang. See photo for exact start.  Follow bolts.

name: High Life
description: Start low. Find the good ledges to pull big move over the roof and cruise to the top. For the brave (read: ballsy), it could be done as a boulder which ends with pulling over the roof.*Potential loose block around this route - be careful*

name: Jelly Beans for Power
description: Start matched on the big hold. Traverse left to the right facing undercling, then use the pockets up and to the left to make your way up to the ledge. Keep your feet on the right side of the crack while you climb up.

name: Whitney
description: Fun boulder/variation to the start of Can't Trust the Weatherman. Start under the overhang on a sloper.  Big moves up to the juggy holds on the ridge-like formation. Don't use the side pull jug on the left - out of bounds. Using this as the start to Can't Trust the Weatherman makes a fun variation that'll pump you out for the rest of the journey up, about 5.10d.

name: Headstone Left
description: Start with left hand on a slot crimper around the left side of the arete, right hand on the main face.  Use the two crimps on the face to gain the large left leaning rail, and then to the top.

name: Headstone Right
description: Start with your feet in the hole, there is a decent foot under the rock on the left side of the hole.  Choose from a variety of starting holds and slap up the opposing arete features to gain the top.

name: Plymouth Rock Center
description: Start with your hands in the horizontal slot.  Head to the face holds that are up and slightly right of the start to a heady top out over a less than ideal landing.

name: Plymouth Rock Left
description: On the left side of the boulder you will see a shallow dihedral with a bulgy arete feature on the right side of the face.  Climb up through the shallow dihedral.   This problem is a bit of a highball.

name: Left of Stretch It
description: Start with right hand on an undercling, or sidepull and left hand on the arete.  Go up as best you can!  I ended up using a right foot on a block sticking out on the right side of the start.  This was the only way I (5'7") could see doing this problem at V2.  My climbing partner (6'1") was able to dyno to the top without using this option.

name: Stretch It
description: Start in the dihedral with a thin hand crack in the back.  Stem up and use a few scattered holds to work your way up the arete above the corner.

name: Bela Lugosi's Dead
description: Start left on an inverted triangle hold and right on an undercling. With difficulty, pull up and begin slapping up the arete on the left and a choice of sharp edges for the right. Mantle over the right side of the boulder.

name: Big Boy
description: A rare Minnesota Wisconsin highball. Opposing full-handed sidepulls and heel hooks up a large face. Stand start at opposing side-pulls and head straight up.

name: Cave Crack
description: Climb the obvious vertical crack. The lower block to the right is off. Head straight up.

name: Cave Direct
description: A nice line up the center of the Cave Boulder, to the left of "Midget." Sit start at crimps and move up through a couple of flat/slopey crimps up to good holds and a somewhat spicy/fun topout.

name: Cave Left
description: Start standing on flat jugs. Work left through a series of incut jugs. Head straight up from there. Mantle is the crux.

name: Cave Left Sit
description: Sit start underneath the jugs of Cave Left on an undercling. Paste feet and make a hard deadpoint. There are a few intermediate holds to bump to the jugs. Finish on Cave Left. Crux is not dabbing on the supporting rock or pads.

name: Cave Right
description: Squat start on the shallow arete using a left hand edge and right hand dish pocket (hands are very narrow). Make a long move to a decent edge. Continue straight up with a hard lip encounter.

name: Cave Traverse
description: Sit start on the far right side, Traverse left staying low, your butt will never be more the 2 feet off the ground.  No top out, "simply" grab the jug on the far left side and you are done.

name: Down Under
description: Start as for Down Under Right with a scrunched undercling, but follow the line of crimps up and left.

name: Down Under Right
description: Very bunchy sit start on underclings. Make a desperate right hand throw to good edge. Work a few small crimps and finish on the the right side of the boulder.

name: Liquid Swords
description: Cool trickery on this problem. Sit start on Midget Sit, traverse low and right and finish on Cave Crack. Low block to the right is off.

name: The Midget Sit
description: Start sitting in the middle of the Cave Boulder on the obvious bulge with your left hand on a left-facing crimp rail and right hand on the slopey crimper.  Head straight up through several crimpers and an undercling pinch and top it out.  The blocky jug about 3/4 up and to the left is off for your hands.

name: The Midget Stand
description: Start standing in the center of the cave above the obvious bulge with a slanting left hand crimp and your pick of two right hand holds.  Stand up to the undercling and work straight up.  The blocky jug out left about 3/4 of the way up is off for your hands.

name: Oxygen Cocktail
description: Start on the Cave Traverse and work left across the rail and stick the crux. Then move up into the undercling of Midget, and finish that topout.

name: Pharaoh Arete
description: This problem sit starts on a sidepull pinch/sloper jug at the left of the Pharaoh Boulder. I believe that the large crimp sidepull about 6 feet from the ground around the right of the arete, and the large shelf at about 7-8 on the right side of the arete are not to be used to keep it at it's original grade of V5. I am not sure, however, and welcome any input from other members. I will post pictures when I can get some.

name: Pharaoh Right
description: Sit start in the middle of the Pharaoh Boulder on two good crimps next to each other. Move up and right through crimps to the lip.    No eliminations/all holds are on.

name: Pharoah Left
description: Start hands matched on a good crimp closer to the left side of the boulder. Move up through crimps and a pinch to the lip.

name: Point Down Left
description: Stand Start on a good side pull. Climb up the Arete/Face using all the good holds.

name: Psych Up
description: Stand start with left hand on the crimp on the overhanging face and right on the Arete. Climb up avoiding all the jugs around the arete. Very fun for being an eliminate.

name: Psyche Up Sit
description: Sit start, left hand on a crimp around the left of the arete and right hand on the sloper pinch of the arete (the same start as Pharaoh Arete). Pounce up to a good edge, then set up for a hard move out left. Compress to the top.

name: Unknown Highball aka Abomination Reborn
description: start on juggy lay back crack, climb up through cool moves on small edges

name: Carry Forward
description: Sit start on the left side of the boulder with good feet and work your way up on comfy crimps and little jugs to a fun top out.

name: Coal
description: Start with right hand on a crimp on the right arete, left on an undercling on the lip of the overhang. Compress your way up the pillar.Very cool, highly featured rock on this one that is similar to that found at Tiny Bubbles

name: Swamp Thing
description: Awesome line! Sit start under the overhang using the lowest jugs as starting holds. For  starting feet Use the pedestal and a high right foot to pull on. Climb straight over the bulge and up the face, using the crack all the way to the top. Can also use a high sloper to the left for the top out rather than the top part of the crack.-There is also a V6 version that starts with double under clings. All rock base footholds are off. Use feet in the roof only.

name: Endgame
description: Start on a flat shelf on left side of the game block.Traverse right and finish on "The Game".

name: The Game
description: Same start as Level Up. Climb to the jugs above, and finish on the far right arete.

name: Level Up
description: Sit start using a left hand crimp and a juggy right hand side pull. Power up to the large shelfs. Use the left hand sloper and a mean tricep press to mental out.

name: R.I.P
description: Stand start on the face and ascend up the wall using crimps and slopers as needed

name: Why
description: Sit start under the overhang using odd side pulls and far feet. Move left hand up to a two finger pocket. Then reach around the nose to find good jugs and slopers to help you top out.

name: Cone Head Boulder
description: -Cone Head Left         -Cone head right  Start on the slopping jugs on the corner and climb onto the left side of the face. from there use compression and some tiny feet to work your way up to the top. -There is a lesser variation that trends onto the right side of the face. Using the same starting holds at the left variation, make similar grade moves over the open ledge and use the pointed top to climb up and over.

name: Dimond in the Rough
description: Start as low as you can. Heel hook and use slopping holds to traverse the underside of the block. Move to the highest point of the block and mantle up and over to top out.

name: Dress up
description: Stand start with good feet and hands, power up to the large ledge in the middle of the face. From there move up feet and grab the top lip of the wall and top out. Tall but has good holds all they way up :)

name: One Piece
description: Low start on the detached boulder under the overhang. Power up to a good crimp in the middle of the face and fire to the top.

name: One Up
description: Sit start low.  Compression squeeze with both hands, find a key right heel hook and fire directly up the block. Finish on the large fin (Walk off is a traverse to the left).

name: Power Tower
description: Start middle of the block, with both hands on slopping ramp. move straight up the bock.

name: Toy Box
description: Sit start in the crack. get into position and power up to the top ledge. Use the big hands on top  of the block and big feet to top out.

name: Weirdy
description: Start in the chimney using the square block/ledge under the over hang. Move up and over the bulge using the left arete and some odd moves. Press onto the face and climb up to the top. Name is aptly suited.

name: Air Conditioned
description: Follow the air conditioned crack (thin hands; crux) up to a ledge.  Continue on somewhat broken rock to the top.  A fun lead that takes good gear.  The broken rock towards the top is a little suspect, but i felt pretty good about all my placements there.

name: Heat Wave a.k.a. Layback Crack
description: Follow the crack up and to the left.  Continue up and to the right to the top.  This route takes gear well at the bottom but pro is a little thin at the top, but still protects adequately.  I thought the crux was figuring out the top.

name: Indian Head
description: Too short but fun movements.  Easily protectable

name: Little Wing
description: Text taken from "RCM&W,"-Mike Farris.    On the south side of the buttress is a right facing corner.  Climb the face to the right, with the crux just off the ground.

name: Lame Left
description: Low/sit start. Fun one mover into the stand.

name: Lame Right
description: A little contrived. After opening move to lip, stay low and bounce out to large sidepull rail near the triangle block of Lame Stand. Once your left hand is on the sidepull rail, then use the holds on or above the lip. From there top out.

name: Lame Stand
description: Short little line but it has some nice movement and cool holds.

name: Lamer
description: Powerful sit start to an engaging top out. Short but enjoyable problem.

name: Mike's Right
description: Start on undercling/sidepull jug to the right.  High right foot @ arete.  Move up using sloping ridge to tiny, 2 finger skinny pocket in horizontal crack.  Large jug ledge to the right is off! Move up to next thin crack pocket & then top.

name: Mikes Left
description: Start on left large undercling/sidepull jug. Using sloping ridge & small pocket up & left, climb up to good sidepull higher on ridge, & dyno to high jug...top out.  Beta is very height dependant...using a knee bar to get to the small sharp pocket is a possiblity if you're exactly the right size.

name: One Hand Jobless
description: Squat start on a good left hand side pull and decent right hand undercling. Either find the good foot and shoot for the ledge or for more of a challenge use the intermediate sloper before going for the ledge.

name: OPJ
description: OPJ is a fun, short problem that is burly and a little dabby. Make one move off the start and jump to the lip. Mantle is powerful as well.

name: Future Fuel
description: A contrivance, but perhaps the best line on the boulder? Start matched on the large flat hold on the left arete (one move into Morass Left) and find a way to get to the large flat edge in the middle of the face (second move of Morass Center). From here make a big move up and right to the top of Morass Right and top out.

name: Morass Center
description: This line is the best on the boulder IMO but I don't think it warrants anymore than 1 star. Either way its a fun warm up. Sit start and work your way up the center of the face. The sit start is the crux as you have to go for a small horizontal. As long as your precise the holds are very positive.

name: Morass Left
description: Sit start and work the arete. The sit start is the crux. I found a small right hand pocket undercling and used the arete for my left. The sit start is about V1 as long as you don't use the 1st good shelf for a starting hold.

name: Morass Right
description: sit start on the right arete. the arete is sharp and bites really well. Sort of layback your way to the top.

name: Slaying the Swap Creature
description: Sit start on the corner, left hand on a downward facing crimp, right on the arete. Make a long move up and right to a blocky crimp on the arete, then find a way to a largish hold on the arete before topping out.

name: Sitting Rock Center
description: Sit start on a large blocky jug just left of the tree. Using underclings and side pulls head to the top. There are a few ways to climb this, all of which are fun. This receives a grade of V3 in the Minnesota Bouldering Guidebook, but the right beta can make it easier.The top out is sloping and can be covered in pine needles but it is easy to walk around and give it a cleaning.

name: Sitting Rock Left
description: Sit start on the left arete and follow it to the top. The crux is getting off the ground.

name: Electric Stove Couch
description: This climb has a combination of crack and face moves. The features are discontinuous, but the moves are fun if not fluid. There are plenty of options to make the route harder, the most obvious being pulling the roof on crimps at the top. The 5.7 version skirts left of the roof and out the wide fists crack at the top.

name: Grishnakh or Gorbag
description: Climb the obvious right leaning crack flake. As of 8/21/16, the blocks that appear that they could possibly be loose high on the route are in fact not loose.

name: Picnic Crack Right
description: This route starts in the prominent right leaning crack at the bottom.  Climb this until about mid height then traverse left under the roof to obtain the crack and face that will let you pass to the top.

name: Rock Dove a.k.a. Picnic Crack Left
description: This is a fun clean route, with the crux near the top.  It is easily identified by the large offwidth at mid-hight.  The route is on the left edge of the face.

name: Trash Patrol
description: Make a couple of easy face moves to reach the right leaning fist crack 10' or so off the deck.  Work upwards through some choss being VERY careful to avoid loose rock. You will soon find yourself at the base of a steep off-width crack.  Proper off-width technique is not all that necessary as there are lots of holds for hands and feet.

name: Cartheuselum Right
description: Cool short problem.This would be a classic easy mantle block if it had a better landing. The most precarious position is over the worst landing for the boulder. Hardest part is committing and not thinking about the landing.

name: Hadoken
description: Once you're through the tough gaston and cross sequence from the bottom, finish on Cartheuselum Right and mantle via a small crimp. Pretty committing finish.

name: Shoryuken
description: Make a hard gaston move with your right hand and a difficult cross and you're home free. Continue via the rail around the corner of the boulder and mantle.

name: Crystal Clear
description: Really fun and hardly done.  Maybe the best line on this boulder and I'm suprised.  Give it a go, it's fun.

name: Geode Direct
description: Stand start on bad feet and decent crimps on the left of the slab. Work up the left side of the slab using a variety of options for holds.

name: Geode Left
description: SDS on the gently overhanging face. Use the large side pulls and underlings to move up towards the lip.

name: Geode Right
description: Stand start on mediocre feet aiming for the jugs directly above.

name: Thunderegg
description: Sit start on a jug on the slightly overhanging arete. Move up the arete on large flat jugs.

name: Lower Twin Center
description: Sit start on a good crimp and slopey jug. Work through two slot crimps and head left to the lower lip. Top out.

name: Lower Twin Traverse
description: Start on a jug sidepull on the right side of the boulder (same start as R to T and Lower Twin Center). Make your way up and left on crimps (same as Lower Twin Center), but instead of topping out make a lunge left to a sloper on the left corner of the boulder. Find a way to match this and top out.

name: R to T
description: Sit start on good sidepull and slopey jug. Use the arete and face holds to climb straight up to the highest part of the boulder. Top out.

name: Upper Twin Traverse
description: Stand Start on the far right side of the boulder. Traverse the boulder using the face and/or slopers on top and top out all the way around the corner on the far side.

name: Jockstrap and Chaps
description: Start at the big flat hold on the right side of the face of the boulder.  Use bad feet to try to gain the large ledge at half height on the boulder.  From there it is a bit tricky to stand up on the ledge and top out.

name: Lighter Than Air
description: The rock hides a lot of holds for this boulder. Pull on the start and maneuver through a series of bad holds (both feet and hands). Gain high feet and chuck for a semi flat ledge "jug." The catch rewards you with an incredibly easy topout.

name: Men at Work
description: Stand start and head straight up keeping right of the arete. The crux comes early and eases off at the end. Because this is a classic, it's a little easy for the grade. This problem has sweet edges and pinches on it which makes you forget about how tall it is.

name: Tucker's Backside
description: Start with right hand on a sidepull around head height.  Work your way up increasingly good holds on the slightly overhanging wall.

name: Sardonic Center Left
description: Hard and long pull off of the start. Delicate feet guard the finish. Good jug up and right for top out.

name: Sardonic Center Right
description: Fun, juggy flake climbing. The topout is the hardest part. Find a couple thin crimps and pull over. The boulder would get a higher rating if it was a bit taller.

name: Sardonic End
description: SDS. Make a couple moves up on crimps to an easy top out. Use anything on the face. Left Arete off.

name: Sardonic End Left
description: Sit start at hamburger jug and whatever feet you can find. Easy holds to top of short route. Do it for the cuties.

name: Sardonic Left
description: SDS with left hand in the sharp crack in the rectangular opening and right hand in the slot. Head up on thin crimps. There are a variety of possibilities for hands and feet that are all equally difficult. Top out by the sloping runnel.

name: Sardonic Lip Traverse
description: Start on the arete just to the right of Sardonic Right.  Gain the lip of the boulder and traverse left on slopers.  Top out on Sardonic Left.

name: Sardonic Right
description: Start with hands on the crimp rail. Move up to the top and an easy top out through a couple crimps and fun feet. It's very short but fun while it lasts. (Right Arete is off)

name: Skittle Center
description: From the sit start, work through a cool undercling sequence and tech or power your way up using holds on the face and the left side of the arete.

name: Skittle Right
description: From the sit start, work a couple of good rails and slopers on the right side of the arete to the lip. Top out is subtle and enjoyable.

name: Taste the Rainbow Link Up
description: Same start as Skittle Center (left rail sit start). Work up through the underclings to a cool cross and finish on Skittle Right.

name: Sugar Buzz
description: The lone problem on the boulder. Stand start on an undercling leads to some thin holds, fun sidepulls and a mossy top out.

name: Pressure Washer
description: Squat start with good hands in the crack. Work upwards on good sidepulls to gain the lip. Hidden crack makes topping a breeze.

name: Tin Roof Center
description: The holds on this problem are amazing. Bomber jugs and edges. The movement is also incredible. Long reach back off the start and a super sweet heel hook move after the roof. The landing is a 45 degree slab sloping downhill which makes the problem feel risky. Definitely one of the best that not many know about.

name: Tin Roof Left
description: Stand start in seam underneath the roof. Pull a long move to jugs on the edge of the roof and then follow the crack up and left.

name: Tin Roof Right
description: Start on horizontal rail, head over the lip and exit to the right on mossy goodness. Would be better if it were cleaner, bring a big brush.

name: Noodle Boulder - Corner Direct
description: I don't like quoting the guidebooks but there's really no other good explanation. sit start on obvious chalked up jug. then work the crimps on either side of the arete up to a sloped top out. left hand finger strength is a must as the 2 left hand crimps are pretty hideous.

name: Noodle Boulder - Shmoil to Woody
description: sit start on obvious chalked up jug on arete (same as corner direct). then work out left using a terrible intermediate if needed (decent feet make it possible). eventually make the span left to the good incut hold on the face (the face facing the river, it's a unique hold, some kind of quartzite maybe). from here head straight up using a "sharks tooth" like hold if needed.

name: Shmoil
description: Sit start with both hands on the jug and head up and to the right using any hands on the right face and the arete.

name: Victor
description: Sit start both hands on v shaped crimp on the left face. Make a big move with poor feet up to another crimp then to the top.

name: Royale with Cheese
description: Using an arete in each hand, bad footholds and heel and toe hook trickery, ascend the tall slender boulder.

name: Show Me Center
description: Sit start up the middle of the boulder using the cool large flat edge.

name: Show Me Left
description: Sit start.  Using the arete with the left hand and face holds and sidepulls with the right, go up.

name: Show Me Right
description: Start on the sharp arete on the right side of the boulder.

name: Crack in the Morning
description: A great crack boulder for those that like easy hand jams and fists into a single stack at the top.

name: Cross Over Artist
description: Start with a slightly overhanging face, then up a finger crack to a very interesting exit over a bulge. finish up an easier hand crack.

name: Edge Lane
description: Tricky little sequence.  The awkward angle of the arete makes you use your brain on how to do it efficiently

name: Gadget Arms
description: An amazing left to right traversing crack system that finishes on an exposed knife edge compression arete. One of the most fun 5.9 climbs I've done in Taylor's.

name: Hand Jive
description: climb past a horizontal hand jam

name: Mental Physics
description: Climb to the small roof and then up the seam.  The crux is near the top of the route.

name: Skin of Rod's Teeth
description: A beautiful finger crack!  The crux of the route is the wider part a third of the way up.

name: Thrombus
description: This inside corner flaring crack can be tricky but is a fun climb.

name: Barn Door
description: Start at the overhanging fang feature and climb offset hand crack to a thin seam with face moves to the top.  Recently scrubbed the holds and removed some loose rock, but would clean up with some more traffic.  Worthwhile and fun climb if you're in the area!!

name: Captain Coconuts
description: Farris MN/WI Falcon climbing book lists this route: solid short climb if in the area. Some fun moves to dance across the face. Wish it was taller.

name: Lost Ego
description: Follow the slightly less than vertical hand and fist crack to a large pod.  Make some commiting moves out of the pod (crux) and continue on the finger crack to the top.  This route protects well for its duration and is probably my favorite lead at Taylor's.  A large cam (#4 camalot) adds some security for the crux.  For Minnesota multipitch fun climb Sentinel Crack as a second pitch.

name: The Prow
description: Use holds on the right side of the triangle, grab the prow, and continue up.

name: Sentinel Crack
description: A classic for the area.  Follow somewhat slabby, broken and run out terrain past a broken tree stump to a small ledge (5.6ish).  Follow the double cracks to the top.  Crack technique helps but is not required.

name: Stay Hungry
description: Five feet left of Yosemite Crack. Do the bottom slab of Yosemite crack and they finish up the wall using the cracks and grips to the left of Yosemite crack. Well worth doing if you setup anchors for Yosemite crack since the climbing is completely different.

name: Yosemite Crack
description: Another area classic, if only the climb were longer.    The climb begins on a small ledge about half way up the cliff.  Two option exist for reaching the ledge.  You can either climb the face below (5.10a) or climb the bottom of Sentinel Crack and traverse left to reach the bottom of the climb.  I'd recommend the face below unless you are leading.  The crux of the climb is getting off the ground.  The climb starts out as thin hands and slowly widens to fists at the top.

name: Stand Start
description: Stand start. Reach up and find whatever works. Throw a right heal and surmount the bulge. The feature is beautiful, but the climbing is physical.    Leave the start up to your own ethics. Either establish a food on the "cheater" block supporting this boulder, or stand start and power through. Both are fun.

name: Talus Arete
description: This problem climbs a beautiful arete and overhanging face. Sit start low and climb the arete.

name: Talus Pit
description: Crawl into the pit, and sit start low with your hands matched on the horizontal rail. Make a few moves to gain the arete, and climb to the top.

name: A Bubble a Day
description: Start low on the left side of the face with your hands on the obvious jug. Climb the most direct route to the top.

name: Meas Traverse
description: Follow the thin seam from right to left.

name: Sound the Horn
description: Start seated on the rock behind you. Establish yourself on the great feat and climb the left side of the face. Enjoy great features all the way to the top.

name: Tiny Bubbles Left
description: Stand start in the small alcove, trend up and right, aiming for the bucket.  Watch the swing if you miss the bucket!

name: Tiny Bubbles Right
description: Climb the vertical crack on the right side of the Tiny Bubbles Wall.

name: Tiny Bubbles Sit
description: Sit start in the center of the wall. Use the poor undercling to pull yourself up, and establish yourself in the thin seam. Follow this left and up.

name: Tiny Bubbles Traverse
description: Start low on the left side of the face with your hands on the obvious jug. Traverse the thin seam right until you reach the vertical crack. Follow this crack to the top.

name: Cryptic Crimper
description: Intricate balancey moves across a white lichen covered face. Don't use the positive arete (part of Tasty Treats) on climbers right to keep it true to the grade.

name: Tasty Treats
description: Black tarnished face up a blocky dihedral to an easy face finish. It can be fairly wet early in the season.

name: Cathuseleft
description: subtle slabby climbing that leads up to a powerful roof pull.  Obviously left of Cathuselum

name: Cathuselum
description: Head up the face to the the obvious jam crack at the top of the cliff.  This is the crux.  There's a way to avoid hand jams using the under cling.

name: chimney
description: Good spot to bring beginners on the wisconsin side

name: Chimney Left Face
description: Climb the crack splitting the face on the lft side of the chimney.

name: Deuchler's Corner Left
description: Reachy route, plan moves ahead

name: Impossible Crack
description: The crux is definitely the transfer into and out of the offwidth crack.  Some may find it useful to use a headjam and it is definitely a route you'll need some energy for.

name: Inside Corner
description: On the inside corner near Batman.

name: Lloyd's Lament
description: An easy climb, but a fun one for kids. Just a little difficult at the end, but otherwise just fun. To get to this route, you will find an access gully at the north end of the cliff. This is a 5.4 descent with a slightly tricky slab at the bottom, so you may want to hang some webbing for safety or even rope up. The first inside corner on the cliff with a big column at its base is where this climb starts.

name: Mother
