description: A great 5.4 to play on while waiting for some harder TR's around Deuchler's Corner area or a great route to take a beginner up. A direct start warrants a 5.6 but it is possible to head up at Cathuselum and then walk right on the slope-y ramp. The bulk of the climbing consists of a series of ledges. Most are very positive but a few are pretty slope-y and this is where a few good jams come in handy. It's almost dead vertical at that point so it makes for a fun climb. Finish by escaping right on easier terrain up top.

name: Rurp City
description: There are two cruxes, one lower and one near the top

name: Softer Than Ice, Harder Than Diamonds
description: Short, but all of it is tough

name: Split the Difference
description: Great crimpy climbing that keeps pushing you left and right.  The climb is 5.10b if you avoid the good holds to the right.  A well-set top-rope will get you this climb and INSIDE CORNER on one rope

name: Triple Overhang
description: Flow up the face without using either edge. Some steep face moves.

name: Able
description: This route is a great way to avoid the crux of 'Cain'. Starts the same as 'Cain' for the first four bolts which brings you to the lip of the 8' roof, though it still ain't easy escaping the roof. Can be a V9 or V10 boulder problem depending on height. Then go straight up into 'Couch Time' for a little shake out before attempting the redpoint crux with a tight two-finger pocket. Clip the 'Cain' anchors on the large roof for the finish.

name: Bolt Ladder to Upper Deck
description: If you ever need to get to the upper deck (one or two more climbs up there) and you are scared to cross the water falls or the area above the water falls I put in a bolt ladder.    The bolt ladder is about 20 feet to the left of the water fall. Look for a U bolt about knee high. Above that about head high is a bolt and hanger. Clip in and pull up. I put a third bolt/hanger up and over the edge, you can't see it but you will have to feel for it.    THis bolt ladder is usually wet and muddy so be prepared to get your hands dirty. But it sure beats getting swept over the falls like some of my friends (Roland and Kelly, broken foot and toes)    I put in full 1/2" bolts, so they won't rust out for a couple hundred years...or I won't be around to find out.

name: Brass Monkey
description: This new route is an extension to the already est. route 'Water Music'. Previously an aid line done by Mike Dahlberg, has now been bolted and freed. Crux is for sure the huge roof pull, with one enormous reach, a toss to the lip, and then some technique to finish the roof pull. The start has some rad moves as well but the rock below the first roof is not the best. Some clips are hard to make. Anchors are right above the monkey face, below a small roof. This is the first route that I have bolted (with the help of Jeff Engel and Mike Dahlberg's aid bolts). Enjoy!

name: Business Time
description: Longest route at Willow with roughly about 70 hand moves and 17 bolts, give or take. Nothing too super cruxy just continuous movement with a couple rests, that will all leave you with a dry throat in the end. Begin on 'Dry Lightning' and climb it across the roof lip to where it meets 'Cain'. Continue traversing left just above 'Cain' on a couple pockets that will bring you into 'Couch Time'/'Genesis Effect'. Keep going left into the 5th bolt on 'Natural Selection'. Climb 'Natural' just over the roof to a decent rest then finish off the forearm burning on 'Midsummer Daydreams'.

name: Cain
description: Formerly "the project," this finaly got sent. Look for two anchor hooks on a large roof towards the "back" (waterfall side). Follow the line of bolts down through big roofs to find the start. First ascent done by Andy Raether.

name: Couch Time
description: Start on Genesis then head up to the chains of Cain.  The first half is like hanging on the couch  big comfy holds.  Then you have to step off the couch to pull the crux once you reach Cain.  Think of it as having to get off the couch to get a beer or something.  Then its back to the couch  big comfy holds to the chains.  Dont fall getting back on the couch though its a little tricky here, but its still pretty couch.

name: Cypher 2
description: Cypher 2 packs Couch Time's fluid moves with big moves reminiscent of Genesis Effect or the Mono Route.      Begin on Couch Time.  Once over the roof (use a double-draw/runner at the roof), climb past three bolts to a large and (often) dirty hueco that is shaped like a shallow V on the bottom.  At the next bolt past the hueco (use a double-draw/runner), head straight up through big, fun moves on big pockets and edges until you meet up with Genesis Effect.  Finish on the last few moves (read: massive jugs) of Genesis Effect.

name: Daily Grind
description: Start on a corner to the right of White Noise, above cheater blocks (use em if you gotta, nobody will blame you). Climb up a slight overhang that passes to the right of a large roof.

name: Doppler Effect
description: This is the only finished route up river from "Leftovers." The route starts with a crux right off the ground. A couple moves yields more moderate pocket pulling on less than bomber rock (at times in the summer watch for bees) to a higher tiered roof section and finishes on hard moves for clipping the anchors.     Carefully cross upper falls from shady side of river. Stick clip the first bolt.

name: Double Trouble
description: On the right side of the black amphitheater. There is a hanging belay off the ledge. Stick clip the first bolt and climb up loose rock.

name: Drop Test
description: Starts 8 feet left of Jar of Flies. Goes straight up. Good holds for all clips.  8 draws. If you want to toprope bring additional draws and use them rather than the anchor biners. It gets a lot of warm up activity so check the top biners and replace if worn.  Less overhanging than most at Willow.

name: Dry Lightning
description: A long link-up route with some of the largest moves at Willow, starts on the 'Rejection and Mercy' crack then takes a hard left at the lip of the roof, bringing you to an exposed traverse across slopey ledges on the lip of this 12' horizontal roof. Then you join up with 'Cain', just in time for the bouldery redpoint crux of this route. Keep pushing through the remainder of 'Cain' to reach a perfect rest right below a set of anchors on another large roof. Either clip the anchors here or traverse left around the roof for two more bolts of climbing.

name: Fox Confessor
description: Beautiful! This route finds the best position on the entire wall. Just unbelievable.   Start with a brutal sequence of long reaches between pockets and edges, coming out of the first steep roof. It doesn't let up until you traverse left at the third bolt, but persevere! Next you have 3 bolts worth of huge jugs, which feels more like the routes below than the others on the Mez.    Rest as best you can in the largest, highest hueco, using a (potentially) awesome kneebar (rt.). Then bust out of there for a 30 foot section of long moves between mostly jugs. Look for a final heart breaker red point crux very high.   Because the Mez can be a little confusing, start on a good left hand pocket and a decent right hand sidepull/undercling. Finish using holds on the left of the dihedral, and finally working into the dihedral to clip the New Beginnings anchors.

name: Genesis Effect
description: Look for the small black cave at the base of the formation. Just a meter or so to the left, climb the slabbish section to a 45-degree overhang. Follow the bolts up and to the right.

name: Getting Slightly Higher
description: This new route is an extension of the Living Slightly Larger roof, allowing it to continue into High Road to China via a harder than it looks 2 bolt traverse.     Strap on your knee pads, pull the improbable and wild moves on Living Slightly Larger, dive into a double knee bar rest then recompose for the final two large roofs and redpoint cruxes of High Road to China.    This route is just incredible and is the epitome of willow river's sport climbing style. A massive, daunting line that will leave you exhausted and smiling.

name: Guess and Check
description: Powerful moves at the start lead to a stand-up or sit-down camper ledge at 20 feet. De-pump completely, because the final moves to the anchor are kinda pumpy.   Not the best rock, but we've been making an effort to brush and knock off the really dangerous stuff. The movement is good, and it makes for a great warm up if you want to work the 12s on the Mez.

name: High Road to China
description: The new enduro line here at Willow. Comparable to "Rejection and Mercy" and "Business Time". Pull through the crux in the first large roof. Then traverse right at the huge hueco (6th bolt) on great solid rock. Then head straight up at the break in the second tier. Climb with caution from here to the anchors, this is a new route, stuff is still breaking off.

name: Hurtful Pleasures
description: Bolted 10 years ago, finally went and turned out to be another hard classic by Engel. Starts on 'Rejection and Mercy' through the one hand jam crux then fades up and left after the lip. Very fun movement through bulges on a steep wall with many pockets to choose from. Eventually ends at the same anchors as 'Cain', but there is an extension past this point that adds two more bolts.

name: Jar of Flies
description: This route had a bolt added to the crux and hours of work put into removing loose and dangerous rock in 2011. Well worth the time.   This climb is located on the left (not so steep) part of the wall. There's a small corner slightly off the ground; start to its right.    The proper sequence through the slight overhang will allow for 5.9 climbing.    Because of the crux section, it is not recommended for beginning leaders to learn on this route. Top rope it first a few times before giving it a lead burn. Get that crux dialed.    Gets some of the earliest sun of the day.

name: Leftovers
description: Start with same first bolt on Water Music which is just left of the wet spot way over by the falls.  Then continue up into the dihedral and follow it and arête to the top.  The top of this route was originally bolted in the late 90's.

name: Link Up
description: Start on White Noise, traverse right on the large shelf and finish on Daily Grind. Popular warm up for the regulars, proud redpoint for the 5.10 leader.

name: Living Slightly Larger
description: This route forces some of the biggest reachs I have ever done. Starting below a two-tiered roof on tan rock, climb up to the roof and prepare to be dumbfounded. Figure out some kind of sequence with many of these partial holds and hold on long enough to reach the bomber jug. From here the next move is a huge deadpoint through the tan scar into another good pocket. Then climb out the lip for two more bolts. And there is some loose flakes on this face, so be cautious.

name: Mermaid
description: An excellent route that is unique for the crag, similar in style to Brass Monkey and Requiem, ie, an actual boulder problem and committing dynamic crux above the waterfall high on the route. The rock quality is perhaps the best at willow and has been newly cleaned after seeing little action for several years (that 10 foot ladder sure can keep climbers away).    Most folks, especially those with less than a 6 foot reach, will likely find this stiff for the grade.

name: Middle Cyclone
description: This is the latest link-up route with a new two bolt section between 'Genesis Effect' and 'Tsunami'. Climb 'Genesis' through the huge huck move then make a slightly awkward transition to the left. Pull the roof for a tricky move to join and finish 'Tsunami'. Another amazing link-up route!

name: Midsummer Daydreams
description: begins to the right of sudden shock and about 10ft left of natural selection. start is located just in front of a large (think dresser size) boulder that is about 5 ft from the wall.    once past the slightly vertical section and at the first/main roof, climb up a shallow, narrow corner. the sides of the corner are only a few feet wide, and the corner itself only about 10ft tall. the holds in the corner are crimps and two-finger pockets, with the occasional jug. after the corner, go left to a big hueco. from there, just follow the chalk and big holds and aim for the top. ends on two long chains set 3-4 feet apart. these chains are visible from the bridge.    if clipping all the bolts, takes around 13 draws. take a few longer draws or a few runners to eliminate drag at the start and underneath some of the other smaller roofs. lastly, thick pants and/or kneepads help for this route. :)    WHEN TOPROPING PLEASE USE USE YOUR QUICKDRAWS INSTEAD OF THE FIXED DRAWS.  because the link-up sudden daydream (12a) shares the same ending as midsummer, these anchors take a lot of abuse.  help us preserve the fixed anchors for as long as possible!

name: Midsummer Selection
description: This might be a good intermediate link up to try if you have your eye on doing Radioactive Man. Begin the same as Midsummer Daydreams until you reach the giant dirty hueco just past the first roof at the 5th bolt. From here a couple big reaches with sick heel hooks brings you into Natural Selection. Finish on Natural.

name: Mono Mercy
description: By the mid 2000s, darkness had besieged the chossy steeps of the river Willow.  Like Gandalf the Grey in the Two Towers, Chris Hirsch, another gangly wizard, shone light into the abyss.  Equipped only with a grigri and some Sobe iced tea, young Hirsch had the foresight -- nay, vision! -- to unearth (literally, this rig was dirty) -- another link-up at Willow, the Mono Mercy link.      Hence that fateful day, the skies at Willow have been bright (however the choss remains, the crowds are bigger, Hudson is still WT...you get the idea).  And, in honor of this great achievement, no one has since -- to this author's knowledge -- had the gall to climb this visionary piece of climbing history.  So, take up your staff (aka stick clips), grab some magic potions (aka a Sobe), and ride in and send.      Once attired in Gandalf robe and staff, begin on the Mono Route.  At the roof that guards the chains for this route, move left and directly tackle the crux of Rejection and Mercy.  Finish on Rejection and Mercy, clipping the lower chains (the top are unequalized, which is bad for your rope and for the higher anchor, which receives much more wear and tear than the lower).

name: Mono Route
description: The real name is actually unknown, Matt forgot what he called it. So we just refer to it as the 'Mono Route' because of the mono finger thread that you have to get on the horizontal roof...pretty cool. Shortly followed by a dyno into a huge hueco right after the large roof. Beware of the hard redpoint crux below the chains.

name: Natural Daydreams
description: Another variation connecting the beginning of Natural Selection into the top portion of Midsummer Daydreams.    Begin on Natural until you flop over the second roof. Head left into Midsummer Daydreams when you arrive at the 8th bolt of Natural Selection. A couple tenuous moves involving a crimp and an undercling deliver you just past the redpoint crux of Midsummer Daydreams. Finish on the top of Midsummer.

name: Natural Selection
description: Start 6' right of Midsummer Daydreams, right of a shallow corner. Climb up the vertical section then hit large (and I mean LARGE) pockets and hueco features on the 45-degree or so overhang. Climb up and slightly off to your left, follow the bolts and you should be fine.

name: New Beginnings
description: The link between Water Music and Leftovers.  A bit easier than Leftovers, as you avoid the crux.  Fun climbing, especially the upper portion.

name: No Crack for Old Men
description: Yes, another link up.  Start on Dry Lightning, which goes out the roof crack then left along the lip of the roof.  Then cross Cain and turn and climb up to the Genesis anchors via Cypher 2.

name: Play Time Is Over
description: Follow Business Time til it links with Natural Selection. Instead of heading out left with Natural into Midsummer Daydreams, head straight up Tsunami.

name: Pride and Prejudice
description: Start about 30 feet right of the pipe, behind two blocks. Stick clip the second bolt and climb loose rock to good rock above.    Routes are on the south side of the river and are "always changing, but nice when dry."

name: Quit Your Day Job
description: Leftmost route in Spring 2017. Starts on arete of left facing dihedral. Two bolts to dirty ledge above (belayer beware). Move slightly left to third bolt where you work up into a mini roof. Find a shelf and some great pockets on the face above to gain the fourth bolt. This is your crux section. A couple more bolts through easier terrain lead to fixed anchors.    This is a new route. Beware loose rock (climbers and belayers). More traffic will help clean it up!

name: Radioactive Man
description: Start on Midsummer move right to link with Tsunami before the second roof.   Pros: This route gets all the hard parts from the low crux of Midsummer, through a fun right traverse then up into the business section of Tsunami. Another option for the bored locals.   Cons: Only 3 new moves on another linkup. Not a super obvious line.

name: Rejection and Mercy
description: Find a corner with two large blocks at the base. Climb the crack through a 12-foot horizontal roof. At the lip follow bolts up and right to the top.

name: Requiem
description: Follow the same start as Fox Confessor till the third bolt.  At this point head straight up into an amazing kneebar (rt).  Rest up to be prepared for  two high cruxs on the climb with a decent recovery in between.      While lowering clip into the bolt by the kneebar or below.  Failure to do so will result in a bath in the falls.  There are multiple leaver-biners on the climb to assist with cleaning.  Recommend cleaning entirely from the top.

name: Speedy Delivery
description: Start at the white pedestal just right of Pride and Prejudice.

name: Sudden Daydreams
description: Start on Sudden Shock, climb four bolts, then traverse right on the jugs past another bolt, under a small dark roof, and finish on Midsummer's Daydreams. A stellar route.

name: Sudden Shock
description: Just to the right of White Noise and Daily Grind, on the black (and possibly damp) dark streak in the rock. Climb up the streak to a 30-degree overhang on pockets, and follow bolts to the top.

name: Sunday Sermon
description: Start under a deep roof and make powerful moves between pockets and edges through the first 2 bolts. Work through vertical, or slightly overhanging rock for 20 feet, and get ready to go big at the last roof. Huge reach! Shorter people can do it, but you get more points for the ascent.    Please message me if I have some details about this, or other routes on the Mez, incorrect.

name: Surf Selection
description: Yes, yes, another link up.. Begin the same as Tsunami following it over the second roof to the 8th clip. Instead of clipping the bolt out right from the giant hueco on Tsunami, clip out left a connection bolt and head straight up into the top section of Natural Selection.     This route isn't done very much to my knowledge, but is well worth a burn. It combines some of the funnest parts of both routes, what's not to love?

name: Tsunami
description: Another pumpy jug haul with a well/over protected sequency crux. Just before the crux is a no hands knee bar which is awkward to get into. This route is soft for it's orginal rating, 13b. Probably more like 12d/13a.

name: Unknown
description: This is the bolted route furthest right on the upper deck/mezzanine. The crux is the roof pull. The route is well-protect and actually pretty fun, though very dirty and chossy. May clean up with more traffic. Good warm-up if starting on a 10c or harder isn't your thing.

name: Water Music
description: Start just left of where the rock gets wet from the falls, just right of an 8-foot shallow black inset. Go up and left to chains halfway up the main ampitheater, just below a large horizontal roof. Apparently this baby is dirty and chossy.

name: White Noise
description: Just before the rock goes crazy overhanging, look for an arete that's to the left of another arete with cheater blocks beneath. Typical Willow climbing. Big moves to big holds. Can be a bit tricky, as all Willow climbs are, since holds are often hiding. Two roofs, the second being the crux. Pull the crux and it's easy to the anchors. Anchors = two chains w/ biners.

name: Catastrophic Kiss Project, The
description: Start on the right side of the roof about head height and climb up to the apex using the slopey rail. Features a nice large flat landing.    I think this might be one of the largest climbable sandstone roofs in Wisconsin.

name: Impossible Face Arete Project
description: Climb the right arete on the impossible face boulder.

name: Impossible Face Project, The
description: Climb up the seemingly blank face. Some holds might be found with cleaning but it looks pretty blank except for a few down low.

name: Hiding from the Sun
description: Start below the left corner of the south face.  Climb to the platform and look right.  Climb the obvious crack to the top.

name: Sidelong
description: Start just left of the corner.  Up to the crack through the bulge, then around onto the face on the right.

name: Straight Shot
description: A clean dihedral.

name: With Flare
description: Start in the back of the flaring chimney, and work your way to the top.

name: Bark Back Mountain
description: Sit start, climb up the face on the small block in front of the tree.

name: Dick Tip Soft
description: Sit start center of face and climb up. There's also the stand variation which is a little easier.

name: Double Brutal
description: Sit start on the left side of the heart shaped boulder. Climb up insecure and committing moves over a not so ideal landing.

name: Full Chat
description: Stand start left side of the boulder in a good pocket, and an okay crimp feature, and climb up. I found it easier to campus the first few moves.

name: Green Swoop, The
description: Sit start under prow and climb up the arete on rad slopers.

name: Hungover Owl
description: Start left side of boulder on the first ledge and climb up the face. Will be much easier and less fun if you're taller so sad day for you.

name: Illumination
description: Stand start, squeeze your way up to the top.

name: Slab left of Sweet'N Low
description: Start on big ledge sticking out of the boulder and climb up the slab.

name: Square Root of Jacked Project
description: This is a project that I cleaned and tried twice. Sit start on two good low incut crimps and climb up the face. The crux seems to be the first two moves.     It's a 20deg overhung detached boulder around 18-20ft tall. The top has perfect slopey jugs.

name: Sweet'N Low
description: Sit start on perfect jug and climb up the face on awesome holds. Excellent rock quality.

name: Truffle Shuffle
description: Sit start on detached boulder and climb the mini horizontal roof exiting up the arete.

name: Underworld
description: Sit start far left under the roof on good crimps, go right and up.     This is a rare Wisconsin floating sandstone boulder with a 60deg roof. The bottom side of the roof is a little chossy and should not be climbed if wet or damp. It sits in the shade so takes longer to dry out than the other climbs in the area.

name: Underworld Left
description: Sit start as on Underworld but climb up the left side of the boulder. Crux is the slopey mantle.

name: Underworld Warmup
description: Start on big obvious jug and climb up.

name: Upside Down, The
description: Fun warm up climb. Start on a left horizontal pinch and a right pocket. Climb up the face. Left arete is off and the right side pull in the middle of the climb is off due to flexage. It is likely to rip off so no touching.

name: Get Off of My Stack
description: Sit start layback and work your way up the overhanging corner to top out.Wall with Precedented Times is off for full grade.Don't let the fact that it's an eliminate boulder distract you from the fact that it's good, classic fun.

name: Philanderer's Field
description: A static climb with solid jugs and small overhangs. Work your way up the edge of the tower. Fall carefully with a small jump back. Falling straight down will bounce you off the rocks before you make it to the deck.

name: Precedented Times
description: Sit start and climb it layback or thin hand jams. Very physical moves to get the blood pumping. Slopey top-out.

name: Republican Hair
description: Flawless, immaculate, pristine, just like that classic republican hair. That's what your send better be if you don't want to bounce off The Donald's pointier bits on your gravity-powered trip to the deck.Easy mantle of the first bulge to mono and two finger pockets of the crux face. Reachy moves. Good jugs and bad feet to second mantle. Finish on the top and walk yourself off the back side.

name: Scaling the Donald
description: A very easy "stair case" with good jug holds all the way up.

name: Sky Tower
description: Hard Sandstone with fairly good clean holds all the way up. crux is right in the middle~ 10'up.

name: Apple Bloom
description: Tricky slab with tenuous feet. Start with large left side pull and right foot back stepped. Climb up the face trending right of the seam. The crux is stepping feet up in the middle. Could use some more cleaning but it goes.

name: Fancy Feast
description: Start slightly overhung on heavily featured rock.  Top out up and to the left.

name: Fontsconsin
description: Start matched on a big triangle undercling and work straight up through the face. Topping out through a sloper finish reminiscent of a Fontainebleau finale. The arete to the right isn't used but wasn't tempting.

name: Modern Leper
description: Climb the left arete of this boulder from a sit.  A nice undercling and a sloper topout await.  Duffy climbed some version of this problem a few years ago.

name: Princess Celestia
description: Start on the left side of the wall, with an edge near the arete for the left hand and a pocket for the right.  Traverse right through the middle of the face through thin holds.  Gain the right arete and top out.  The underclings at your waist are not used.

name: Slippery Slab
description: Climb up featured slab.  Trickier than it looks.

name: Tidy Cats
description: Start on crimpy rail.  Move up and right for the top out.

name: Are We There Yet?
description: Sit start onto small, beta intensive crimps.  Large move to the finish.  Super neat route.

name: Isolation A·rête
description: Route follows the arete with some hand holds right.

name: Isolation Station
description: Start on left with high left foot. Route climbs face of boulder. Mineral deposits provide positive crimps at top of boulder.

name: Sea Foam
description: Starting low on good pockets, move up boulder with slopey edges and side-pulls.  Bottom is dirty and a little chossy.

name: What's Crackin'
description: Dirtyish crack, with a fun layback in the start.

name: What's Left
description: Climb the remaining holds.  Be sure to have a spotter to keep your head off the wall to your back.

name: Derpy Hooves
description: Start as for Nightmare Moon, sitting with left hand on the arete and right with a low edge.  Traverse right, staying low through the face.  Gain the arete and top out, moving slightly right on good holds. Kind of alotta moves and packs a bit of a punch.

name: Nightmare Moon
description: Sit start left on slightly overhanging block and climb up the middle of face on small holds. The crux is a throw to the break, perfect jugs for the top out.     We built up a small landing since it slants severely down hill. It's still pretty terrible so be careful.

name: Rainbow Dash
description: Sit start with an undercling and a sidepull & climb to the top. Huge shout-out to Joel for having the vision and cleaning up this block. This has to be one of the best lines in the park.. maybe even the state. Second ascent - Duffy.  Update - originally did as a stand, seems like the original left hand broke, but there's a lower left hand and the move still goes

name: Scootaloo
description: OffwidthThis gorgeous inviting crack just grabs your body and invites some solid thrutchy scooting all the way up to the top. Sit start on each face of the crack with the nice left hand hold. Huck your shoulder into the crack and away you go. For maximum style points only use feet that are inside the crack from the arete, rather than feet on the face. There are two nice left feet that act as rests with plenty of fun in between.  Recommend having a right-knee pad of some kind.

name: Sunset Shimmer
description: SDS matched in jug pod. Climb tricky and consistent moves directly up the arete.

name: Big Chief
description: Incredibly exposed route with a gorgeous view of the Wisconsin Hillsides. Pretty bad landing, but not the worst here. Follow wide crack and various feet.

name: Breaking and Entering
description: Start in jug slot at base of arete, move up on a cool Ball hold, meat hook and other neat holds to a juggy topout in No Fall territory.

name: Cat Burglar
description: Sit start on good holds under the bulge, make powerful moves up to obvious slanting jug, jugs to the top.

name: Crime Scene
description: Climbs the face left of Fat Mon. Start on obvious ledge on arete and trend up and left through a series of face holds.

name: Fat-Mon
description: Route on (arguably) the best rock of the main overlook. Slabby top out, start on the left side, crux will be the first or second move, if you do it correctly. then, work your way up using good feet and large holds

name: Grand Larceny
description: Start on positive side pulls with solid, obvious ledge for feet. Move up series of crimps on the long zig-zagging edge to a high right-hand sloper. Crux is moving from the sloper to solid jug up and to the left. Top out on solid jugs. Bring at least a couple pads as landing is steep.

name: Meaty Gams
description: Start with hands on either side of arête and with foot in obvious pocket.  It is recomended that you top out left of the arête for safety reasons.

name: Overlooked
description: Exposure makes up for lack of height on this one. Start left hand in a pocket and right hand on a crimp on the bottom right side of the face. Climb up and left to the mantle using some amazing slopers.

name: Wee Chief
description: Start left hand on a good pinch on the arete. Right hands start on sidepull about a foot off the ground. Climb the arete.

name: Arete Right of Scary Door
description: Climb arete right of Behind the Scary Door. Good warm up before trying the face.

name: Behind the Scary Door
description: Sit start right hand inside amazing pocket left on a sloper. Climb up the face on a few very small crimps, a couple pockets, and then jug out the top. Duffy Hutchins has the 2nd ascent.

name: Crack Right of Scary Door
description: The prominant crack feature to the right of scary door.  Mostly a slanting arete.

name: Deer Season
description: starts with angled feet and small hand holds, up to a good pocket on the left and crimp on the right, there are a variety of hands after that but stay right, away from the easy stuff. Top out for a good view, there are good hands leading right once over the formation in the top circle.

name: Alligator Clip
description: Start with two hands on the bomber ledge and work your way to the left using the smaller aretes. Follow them back right again and finish just above where the crack starts.

name: Choss Avenue
description: Thin Finger Crack runs 1/3 of the way up, turning into a reaching crux for 1/3, last 1/3 is loose stone nub holds to the top-out.null

name: Crimp City
description: Start almost directly beneath the old bolts. Climb up, and start heading to the left. There should be, near the end, an edge, another one after that, then a set of two crimps. The finish hold is an edge up and to the left of those crimps, about three feet to the left of the highest old bolt, the one with an orange loop through it.

name: Drag Queen
description: Start on large belay ledge, climbs up to two other ledges at lower than 5.8 then to a finger crack roof crux

name: Gnome Mercy
description: A compressed traverse sure to challenge the lankier among us, but no cakewalk for shorter climbers either. Start with two hands on the obvious crack, then work your way right staying under the low ledge - feet anywhere you want, but no hands above the roof. Avoid touching the loose rock in the center of the traverse, as it is unstable/unsafe, but the horizontal crack to the right of the loose rock is good once dusted off, and there is one good pinch just under the roof. One option is to mantle the roof in a classy "waiter" move. Finish with two hands on the low sloper around the corner. Roll off to dismount!

name: Half Moon Slab
description: Solid face with pockets and crimps for hands, and a crux with feet on a small half moon shaped slab.   Starts with both hands on crimps and right foot on a small ledge. Left hand goes up to one of 2 good holds, and your right foot moves to the slab. Work your right hand up to the small pocket in a layback move, then power on up to the top 2 great holds. From here it's easy to work feet over to a large ledge to the left, it's a good place to rest as you don't really top, then just drop to the pad

name: Living covida loca
description: See picture for start and end. Start on the low ledge and feet up. Reach for the crimp and find a 2 finger pocket to lean on. Grab the next ledge. The rest is pretty easy.

name: Lockup
description: Start with great holds at the bottom and work your way up to a sloper crossover then big bump to the top. Watch rock quality, some feels weak.

name: Losing Touch
description: Super Clean Drill Hole Line

name: Low Hanging Fruit
description: Start with one hand in a pocket and one in a single grip before following a quick route ending in a two handed grip on an overhanging ledge to the right of the start.

name: Pablo Picasso
description: Mini-approach to the main crack, main crack runs up 2/3 the height of the wall, offwidth but solid rock, deep and bad feet all the way to the top-out

name: Parvus
description: "Parvus" lies just to the left of "When in doubt..." Start holding on to the left facing "crack," then reach up to the sloper that can really only be held like an undercling. Next handhold is a crimp, and finish on a horizontal edge.

name: Pinch left
description: SDS on the nice ledge, climb straight up avoiding the temptation to use the drill scar/crack to your left. Top out at the two nice pockets.

name: Pipe Dreams
description: An old drill scar. Starts with an undercling directly below where the scar disappears. Once up a little higher all hands and feet are inside or directly along the edge of the scar, other than the final feet, which are 2 nice ledges well outside the scar. In the lower portion of the scar there is a crack along the back that offers possible hands and good feet.

name: Pretty Machines
description: Hand crack that turns into an off-width halfway up, not vertical so a fall is dangerous, bad feet the whole way but solid crack holds

name: Sandstone Throne
description: After the starting ledge (green line), the only holds "on" for the starting wall are the crimp (purple arrow) and the second ledge (purple line) near the large diagonal crack. The next hand is a mantle off the left face on the upper section of the right wall (yellow). The middle section of the right wall is off (red lines). Using small crimps on the upper section, find feet below on the lower section and traverse across. Gain the upper ledge (blue tick). Top is at the white carat.

name: Unnamed warmup
description: Start from opposing jugs, go straight up to the crack under the small roof

name: When In Doubt Direct
description: Start in the crack in the corner right of "When in Doubt".   Do a few nifty moves to avoid the dyno start of "When in Doubt" and finish the same way

name: When in Doubt...
description: This is on the lower terrace of the park, very visible just as you enter the park. The route is to the right of the face. The start is a running dyno to a large flat edge. Climb the rest of the holds up.

name: Best Jams in Wisconsin
description: Obvious crack that widens at the top. No real defined crux, just continuous jams all the way to the top.

name: Clinical Procedure
description: P1 (5.5, 45'): Climb the hand crack that goes up two feet right of the arete, to a ledge with a big tree. You can walk off left from here, if desired.    P2 (5.8+, 75'): Move the belay back on the ledge system to the base of a slabby block. Go up the slab to a tight dihedral. The crux is near the top of the dihedral. Top out onto the ledge system above, traverse right along the wall for a few feet then lie-back up a sandy crack (about 3 feet left of a tree that stands close to the wall) choked by a chunk of shrubbery (the "shrubbery" might just be a stunted pine - I can't remember).        Descent: Walk (or rap from a tree) off from the summit.

name: In Your Face
description: Crux at the top after the large jug. May be a scary lead going between bolt 1 and 2.

name: Whitney's Chimney
description: This was formerly known as the "Off-width of Death", but upon actually climbing it there's good pro all the way and FUN chimney climbing at the top with a jug top out that goes at 5.9.    Follow the nice crack left of Best Jams to a pod in the Chimney with a no hands rest. Plug bomber gear and thrash to the apex of the roof and plug a #5 C4 to protect the top out.

name: Cheaper Than A Shot Of Whiskey
description: Easy bouldering crack.

name: Downclimb
description: First thing you see when walking to the boulder from Bigfoot Pillar.

name: Slopey Seconds
description: The route starts with a few moves through slopers and finishes using large jugs.

name: So Black It's Blue
description: Easy warm up problem. Start on chalked holds. Topping out is made difficult by pine needles and moss.

name: An Eye for an Eye
description: A great moderate outing with bolted face climbing, and a gear protected crack section. Start out right of the first bolt on small holds. Climb up to reach a left diagonal rail feature. At the third bolt do a balancey move left to reach the arete. Climb up to the crack past another bolt and then follow the right facing dihedral to a set of anchors with a nice stance. Don't forget to look for jugs on the left side once in the crack.

name: Bucky's Paradise (formerly "Unknown far left")
description: Begins up Eye for an Eye to the roof, then traverses left on big holds and around the corner up increasingly thin edges on a slab face.

name: Buddha Bukstein Crack
description: Tall climb with the full top out. Start in the crack and go slightly right to under the roof. Go right of the roof straight up to a ledge. Find a crack system on your right (look to your right for the rap chains) and take it to the top.

name: Just The Fad
description: Easy warm up.

name: Panacea Roof
description: Climb up slab to powerful roof moves up and right.

name: Remedy
description: This pitch was a temporary remedy for the chronic itch of finding new routes, as well as, the situation with the abandoned, old timey glued holds on the steep face right of the route. A very nice line with two distinct cruxes. Start on scruffy rock to reach the first bolt, then out onto the main face. The first crux comes at the third bolt and is a mix of sidepulls and deadpoints.   At the middle of the route soak up the rest as the top half is quite steep by WI standards. Climb jugs on the arete past two bolts. The third bolt on the arete is a hard clip and right at the begining of the second crux. Cranking on some small holds and divots will set you up for the throw to distant jugs. Enjoy the easier climbing to the top.  When you are lowering off take a look at the rediculous botch job to the right. Four ugly glued holds were abandoned by their creator. Probably out of self loathing. One of these holds is close by at the crux, though I didn't use it on the FA. These holds are a good example of what not to do when developing routes. There isn't even a line where they are at. It’s just too stupid. Anyhoo, I ripped the one bolt that was over there, and whoever is responsible for this mess should be ashamed of themselves.

name: Turn the Other Cheek
description: Despite the ugly looking moss, this line has some really nice moves, and just enough moss has rubbed off to reveal the crucial holds.    Start from either the left or the right, move up to the bottom of the groove - nice rail on the left.  Work up into the dihedral.  Either slab & mantel, or stem up to bomber hand jams.  Shift left onto easy ledges.  Head up just right of the pine tree to the steep finger crack.  Find the jugs and head straight up to a good ledge.    On lead, we went left here and scrambled around to the summit.  On TR, continue straight up:  the final headwall is 5.9/5.10-ish, and could use a bolt for protection.

name: Walk The Line
description: To the right of Remedy is a crack line that goes over some bulges at the top.  The first bit of climbing is hollow and the first piece of gear is roughly 12 feet up, but both the rock and the gear after that are good. Fun moves with crux at about 1/3 hieght.

name: Arete Action
description: Traverse in from the right. You can either stick clip the second bolt on Barely There or clip the first bolt on the project to the right and then continue up an left to a great knee bar rest before the final push.

name: Barely There
description: Direct start to Arete Action.  Stick clip the new first bolt and climb straight up the blank face.  A shouldery boulder problem on opposing gastons and underclings lead directly into the crux of Arete Action.  High quality climbing from bottom to top with no fluff.  Best route on the wall!

name: THE FINAL STRAW
description: Start out on Kingdom Come and move left below the roof.

name: Half Hearted
description: This is the short, steep arete on the left hand side.  Though short, it starts 30 feet off the deck so at least you get some added exposure.  Climb arete. The crux comes early on at the second bolt layaway/laybacking to a jug. You will need a little more than a half hearted try to finish it off.

name: Kingdom Come
description: When I first spotted this line it felt divinely ordained, and I was suddenly on a mission for god to bring a little piece of heaven to the earthly realm. Kingdom Come is perhaps the best sport pitch in Southern Wisconsin for the grade. It's a little bouldery, a little techy, and sure, a little upsetting that it isn't longer. However, it packs in a number of sweet moves on a series of seemingly divine natural holds, all the way to the top.   To the right of Half Hearted. Start on the arete and work up to a jug underneath the roof. Some dynamic moves and serious cranking will take you through the crux and onto the corner/nose feature. A couple more balancy moves gaurd the anchor. Just a beautiful line with engaging moves, that will require a little more than a wing and a prayer for the onsight.

name: On Wisconsin
description: On the right hand end of the wall there is right leaning corner which is slabby, colorful, and fuzzy. The two bolts that protect this line appear to be just slightly older than the rock itself. But who knows. They look like welded rod. They also appear to be some sort of glue-in, though they may just be pounded. I haven't found time to investigate, but am intrigued...

name: Rusted Ring Right
description: Slab route, with small crimps in between large holds. Climbs well even when it looks mossy.

name: Whitney's Revenge
description: A two part climb. Ascend the flaring chimney directly under Half Hearted, then step left into the finger to hand crack a few feet left of HH.

name: Awsome Arete
description: Amazing route like none other in Wisconsin. Moves straight up the arete, utilizes a bunch of heals to stop the barndoor, and lots of pinches and slaps up the arete. The crux comes up high with some thin vertical seams.

name: Choss to Treasure
description: Head up the slab through some loose rock, some neat moves lead you into the small overhang on positive holds. After pulling over the small roof head out and left though the crux to gain a rest ledge...After clipping the next couple bolts you can either move out to the exposed arete (5.10/11), or head up direct(desperate feeling 5.12ish).

name: Dihedral Dance
description: Move up the slab and over roof using 4 bolts, finish  using small gear in the crack. The crux is at the last bolt getting into the crack.

name: Mark it Zero!
description: Begin at flaring crack (usually filled with beetles) and climb up and left, 30 feet, to crack system just below the first overhang.  Pull the overhang and advance to second overhang (crux).  Continue up face using bomber holds to a jam crack.  This crack leads you to a point where the angle eases and eventually tops out on a nice, roomy belay ledge.  Finish climb or continue to scramble up to Castle Rock summit.  A fun and varied climb!

name: Rainday
description: Nice face route, fairly sustained. The crux is right at the top. You can clip the anchors of the crux holds if your tall, or its a couple more tough moves to gain the ledge.

name: Sorry Devin
description: Without knowing more of the history of this area I can't claim FA but seems like something that may get ignored. Also a nice route to do to get some height. Starts as a crack/chimney climb. Once you hit the tree in the crack go left straight up to top out. You know you're about to top out when you see beer cans in a crack. You can walk off or setup a top belay.

name: Gamma Bomb
description: Sharp arete 20 feet right of the Hulk.  Scramble up to the arete and stick clip the high first bolt.  Start with your right hand pinching the arete and a left hand edge.  Layback and smear your way past the second bolt and then cruise the last couple feet to the anchor.

name: Incredible Hulk
description: Short stout and green.  This is the middle route on the wall.  The dihedral and boulder to the right are off.  Use just the right feet and a very long reach to setup for the subtle sloper match before the second bolt.  Get a quick shake and release your inner hulk to surpass the boulder problem guarding the anchors.      Unfortunately there is a drilled three finger pocket to the right of the third bolt.  It can be avoided with a very long reach.  It does not offer much purchase for those of us with fat fingers.

name: The Phoenix
description: Starts 10 feet right of Slab Me Silly.  Use the arete and face holds to climb past 4 bolts to the shared finish (3 more bolts) of Slab Me Silly.      A few tough moves around the second bolt lead to a good rest.  Shake out before tackling the upper crux.

name: Slab Me Silly
description: Like many of the longer routes at C.R., this route has two distinct and difficult sections divided by a sit-down rest.  The lower section is a 5.12 slab that requires a hard pull on a sharp crimp with zero feet.  Technical and thought provoking this section won't disappoint the slab enthusiast.  The upper face is a bit easier 5.11 climbing, but the movement is fantastic.  Look for an unlikely sloper with the right hand to navigate the crux.  All in all a really fun route.

name: [Redacted]
description: Obvious sit start far left side of boulder. Work your way up slopers and small feet. Crux is 3rd or 4th sloper to large jug. Then finish up the same as White Trash.

name: White Trash
description: Stand start on the slab, right side of the boulder. Use obvious holds to ascend to top. Arete on. Fun movement through the roof.

name: Locomotive
description: A very consistant mixed pro climb. It is long and requires the whole array of climbing techniques (layback, jams, mantling, undercling, ect.) So much fun, it's too bad that atthis time the area remains closed after over 5 years of discussion over the future of the park. There are talks about the possible transfer ofthe park to DNS, however, it looks as if the potential owners are no more favorable to climbers than the previous.The best thing to do is to refrain from using the area for climbing. We do not want to jeopardize our meek chances and send a wrong signal to the powers to be.

name: Backside Warm-Up
description: Climb up the backside of boulder using horizontal cracks and large ledge for feet.  Corner is optional for a little diversity.  I think this often gets forgotten about.

name: Plutocrat
description: Start with right hand low on the right side of the arete, left hand on a cool iron crimp. Slap your way up the arete and top out directly.    Short but has some fun moves.

name: space ship traverse
description: sit start on far left of boulder.  make move into the "flying saucer" type sloper/jug thing.  Probably the coolest hold I've ever grabbed.  Then its a very casual traverse across the lip on jugs to the end.  be careful for potential holds to break along top.

name: Tight Space
description: Traverse the entire boulder avoiding the lip till the last move. Crux comes after squeezing past the big tree. Fun little crimps!

name: UFO Slab
description: Pretty awesome climb, but I am sure someone has done it before.    Climb the slabby face right of the backside of the boulder. Use anything left of the big crack on the right side (including arete up top), and anything right of the crack on the left. Make your way up the face using good holds till you reach the top. Only problem is that it is super dirty. Could use some cleaning!

name: Zoro's Conundrum
description: Start on the far right of the horizontal crack, traverse left then up the arête. Top out at the apex.

name: Shapes Of My Soul
description: SDS. Start low on right side pull up on bulbous slopers. Keeping low work left and uphill around the overhanging horn then up and left to top. Delightful and Sequency moves.

name: Soul Food
description: SDS. same start as Shapes Of My Soul, but when you reach the horn, mantle over top and up.

name: All in All
description: Perhaps 35 feet or so of continous bouldering at solid 5.12 climbing. Something like that. Start way down on the right side of the big boulder on steep arete at some really good pockets. Work up the arete using whatever feels good to the corner. Get a little rest and then start into the left tending traverse over crimps and slopers to the pointed jug on All In The Family, and continue to the top of that route.

name: All in the Family
description: A long line that starts out in the hole and works up separate features to join Godfather at the top. Sharp low holds for the sit down lead to a pointed jug. With low left undercling reach up and hit the first in a series of slopers. Work left to a positive undercling rail and the crux. Follow that sucka to the top through more crimps, pockets, and flakes. A true classic for the park.

name: An Offer He Couldn't Refuse
description: Starts on easy corner problem, into good pods from 'the good times are killing me' then goes out right to break in the rock. match and then up and right on what could be fragile pockets, so be careful when up there. word

name: Call in the Cleaners
description: Start on arete and traverse right to center of face and climb up to lip. Be care full of the good features up high they need more climbing to see if any more are going to break. I did not step on any of them for fear of them breaking.

name: Corleone's Corner
description: goes straight up the corner to the left of 'the good times are killing me'

name: Cosa Nostra
description: Start on crimps about head height just left of the arete.  Work up the tall face using small holds while avoiding the arete until you can reach the jugs at the top.

name: Ehhh Tony
description: A sort of compilation of a few lines.  Starts on the very bottom portion of the arete right of the "Godfather" line on pockets.  Cross right hand up to a two finger dish, and left hand move to an sidepull/undercling on the other side of the arete.  Shimmy up the arete to the crip rail, and transition onto Cosa Nostra. Top-out on good jugs.

name: The Godfather
description: One of the most recognizable classics in the park, this line was first cleaned and bouldered by Dave Groth in the mid eighties. Early repeats by John Sherman and Eric Zschiesche, during their Stone Crusade tour in the early 90's.  This tall, steep, beautiful problem hosts an awesome series of side pull and gaston pockets. The movement flows well with a wide selection of footholds and positive handholds while steadily growing harder until the lip which sports a rather thoughtful mantle. It ain’t over until you're standing up.

name: The Good Times are Killing Me
description: You can't miss this line on the north side of the big boulder.  Look for the set of solitary pockets out on the face.   Then look at how perfectly smooth the wall is below them.     Start out on the boulder to the right of the pockets.  With a right hand side pull on the arete, hop up into the pockets and get established.  A small foot pocket way out left will let you pop up to the lip.  Climb into the shallow trough.  Pretty fun and just steep enough to be really enjoyable.    You can also climb up the left arete to a couple of deep pockets and then move out the pockets on the face.  About the same difficulty.

name: Sleeping With The Fishes
description: Start on the horn from "All in the Family" go to seam or slopey crimp to the left, then up with left hand farther up and left to slopey crimp hold with a thumb catch, foot up near right hand and press up. go to small seam that runs along just under where rock turns vertical, match and up to the lip.

name: The Snitch
description: On-Sight Beta:   Begin matched on the Godfather start. Climb into, then up the blunt arete between GF and The Good Times Are Killing Me.    Flash Beta:    Move up and away from God Father via gastons/side-pulls on the arete's right side. Established at the base of the arete, the crux works through left-hand crimpers/pinches from a high right-hand crimp/pinch, culminating in a semi dynamic dead-point. Jug layback to the top.

name: under arete's
description: Climb up arete using good under clings and large crest, but be light on your feet it flex's but I could not break it when I tried.

name: Tick Me
description: Sit start on jagged boulder with hands on jugs, slap up the arete and sloper to the left.

name: Tick You
description: Starts on jugs, lock off with high feet a throw to the jug and up the slab, really fun shortie actually.

name: Blade
description: Sweet little problem that starts on the boulder protruding from above two boulders on either side.     Cleaned and established by Zach Mathe.

name: Flavor Savor
description: An amazing new addition to the Box Canyon.  Stand start and climb up tall and steep arete.  Topout is the trick on this one.  Super fun and powerful!  Thanks to Vince and Rhoads for seeing and cleaning the line.

name: The Lorax
description: Traverse the mustache boulder lip on bad slopers and crimps. Head straight up to a crimp when you reach the corner and top out. Watch your head on the rocks behind you on this problem.    The crimp at the end of the problem has broken into a smaller one since we did this climb which has probably made this climb harder.

name: Midwest Mustache Ride
description: Sloper problem. Sandy feet at the very bottom but the rest of it is good.

name: Pushbroom
description: Nice three move warm up with a secret jug! Stand start.

name: Soul Patch
description: Fun slab climbing. Starts with fairly hard mantle, then continues up the face, angles a bit right, then left at the lip on slopers.

name: The Basilisk AKA Cannons Sit
description: Start left hand on the lowest part of the arete on the corner and right hand about a foot higher on a mediocre slopey hold.  Do some campusy moves and follow the arete all the way up.  Cold temps are nice for this one.

name: Cannons
description: 50 yards past Flavor Savor to the right, 10 yards downhill from the cliff line.   Start low left on slopers with thumb catches and go up right, top out at apex.   Possible lower start...

name: Dick in the Corner
description: Funny problem. Start right hand in right facing ledge and left hand on arete. Move left hand up and scurry your feet up. good luck

name: Funky Tut
description: For full credit sit start on the ground with hands matched near the middle of the rail, do a few moves and mantle over the lip.

name: The Monster In The Mirror
description: On-Sight Beta:   Start on the obvious sweet spots at the base of the uphill rail running parallel to the Cannons rail. Climb into and finish out Cannons.    Flash Beta:   Technical and surprisingly good low-ball climbing gives way to power endurance. The crux involves setting up for and transiting into Cannons without dabbing. Heel / toe hooks are clutch for the opening moves.

name: Prick
description: Sit start on huge undercling, reach up for the sharp crimp in the middle of the face and throw for the lip of the boulder. Follow Prickler to the top.

name: Prickler
description: Climb slanted arete using good holds and heel hooks. Don't chicken out at the crux and top out early.

name: Don't Fear The Knob
description: Sit start on the lowest part of the face go straight up.

name: Mint Julep
description: Sit start climb the face

name: Afternoon Delight
description: Sit start on left crimp and right gaston, go up for large ledge on the right, continue up ledges.

name: The Good, The Bad, The Dodge
description: Sit start low left sidepull and large right pocket in the middle follow the arete up

name: Singled Out
description: Sit start on the side pull, follow crimps and ledges left and up.

name: Deustchlander Uber Alles
description: This is a proud line that climbs the rightside of a prominent double streak on the right hand side of the wall.  A fixed pin is still in place to hold your swings...  Oh and you will swing...  A proud effort of Rich and Rob.  Slightly overhanging the climbing involves small holds of which a lot seem to face the wrong way.  Hard all the way to the top.

name: Schizer!
description: Easier line on the wall. A chossy hard mantle or a lunge for a horn leads to good moves and better rock up higher.

name: Was ist Das?
description: This is the crack line to the right of Deustchlander.  It starts out sort of slabby and then gets steeper and harder the higher you go.  Some big moves at the end will keep your atttention until it is all said and done.

name: 5 more minutes
description: start the same as grounded for life. continue to the first sloperhold this becomes a small side pull for your right hand and exit out straight up from here. fun little variation

name: Big Jim
description: Large boulder that faces downhill from the Deutschlander wall.  Start on jugs and cruise your way up steep prow.  Super fun!

name: big jim center
description: start on right hold of upper crack and climb line between the two aretes.

name: big jim left
description: start on left side and move up left crack to high jug then make big move up and right to top out

name: Big Jim Mantle
description: An initial low mantel move (4 feet off ground)into some very easy slab work. Fun practice and very low risk.

name: Capitalization Separates Us From the Animals
description: Climbs directly through "time out". Starts on a good left hand sidepull in the wide horizontal. Good sloper on the lip and jugs to top out.

name: Corporal Punishment
description: Start sitting with your right hand on a low undercling and left hand on a pinch on the arete, pull on and bust a hard move up and right then set feet and throw for a decent sloper higher on the arete.

name: Grounded For Life
description: Crux is pulling up to the face and topping it out. Also odd at first to have the rock behind you for the traverse in. Not bad when you get used to it but kinda "inspect her gadget" at hp40 ish. but not as intrusive. cool features and good movement. Starts on obvious jug and goes to the right using the various lip holds and also the crack inside the roof for about 5 feet or so and then up the face

name: House Arrest
description: If you're facing 'Out Past Curfew' it's on your left. Start on the far left and traverse right and up. not a bad little warm up.

name: Judas Cradle
description: Sit start on the low sloper with a heel-toe cam in order to grab a pretty decent crimp in the crack. Once you've gained control of the crimp bring your foot up to the big ledge then move the left hand up to an intermediate then bump to nice rail then top out. This is no ultra mega classic route by any means but definitely one id suggest hopping on if you're looking for something to do in the area. Felt easy to me but maybe harder for taller climbers.  Send vid: ​https://vimeo.com/398395225​​​

name: Lost Zane
description: Start with a good arm hook under the arete and a undercling with the left hand. Top out is tricky.

name: Muramasa
description: Stand start  two crimps in the middle of the face, paste your feet and hit the top.   Sit start is possible

name: Out Past Curfew
description: Stellar problem.  start on jugs reg. or underclings on the arete.  up to obvious sidepull match and to the top for topout.

name: time out
description: start on far right and climb low ledge hand over hand to the arete then top out.

name: Tree Slab
description: Around corner from Big Jim, climb easy slab next to tree.

name: Twinkle Toes
description: Sit start around the far right corner on the decent sloper crimp of the low ledge. Then work your way out left using heel hooks to shimmy yourself over to the far left where you will top out. The hardest part is moving around the first corner and keeping the heel on because if it pops a dab is certain.  Beta: ​https://vimeo.com/398395988​​​

name: Chalk & Chocolate
description: SS with left hand on vertical edge gaston, right hand on crimp, left foot on bulge, right foot toe hook around right arete. Use a hold on the slopey left arete, slopey hold in middle of face, bump right foot out to start crimp and pull yr toe in to finish on the right arete and mantle over thin arete to finish. This problem is worth it if you're in the area. Why not?

name: The Bulge
description: Short bulge just to the right of the crack project.  Start low in the break with underclings, up and left to pockets.  Big move to slopey rail and top out.     Top might need some more cleaning.

name: Freaney's Fin
description: Move up the ever-thinner fin using good holds on either arete to tall topout.

name: Freaney's Fright
description: Cruxy start, then up the arete.

name: Illusions of Paradise
description: The first roof I've found at the Dodge. This thing is sssssiiiiccckkkk. Lots of tension, ok holds and poor feet.  Do some crunches before you get on this thing. Start on lip side jug move into seam behind you, slaps on both sides out to pointy arete, to the top.

name: Natural Highs Come a Whole Lot Cheaper
description: I've been looking at this one for awhile now. Before I broke my wrist, actually. It was a great way to get back into the game. It's the face with the death landing. A low crux leads to a thin, really sketchy slab. The slab includes a mono, a few holds that broke multiple times while cleaning and working, and some really skimpy feet. Needs more traffic, but I'm not sure that will work out. It cleaned up to be one of my favorite problems in the Dodge. As classic as most climbs of the same grade and danger in Bishop in my opinion.   youtube.com/watch?v=I_5hi7i…

name: Two tickets to paradise
description: Same Crack as right hand from Illusions.  I Start with nice toe hook and right hand on round under cling hold left on first crimp in crack.

name: Creature of the Deep
description: Stand start on the corner to the right of Sasquatch Face, and balance your way up the arete

name: Dead Wood
description: Sit start on a jug on the right side of the face. Make a long move up left to a jug and top it out.

name: Lochness Arete
description: SS on the jug directly on the arete. Climb up using arete and some stuff just to the left as well.

name: Sasquatch Face
description: The face to the right of Loch Ness Arete.

name: The Taint Of Truth
description: Start matched mid-face standing on top of the boulder on a good edge.  You kind of have to step your feet down from the top of the boulder to get on.  Move up and right on a couple of small crimps and another good edge to the topout.    It also seems possible to start sitting down on the right using some combination of the pockets found there.  I found the holds between the SDS and the hold I started on to be rather unpleasant though.

name: Tainted Love
description: SDS to The Taint of Truth.  Sit start on good pockets. Make a move left to a good edge and then lock off to a small right hand crimp. Throw a semi-desperate move to a good shelf on the left and then move up through the rest of ToT.

name: Deferred Judgement
description: On the face of the Pimp boulder.  Start on the obvious huge flake undercling low and right, surf up and left, top out on sweet sloper.

name: Keep Your Pimp Hand Strong
description: Start left hand good gaston, right hand poor crimp.  Move up on crimps to cool, slopey topout.

name: Word To Your Mother
description: Start on big undercling and climb up the arete until you can topout on big, rounded slopey jug.    FA dyno'ed from the undercling all the way to the jug.

name: Another Daydream
description: On the right side of the Daydream Boulder ST with hands on good jugs.  Work past gaston into undercling, and then into two locker hand jams.  Jugs at the top.  This is deffinately one of the reasons for a visit.  Good clean fun.

name: Curl right
description: Sit start on right corner and move up and left.

name: Curl Slab
description: climbs left side of curl boulder.

name: The Curl
description: Most obvious line on the boulder. Climbs up sharp holds.

name: Daydream Arete
description: Start with both hands on the arete in low, good holds.  Work up the arete via gaston and left face crimps to jug right on the arete.  Go left onto the face to finish up. An interesting inside heel hook adds the extra core tension to surf out onto the little holds.      Another good variation is to work further left on the face after you hit the good jug.  Adds a nice horzontal dyno.

name: Flake Face
description: Climb good flakes just right of center on the clean face.

name: The horn
description: Start on sloppy holds then move into two side pulls and bump to sandy horn.

name: Left  Alone
description: Start out on the left of the Lonely Boulder.  ST with hands on large holds.  Work up to the incut and a gaston with the right to jugs at the top.  Very fun moves.

name: Left Arete
description: Climb leaning left arete to top.

name: Lonely right face
description: On the far right side, start out with two large holds.  Go straight up.

name: Loner right Arete
description: Start out on the right side of the Lonely boulder off the ramp.  With two good holds on the right face, work your way left to the obvious slanting jug rail on the arete.  Follow this to the top.  Good moves and just fun.

name: The Loner
description: The Loner goes straight up the line of pockets without using anything to the left. Start out at two good pockets and gun it to the jug. The crux is getting your feet off the ledge and deadpointing the jug, though it is not quite over just like that.

name: Only the Lonely
description: Only the Lonely climbs out the overhanging bulge using holds on the left and right.  Start out with left hand on incut finger bucket, right hand on good side pull pocket.  Work up a bit on opposing side pulls to a big move over to the jug on the right.  This is and extremely satisfying move.  Jugs to the top.

name: Sweet Dream
description: Short but Awesome! Squeeze and slap your way up the arete.

name: Top out delight
description: Start on ramp and side pull and reach up and over to great sloper hold and top out

name: Wingspan
description: Start right hand on the low arete to the right of the Daydream Boulder, left hand on the flake in the front.  Feet go on the ramp in the middle and on the right arete of the boulder.   Power up the hollow flake on one side and the arete on the other, meeting up in the middle for the send on the boulder.

name: A Red Recollection
description: The year was 1996. Slick Willie was president. The Macarena was sweeping the nation. The internet was a torture device. And the U.S. sport climbing scene was still in it’s wild and rebellious adolescence. After a six month road trip of some the best sport crags in the nation at that time, Seth and I came back to Wisconsin with a whole new perspective on life. A Red Recollection was the first line we established here for obvious reasons, and it is named after the Red River Gorge, which I thought had the best sport climbing I'd ever seen.  The line climbs the center of the wall up a unique "tufaesque" layback feature for thirty feet with awesome non technical stemming. The crux seems to come all too soon and involves a thought provoking bulge, which is passed on the left. Continue up to your choice of low, or high anchor.

name: Crack left of Leftwing
description: Directly left of Leftwing is a fairly parallel-sided crack. Stem up the bottom, then pull around a bulge before squeezing through the crack to finish. Abundant face holds and feet make it a comfortable lead.

name: Espionage
description: Climb to the upper anchors of Red Recollection (clip with long sling), climb right, clip the last bolt of Secret Agent Man, and fire the final ~V3 crux leading to the anchors of Secret Agent Man. Of course, don't stop until you top out Secret Agent Man (only clipping the chains below the lip invalidates the ascent, you know).    A 007 way to clip the anchors of a great 13a. Also a good warm up...

name: Fahrenheit 23
description: From Huston's topo:   Boulder through the first three bolts (crux), shake out, and then continue up the wall above avoiding the chimney on your left. The grade is unconfirmed. Shares the final two bolts and chains with the previous route.

name: Get a Horse
description: Possibly the most underappreciated, if not downright overlooked, cracks in Wisconsin. I am astonished that this has not been developed or heavily climbed in the last 10 years. This overhanging crack climb contains some of the most prolonged, secure, well-protected trad climbing in the area, but be prepared to work for it. Start out with somewhat heady and insecure for the grade, face and arete moves on the same line as More Choss than Moss. Upon reaching the overhanging wall, traverse right and continue up the obvious crack in the corner using great hand jams and stemming feet. The crux for me was the awkward mantle about 3/4 of the way up the route. Continue up the rest of the crack system and build an anchor on large ledge (or be prepared for a long runout and serious rope drag)."Get a horse!", as shouted to us by one of the horseback riders upon seeing us hauling our gear up the trail, accurately describes the feeling after topping out this climb. This is fantastic crack climbing that will work you in a relatively short distance, with very few breakable holds for how untouched the rock has been in recent years.

name: Leftwing
description: Perhaps the most enjoyable 5.10 on the warmup wall, with a liberal grade. This route features fun, technical climbing on pretty good features. A few awkward moves at the crux detracts from the overall quality, but still a worthy route to get the blood moving.  You can easily TR Sobriety Test or hang draws.

name: Long Time Coming
description: Start on a good undercling and bump your way up to a gaston. Turn it into a sidepull and top out left using one small hidden crimp on the ramp.

name: Mean and Green
description: Mean and Green climbs the left hand version of the two routes on the first tall golden wall. They share the first 4 bolts. Crux at about 2/3 height leads to some amazing jugs up high. The quality can vary quite a bit on this route but a fun outing if you are not too offended by choss.

name: The Nordwand
description: From Huston's topo: Start up the first two bolts of Secret Agent Man before stepping to right around arete and charging up the steep north face. Better than it looks.

name: Now or Never
description: The left line of bolts on the S.A.M. pillar, Now or Never traverses up and left with very cool moves from near the start of a Red Recollection.  Crimpy moves take you up the steep face.  It's definitely harder (12a/b?) to stay on the face and avoid the jugs to the left.  Most stop at the first set of anchors over the bulge (same anchors for Red Recollection).

name: Nut Job
description: Perhaps the most enjoyable climbing on the wall, Nut Job is great warm up if you are confident at the grade. Named for the plethora of wired nut placements found along the route. Follow the obvious thin crack line in the center of the wall through jugs, and a few jams out featured rock. One bolt up high.

name: Quail Stew
description: Climb "Warm up 1" to it's third bolt (Warm up 1 crux). Then angle leftward through "Warm up 2" (clip 3rd bolt of Warm up 2, climb up and execute Warm up 2 crux). Next traverse across horizontal break into "Nut Job" (1-2 pieces of gear. execute Nut job crux). Traverse left just below the small roof and finish on the last two bolts of "Pocket Warmup" (crux of "Pocket warmup" and crux of entire link-up).   A fun warm up and a nice way to make for a longer pitch on a somewhat short wall...

name: Quality Control
description: This is a sweet problem that climbs a cool hanging block with an amazing iron band/tufa around the left end of the Qual Wall. It's a nice boulder to hit on your way back from warming up at the Lonelies.  Start on a jug in the break under the block, and climb out on to the face using amazing iron band crimps, then bust out left to the arete.  Head up the arete, then move back right to top out.

name: Secret Agent Man
description: Alongside the super classic Whiskey a Go-Go at Necedah, Secret Agent Man, has over the last couple decades, become a must do 5.13- sport route in Southern Wisconsin. This stunning face/arête line easily has some of the best rock in the Dodge, however, if you have spent much time walking cliff bands in the park, you know this wall is the 1% as far as roped climbing goes.  Start up big moves on good edges and arête to a high first bolt, then enter the short lived little dihedral. Work out left past a small bulgey boulder problem to gain an adequate shake above. Stay focused, and stay one the line, then launch into a series of breathtaking boulder problems stacked on top of each other on the left side of the sweeping, overhanging arête.

name: Slab Me Harder
description: Fourth route from the left hand side.

name: Slab Right
description: Far right bolted line on warm up wall. Kind of jacked.

name: Sobriety Test
description: The the most difficult of the warmups, and it looks better than it climbs. Fun climbing though, with an assortment of holds. You can’t miss the large pockets. Shares anchors with Leftwing.

name: Social Distancing
description: A nice boulder for warming up or if you didn't bring a pad. Sit start at the bottom of the funnel and traverse right into the bear cave. Follow the continuing overhang to ledge. This is a low traverse boulder. Maybe someone will send a vertical boulder here but the landing is seriously sloped and pretty janky.

name: Swim Test
description: Problem located below the left side of the sport cliff. Turn left on a trail just before the end of the cliff. The boulder is 20 feet down this trail on the left hand side. Can't miss it. Start on two mini jugs, go up right to a sloper, and straight up through another jug and undercling to the lip. Top out straight up over the lip.

name: Symptomatic
description: Classic highball for the park. Start in pit on obvious right hand sloper sidepull and left hand a little lower in the crack. Climb the arete through some nice holds. Trend a bit left as you near the top and finish to the left of the mushroom cap. Crux is low, top is easy but pumpy.

name: Tramadol
description: Tramadol: A narcotic for moderate to severe pain, with a high risk for addiction... Far right on the warm up wall, this "two" pitch route is quite unique for Wisconsin, providing a multi pitch opportunity for the novice climber to become addicted or to simply link the pitches, which keeps the pain away.  Pitch one climbs up the short, small right facing dihedral found above the water grooved, weathered rocked. A few perfect jugs, and crimps to the ledge above. Pitch two leaves the flat belay ledge and up a few more bolts on the fluted rock to the highest point of the wall.  Pitch one variation, start low and right of the first bolt and continue right of the bolt line to rejoin the route at bolt #3 for a 5.10- experience. Stick clipping the first bolt is highly recommended.

name: Unknown / "Meaner than Green"
description: The first route encountered when arriving at the Qual Wall from the Horse trail.    Follows a line of bolts up the face and takes the rightward line when bolts split at halfway.  Continue up to the sweeping headwall for the bouldery crux.

name: Unlisted Number
description: Thin climbing to a mid-height crux.  Feet are the key here.  A couple steep moves on big holds at the top.  Chains and biners at the top.

name: Chris Cross Choss
description: This line starts low and left, same as Cool Hand Luke.  Come around the corner with heel hooks and keep going up the thin rail to topout on center of face.      Overhanging Boulder uphill and more or less in the center of the Group A boulder cluster.  The overhanging face faces north.  Problems start in a pit.  Worth a session if you have done everything else.

name: Cool Hand Luke
description: Start low and left in the pit at an obvious jug at eye level.  Move up and round the corner to your right onto the face and up arete to mantle topout.  Hard to avoid the butt-dab on the rock behind you.

name: Dragons
description: Start on two slopey holds in a seam with a slopey heel hook.  Then slap your way up the pointed arete and finish the problem.

name: Dungeons
description: Starts in a pit on two good holds, traverses upwards then to the left to a good jug.  The slap up the top and mantle out.

name: Just Dew It
description: SDS low and right in The Pit and moves up the face to mantle topout.

name: Leprosy
description: Undercling start (with choss) bump crimp up to the flake, and top out.

name: Ashmatica
description: Climb overhanging arete to top.-

name: between a tree and a hard place
description: climb face using pockets to slot then big move to the top.  Holds are good you just don't want to fall.  Tree behind you but landing is OK.

name: Call Girl
description: Good arete warm up with cool hueco holds.

name: El Gran Encuentro
description: This is a nice little problem and the grade is harder if you have a small ape index.  Follow the double arete nestled in the corner directly straight up. Start with left hand on small crimp and right hand on undercling/side pull.  This problem includes fun sidepull crimps, a nice arete meat hook, and great heel hook and a wondrous top-out. Enjoy.
