name: The Firing Squad
description: starts on obvious jug on left of wall, staight up

name: Foothold Massacre
description: start on Mr. Longarm and traverse left to arete then up. It mostly stays on the arete with left hand and right hand on face. fyi

name: Full Execution
description: start far left on jug. traverse through hangman and continue along using the 3 underclings and left hand slopers round the corner and up.  should be a really hard linkup.

name: Get the Hell Outta Dodge
description: A classic mantle problem. Start under steep part and climb the steep seam to the lip and a tough mantle onto the sloping top.   #23 JJ's old topo.

name: Get The Hell Outta Dodge-Exit Right
description: Start under steep part and climb the steep seam to the lip. Instead of Classic Mantle  proceed to throw far right to a gaston.  Use a left heel where you matched hands originally and move left hand over with right. Finish by topping out straight from there.  This adds some challenging fun to an already classic route.

name: The Guillotine Left
description: start on right side of execution boulder on rock. small left crimp and big right sidepull.  step onto the wall. left up to bad sloper. right. Try not to loose your head while trying to lunge to good ledge left and topout... kind of a pun. get it?

name: The Guillotine Right
description: tops out guillotine to the right.

name: Hangman
description: start on obvious left jug, up right to good hold, match, out right to sloper, match and shoot for jug above. topout.

name: Highly Executed
description: start on hangman and continue on the top slopers until the corner, then u top out.

name: Internet Predator
description: Start on ledge between "Get Outta Dodge" and the arete.  Using anything right of the seam on Dodge and anything left of the arete make your way straight up.      Spoiler Alert!!!   Specific FA Beta: started left hand on good crimp on slopy ledge and right hand on dimpled corner with a right heel hook out on same ledge a bit further out. Reach up high to a series of two sharp pocket/crimp/pinchy things. Pick you fav. and then go up to lip with left hand (my feet would cut)Surf out right, hand foot match left and  press it out.

name: Lethal Injection
description: start on obious jug on left, right to decent ledge and up from there.

name: Mark it Zero
description: Climb face on right side of arete using good pockets and arete.  Holds are good but some of this might still break so test things.

name: Massacre Crack
description: Nice handcrack in the Massacre area.  Not sure if it’s in the guidebook but it wasn’t here.  Stay in the crack for full value.

name: Massacre Direct
description: start right hand on good sidepull left on arete. straight up

name: Midwest Harcore Presents......"Boulder Problem of the Year"
description: Great route! Starts on underclings and heads straight up on crimps to a throw.

name: Mr. Longarm
description: start on on either double underclings or right hand on jug left on undercling. up right hand to high sidepull match, then up to seam.  From here you go left hand out bulge to a flake. Highstep right and go to top or small intermediate and to the top.  match carefully, then reach back to good seam.

name: Mrs. Shortarm
description: Start on right hand undercling and left hand jug to the right of Mr. Longarm.  Move to the two crimps and continue up the corner utilizing holds on both sides.  Top out on the corner.     It may or may not be a new problem and it could definitely use some more cleaning.  There is a really cool jug at the right on the top that I would be careful when you grab too.

name: slugs
description: I was half asleep when I put this up the first time. Sorry the description was wierd.      It is a sit start on ashmatica and then you go across to the start of get the hell out of dodge and finish up that.

name: ticks
description: start on get the hell out of dodge and traverse into the arete.

name: Another Warmup
description: Climb up on good edges

name: The Bane of Vince
description: Slightly contrived, maybe reachy, but there are fun moves. Vince has been trying to work the face directly, this line strays slightly right.

name: Battle of the Bulge
description: Sit Start under the left side of the roof on large jug, move out the bulge, onto the face and directly up the arete using sidepulls on either side. Crux comes when trying to get fingers into the small vertical crack on the right hand face.

name: Battle of the Midwest
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: Belly of the Beast
description: Climb offwidth chimney just right of the Picasso lines.

name: bottom of the barrel
description: Sit start on OK right hand and small left crimp with good right foot, move up and right to slot one more move to the top. Fun hard sit start to nice mantel top out. Full Rib Mt style problem.

name: Dangle
description: Start same as for Left Out, but move up the right arete staying and finishing on the face. After the roof there is a great sidepull around the right corner and up, after grabing this with right hand throw high and left for small crimp on the face. Crux is hitting the next sloper and keeping your feet from dangling.

name: Dire Straight
description: Start by using both cracks. Deep fingers get you into the climb. Climb past wobbly block on right. The right crack becomes to small to get fingers in and the left crack stops for a bit. Layback the small arete on the right crack and move up. Reachy moves to topout. The crux is in your mind. This thing gets scary.

name: Early Bird
description: Starts on right arete and moves up and left using sloper rail and crimps

name: Eighteen (and life)
description: Start at a large, right facing sidepull. Layback up to some decent holds and move up to the lonely sidepull.   Up to the top. #18 JJ's old topo.

name: Face Left of Wright's Arete
description: Maybe this is Wrights Arete, but there is a direct line that avoids using the arete and staying on the face.  A good fun highball none the less.

name: first things first
description: climb up left arete and top out.  Super fun for any one in the group that needs confidence improving lines.

name: Forgotten Finger Crack
description: Climb Finger crack to top and either exit left or move up face to top out.

name: Layback Crack Attack
description: A fun angled crack climb with plenty of good hands and feet.

name: Leaning Rock
description: You can start down and on the right low, or on the left.  Hit the arete and up and over.  #11 JJ's old topo.

name: Left out
description: This route starts in the middle of the face and works its way up the left arete. The crux is a right hand throw to the bad arete, after securing a left hand crimp on the arete. Bringing the feet up over the lip of the roof may also be a comittment crux for some.

name: Me So Gorny
description: Decent problem if you ignore the little ledge and the boulders below you.  Move up slabby face on decent holds and high feet.

name: Me So Gorny Direct...AKA Don't Commit! The Footchip You Are On Is Broken!
description: Starts the same as Me So Gorny, then straight up the face, crux at the top. Right face is off.

name: Midwest Hardcore (aka 6hrs)
description: Start with right hand on small nob, left hand on small crimp, work your way up crimpy face into sidepulls up to a great jug rest, hike your feet and go for large ledge out left.  Topout.

name: Mr. Clean
description: Start with undercling and climb flake and face to jug topout.

name: Nameless
description: This is a stand out classic.  Climb the arete on the right side with powerful gut tension core popping moves will keep you moving until you reach the first of two crimps on the arete up high.  One more set of moves and it is nearly all over...  #15 JJ's old topo.

name: Nameless Sit
description: Start sitting and climb Nameless.  A couple holds on the right face may just be important.  This adds a few interesting moves to an already awesome climb.

name: Nameless Slab
description: Climb slab route just left of Nameless Arete.  Fun warm-up.

name: One Hand Clapping
description: Climb crack- some very nice jams in there...  #19 JJ's old topo.

name: Picasso Center
description: Start out with hands on either side of the arete.  Get the pocket jug with the right and work up arete using side pull crimps on left and larger holds on right.  Finish with a jam in the finger crack at the top.  Very exciting.  #21 JJ's old topo.

name: Picasso Left
description: Start out on a good left crimp and right crimp sidepull.  Go up to the hollow jugs and then work to the right corner.  Climb to top just left of corner.  #22 JJ's old topo.

name: Picasso Pillar
description: Ascend the narrow pillar on crimps and slopes straight to the top. This climbs surprisingly well considering its width...

name: Picasso Right
description: Start out on arete, and work to two pockets.  Straight up corner to the top.  #20 JJ's old topo.

name: Picasso way left
description: All large edges, a big crack and big foot holds make this a good warm up.

name: Popalicious
description: Start as for Sandstone Violence, traverse left to Nameless Arete.  Adds a fun few moves and hard to go wrong finishing on Nameless.  Maybe easier for the tall.

name: Product of the Southwest
description: Stand start on right low crimp and high left pinch/sidepull. The meat of the route comes next with intricate footwork leading you into a very slopey right leaning rail. Continue to apex of rail and top out directly. (hint: the lip right above you is bomber)

name: The Prostrator
description: Super sharp crimping the whole way, youll want good finger pads , or a zen like mind state to do this one...

name: Sandstone Violence
description: In many ways THE line on Backbone Ridge if not the whole park. This slightly overhanging line is filled with unique moves and an all out toss to a jug at 3/4 height. Start out in the middle of the block on a good sidepull. Work straight up past hard holds and an almost ghostlike crimp up high to the horizontal. Top out through a niche at the top. A very tall, proud line.  #14 JJ's old topo.

name: Scarete
description: The bottom has nice jugs/edges to get to the middle of the problem staying on the left side to center but once past the overhang the small tiny crimps, edges, and pinches come out to play.  Straight up a little to the right.

name: Take My Picture
description: Climb tall arete using crack out left.  Top-out can be tricky.

name: Topshelf
description: Work your way up to the ledge with well-placed and obvious hands. Mantle and top out.

name: Trail Crew
description: Start with a high right and move to big side pull for left hand and move up and out left to sloppy ramp.  climb get a bit scary up top due to marginal holds.   Tread softly on the right hand side pull it might come off some day soon.

name: Twelve A
description: Nice warm-up with pinches, pockets, edges, and jugs.  #12a JJ's old topo.

name: Twelve High
description: Start in notch with small roof. Work up some small holds tending left to jugs. Straight up to top.  #12 JJ's old topo.

name: Udaho
description: sit-start and move up through side pulls in to big undercling, hike your feet and move to horn.

name: Vitamin V-less
description: Start at some small holds and get up to the curved jug.  Work your way into the corner to finish up.  You can also start over on the ear lobe hold and work into the start for a bit more difficulty.  #13 JJ's old topo.

name: When I was Seventeen
description: Start out on good holds and work your up to better ones on corner to top.  #17 JJ's old topo.

name: World Peace
description: Start sitting below Nameless and climb into Sandstone Violence.  This climbs through the entirety of the proud wall and the movement is fantastic.  Similar in difficulty and style to the Keymaker at Devil's Lake, though maybe a touch harder.

name: Wright's Arete
description: An excellent highball though a tad spooky. Climb arete and just to the left to the top.  #16 JJ's old topo.

name: Yet Another Warmup
description: Start on the obvious bulb near arete, climb straight to top on good holds.    A doable, but possibly heady route for the new climber.

name: Butthole Left
description: A Bit Contrived, but start under the cave and use the face hold on the lip and the slot to move to the left arete. Bump up left arete and swing feet over to eventually top out. Hidden Heel toe cam to make the move easier

name: Butthole Right
description: Climb the Right side of the boulder starting under the small roof. Use the Right Arete and some face holds to top out. Easy Route.

name: Cube
description: Start on right corner of the cube, get the foot, work left across the lip and up. Staying off any other boulders.

name: Cube direct
description: Start left corner of Cube and go up.

name: Direct Butthole
description: Starting under the boulder pull directly on to the face after the roof. Avoid the arete on both sides and use only face holds. Good slots to a sharp pocket.

name: Ender
description: start on round bulge and move in the corridor then up to keystone and out to the lip, then roll over top of the key stone.  Avoid the back wall.  Don't slide back or this might be a Day Ender.

name: Got Shorty
description: Start on good jug, go up and top out.

name: Groth Spurt
description: This line starts at a triangular hold at chest height half way back in the cave on the left side, comes out the cave and climbs over the first bulge to the left.

name: High Anxiety
description: Work up  the right face and arete to a good undercling under the roof.  Up and over.  #5 JJ's old topo.

name: Huston's Arête
description: Start at the jugs in the middle of the face. Move up and right over good holds until you are hugging the shield, then climb up the arête. I have a feeling that this one may end in an all out dyno for the top. I wouldn't mind having a couple beefy pads down below...

name: Irrationality
description: This line links up Split personality and Resolution.  SDS on Split and cross through to two finger pocket, lock-off and get good gaston on Resolution.  A couple hard moves to the finish and top-out.   We weren't sure if this had been done before, but the moves are cool and harder than Split.  If you like sharp holds go get on this one.

name: Napolean Complex
description: SDS, slap your way up the steep pointed arete to top out.  #2 JJ's old topo.

name: Napolean Face Left
description: Left side of the uphill face of the Napolean Boulder.  Sit start on good holds, move up with a big move and topout.      Left side of the face in the sun.  Low start, move up and topout.  This is the Napolean Boulder, the overhanging arete on the left is the V3 Napolean Complex.  About 100 feet downhill from Huston's Arete.      Couple lines on the Napolean Boulder.  Napolean Complex overhanging arete on the very left.  The right (uphill) face holds 2 decent seperate lines, undoubtedly done before (Schlick?).  Napolean Face Left and N. F. Right.  Both around V1, both pretty fun warmups for the area.

name: Napolean Face Right
description: Sit start right hand good jug and left on low edge.  Big move up and left to cool gaston.  Top out.  Or whatever you want.

name: Press It Out
description: start on arete and move way out right to next good hold then up.  Top out is the crux.

name: Press it out Direct
description: Climb up Arete with out going to the large right side pull.  Top outs the crux but the right hand is pretty sharp too.  going up direct changes the problem a lot with only cutting out one hand, you have to move your left to a worse hold and can't use the better right foot that is to far over.

name: Resolution
description: Start on the left of the face down low.  Work through a painfull side pull and go straight up to small holds or slap out left to corner and then up and right.  #10 JJ's old topo.

name: Schizophrenia (Right of Split Personality)
description: This was a fun warm up that starts with the corner jug of Split Personality and goes up the right face. Hand jam to top out.

name: Seperation Anxiety
description: Pretty classic arete/face problem on the opposite side of the boulder from High Anxiety. Climb great features to the right of the large sugary flake. #3 JJ's old topo.

name: Seperation face
description: Use far right crack system and left face holds to move up.  Last move before the top is a little more committing then the rest of the climb. Nice warm up.

name: The Seperatist
description: Climb up the seam left of High Anxiety to a hard undercling move, then up to the top.   #4 JJ's old topo.

name: Smack Crack Left
description: Ahh yes...  It is good if you don't mind getting a little physical.  Climb up big holds to roof.  Up and over via the crack.  #6 JJ's old topo.

name: Smack Crack left Dyno
description: Climb inside corner of Smack Crack to good holds at center break and Dyno for the lip (the top of the bluff, not the jug at mid height).

name: Smack Crack Right
description: Climb up to the roof and plug good hands throught the roof.  #7 JJ's old topo.

name: Smack Crack WAY Right
description: There are three cracks for Smack Crack, this one is farthest right near the edge of the formation. Start just below the crack, off fingers crack at the top.

name: Split Personality
description: Quintessential bouldering on a flawless shield of slightly overhanging stone. Start out low on sharp positive crimps on the right side of the boulder and keep crimping till you hit the jugs up high and then surf left.   #9 JJ's old topo.

name: Things just got harder
description: Start on jug with side pull and get feet high and move up avoiding the left arete.  Was a lot easier and the hand broke making it a little more interesting.

name: Veasy AKA "Why Not?"
description: Great big holds but steep enough to be fun.  #8 JJ's old topo.

name: Venom
description: Sit start on the large Horizontal flake and move threw a few under cling laybacks to a series of progressively  smaller holds. last two are very bad but its still one of the funnest lines.

name: Warm up Center
description: Climb center Crack up nice holds.

name: Warm up Left
description: Start on left side pull move your feet up and hit the lip.  Nice warm up area.

name: Warm up Right
description: climb right crack to fun top out.

name: A Test of Tesselation
description: Start as for SMAC, but move to the right of the arete and up the face. The first move with be more aesthetic for the funnel chested folks.

name: Brushrunners Delight
description: Start on the prominent knob and work up the crack, using both crack and face holds.

name: Carrion
description: SDS on slopers, up to knob, climb face to mossy slopey topout.

name: Little Bit of Lank
description: Start low on the horizontal break and move  up the face avoiding the crack. The crux is right at the top.

name: Low Down with a S.A.D. Frown
description: Sit start on the lowest end corner. Traverse up and right into a mantle top out.

name: Mossius Enigma
description: Climb the unfun dirty crack to a very difficult move and top out....or dont bother

name: Strong Men Also Cry
description: Every move is classic on this new Dodge testpeice. Super complex sequencing, burly moves, complete with a highball topout. This route may rival Sandstone Violence in both quality and difficulty.    Sit down start under a bulge, move up staying on the left side of the arete.

name: Zpring Time Arete
description: Sit start with right hand on the arete, bump up with difficulty, Zpring for the horisontal break, then finish up with thin crimps on the uppper half.

name: Zummer Time Crack
description: Climb this tricky crack from a crouch start. This is not as easy as it first looks.

name: Born Full Grown
description: Start on the obvious jug and jump to the lip.  Be careful where you grab, the lip is sharp in some places.

name: Cat Scratch Fever
description: Start the same as for Born Full Grown, but traverse right on good holds and ledges.  Topout by the small horn.

name: Head Trauma
description: Sit Down Start with left hand on arete and right hand on good undercling. Move up using arete and crimps right of arete to the top

name: Mesmerizing The Ultra
description: Climb up the slabby, cracked face just left of the arete.

name: Pangea
description: on the same boulder as Born Full Grown. Looking at BFG go around the boulder to the left. Start right hand on high sloper and left on sidepull. Move up and left to slopy slot then straight up.

name: Young Goodman Brown
description: Climbs up to the right of the arete.  Start using a funky pocket hold, and move up the face using the crack on the right and some face holds on the left.

name: The Catacomb
description: Sit start with right hand on a crimp, and left hand on crimp on the arete.  Work up arete and on sharp holds. Top out straight up.  Felt very sharp, though maybe more traffic will help take some of the bite out of the holds.

name: The Champ
description: Same start as Full Extension Direct but more up and right and avoid the arete/crimps on FED. look carefully to find the good crimps/sidepulls. Top will probably need to be cleaned before attempted.

name: Full Extension
description: Start above little drop off on jugs and move low and left and go up left arete

name: Full Extension Direct
description: Start on jug and move left/up using arete and crimps

name: Coagulation
description: Start on right side on good holds and move left along sloper rail using heel hooks and low feet. Avoid jugs above till all the way to the left. Follow the posted picture

name: Hemophilia
description: Same side as Coagulation but going from left to right. Start on jug and work your way right through worsening slopers, make big move and work around top right of boulder

name: Birds Of Prey
description: Climbs the face just right of Nobody You Know.  Start in the horizontal break, and go straight up.

name: Coffin Varnish
description: Climbs up just left of the arete.  Start low on a good hold, move up the crack to the horn, and top out straight up.

name: Jurassic Park
description: Starts the same as for Pot Kettle Black, but instead of traversing right, continue straight up.

name: Nobody You Know
description: Climbs up the arete on the south face.

name: Pot Kettle Black
description: Start on top of the small slab/block.  Move up to the break then traverse out right along the break to the arete, and top out.

name: De Wallen
description: Start sitting with both hands on the right arete, compress out steep terrain to an exciting finish on the left side.

name: Red Light District
description: Fairly tall boulder near the base of the southern end of the bluff.  Pretty cool red rock with a few big ledges on it.  The ledges sounded kind of hollow so be careful.

name: Speakeasy
description: Start matched on the obvious sidepull, bump up to the lip and top out.   The top out can probably use some more cleaning.

name: The Sweatshop
description: Far left side of the same shortish boulder as Speakeasy.  Sit start, and work up to a somewhat difficult mantle.

name: The Devils Urn
description: SDS as for I.P. But move up and right through the iron knobs and excellent moves. Dynamic moves up high take you to a crux stab for a half-baseball pinch. Top out with a couple more moves up the right side of the face/slab.

name: Identifiable Percolation
description: SDS on a left side pull and a right crimp. Move up to a tiny 2.5 finger edge, then move strenuously up through more small difficult holds. Finish with a classic mantle, and top out the slab.    This route is fairly steep for the dodge. Perhaps 10 degrees overhung?

name: Pallium Problem
description: Start on the left side of the Wave Boulder. Traverse high and to the right on good incuts just below the top. Hit the top jug, and do the classic mantle top out moves.

name: Project Perhaps?
description: Just above the Wave Boulder there is an off vertical beautiful looking wall with an orange streak through it. Climb more or less straight up using small crimps etc.    Dew and I climbed half of this route. But were with out pad...someone go clean it up.

name: Scooby Dooby Dew
description: Climb up the finger sized crack to the blank looking face up top.

name: Estellar
description: Climb the right arete/face just next to Vanis. To a high slopey topout.

name: Vanis
description: Climb the face/crack on the left side of this striking boulder. Tricky and the start, and top out depending on how tall you are.

name: Bramble On
description: Start on low flake and climb up through fun moves on featured face.

name: Good Day Governor
description: A must do if you're in the area. Start low in vertical crack and work your way into double pockets on face. Make a big lock-off move to crimps. Top-out.

name: Pop Corner
description: Starting low right hand undercling, work your way up the corner of boulder to a big bump move to large flake.  Slopey top-out.

name: Playtime
description: Climb the nice grey stone up the slab/arete to the highest point on the boulder. Fun easy movement.

name: Oak Tree Crack
description: Climb finger sized crack to top.  Left side of face on Oak Tree Boulder.

name: Oak Tree Groove
description: Climb nice sized groove on the Oak Tree Boulder.

name: Prairie Fire
description: Start low on pockets and flakes and move up and left to top-out.  Cool features on this boulder.

name: Under the Sun
description: Same start as Prairie Fire, but head straight up.

name: Eli's Brambles
description: Begin on a flat jug on the right side of the boulder. Drop down and left to the good jugs in the middle of the face (the starting jugs of Rock Garden Roof) and finish through Rock Garden Roof.

name: Lumpy Corner
description: Climb large bulges on corner.

name: RGR Direct
description: Same start as Rock Garden Roof, but you bump up to crimp at the lip and gun for jug on upper corner.

name: Rock Garden Roof
description: Start on good jugs in middle of face, crank your way up and left to a great top-out.  This may be what Trav was calling "You Tell Me".

name: Sunnyside Slab
description: Climb slab just right of Lumpy Corner.

name: Rock Slide
description: Climb out small bulge in middle of boulder.

name: Bulls In A China Shop
description: This problem is on Boulder 2, just a few feet right of Open Season. Start on a good right facing gaston, then go to a good right facing sidepull and continue up and right through some smallish crimps. Topout in the notch.

name: Corner problem
description: Obvious line on left side of boulder 2.  Start with left tips jam, right good hold.  Move up past pocket and flake to top.

name: Dirty Bird
description: Start same as Dirty Traverse, top out in middle of block instead of far left side

name: Dirty Direct
description: Start on sidepull and crimp go up to the crack, then arete and top out.

name: Dirty Traverse
description: Start the same as Dirty Direct,move into crack and traverse left across block. Top out near red right arete.

name: Gennaro
description: Start sitting on undercling to the right just like "Just a Handful" and make move out left to jug. Then move up the right side of the sloper arete

name: Half Crack
description: The left of the face lines on boulder 1.  Climb up good holds to a finger jam.

name: Hidden in Plain Sight
description: Start low and to the right under roof with right hand pinch/jug and left hand on the ledge. Move left and up bulge

name: If Not Here, Where?
description: The Sit Start to If Not Now, When?     Start on thin pinch and sloping dish. Continues into If Not Now, When?

name: If Not Now, When?
description: Start on left pinch and crack underneath small roof. Make some fun moves through a sloping rail and pinches on the arete to a delicate move to gain the top.    Right wall is off

name: Just a Handful
description: Start on right undercling. Move left to jug and up left side

name: Low and Behold
description: Traverse left through some fun roof moves being careful not to dab the two small trees at the tip of the roof. Make a tight move to gain the left lip of the boulder. Mantle to finish.

name: Open Season
description: On boulder 2 climb the orange streak in the middle of the face. From edges (seeping?) and sloper go up and left for sidepull tips jug. Big move to the top.

name: Right leaning ramp
description: From good holds work your way up and right into long right angling dish feature with crimps in it.  Feet are just tricky enough to make this enjoyable.

name: Right Red Arete
description: The right side of boulder 1 there is a line that can start low or off a good low pinch with the right and good left edge.  Go up pinching, highstepping, and side pulling.

name: Secret Handshake
description: On-Sight Beta:   Climb the arete from a sit-start.    Flash Beta:   Climb the arete from a sit-start with both hands on the long vertical edge. Paste the right foot on, engage core, and go. Using the arete as an intermediate while moving up to the tooth seems unlikely but helps more than a little.

name: Shister Wall
description: There are a handful of other lines here that follow the natural lines.  Watch out for the shit on the ledge if you go up the semi chossy middle line...  The way left line is good, top out left.  Plenty of variations.  Fun steep stuf to swing your heels around on.

name: The Shister
description: The Shister takes the prominent bulge/arete up to the high break via piches and jugs.  Start low on rail and enjoy the holds.  Traverse right at second brake is highly recomended.

name: Alpine Bouldering Club (A.B.C.)
description: Hard sit start on the left side of the boulder. Tough gastons to start, then into hug and heeling moves. End with many different variations...big pocket out left...continued gastons... or by slapping the crack out right. Choose your own adventure.

name: Breakaway
description: Starts seated on the right arete. While staying on the main face, pull up and left to a fossilized prune knob, followed by a small sidepull just next to the arete, then direct to the top using a left pinch and foot work. A slightly easier variation uses the right arete and round the corner holds at V2-3.

name: Broken Dreams
description: Same start as A.B.C. goes right to really positive iron deposit and goes up from there using left hand side pulls, as stab to the pinch from breakaway (using it the opposite way) and a thrutch for the top.   youtube.com/watch?v=TedI-rQ…   video of the F.A. for a better idea.

name: Project ( We call it titty twister)
description: Start on left side pull and move to largest piton and move up right to nipple get a twist in a move on up.

name: A Real Cool Hand
description: Move up the blunt arete using a sloper and a couple crimps. Pull your feet onto the main face and throw for the top corner. Feels like it ends too soon.

name: Almost Left Behind
description: Climb the arete up and to avoid scary top out move left sooner then later

name: Beached Whale
description: Climb pocketed face to a big horizontal break. no top out.

name: Cat Fancy
description: Squeeze the blunt arete up to a good left hand jug, then end on the big horizontal break. Traverse off easily left or right. If you are very bold (or silly) you could top it out.

name: Early Release
description: Starts on small right hand crimp and move up and left to a sloper. Crux is either groping the sloping mini prow, or a throw to a small positive hold just at the top of the prow. Fun foot work and body positions on this.

name: Eschew Obfuscuity
description: Squat start in diagonal undercling rail, move up to two good crimps. Head up using some small slopes on the left and underclings on the right. The crux is squeezing hard enough to bring your feet up high enough to reach the final pocket.  As with its neighbor to the right the sit start does add some difficulty but just isn't that fun.

name: Fairytale Land
description: Sloping crimps lead into a faintly right leaning crack, on a face speckled with with small golden crimps. Fun movement the whole way, the crux comes low on the route as you get into the first crack hold. Top half is intimidating due to the height, but fear not ye for the lip is full of awesome jugs.

name: Hang Loose
description: Start on low holds and traverse horizontally into the overhanging arete, move up to large flat ledge on corner and traverse off and around the corner. This route does not top out (ends at top of beached whale).

name: Herding Cat
description: Start on top of a freshly fallen block using underclings. Follow the left arete and top out on the flat platform.

name: It Gets Nervous
description: Slab, balance oriented slab route ending with a tough gaston or two. Stay off the mossy fern covered  ledge for full value (and cause its purty). High exciting topout. (Route is somewhat reminiscent of Feels like butter at Rib mountain)

name: Lichen Love
description: Small crimps on a vertical face, crux is making good use of the small feet.

name: Makes Me Smile
description: Small boulder start on right arete , work up and left.

name: Pale Gardener
description: Start on a set of lieback/underclings. Move to the left, pull a sharp gaston (or super reachy move if your tall)  then top out easily....in the moss. A bit more brushing would make it a more classy route.

name: Parole Violation
description: Start is just left of the right arete on small crimps. The route stays on the face using crimps and a long move to reach the top. An easier variation to this route moves to a large jug on the right arete and tops out using some small holds on the face and around the corner.

name: Steve Done
description: Very fun overhanging arete that leads into a vertical arete topout. Low to the ground much of the way. For those who have done Kings throne at Westby, this is nearly the exact same route, the lower section is just a few moves longer. SDS.

name: Testtickler
description: Climbs arete powerfully, using pinches, crimps, heel hooks, and a throw. Sit start adds a grade in difficulty but not in aesthetics.

name: Tread Lightly
description: start on Arete right of Welcome to the top move up using side pulls and the large foot but Tread lightly for the foot might break some day.  For full value try not to use center pocket from Welcome to the top.

name: Welcome to the Top
description: Stand start on an undercling and move up positive edges on this 5 degree pitched face. Top out easily. Its tall, but only a few large moves to the top.

name: What would Steve Dew?
description: Start 2 hands in horizontal break at chest height.  Strenuous moves up to next break, topout.

name: Little Prow
description: Start low on slopers near right corner of boulder, just right of melincholy, and work your way up and left through good holds.

name: Melincholy (AKA Little Roof)
description: Melincholy is actually pretty fun on good rock.  Start low and right on the smaller of the 2 Melin Boulders.  Use good holds and edges, a nice hidden jug underneath for your left hand, and traverse left to the corner and up with edges and a cool round iron knob.  Kinda mossy but brushes easily, so bring one.      Low and right start on the smaller boulder.      Maybe 15-16 feet tall?  Hard to tell since there was 2 feet of snow on the ground.  The overhanging face has some slopey ledges but I couldn't tell with all the frost on it if it was chossy or if there were any other features.  I presume it's been checked out before, it's not far out of the way.

name: Melinhead (AKA Sandbox Arete)
description: Just down the slope from Barrel Ridge towards the road lie these boulders.  You can see them if you drive slowly past the ridge and look up and right.  Dismissed by some as choss, the larger boulder is, in fact, choss.  Melinhead climbs the slightly overhanging corner closest to the ridgeline using edges and sandy sidepulls on the big boulder.  A committing final move leads to the mossy topout.  Another line could go up the overhanging face on the ledges but would be somewhat scary.    The corner of the larger boulder facing you in the photo.      Maybe 15-16 feet tall?  Hard to tell since there was 2 feet of snow on the ground.  The overhanging face has some slopey ledges but I couldn't tell with all the frost on it if it was chossy or if there were any other features.  I presume it's been checked out before, it's not far out of the way.

name: Sandbox Dyno
description: Start on good jug and hike right foot high, throw for the goods on the lip.

name: Sandbox Warm-up
description: Climb up face just right of Melinhead. Easy and a bit dirty.

name: Scared of the Sandbox
description: Starting with left hand on the flake and right side-pull in crack work your way up tricky face avoiding the left corner to a heady top-out.

name: The Wanderer
description: Head straight up the pillar using both aretes. The fall is a bit dicey on this one...fall left no prob, fall right and land 10feet down in a pile of rubble.

name: High Tide
description: Start on left side pull and right thin crimp next to rock on left side of roof. High step and climb slab to the top. For full value stay on face and off right side.

name: Sand Stone Sur Fin
description: Sit start under roof on right side using heel and holds on right fin. Gain face and surf the fin to the top.

name: Egghead
description: Climb the small corner/face straight up. Several variations exist for the top out. The best of which is straight up from the start.

name: It's Oral Over
description: Thin! Stand start and move up a series of small/sharpish pinches. Bump to a good pinch just off the right arete, and move left onto more thin bad holds. Either make a final deadpoint to a minipocket out left, or dyno for the huge jug at the top. Super fun route!

name: The Scientists
description: Nice sit start on the corner. Move straight up to a jug, using the arete and vertical crack. From here roll easily over the lip using large holds (V3). For more spice and class, stick to the face and use the blunt arete and small crimps for the last 6 feet (V4).

name: Saloon Doors
description: Saloon Doors is a nice dihedral near the east end of the main wall at the Twin Valley Campground Bouldering Wall.  Climb up the dihedral to a nice topout.  A nice easy warmup.

name: Too Soon
description: Squat start low as you can with poor feet. Bump up the overhang, and make a toss to the lip.

name: Cold Dinner Tonight
description: Start in a crouch with a good right pinch and bad left sloper. Move up and right using a super cool dynamic left hand pinch grab.

name: The Creeper
description: SDS just left of Cold Dinner, on the left arete. Climb up the corner.

name: Last Call
description: Sit start with left hand on arete, right on side pull. Bump up the arete into a tough mantle topout.

name: Sauin
description: Start with both hands on good underlings at base of roof, a couple long hard moves around the lip lead to an easy top out.

name: White Van
description: Start with both hands matched on low edge of arete for Creeper. Climb right into Cold Dinner via interesting holds and creative footwork.

name: 87th Best
description: Start on the clean white face, and climb directly to the top. Follow the crimps into progressively larger holds. High topout.

name: Life on the Prairie
description: Sit start at the right base of the big face. Climb right along the arete using a couple holds on the right face, and left hand on the arete.

name: Prairie Dog
description: Start sitting on jugs and traverse up and right on lip to committing crux move at mantle.

name: Pudding Tree Arete
description: Walk up ledge to stand start on arete left of 87th Best. Use large flat ledge to start. Climb up arete while making use of a jug on left, jugs & crimps on right, and jugs on arete itself. Towards the top you will most likely go out to the right more on crimps, then creep back in on the arete again. Watch out for a jug about half way up on the right that rocks back and forth, can be used, but it might get pulled out someday. The top out is also fairly dirty, but you can still grab the nub to pull yourself up. Climb down the pudding tree to get down off the boulder, but be careful, that thing might smush off the boulder very soon.

name: Training Weight
description: Move up the lobular arete on nice comfy holds. Top out on slopey business.

name: Aibohphobia
description: Sit start on lowest holds and move up into crack system, topout on nice jugs.

name: Live Not on Evil
description: Stand start on jug ledge, move up on arete and face to topout.

name: Party Boobytrap
description: Sit start on sloper and crimp, up into dual cracks, top out.

name: So Many Dynamos!
description: Stand start on low block, use undercling and crimps to strenuously topout.  Careful of block below topout.

name: Chunk Arete
description: Start on the obvious chunk and climb up the right arete of the crack using face holds as well.

name: Hmm, That's a Good One
description: Scope out the good pockets that aren't razor sharp, sit start, and pull on them until you're up top.  Bring tape, a good attitude, and a good microbrew.

name: The Gray Traverse
description: Find the short, long, gray wall with good rock and traverse it from either side.

name: Bone Cave
description: Start low (beneath the small cave with bones in it) and move up and left through roof or along the juggy arete. The roof pulls over into more vertical but vegetated climbing. The shortest downclimb is on the opposite side of the boulder.

name: Moderately Overweight Physician
description: Arete to the right of Sandscape.  Sit-start on the two obvious pockets on the right slab face and make your way up the arete using more pockets and a heel hook or two, while staying off the slab to the right.  The top-out is pretty simple, but be delicate - the bomberness of the shelves is questionable.

name: Pinche Arbol
description: Sit start beneath a sloper and move up through pockets, past a ledge and left around the tree to top out, which is the crux.

name: Sandscape
description: Sit start below the lowest good jug. Left hand sidepull w/ thumb pocket, right hand in a double hueco. Move up to the first good jug, then up and right through pockets to the crimpy ledge. Up and right some more through good pockets to a minty but thorny top out. Beware of loose blocks up there.

name: Stop Hitting Yourself
description: Start on a horizontal crack and go straight up the overhang - look for the crucial roof pocket. Topout crux with not much to grab, try throwing up a heel.

name: Blue Lines
description: Ok route consisting of plentiful pockets and colorful crimps.  Crux at the top with not much to grab.   Trees are off, unless you want to use them.

name: Drop Party
description: Sit start below the big bread loaf (pictured) and move up through slopers and pockets. Short slab tops out just next to the juniper.

name: Drug Rugs and Chemtrails
description: The crux is fairly mental, being the most highball route on the slab.   A few small pockets and meager footholds make this route quite balancey and fun.

name: Frosted Flakes
description: Follow the flakes next to the arete without using it to the top.  Great route to warm up on, easy the whole way up.

name: Left Arete
description: Follow the left arete to the top. A little steeper than the right side, but you can still do it!

name: Right Arete
description: Follow the right arete to the top, just do it.

name: Slip and Slide
description: The middle route on the Tagged Slab. Crux in the middle - use small crimps and some fancy footwork to top it out.

name: Who Needs GF when You Have GP?
description: Sit start at Yes/No checkbox. Move up through bright blue graffiti. Reach a lip and work slopers up short slab to top. Convenient tree for down climb.

name: Don't Mess with Treesus
description: Sit start, two easy moves to a dirty top out.

name: W.W.T.D.
description: Swing up right from the sit start for a decent crimp that bumps to a jug. Traverse out around the corner and top out in the corner.
